<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>VETERAN ENVIRONMENTALIST'S- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>
 </HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
 <center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
For Immediate Release: June 23, 1995 <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
<CENTER><B><H2>WWF Urges Indian Prime Minister To Save Veteran Environmentalist's Life</H2><BR>
</B></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>GLAND, SWITZERLAND</B> -- WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature today
appealed to the Indian Government to intervene immediately to
save the life of Sunderlal Bahuguna, a veteran Indian environmentalist.
Mr Bahuguna is on fast for the last 44 days in protest against
the construction of the Tehri Dam on a tributary of the Ganges
River in the western Himalayas in the northern State of Uttar
Pradesh.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
This is the second time Mr. Bahuguna has gone on fast for the
same cause. In 1992, he broke his 45-day fast after Prime Minister
Narasimha Rao gave him an assurance that the Tehri dam project
would be reviewed by a high-level committee. While construction
work was suspended, the promised review was not undertaken. In
April 1995, construction restarted.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
WWF India President, Dr M S Swaminathan, has already written to
the Indian Prime Minister, Mr P V Narasimha Rao, asking him to
suspend work on the controversial Tehri Dam project and institute
a techno-economic review. He has also asked the Prime Minister
to honour the assurances given to the environmentalist in 1992.
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;WWF supports Mr. Bahuguna and the cause for which he is
fasting,&quot; said Dr. Claude Martin, Director General of WWF
International. &quot;We are concerned by his worsening condition
and appeal to the Indian Government to suspend construction work
on the Tehri Dam. An actual review of the project, already promised
by the Indian Government, can save Mr. Bahuguna's life.&quot;
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Mr. Bahuguna began his fast on May 10, after he and four other
colleagues were arrested for blocking the road to the dam site.
He said he will not break his fast until the Tehri Dam 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
construction is suspended and a committee formed to review the
project. Meanwhile, the Allahabad High Court has ruled against
attempts by government officials to force-feed Mr. Bahuguna in
hospital.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Planned to be the highest dam in Asia, the 260 metres-high Tehri
dam has been mired in controversy since its approval in 1972.
Construction is still at a preliminary stage. Cost estimates have
however jumped 30 times, from Rs 2 billion in 1969 to Rs 60 billion
($2 billion) in 1994. It is supposed to provide 2000 megawatts
of electricity, irrigation and drinking water. However, its benefits
have been serious questioned given the high financial cost and
substantial environmental damage.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
.....2<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
-2- <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
WWF has been consistently opposing the Tehri dam project for several
reasons. Seismologists and other independent experts have warned
against the danger of building the dam in a highly seismic zone.
An earthquake could, for instance, wipe out the holy cities of
Rishikesh and Haridwar, and flood the densely populated North
Gangetic Indian plains downstream.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Moreover, construction of such a huge dam in the upper catchment
area will adversely affect the water quality of the River Ganges
- sacred to millions of Indians- primarily because free flow of
water would be allowed only once a year during the monsoon. Migration
of fish has already been blocked. In addition to the flora and
fauna of the region which would be lost, the farmers of western
Uttar Pradesh also stand to lose in terms of natural irrigation.
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
- End-<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For more information, please call Biksham Gujja at +41 22 3649509
or Someshwar Singh + 41 22 364 9573 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
