<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>WWF and Indigenous Alliance Join Forces to Affirm Indigenous Peoples' Rights In Tropical Forests</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>


<P>
<center>
<H2>WWF and Indigenous Alliance Join Forces to Affirm Indigenous Peoples' Rights In Tropical Forests</H2>
</center>

<P>

<B>GLAND, Switzerland</B> -- Representatives of WWF-World Wide Fund For
Nature and the International Alliance of Indigenous Tribal Peoples
of the Tropical Forests will hold a landmark meeting in Ecuador
between June 3-5 to establish direct cooperation in international
efforts to protect tropical forests, WWF announced today.

<P>
The representatives from WWF and the Alliance will meet in the
eastern Ecuadorean village of El Puyo, where they will discuss
alternatives to strengthen the role of indigenous peoples in tropical
forest conservation.  Both organizations aim to find ways to address
the insufficient recognition of indigenous peoples' rights present
in international initiatives such as the UN Convention on Biological
Diversity (CBD), which meets this September in Buenos Aires, Argentina.


<P>
&quot;The role of indigenous peoples in the conservation of  the
forests of the planet and their diversity of life is vital, and
must be adequately considered in international instruments such
as the CBD,&quot; said Gonzalo Oviedo, Forest Officer at WWF International.
 &quot;Up until now, the positions adopted in international agreements
are insufficient and do not reflect the importance that indigenous
peoples have in the nature conservation.  This is why WWF hopes
to help indigenous organisations to strengthen their role in the
CBD and other agreements.&quot;

<P>
According to the Alliance, around 50 of the 300 million indigenous
people living in the world today inhabit tropical forests.  These
forests, in turn, contain many of the areas which are considered
to be richest in biodiversity.  The Alliance represents indigenous
peoples from 31 countries in Asia, Africa and Latin America.

<P>
Nevertheless, according to the WWF, current international conservation
instruments keep treating the issues affecting indigenous peoples
in an unbalanced manner and do not guarantee their participation
in the conservation of the natural areas where they have lived
for centuries.  The fundamental flaw in these instruments is rooted
in the lack of a clear recognition of the rights of indigenous
peoples.  &quot;This is a structural flaw that needs to be corrected,&quot;
said Oviedo.

<P>
<font size=-1>
For more information, please contact Javier Arreaza at +41 22
364 9550 or fax +41 22 364 8307.</font>




<P>

<br>

</blockquote>

