<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>HURRICANES IN CARRIBBEAN- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>
 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
For immediate release  12 October 1995<BR>
<BR>
<B><H2>  <CENTER>Hurricanes Wreak Ecological Havoc in Caribbean</CENTER></H2>
<BR>
<BR>
WASHINGTON, DC -- </B>The endangered hawksbill turtle is just
one of the victims of the unprecedented hurricanes that have ravaged
the Caribbean this season, according to a report released today
by WWF - World Wide Fund For Nature.     <BR>
<BR>
WWF reports that storms have destroyed half the nests on Buck
Island, the US's premier hawksbill nesting area. Scientists assessing
the damage to the Virgin Islands National Park on St John (one
of the country's most popular and important coastal parks) also
found widespread destruction of the park's forests: leaves had
been stripped  away and many treetops completely sheared off.
<BR>
<BR>
The team reported massive kills of rare brown pelicans -- all
the nests at the park's principal nesting site were lost and baby
pelicans were found hanging from trees. Coral reefs suffered too:
large-scale debris such as wrecked yachts compounded wind and
wave damage, and at one site, reefs were almost completely destroyed
down to more than 10 metres below the sea surface. Fish had completely
disappeared from most of the reefs surveyed.<BR>
<BR>
Many scientists believe that the ecological damage caused during
this year's hurricane season - the worst since 1933 - may be just
the beginning.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;After riding the wild weather rollercoaster of 1995, everyone
should recognize that climate change has become a part of everyday
life&quot; says Adam Markham, Director of WWF's Climate Campaign.
&quot;The marine ecosystems of the Caribbean may be the coal-miner's
canary and we should heed the warning before saving the climate
is completely beyond our control.&quot; <BR>
        <BR>
Next week (16-20 October) experts from around the world meet at
the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) in Montreal
to finalize a state-of-the-art scientific report that sheds new
light on these storms. The new IPCC report concludes that:<BR>
                                                             
                            <I>more....<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</I>                                                2<BR>
<BR>
* The burning of fossil fuels is a critical causal factor in the
current global warming        trend<BR>
<BR>
* We can expect even more rapid warming in the coming decades
<BR>
<BR>
* The warming may lead to an increase in the number and severity
of tropical storms.<BR>
<BR>
                                                             
                                <BR>
Said WWF Senior Scientist, Dr Tundi Agardy: &quot;The ecological
wounds from these storms may never completely heal. The devastation
of important sea turtle nesting beaches casts a huge shadow over
this already critically endangered species. And it is a tragedy
to see coral reefs that have taken thousands of years to generate
being scoured away by storm surges and battered by the wreckage
of boats and other debris.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
IPCC scientists suggest that the trend is set to continue. Hurricanes
Luis and Marilyn ripped through the Caribbean within days of each
other in September. Hurricane Opal cut a swathe through Mexico's
Yucatan peninsula in early October. Now Hurricane Roxanne is sweeping
through the region. Storms of this kind rarely hit the same place
more than once in a century, yet the US Virgin Islands National
Park has now been struck three times in six years, giving ecosystems
no chance to recover from one hurricane before being subjected
to another. <BR>
<BR>
           ENDS<BR>
<BR>
For more information and copies of <I>WWF's Assessment of the
Ecological Impacts of Hurricanes on the Ecosystems of the US Virgin
Islands National Park and Surrounding Caribbean Areas</I>, contact
Sarah Russell  on +41 22 364 9554.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Editors' notes:<BR>
<BR>
</B>The US Virgin Islands National Park was established in 1956
and was designated a Biosphere Reserve under the UN Educational
Scientific and Cultural Organization's Man and the Biosphere Programme.
Its clear blue seas, colourful coral reefs, and white sandy beaches
 attract more than one million visitors a year, making it one
of the US's most visited coastal parks. <BR>
<BR>
The park covers two-thirds of the island and is home to many rare
species such as queen conch; green, hawksbill, and leatherback
turtles; brown pelicans, white-crowned pigeons, and moustached
quail doves. <BR>
        <BR>
  <BR>
        <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
