<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WWF  Calls for Stronger Action to Combat Climate Change
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Relaese">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>

<center><font size=5><B>
WWF  Calls for Stronger Action to Combat Climate Change
</font></b></center> <P>
<img src="/graphics/sunsetbuilding.jpg" align=right>
<b>MONTREAL, October 16, 1996</b> -- WWF today urged the world's conservation
community to
develop strategies for protecting wildlife and natural ecosystems from the
growing problem of
climate change caused by global warming.
<p>
At the World Conservation Conference in Montreal, WWF-World Wide Fund for
Nature (in Canada
and the USA known as the World Wildlife Fund) reaffirmed that climate change
as a result of global
warming represent a serious threat to the survival of biodiversity -- the
variety of plants and animals
found within a region -- and the protection, management and rehabilitation
of protected areas.
<p>
"National governments and organizations like the IUCN have to stop hitting
the snooze button on
the alarm bell for action that global warming represents," said Adam
Markham, Director of WWF's
Global Climate Change Campaign. "How many ecosystems must be threatened
before we listen to
this wake-up call?"
<p>
Scientists agree that climatic changes affecting the planet are caused
mainly by the burning of coal,
oil and gas. Huge quantities of pollutants like carbon dioxide trap more and
more heat in the
atmosphere, ultimately disrupting the global temperature balance. As a
result, temperatures in some
areas have risen. At the speed the climate is now changing,  scientists
predict the world will soon be
warmer than at any time in the last 10,000 years.
<p>
Some 2,500 scientists involved with the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate
Change (IPCC) found
that atmospheric concentrations of CO2 are now 30 per cent above the
pre-industrial level, and that
a warming trend in global mean temperature can be detected since 1860. The
IPCC concluded that
"the balance of evidence suggests a discernible human influence on global
climate" and that
"significant loss of species must be considered as one of the most important
impacts on climate
change".
<p>
WWF is calling on the IUCN to work with the IPCC and the Framework
Convention on Climate Change to take the following action:
<ul>
<li>The Commission on National Parks and Protected Areas (CNPPA) to develop
new guidelines for
protected areas management and planning and recommend strategies aimed at
minimizing the
impacts of climate change.
<li>The Species Survival Commission (SSC) to examine the feasibility of
developing a red data book
type listing of species most vulnerable to climate change.
<li>The Commissions in general to assess the implications of climate change
for their goals and
operations, and then on the basis of the results of these assessments, to
develop work programme
elements to integrate climate change into their activities.
</ul>
</td>
 </table> <p> <a href="/graphics/toolbar.map">
<img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
</BODY>
