<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
NEW SIBERIAN TIGER COUNT GIVES HOPE
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">

<table width=580>
<td>
<br>

<CENTER><B> <FONT SIZE=5>
New Siberian Tiger Count Gives Hope
<BR>
 
</FONT></B></CENTER><br>
<img src="/graphics/tiger.jpg" align=right alt="forest" hspace=5>
<b>Frankfurt am Main, Germany</b> -- While a new count now gives us hope that there are more Siberian tigers than once thought - 
between 415 and 475 of these great cats today roam the forests in Russia's far east - the Siberian tiger is still in 
immediate danger of extinction. 
<p>

This is the  conclusion of US and Russian scientists evaluating thousands of tiger tracks after large scale field research  
commissioned by the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF) - Germany and the US  Programme for Environmental Co-operation 
(USAID-EPT/RFE) in the Russian far east. 
<p>

The last large survey in 1985 only identified 240 to 250 animals. But during the winter of 1995/6, 675 counters  looked for 
tracks in the Siberian tiger's habitat. The result announced by WWF- Germany: approximately 330 adults and 104 cubs.
<p>

"We can build on this result," said Dr. Georg Schwede of WWF - Germany. Now conservation organisations can focus tiger 
protection initiatives on the newly identified numbers, rather than significantly lower numbers identified earlier. 
<p>

The identification of this rare, mostly nocturnal species is difficult. Snow conditions and the distribution of the wild 
cats, as well as selected survey methods,  influence the results. "The new study was significantly more onerous than before, 
and has finally delivered a more valid assessment of tiger numbers," Dr Schwede added. 
<p>

In addition to the continuous survey running throughout the winter, scientists organised a  two week search during February 
1996, involving all the counters. The results can therefore be considered statistically significant.
<p>

However, the new count does not give any cause for WWF to relax its efforts. Tigers continue to be endangered. Poached tigers 
are traded illegally to meet the demand for traditional Chinese medicine.
"Since 1991 at least 180 tigers have been poached," Dr Schwede explained. "  While WWF's work in supporting anti-poaching 
wardens is bearing fruit and there is a reduction in poaching, the support of anti-poaching measures is now more important 
than ever."  
<p>

In addition to supporting anti-poaching measures, WWF will work even more closely with customs and other state 
administrators. WWF is also working in conjunction with Russian and American partners in Primorje and Chabarovsk, whose 
65,000 sq kms represents the worlds largest network of protected areas.
<p>

Local environmental education programmes should promote awareness of local people for conservation. A large scale awareness 
raising programme, especially in China, is designed to influence users of tiger products.
<p>

Together with the USAID-EPT/RFE project, WWF is attempting to propagate sustainable economic practices in the region. This 
includes strategies for developing eco-tourism as well as the promotion of sustainable forestry practices.
<p>
One year after the start of the tiger campaign of WWF-Germany, Dr Schwede concluded: "The signatures of approximately one 
million German supporters of the campaign has led to the implementation in Russia of our objectives. We must now build on the 
excellent working relationship with the Russian authorities and perpetuate our protection projects through targeted 
environmental education work."

<p> </table> <p> <a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
</BODY>
