<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CONVENTION ON BIOLOGICAL DIVERSITY- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif">
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
For Immediate Release: 17 November 1995<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><FONT SIZE=4><CENTER><H2>Will Governments Help the Convention on 
Biological Diversity</h2> </FONT></B> </BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><FONT SIZE=4><h2>Deliver on its Promises?</H2></CENTER></FONT></B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>JAKARTA, Indonesia</B> -- WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature urges
the 134 governments, which have ratified the Convention on Biological
Diversity (CBD), to implement the recommendations on forest and
marine and coastal biodiversity from the second Conference of
Parties (COP2), which ends here today.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;We are reasonably satisfied with the outcome of COP2,&quot;
said Nancy Vallejo, Coordinator of International Treaties of WWF
International. &quot;The Convention has flagged its role and responsibility
on many other important issues. But the important decisions taken
by COP2 are just the beginning of process of implementation. Governments
have to shell out the resources to follow through these decisions.&quot;
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
One of the most significant results of COP2 was the decision to
develop a protocol on Biosafety. It recognized the need for further
analysis of existing national, regional and international regulations
and legally binding instruments of relevance to the impact of
Living Modified Organisms (LMOs)on biodiversity. The draft protocol
is to identify relevant categories of LMOs resulting from modern
biotechnology. It will also elaborate the key concepts and terms
to be addressed in the process. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Other positive outcomes relate to promoting sustainable use of
forest or marine biodiversity; and helping indigenous and local
communities benefit from genetic resources they preserve. However,
these are issues that seek some fundamental changes, including
social and political, to make a real difference.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;The CBD is beginning to send the right messages.The real
need, however, is for governments to take urgent national action
to address the immediate and severe threats which are likely to
cause irreversible damage to key components of biodiversity,&quot;
said Ms Vallejo. &quot; Priority measures can and should be taken
immediately, at the national level, to address the most pressing
threats to biodiversity. Developed country governments have a
special responsibility to live up to their funding obligations
in this respect.&quot;
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
On the crucial subject of Intellectual Property Rights (IPRs),
COP2 has decided to liaise with the World Trade Organization,
to undertake analysis of impacts of IPRs on biodiversity conservation
and use, and to hold consultations with all stakeholders (private,
indigenous and local). The issue will come in COP3. On the issue
of Access to genetic resources and benefit sharing, however, COP2
has made no real development, except for identifying it as an
important issue. There is no guidance to countries on what they
should do about it. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The focus of COP3, which Argentina has offered to host, will include
Incentive Measures; agricultural biodiversity; Issues related
to technology; Access to genetic resources; Knowledge, innovations
and practices of indigenous and local communities; and Future
programme of work for terrestrial biological diversity.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=1>-End- </FONT>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=1>For more information, please call Nancy Vallejo or
Someshwar Singh at +62&nbsp;21&nbsp;570&nbsp;3600.</FONT> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

