<td width=104><img src="graphics/dot.jpg"></td>

<td width=396><font size=-1><b>Issue 1 April 1996</b></font></td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>

<table width=620 border=0>
<tr>
<td width=100 align=middle valign=top>
<img src="graphics/logo.jpg"><br>
<hr noshade color=000000 width=90 align=left>
<p><br>
<b><font size=4>
<a href="page1.htm">Regional Update</a><p><br>
<a href="page2.htm">Country Updates</a><p><br>
<a href="page3.htm">From the Field</a><p><br>
<a href="page4.htm">Contact the IGCP</a><p><br>
</font></b>
<hr noshade width=90 color=000000 align=left>
</td>
<td width=20><br></td>
<td width=500 valign=top align=left>
<center><font size=6><b><i>IGCP and its Work in the Region</i></b></font><p></center>
<font size=6>T</font>he International Gorilla Conservation
Programme (IGCP)'s overall goal is 'to
ensure the survival and long term
conservation of mountain gorillas and
afro-montane and medium altitude forest
habitats in Rwanda, Uganda and Zaire'. It is
working towards achieving this goal through
close collaboration with the protected area
authorities in each country.
<p>
Evolving from the Mountain Gorilla Project
which was started in 1978, IGCP was launched
in 1991 as a joint initiative between the
African Wildlife Foundation (AWF), Fauna and
Flora International (FFI) and the World Wide
Fund for Nature (WWF). It is the only
conservation programme that works within the
entire region where mountain gorillas are
found, and the only one to work in
partnership with all the protected area
authorities within that region: Institut
Zairois pour la Conservation de la Nature
(IZCN), Office Rwandais du Tourisme et des
Parcs Nationaux (ORTPN) and Uganda National
Parks (UNP).
<p>
IGCP's regional approach, technical
background and programme flexibility have
enabled it to react rapidly, and
effectively, throughout the recent crisis in
Rwanda and Zaire. Zaire's Virunga National
Park (PNVi), created in 1925, is Africa's
oldest National Park and has been declared a
World Heritage Site. About 700,000 refugees
fled Rwanda at the end of the war in 1994
and were accommodated in camps along the
edge of the park. Through provision of
funds, equipment and technical assistance
when most needed, IGCP has been able to
underpin the work of the protected area
authorities.
<p>
With this support, IGCP has been able to
help IZCN control the refugees' use of the
Park's natural resources as well as
co-ordinate the necessary anti-poaching
activities. In Rwanda, IGCP has provided
financial and technical support and has been
instrumental in enabling ORTPN to recommence
and plan its essential conservation
activities. 


</td>
</tr>
</table>

</table>
