<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>SOUTH AFRICAN DROUGHT- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For release Tuesday 17 October 1995<BR>
<BR>
<B><H2>
<CENTER>Global Warming Causing Southern African Drought</CENTER>
</H2><BR>

GLAND, Switzerland</B> -- Global climate change could cause severe
water shortages in Zimbabwe, Namibia, Botswana, and South Africa,
according to a groundbreaking computer modelling project undertaken
by WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our research reveals that a hundred years of global warming
may be developing into a long-term drought here in southern Africa,&quot;
said Adam Markham, Director of WWF's Climate Campaign. &quot;It
also shows that the situation is likely to get worse.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Global warming is an increasingly urgent problem. The Intergovernmental
Panel on Climatic Change (IPCC) -- the world's  top climate scientists
-- is currently finalizing a report which states that global warming
is fact not fiction, and that pollution is at least partly to
blame. The report will be released in December this year. This
week a group of IPCC experts meet in Montreal to discuss the section
of the report that deals with the impacts of climate change on
people and the environment. <BR>
<BR>
The WWF research highlights the fact that the first victims of
drought are often poor people living in rural areas. Next week,
on 25 October, Zimbabweans  traditionally celebrate the beginning
of the rainy season and  start planting their crops. This year,
they will plant with heavy hearts, fearful that the harvest will
fail.<BR>
<BR>
For the past 13 years, rainfall has been so low and crop failures
so common that villagers in western Zimbabwe have become more
and more dependent on international food aid. Bore holes are drying
up, making it impossible to maintain livestock herds and forcing
women and children to walk further and further to collect water
to meet their families' needs.<BR>
<BR>
Urban dwellers are also affected. Zimbabwe's capital city, Harare,
only has water supplies for 10 months and is experiencing power
shortages. The Kariba Dam, which produces most of the country's
electricity, is running at 14 per cent capacity. <BR>
<BR>
                                                             
                                   <I>more...... <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</I>                                <BR>
Animals are suffering too. Larger species such as hippos cannot
survive without regular supplies of food and water. The WWF study
also identifies animals living in the high grasslands near South
Africa's Cape of Good Hope as particularly vulnerable. Warmer
conditions will reduce habitat for Cape mountain zebra, grey rhebok,
grysbok, mountain reedbuck, black wildebeest, bontebok, and blesbok.
 <BR>
<BR>
WWF aims to make the computer modelling programme available to
scientists and policy makers elsewhere in Africa so that they
can adapt to the inevitable changes that will come with global
warming.<BR>
<BR>
Said Dr David Cumming, WWF's  Senior Conservation Officer in Harare:
&quot;Southern Africa is a naturally dry region. Increasing aridity
will only exacerbate the already considerable problems of feeding
the region. It will also hinder industrial and urban development.
Given that population growth is around three per cent per year,
this has serious implications for the future.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
WWF is therefore working to alert policy makers in the region
to the likely impacts of climate change and to break down widespread
resistance on the part of governments and industry to curb the
greenhouse gas emissions responsible for the rising tide of global
warming.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Industrialized countries' governments, and the oil industry
have tried to fob us off for years with the excuse that there
isn't enough scientific proof that climate change is a real problem,&quot;
said Markham. &quot;The writing is now on the wall: global warming
exists, largely as a result of the activities of rich 'developed'
countries' activities. And people and wildlife in poor countries
are suffering as a result.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The WWF programme has been developed by scientists at the Climatic
Research Unit at the UK's University of East Anglia, in consultation
with experts working in Africa and Europe.<BR>
<BR>
                                                ENDS<BR>
<BR>
For more information contact Sarah Russell at WWF International
 on +41 22 264 9554.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
