<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
GREAT INDIAN RHINO THREATENED BY RENEWED POACHING
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>
<p>
<center>
<font size=4><b>
GREAT INDIAN RHINO THREATENED BY RENEWED POACHING
</b>
</font>

<p>
</center>
<img src="/graphics/rhino.gif" align=right><b>GENEVA, Switzerland</b>
-- The greater one-horned
rhinoceros (Rhinoceros unicornis) faces a
continuing poaching threat in India, where 
killing methods that include electrocution
are being used, according to a Species in
Danger Report released today by TRAFFIC, the
wildlife trade monitoring arm of the World
Wide Fund For Nature (WWF) and IUCN-The
World Conservation Union.
<p>
The report Under Siege: Poaching and Protection
of Greater One-horned Rhinoceroses in India says
that only two viable populations of rhinos
survive in India, with a total population of
around 1,500 - approximately half that of
tigers.  The Javan rhino is believed to have
become extinct in India as early as 1900,
while the Sumatran rhino disappeared in
about 1935.
<p>
Greater one-horned rhino numbers in India
have been increasing steadily since the turn
of the century, when only a handful
remained.  However, resurgence of poaching
in the 1980s saw the loss of 483 rhinos. 
Illegal killing accelerated again in the
early 1990s, which resulted in a further
loss of 209 rhinos (or 13.8 per cent of the
country's total population) between 1990 and
1993.
<p>
The IUCN Species Survival Commission's Asian
Rhino Specialist Group estimates that  31
Indian rhino were lost in 1994 and at least
35 in 1995. Poaching for horn has reduced
the country's second largest population in
Manas National Park from between 80 to 100,
to only 12 today. Shooting remains the most
common method of poaching rhinos in India
and in 1995 the first recorded incident
involving a silencer was reported.  Poachers
also electrocute rhinos by dangling wires
connected to high tension powerlines across
rhino paths.  Pit traps are also employed in
areas of suitable terrain.
<p>
"The worse rhino crisis is now in Asia,
where all three surviving species are
endangered," said Elizabeth Kemf,  Species
Policy and Information Officer at WWF
International. "Despite increased
protection, the Sumatran rhino is still
declining. The Indonesian Government itself
says illegal killing of the rhino in Sumatra
is  'uncontrollable' and 'overwhelming'.  In
1995, between 390 to 540 Sumatran rhinos
survived, but that number is believed to
have dropped to between 250 and 450."
<p>
Rhino horn is used in traditional Oriental 
medicine. Horn from Asian rhinos is believed
to be more potent and is far more valuable
than horn from African rhinos.  The new
report identifies trading routes going from
India through Bhutan, Nepal and Bangladesh,
from where it is sent by air to markets in
South East Asia.
<p>
"Security measures to protect rhinos need to
be reviewed and strengthened," said Vivek
Menon, author of the report.  WWF calls for
intelligence networks to collect information
on poaching and trade, increased motivation
for park staff and the removal of high
tension wires from parks.
<p>
For more information, please contact Bobbie
Jo Kelso at TRAFFIC International, +44 1223
277 427, or Javier Arreaza, WWF
International, +41 22 364 9550.

</table> <p> <a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
</BODY>
