<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Caviar Trade Endangers Caspian Sea Sturgeons 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">

<table width=580>
<td>
<br>

<CENTER><B> <FONT SIZE=5>

Caviar Trade Endangers Caspian Sea Sturgeons
<BR>
 
</FONT></B></CENTER><br>
<img src="/graphics/sturgeon.jpg" align=right alt="sturgeon">

<b>GLAND, Switzerland</b> -- Failure to protect  sturgeon fisheries is threatening the species and its  prized byproduct, 
caviar, according to WWF-World Wide Fund for Nature. 
<p>
A new TRAFFIC* report released by WWF quotes experts who believe that world sturgeon populations  could already have declined 
by up to 70 per cent. And most of the damage is being done in the Caspian Sea area, which provides 90 per cent of the world's 
sturgeon catch and caviar.
<p>
WWF has called for urgent steps to regulate sturgeon fisheries in the Caspian Sea and the resulting, often clandestine, trade 
in  caviar. Rampant overfishing and poaching of sturgeon, and illegal production and smuggling of caviar, are causing further 
decline of the threatened fish. 
<p>
"Immediate measures to seriously control the whole industry from fisheries to the consumer are required if the caviar 
industry and sturgeon are to survive," according to Tom De Meulenaer, Director of  TRAFFIC Europe.
<p>
Things have got much worse with the disintegration of the Soviet Union. Before 1991, that country and Iran, the two littoral 
states of the Caspian, tightly controlled the fishery, among the most profitable in the world.  Now five states including 
Iran surround the Caspian Sea, and an absence of fishing restrictions and  enforcement is causing havoc. 
<p>
Fishing is now extensive even on the previously prohibited open sea, often using methods outlawed by the former Soviet 
government.  Some sources claim 90 per cent of the sturgeon catch is illegal. In 1994 alone, Russia detained 1452 poachers 
and confiscated over 110 tonnes of sturgeon and five tonnes of caviar.
<p>
Major caviar importers are the European Union, Japan, the USA and Switzerland. The EU takes half the total amount.  Germany 
is its largest importer and France its largest consumer. There are several indicators of an enormous illicit caviar trade 
from the three poached Caspian Sea sturgeon species. For instance,  in Germany caviar which should be selling at US$700 per 
kilogramme was going for as little as US$150. 
<p>
To halt and reverse this alarming trend, the TRAFFIC report has suggested coordinated management of sturgeon fisheries in the 
Caspian basin, regulations in littoral states governing production of caviar, and trade controls. It also suggests a 
certification scheme for caviar produced from legal and sustainable sturgeon fisheries, and an evaluation of CITES listings 
for Caspian sturgeons. 
<p>
Contact: Bobbie Jo Kelso at +44 1223 277427 or Someshwar Singh at +41 22 364 9553
<p>
<i><sup>*</sup>TRAFFIC is the wildlife trade monitoring programme of WWF and IUCN-World Conservation Union</i>
<p>
</table> <p> <a 
href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
