<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>SWISS GOVERNMENT FOR CONSERVATION- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
For release 10.00 GMT Thursday 7 December 1995<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><H2><CENTER>Swiss Government Gives WWF Fr5 million for Conservation in Russia</CENTER></H2><BR>
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>GENEVA</B>--The Swiss Federal Department for Foreign Affairs
and WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature today signed a Fr5 million
contract for conservation in Russia. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;This is the biggest grant that our department has ever earmarked
for an environmental project in Eastern Europe,&quot; said Remo
Gautschi, Deputy Director of the Swiss Development Cooperation
Office in the Federal Department for Foreign Affairs. &quot;It
is also the largest project that we have so far carried out with
a non-governmental organization.&quot;<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Recent political, social, and economic changes have brought new
threats to Russia's natural heritage. In the past, the state funded
all conservation work, which was generally of a very high quality.
Now, however, there is little money for conservation, and there
is a risk that most of the valuable work carried out in the past
will be undone. Some park officials are abandoning their posts
to take up less skilled but better paid jobs elsewhere. Others
are supplementing their incomes by farming livestock in and around
protected areas.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The strictness of Russia's long-established system of protected
areas or &quot;zapovedniks&quot; is an additional problem. Under
the Soviet regime, people were not allowed to enter these areas
or use the natural resources they contain. This approach tends
to antagonize local communities, and does little to raise their
awareness of conservation issues. There is therefore a need to
develop new conservation methods and attitudes.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The Swiss-funded part of WWF's Russian programme aims to:<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
* secure the long-term protection of the Pechora Ilych forest
reserve in the Komi Republic by 2000
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
* develop a sustainable forest management programme for Pechora
Ilych and help local communities benefit from the forests and
their resources
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
* conduct education and training programmes for conservationists
and foresters
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>more.......</I>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
2
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
* increase public awareness of environmental problems and solutions
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
* develop management plans for protected areas that take into
account new social and economic conditions and the need to seek
funding for protected areas from alternative sources
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
* create a Conservation Fund for Russia to improve management
of protected areas<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;Russia is one of the last countries in the northern hemisphere
where one still finds large areas of virgin forest,&quot; said
Dr Claude Martin, Director General of WWF International. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
He added: &quot;It would be a tragedy if the world were to stand
by and let areas like these forests be destroyed. We cannot let
Russia sell off its natural assets, simply to finance the difficult
and costly process of adjusting to a new political and economic
regime.&quot;<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
WWF opened its Russian Programme Office in Moscow in July 1994.
It currently runs a dozen projects in Russia, ranging from the
Arctic to the Volga delta, and from Kamchatka to the Far East.
Here, WWF is helping to build up anti-poaching brigades to prevent
further killings of animals such as the rare Siberian tiger which
provide prized ingredients of traditional Chinese medicine. Over
the past five years, poachers, in cooperation with organized crime
networks, have slashed the Siberian tiger population from 300-400
to around 200.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
In 1993, WWF joined forces with Russian specialists to compile
a portfolio of 75 priority projects for conservation in Russia.The
Swiss-funded projects were all selected from this document.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;Switzerland's grant is a milestone on the path to the implementation
of the environmental campaign programme for Central and Eastern
Europe decided on by the ministerial conference, Environment for
Europe, in Lucerne at the end of April 1993,&quot; added Gautschi.
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
At the last Environment for Europe conference, held in Sofia in
October this year, Switzerland signed an important &quot;debt
for nature&quot; agreement with Bulgaria.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
ENDS<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For more information contact: Sarah Russell, WWF International,
+41 22 364 9554. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

