<HEAD>
<TITLE>EUROPEAN FOREST CONSERVATION- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Embargo: October 5, 1995<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><H2>
<CENTER>Europe Lags in Forest Conservation, says New WWF Survey</CENTER>
</B></H2>
<BR>
 
<B>ENGLAND, Switzerland</B> -- Most western European governments
are not doing enough to sustainably manage their  forests or to
protect the few remnants of ancient forests, according to the
first of a series of annual surveys of forest conservation in
Europe released today by WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature.<BR>
<BR>
With five different objectives as criteria, the &quot;European
Forest Scorecards&quot; grade the forest policies and performance
of 13 European countries on a scale ranging from A (excellent)
to F (failed). <BR>
<BR>
Of all the countries surveyed -<B>Austria, Belgium, Finland, France,
Germany, Italy, </B>the<B> Netherlands, Norway, Switzerland, Sweden</B>
and the <B>United Kingdom</B>- the <B>Netherlands </B>and <B>Sweden
</B>had the best overall performances.  The first scored high
marks for, among other things, complying with the EU's Habitats
Directive and creating plans to restore some 75,000 hectares of
both public and private forest lands; and <B>Sweden</B>, for having
developed a comprehensive set of inventories as a step towards
protecting its old-growth forests and ensuring adequate management
of forests outside protected areas.<BR>
<BR>
Regarding many of the other countries surveyed, the review says,
&quot;the lack of comprehensive inventories of biologically valuable
forests and the almost complete absence of any structured system
to monitor the effects of forestry on biodiversity&quot; -even
in countries claiming to be conducting sustainable, non-destructive
forest use- &quot;are clear indications of the low priority assigned
to biodiversity issues&quot;.    <BR>
<BR>
The country with the worst performance was <B>Spain</B>, which
lacks reliable data on protected areas, has no clear strategy
for monitoring the impact of forestry on rare plants and animals,
and in addition has not taken adequate steps to reduce emissions
of its forest-damaging sulphur dioxide and other pollutants.<BR>
<BR>
Most of the countries reviewed showed more or less poor performances
which, according to Per Rosenberg, WWF's European Forest Officer,
&quot;reflect the lack of political will to manage forests sustainably.
 Many of these same governments  are often quick to criticize
developing countries for exactly the same reason.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We have started this annual review in the hope that it will
help European policy-makers and conscientious citizens keep track
of the their government's performance and commitment to forest
conservation&quot;, said Rosenberg. <BR>
<BR>
The final scores on a grade scale of A, A-, B+, B, B-, C+, C,
C-, D+, D, D- and F, from best to worst, were:<BR>
<BR>
Austria: C+<BR>
Belgium: C-<BR>
Denmark: C+<BR>
Finland: C<BR>
France: C-<BR>
Germany: C<BR>
Italy: C-<BR>
Netherlands: B-<BR>
Norway: C-<BR>
Spain: D+<BR>
Sweden: B-<BR>
Switzerland: C+<BR>
United Kingdom: C<BR>
<BR>
&quot;On the whole, most countries have a long way to go  before
they fulfill the pledges to sustainability made at the Rio Earth
Summit&quot;, said Rosenberg.<BR>
<BR>
<B>END<BR>
<BR>
</B>For more information or a copy of the survey, please contact
Javier Arreaza, Press Office, WWF International, Tel: +41 22 364
9550 and Fax: +41 22 364 8307.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
