<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Accounting for the Environment
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Relaese">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>

<center><font size=5><B>
Accounting for the Environment
</font></b></center> <P>

<img src="/graphics/economy.jpg" align=right>

<b>MONTREAL, October 18, 1995</b>  -  WWF today called on the World Conservation
Congress
to persuade governments and international institutions to fundamentally
change the way
they currently formulate and implement their economic policies.
<p>
Currently governments and international institutions such as the World Trade
Organisation consider environment in isolation and not as an intrinsic part
of the
economy.  In talking about economic reforms, they focus on efficiency,
competitiveness
and growth without considering the natural resource base which determines
the long
term viability of any economy. 
<p>
According to Mr Fulai Sheng, a senior WWF economist, "This fundamental flaw in
economic thinking will lead to increasingly scarce and degraded natural
resources,
which will cast a pall over any future improvement in the quality of human
life."
<p>
Policy makers need to immediately set-up social and environmental objectives
in their
debates on future economic policy, and change the way economic progress is
measured
by incorporating environmental costs in national accounts.  More important,
the private
sector and civil society should be encouraged to participate in  dialogues
with policy
makers in determining the future. 
<p>
Meanwhile, WWF's trade specialist Charlie Arden-Clarke urged all members of IUCN
to press for an environmental impact assessment of the World Trade
Organisation's
(WTO) Uruguay Round trade agreement and global trade liberalisation. "This
assessment is urgently needed as there is now consensus that trade
liberalisation
damages the environment unless strong environmental policies are
simultaneously put in
place," he added.
<p>
WWF hopes that the combined environmental impact assessments of IUCN members
and individual NGOs will help redirect the implementation of the Uruguay Round
Agreement so its damaging environmental impact is reduced. WWF wants environment
to be on the agenda of all future trade negotiations in the WTO. The trade
organisation's 
processes must generally be more open to environmental officials and the
general public,
if the institution is to produce trade agreements which support sustainable
development.

</td>
 </table> <p> <a href="/graphics/toolbar.map">
<img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
