<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Third Conference of the Biodiversity Convention Ends Without Many Concrete Conservation Results</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">

<table width=580>
<td>
<br>

<CENTER><B> <FONT SIZE=5>

Third Conference of the Biodiversity Convention Ends Without Many Concrete Conservation Results
<BR>
 
</FONT></B></CENTER><br>
<img src="/graphics/biodiversity.jpg" align=right alt="sunset" hspace=5>

<b>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina</b> -- While the Third Conference of the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) came to an end 
on November 15 in Buenos Aires, WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature considers that much of the excellent rhetoric put forward by 
visiting ministers was not translated into action by their civil servants at the negotiating table.
<p>
"The right words were spoken by Ministers but they have not been matched by commitment to action in the working sessions of 
the meeting. Negotiators have not shown the will necessary to get the main objectives of the Convention implemented," said 
Gordon Shepherd, Director of International Policy at WWF. "Some of the countries that gave the best speeches were also among 
the most efficient at blocking many substantial proposals."
<p>
In all, some 1,500 delegates have attended the conference, which was addressed on Wednesday by President Carlos Saul Menem of 
Argentina. President Menem stressed in his speech the importance of putting an end to the pollution and destruction of the 
environment, and the urgent need to slow down and eventually stop the wrongful depletion of the Earth's natural resources. 
"However, this call by the President doesn't seem to have been heard by the Conference," stressed Mr Shepherd.
<p>
One of the major disappointments of the Conference was its inability to establish a concrete programme of work for the 
conservation of forests, which contain about 70-90 percent of the world's terrestrial biodiversity. "Instead of assuming its 
natural role in the conservation of these essential ecosystems, the CBD decided to postpone for another 18 months taking a 
decision on what it will do with regards to forests," said Mr Shepherd. "How can we know if it's going to take a decision then?"
<p>
Conservation experts have calculated that, at the present rate of deforestation, some 50 million hectares of forests could be 
destroyed around the world between now and May 1998, when the Convention is to meet again. This area equals abut one and a 
half times all the forests in Argentina.
<p>
Minimal progress was made on the issue of how the rights of indigenous peoples will be recognized and how their traditional 
knowledge will be protected in the implementation of the Convention. However, the only commitment made by the Conference is 
to hold a five-day meeting to discuss indigenous peoples issues sometime between now and May 1998.
<p>
On the positive side, the Convention agreed to include protected areas as a priority theme to follow up implementation at the 
national level. Also, the Convention decided to incorporate into its sphere of action the issues of pesticide reduction and 
the conservation of wild sources of food.


<p>
</table> <p> <a 
href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
