(1994), Top 150 Listing, <I>Pulp and Paper International</I>,
9/1995, Belgium (Ranking is made on the basis of earnings rather
than total sales)
<P>
<HR WIDTH=510>
<BR>

<P>
The paper and board industry remains confident about
the potential for further expansion in the future. Use doubled
worldwide between 1975 and 1991, and FAO predictions suggest that
total pulp consumption will grow by 3 per cent per year between
1989 and 2010. Some FAO estimates are given below in Table 3.
However, a recent downturn in the trade may mean that these figures
are overestimates, and there has been a (probably temporary) downturn
in some former Soviet bloc countries such as Romania. The pulp
industry in former Yugoslavia is also in disarray. On the other
hand, pulp industries in Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary
have all developed since the introduction of a market economy.
Use declined during the early 1990s in some developing countries
due to devaluations and economic reforms, as was the case in Venezuela,
and in Chile where several planned new pulp mills have been put
on hold.<BR>

<P>
<B>Currently the most rapid rate of increase in pulp
and paper use is in Newly Industrialised Countries such as South
Korea, Taiwan, Brazil and Chile.<BR>
</B>
<P>
For example, in South Korea, demand for imports and
production of paper both increased by 12-13 per cent towards the
end of the 1980s, making it one of the world's most rapidly expanding
pulp markets. The 1990s have also seen a rapid proliferation of
pulp mills in Latin America, particularly in Chile, which has
resulted in the region's share of the top 150 market pulp production
rising from 5.1 per cent in 1991 to 10.3 per cent in 1992. In
1994, paper and board production in Thailand grew by over 27 per
cent, and by 17.5 per cent in Indonesia. However, on a global
scale the continued dominance by the North makes these changes
relatively insignificant. Whilst paper production in Africa increased
by 70 per cent in the 1980s, Africa's total production remains
only 3.5 per cent that of the United States and 20 African states
have no paper-making industry at all.<BR>

<P>
<B>Table 3: Pulp and Paper Capacities<BR>
