<HEAD>

<TITLE>GORILLA KILLINGS IN ZAIRE- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>
 
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

For Urgent release:  August 18, 1995<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua"><H2>
<CENTER>New Gorilla Killings in Zaire</CENTER>
</H2> 
<BR>
</FONT></B>
 
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">GLAND, Switzerland</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">
-- The International Gorilla Conservation Programme (IGCP) and
the Institute Zairois pour la Conservation de la Nature (IZCN)
today confirmed poachers recently killed two adult mountain gorillas
at the Virunga National Park in eastern Zaire.  The new deaths
raise the number of mountain gorillas poached in 1995 to seven.
This follows a ten-year period in which no gorillas were killed.
<BR>
<BR>
According to park staff, the two gorillas were killed at about
2:30 pm on August 13, 1995, only a few hours after they were last
seen by tourists.  The motive of the killings is unknown. IZCN
is investigating the identity of the poachers.  <BR>
<BR>
The dead gorillas -- a male and a female -- were discovered on
August 14 by a tour guide who reported the matter to park authorities.
 Both animals, who were not shy of human beings, had been shot
through the heart.  The male's group had been followed on a daily
basis for the last ten years. The dead female's baby has been
adopted by another gorilla.<BR>
<BR>
The Virunga volcanos are a system of contiguous national parks
in Zaire, Uganda and Rwanda.  The Virunga National Park contains
about 300 mountain gorillas. They constitute half of the world's
remaining mountain gorillas.<BR>
<BR>
For a decade no poaching was reported either in the Virungas or
at Bwindi National Park, Uganda, which contains the rest of the
gorillas.  The deaths come only one week after the silverback
Salama was found dead in Bukima, Zaire, a month after he had gone
missing.  Four gorillas were found dead at Bwindi in March this
year.   For a total world population of just over 600, this is
a significant loss.  The death of a silverback has particularly
serious implications. Its group's unity and composition is severely
affected.<BR>
<BR>
The International Gorilla Conservation Programme (IGCP) is a joint
programme between the African Wildlife Foundation, Fauna and Flora
International and the World Wide Fund For Nature.  Established
in 1991, the IGCP works towards ensuring the conservation of gorillas
and afro-montane and medium altitude forest habitats in Rwanda,
Uganda and Zaire.<BR>
<BR>
<B>        -END-<BR>
<BR>
</B>For more information contact Javier Arreaza at +41 22 364
9550.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

