<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WWF NETWORK OPENS NEW AUTONOMOUS ORGANIZATION IN BRAZIL
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>
<p>
<center>
<font size=4><b>
WWF NETWORK OPENS NEW AUTONOMOUS ORGANIZATION IN BRAZIL
</b>
</font>
</center>
<p>
<b>GLAND, Switzerland</b> -- The World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF), one of the largest conservation organizations, which  invests 
US$ 5 million a year in conservation programs in Brazil, has now an autonomous organization in that South American country.
<p>
The first board of directors took office on August 30. It includes environmentalists, businessmen and representatives of 
other sectors of the Brazilian society. WWF Brazil board's first President is Jose Roberto Marinho, an entrepreneurial 
businessman with a strong interest in the environment and a director of the largest media network in Brazil (Globo).
<p>
Mario Augusto Frering (CAEMI holding) and Paulo Nogueira Neto (member of WWF International Special Advisers Group) were 
appointed Vice-Presidents. Other members include: Jose Pedro de Oliveira Costa  (Atlantic Forest Biosphere Reserve 
Consortium),   Joseph Safra (Safra Bank), Luiz Fernando Levy (Financial Newspaper),  Maria Christina de Carvalho Pinto 
(Advertising Agency),  Roberto Paulo Cezar de Andrade (BRASCAN holding), and Roberto Rodrigues (Agricultural business).  Garo 
Batmanian was confirmed in the post of Executive Director.
<p>
With the establishment of this autonomous National unit, WWF-Brazil is now able to give the necessary attention to the 
conservation problems in Brazil. Also, it will make possible to leverage the results of the projects already developed for 
broader conservation impact. 
<p>
WWF is active in Brazil since 1971. During these 25 years it has developed about 350 conservation projects, most of all in 
partnership with regional non-governmental organizations and government agencies of all levels.
<p>
Some 40 projects are currently being implemented in the country, ranging from scientific research, field projects, 
legislation, public policies, to environmental education and communications.
<p>
Apart from being one of the few megadiversity countries, housing about 10 percent of the world's biodiversity, Brazil is 
emerging as a leading country in the environmental debate, particularly in fora like WTO and ITTO.  Brazil is also a focal 
country for the Latin American Free Trade Market (Mercosur) and host country of the Rio 92 Earth Summit and "Rio plus 5" (the 
NGO preparatory conference for the Earth Summit Review, scheduled for 1997). 



</table>
<p>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
</BODY>
