<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>GREEN LABELLING- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>

 </HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=2>For release Friday 23 June 1995<BR>
<BR>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Impact"><H2><CENTER>Future of Green Labelling at Stake
in Oslo, Warns WWF</CENTER></H2><BR>
<BR>
</FONT>OSLO, Norway</B>--A meeting of the International Organization
for Standardization (ISO) could permanently undermine the credibility
of eco-labels on products, warned WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature
today.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There are clear signs that the ISO could next week adopt
policies that will allow producers to stick green labels on products
that are actually a dirty shade of grey,&quot; said Charles Arden-Clarke,
Policy Analyst at WWF.<BR>
<BR>
As consumers become more aware of the damaging effects of deforestation
and chemical pollution, more and more people are seeking out &quot;green&quot;
products which do relatively little harm to the environment. Market-sensitive
producers are responding by putting labels on their products testifying
to their environmental credentials. Even cigarette packets carry
symbols signifying that they can be recycled.<BR>
<BR>
But how reliable are those labels? It is hard to tell. In an effort
to clarify the situation, the ISO is now working to set international
standards for eco-labelling which could provide just the green
seal of approval the eco-consumer needs. They could, however,
do the very opposite.<BR>
<BR>
This is partly because the ISO is developing certificates that
are more likely to confuse consumers than enlighten them. The
organization has recently extended its focus from assessing products
(developing international standards for film speeds, etc.) to
examining the way companies are managed. So instead of developing
standards that gauge the environmental impact of products, the
ISO is focusing on companies' &quot;environmental management systems&quot;
-- i.e. how well buildings are insulated, how much recycled paper
is used, etc.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This focus on management systems is extremely worrying,&quot;
said Jean-Paul Jeanrenaud, WWF's Senior Forest Policy Officer,
&quot;Particularly in the light of a recent Canadian attempt to
get the ISO to establish an environmental management standard
for 'sustainable forestry' rather than adopt a standard for forest
products themselves.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
There is currently nothing to stop producers putting ISO certificates
on products that simply testify the quality of their environmental
management systems. But purchasers are likely to mistake these
certificates for a guarantee of a product's greenness. <BR>
<I>more.....<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</I>2<BR>
<BR>
Another problem is that the ISO may fail to make improving the
environment one of its explicit goals when setting eco-labelling
standards. A number of industry-led delegations are arguing against
including any reference to securing environmental improvement
from eco-labelling.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If the ISO is not careful, it could end up making eco-labels
totally meaningless,&quot; warned Arden-Clarke. &quot;This would
deprive the world of an extremely potent conservation tool, and
could even undermine the credibility of the ISO.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
-ENDS-<BR>
<BR>
ISO Technical Committee 207 Environmental Management meets at
the Radisson SASS Scandinavia Hotel, Oslo from 24 June to 1 July.
<BR>
<BR>
The ISO is a federation of national standards bodies. It aims
to promote the standardization of goods and services and thus
to facilitate international cooperation.<BR>
<BR>
The ISO is a private organization. Its standards are not legally
enforceable: producers volunteer and pay to be inspected and certified.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>For more information contact Charles Arden-Clarke on +41 22
364 9513 or Sarah Russell on +41 22 364 9574.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

