<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>UN CONFERENCE- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<A NAME="OLE_LINK4">FOR RELEASE: 27 March 1995 6/95<BR>
</A>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B> <H2><CENTER>UN Conference Crucial to Halting Fish Wars</CENTER></H2> <BR>
 </B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>GLAND, Switzerland</B> &#173;&#173; WWF-World Wide Fund For
Nature warned today that the world's fish populations will continue
to decline unless governments cooperate to control overfishing.

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The concern on overfishing was voiced at a joint briefing by several
NGO's in New York, at the start of the UN Conference on Straddling
Fish Stocks and Highly Migratory Fish Stocks (March 27- April
12, 1995). <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;This UN conference offers a vital opportunity to improve
the management of the global fishery resource that must not be
squandered,&quot; said Michael Sutton, head of WWF's International
Fisheries Campaign. &quot;The Canadian-Spanish row is just an
example of the 'gunboat diplomacy' that reigns on account of the
widespread, chronic unsustainable use of world fisheries.&quot;
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Governments have had over eight months, since the August 1994
session, to consider the Draft Agreement which is supposed to
conserve and sustain world fisheries and resolve conflicts among
nations. The final session of the Conference is to be held in
August 1995. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;Decades of short&#173;sighted overfishing has resulted in
devastated fish populations and thrown marine ecosystems out of
balance,&quot; Mr. Sutton added. &quot;The plight of unemployed
fishermen and fish-factory workers has helped fuel international
tensions. We're going to have to come to grips with global overfishing
if we hope to avoid future confrontations on the high seas.&quot;
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
A report released earlier this month by the UN Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) concluded that 70 percent of the world's fish
stocks are overfished. WWF maintains that a 'sea change' is necessary
in the way marine fisheries are managed, shifting the focus from
development and expansion to conservation and sustainable use
of these important resources.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
In addition, the future of millions of people in coastal communities,
who depend on fish for survival, needs to be ensured.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
At the UN Conference, WWF has been pushing for a strong, legally-binding
and conservation-minded treaty. The treaty could reverse the widespread
decline of world fisheries and advance new international norms
and minimum standards for sustainable world fisheries.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
-End-<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For more information, please call Yael Bradbury at +1 202-778-9536
or Cherry Farrow at +44 483 426 444 or Someshwar Singh at +41
22 3649573.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
