<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Joint Statement on the Knowledge, Innovations and Practices of Indigenous People and Local Communities
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/position.gif" alt="WWF Position Statement">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>
<br>

<CENTER><B> <FONT SIZE=5>Joint Statement on the Knowledge, Innovations and Practices of Indigenous People and Local 
Communities<BR> </FONT></B></CENTER>


<P>
<P>
<img src="/graphics2/indogirls.jpg" alt="Indonesian girls" align=right>

CoP.3 will address the implementation of Article 8(j), related to the knowledge, innovation and practices of indigenous and 
local communities, embodying traditional lifestyles relevant to conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity.
<p>
WWF adopted, in May 1996, a Statement of Principles for partnership with indigenous peoples in conserving biodiversity within 
indigenous lands and territories, and promoting the sustainable use of natural resources. The statement is the result of a 
process of consultation within WWF and with indigenous peoples' organizations.
<p>
The outcome of SBSTTA.2 in this matter proved the urgent need to promote and facilitate an open-ended mechanism under the 
Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD). Under such a mechanism the issues pertaining to the CBD's implementation related to 
indigenous peoples and local communities can be discussed and advanced in a proper manner. It has to be noted that not only 
Article 8(j) but several other provisions of the CBD are relevant to the role and interests of indigenous peoples and local 
communities, such as those related to in situ conservation, environmental impact assessment, access to genetic resources, 
incentives, capacity building, etc. 
<p>
In addition, there is a need for better coordination of the different, existing international initiatives on indigenous 
peoples which are relevant to the CBD's implementation.
<p>
WWF calls on the Parties at CoP.3 to:
<ul type circle>

<li> establish an intersessional open-ended working group on indigenous and local communities, to advance work on Article 8(j) 
and other provisions of the CBD relevant to those peoples and communities.
</ul>
<p>
This working group, which should include the participation of indigenous and community organizations, would carry out its 
duties at least until future CoPs review again the status of implementation of Article 8(j), and would establish the 
appropriate linkages with other relevant processes, bodies, and mechanisms, including the UN Working Group on Indigenous 
Populations.
<p>
As a practical way of promoting and facilitating coordination of the different existing international initiatives on 
indigenous peoples in various fields, this intersessional working group should bring together at its first meeting all those 
relevant institutions and initiatives working on indigenous and community issues relevant to the objectives of the CBD. They 
should be invited to prepare and present at the intersessional meeting a summary report of their actions, plans and 
proposals, so as to ease coordination and synergy.
<p>
<b>WWF suggests that the terms of reference for the proposed working group include inter alia the following elements:</b>
<ul type circle>
<p>
<li> Article 8(j)
<p>
<li> the role of indigenous and local communities in in situ conservation, particularly the establishment and management of 
protected areas
<p>
<li> access to genetic resources
<p>
<li> incentive measures and benefit sharing
<p>
<li> environmental impact assessments in indigenous and community lands
<p>
<li> capacity building for indigenous and local communities.
</ul>
<p>
<b>In defining the terms of reference for this working group, the CoP.3  should:</b>
<ul type circle>
<p>
<li> consider issues concerning indigenous and local communities not only in terms of the specific contents of Article 8(j), but 
in the wider context of the objectives of the CBD
<p>
<li> take note of other international processes where the broader issue of indigenous peoples' rights is being dealt with. The 
CBD could in this sense acknowledge the efforts of the international community aimed at addressing the situation of 
indigenous peoples worldwide. Both the human rights process and the CBD (and other environmental instruments relevant to the 
issue) should be mutually supportive for the benefit of indigenous peoples, and for a better achievement of conservation purposes
<p>
<li> acknowledge the fact that land- and resource-use rights are the basis for the maintenance and development of indigenous 
knowledge, innovations and practices, and that the CBD's efforts to protect and preserve these could be unsuccessful if such 
rights were not recognized and ensured. Thus, it is in the interest of achieving the objectives of the CBD that Parties 
should adopt clear commitments to contribute to an appropriate recognition and respect of indigenous peoples' rights to land 
and resource use
<p>
<li> adopt two fundamental principles in developing and implementing the CBD: the right of indigenous peoples to determine 
sustainable development priorities for the territories they traditionally occupy or use; and free, prior informed consent. 
Conservation or sustainable use activities carried out in indigenous peoples' territories in the context of implementing the 
CBD should be consistent with these principles.
</ul>


</table> <p> <a 
href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
