<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Biodiversity Convention Fails to Act on Forests
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">

<table width=580>
<td>
<br>

<CENTER><B> <FONT SIZE=5>

Biodiversity Convention Fails to Act on Forests
<BR>
 
</FONT></B></CENTER><br>
<img src="/graphics/bioforest.jpg" align=right alt="forest" hspace=5>

<b>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina</b> -- At a late November 11 session of the Third Conference of the Parties to the 
Convention on Biodiversity (CBD), an inter-governmental working group systematically rejected any substantial proposals for 
urgent action to conserve and sustainably use the world's forests, WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature warned on Tuesday, November 
12. According to WWF, the group even failed to agree on a priority list of critical research activites proposed by their own 
scientific advisory group. 
<p>
"It is incredible that the Governments have failed to agree to take serious action in spite of the fact that next June the 
Convention on Biodiversity passes its fifth anniversary and is subject to a five-year review by the Commission on Sustainable 
Development", said Nancy Vallejo, Biodiversity Treaties Officer at WWF.  "This should be an occasion for both celebration as 
the Convention comes of age and satisfaction that it has demonstrated its relevance to the next century" she said.
<p>
The conservation organization said in a statement that "when it comes to conservation priorities there can  be no more 
important issue than forests."
<p>
Yet after five years of meetings the Government members of the Convention have not even agreed a programme of work on 
forests, in spite of the facts that terrestrial biodiversity is a priority for its work and that 70 - 90% of Biodiversity is 
in forests 
<p>
"Before these Governments make a decision on a programme of work at the next Conference of the Parties, more than 50,000,000 
hectares of forest will be lost as current rates of deforestation continue" said Steve Howard, WWF Forest Conservation 
Officer. "This is equivalent to one and a half times the total forest  cover of Argentina.  In fact, it is estimated that the 
rate of deforestation of some of the world's key forest eco-systems has increased by more than one third since 1992", he said.
<p>
Ms. Vallejo pointed out that it is still not too late for Governments to accept their responsibilities in the last days of 
the conference by reversing the working group decision and  committing to a concrete  programme of work to save the world's 
forests. The Conference should agree to a work programme of implementation of the CBD including:
<ul type circle>
<li>Comprehensive  rehabilitation and restoration of representative forest ecosystems.<p>
<li>Conservation and sustainable use of forests<p>
<li>Inclusion of indigenous peoples and local communities in decision making and recognition of their traditional rights.<p>
<li>Establishment of a system of incentives for forest conservation.<p>
<li>Mandating Parties to act immediately on these issues and to report on progress at the next COP.<p>
</ul>


<p>
</table> <p> <a 
href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
</BODY>
