<HEAD>
<TITLE>World's First Transfrontier Marine Turtle Sanctuary</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>


<P>
<center>

<H2>World's First Transfrontier Marine Turtle Sanctuary</H2>


</center>
<P>

<B>GLAND, Switzerland</B> --  Malaysian Foreign Minister HE Datuk Abdullah
Haji Ahmad Badawi and Philippines Foreign Minister HE Domingo
L Siazon  today signed an agreement in Manila establishing the
world's first transborder conservation area for marine turtles.
The Turtle Islands Heritage Protected Area is also the first transborder
marine protected area in ASEAN (Association of South East Asian
Nations). 
<P>
WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature, with funding from the MacArthur
Foundation, has been working with both governments since 1994
to establish the protected area.  Other collaborators include
Malaysia's Sabah Parks Office and the Philippines Department of
Environment and Natural Resources,  whose support and dedication
made this sanctuary possible. 

<P>
&quot;We congratulate both governments for establishing this protected
area for marine turtles,&quot; said Mr Dawood Ghaznavi, Asia/Pacific
Programme Director at WWF International. &quot;Considering the
highly migratory nature of turtles, this transborder protected
area will help ensure the successful conservation of the endangered
green and hawksbill turtles that frequent and traverse these islands.&quot;
 takes into account implementation of a joint marine turtle
resource management programme and human resources development
programme for sanctuary staff, besides ecotourism plans.

<P>
With bilateral formalities completed, WWF hopes actual conservation
work  in the area can begin. It will help both governments to
develop a joint management plan for the sanctuary, prepare an
ecotourism development and management plan, and introduce sustainable
income generating schemes, some taking advantage of the area's
abundant untapped fisheries.           

<P><font size=-1>
For more information, contact Chng Soh Koon in Switzerland at
tel: +41-22 364 9326, Romy Trono in the Philippines at tel: +63-2
924 3937 or Sabri Zain in Malaysia at tel: +60-3 757 9192. 
</font>

<P>

<br>

</blockquote>

<center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" 
border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For 
Nature</i></h6></center>


