<HTML>
<HEAD>
 
<TITLE>FORGOTTEN ELEPHANTS- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>ATTENTION: <U>EMBARGOED until November 9, 1995 <BR>
</U></B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><CENTER><H2>Asia's Forgotten Elephant's in Need of Help, says WWF</H2></CENTER></B> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>GLAND, Switzerland</B> -- Asian elephants are being devastated
by human activities which have destroyed huge tracts of habitat
and shrunk the elephant's range to a tiny fragment of what it
was 50 years ago, according to a species status report released
today by WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The report by Elizebeth Kemf and Peter Jackson <I>Asian Elephants
in the Wild</I> says that the &quot;forgotten&quot; elephants
of Asia are being quietly squeezed out of the most densely populated
region of the world. Unchecked logging, habitat clearing for agriculture
and ill-planned development have driven elephants from their forest
home and resulted in an unprecedented spate of human-elephant
conflict. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;The entire population of Asian elephants is about 10 percent
of the total African elephant population&quot;, said author Elizebeth
Kemf, Species Conservation Coordinator at WWF. &quot;Yet, their
population is even more fragmented and vulnerable. The primary
threat to Asian elephants is habitat loss - one of the toughest
and most expensive conservation problems to solve.&quot; 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
According to the report, &quot;clearance of forests for settlement
and agriculture is disrupting traditional elephant migration routes
and leading to violent clashes between people and elephants when
hungry elephants raid crops.&quot; In India alone, as many as
300 people have died in the course of a year as a result of these
people-elephant clashes. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Asian elephants once roamed from modern Iraq and Syria to the
Yellow River in China. Today they only survive from India to Vietnam,
with a very small population in the extreme southwest of China's
Yunnan Province. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Around a half of the estimated Asian elephant population (between
35,000 and 50,000) is found in India where poaching of males for
ivory is severely damaging the sex ratio, particularly in the
South. In Vietnam, the elephant population has declined by 75
per cent over the last 25 years to between 300-400 individuals.
The once widespread population in China has been reduced to between
150-300 elephants. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Little is known about the status of elephant populations in other
range countries, such as Myanmar (Burma), Laos PDR and Cambodia,
where protection for wildlife is minimal. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
WWF warns the Asian elephant will not survive without concerted
efforts to halt the assault on its habitat and resolve the escalating
people-elephant conflict. The organization has conservation projects
in several of the elephant-range states but much more is needed
to ensure coordinated and concerted efforts to save the species.

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;The relationship between people and elephants is so unique
that the animal has become at times a sacred and beloved deity,&quot;
said Ms Kemf. &quot;The growing conflict between humans and elephants
is one of the most tragic and urgent challenges facing governments
in Asia. Conservation programmes which reconcile the needs of
elephants and people are of the utmost priority.&quot; 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
-END- <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;Asian elephants in the Wild&quot;, by Elizabeth Kemf and
Peter Jackson, a new WWF status report on Asian elephants, is
available on request from Javier Arreaza at WWF International,
tel. +41 22 364 9550. Ms Elizabeth Kemf, one of the report's authors,
is available for interview at WWF International on +41 22 364
9424 on November 9. <BR><BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

