<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> ILLICIT WHALE MEAT TRADE- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif">
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
For Immediate Release 12 May 1995<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><H2>
<CENTER>WWF Warns of Major Loopholes for Illicit Whale Meat Trade in Japan</CENTER>
</H2></B>
<BR>
 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
There are serious loopholes aiding smuggling and laundering illegal
whale meat in Japan where prices have reached up to $500 per kilo,
according to a recent investigation funded by WWF.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The survey carried out in East Asia by TRAFFIC, WWF's wildlife
trade monitoring programme, found whale meat widely available
in Japan. Traders claimed the meat came from Bryde's and pilot
whales, as well as the minke whales which Japan continues to hunt
under the guise of &quot;scientific&quot; whaling. Japan's last
official Bryde's whale hunt took place in 1987 when 317 were killed.
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Whale meat, a speciality food in Japan, was found on sale in 51
premises in 13 cities surveyed. Most merchants claimed their meat
came from minke whales killed by Japan's &quot;scientific&quot;
whaling programme. However, one outlet also advertised Bryde's
whale skin and fat while another, in a Tokyo wholesale market,
claimed its meat came from pilot whales.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The TRAFFIC investigators purchased 53 samples of whale meat for
future DNA analysis to determine the species of origin. Duration
of freezing would also have to be proven to establish if whale
meat other than minke came from legal stocks. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Japan holds legal frozen stocks of more than eight cetacean species,
leaving a serious potential loophole for laundering illegal whale
meat. It is also possible that illegal whale meat is chopped into
small pieces and sold as legally-taken small cetaceans. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;This report underscores the potential massive problems in
controlling trade in whale meat,&quot; said Cassandra Phillips,
WWF's Cetacean and Antarctic Officer. &quot;There is clearly a
huge financial incentive to smuggle and launder whale meat in
Japan because of the sky-high prices.&quot; <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
TRAFFIC also noted an ongoing illegal domestic trade in whale
meat in South Korea. In April this year, baleen whale meat was
found openly on sale at several market stalls in the southern
port city of Pusan, in contravention of Korean law. South Korea
has also been linked to a number of cases of illegal whale meat
shipments to Japan - including 11 tons seized by Nagasaki Customs
officials in 1994.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR> 
No whale meat was found on sale in Taiwan where all cetacean catches,
including incidental ones, have been illegal since 1990. 
<BR>
However, one dolphin was noted for sale in the port of Donggang.
Taiwan has been linked to numerous whale meat smuggling incidents
in Japan.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
TRAFFIC found minimal demand for whale meat in China and Hong
Kong, but recommended further investigation of consumption within
China's Japanese community, and the possible role of Hong Kong
as an entrepot in the illegal trade in whale meat.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
- Ends -<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>For more information, or a copy of the Report &quot;Observations
on the Whale Meat Trade in East Asia&quot;, please contact Lucy
Farmer on +44 1483 412335.<BR>
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>NOTE TO EDITORS</B>:<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#168;</FONT>The International Whaling Commission
meets in Dublin between 29 May and 2 June.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#168;</FONT>Taiwan is not a member of the
IWC. South Korea acceded to the UN Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species in 1993. All of the great whales are
banned from international commercial trade by CITES, in alignment
with the IWC's moratorium on commercial whaling. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#168;</FONT>Japan killed 330 minke whales
in the Southern Ocean sanctuary in 1995 and has killed a total
of 2,419 minke whales in the Antarctic since the moratorium entered
into force in 1986.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#168;</FONT>Japan caught a total of 111,297
cetaceans between 1990 and 1993, including over 71,609 Dall's
porpoises.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#168;</FONT>Between 1980 and 1991, Japan
imported a total of 123,955 tons of whale.<BR>
<BR>
<BR> 
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

