<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WWF LOOKS TO NEW ARCTIC COUNCIL  FOR INCREASED PROTECTION OF ARCTIC ENVIRONMENT
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Relaese">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>

<center><font size=5><B>WWF Looks to New Arctic Council for Increased Protection of Arctic Environment</B></font></center>
<P>
<img src="/graphics/arctic2.jpg" align=right>
<b>TORONTO, Canada</b> -- The Arctic Council, which is being inaugurated today in Ottawa, has the potential to ensure that 
environmental protection becomes a priority for all Arctic nations, according to the WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature. 
<p>

Bringing together representatives of the governments of Canada, Denmark, Finland, Iceland, Norway, the Russian Federation, 
Sweden and the United States, the Arctic Council is designed to promote co-operation on issues regarding environmental 
protection and sustainable development in the world's Arctic region.  
<p>
A key task will be to implement the Arctic Environmental Protection Strategy which had its origins in a meeting of Arctic 
Environmental Ministers in Rovaniemi, Finland in 1991.  WWF will closely monitor the Council's activities and work with its 
members to ensure Arctic environmental protection is strengthened. 
<p>
WWF applauds this initiative and looks forward to working constructively with the Arctic Council.  The timing of its 
formation is especially critical for Canada, as the Central Arctic has just undergone major mineral staking - including 
diamond mining - which stands to impact greatly on the people and the wildlife that inhabit the area. 
<p>
"We hope that the Arctic Council will work towards sustainable development driven by sound ecological principles," said Monte 
Hummel, President of WWF Canada.  "For example, the Arctic Council should promote planning that considers the cumulative 
impact o f development activities, as well as an ecologically representative network of protected areas established at the 
same time, and not after development takes place."
<p>
WWF will monitor the Arctic Council closely and work with it on issues of strengthening its commitment to the Arctic 
Environmental Protection Strategy; assuring the full participation of northern indigenous peoples; and being open to the 
participation of all stakeholders in protecting the world's Arctic. 
<p>
For further information, please contact Judi Levita at +1 416 489 4567, #276. WWF's Arctic Programme was established in 1992 
and is based at WWF Norway in Oslo.  Dr Peter Prokosch, Coordinator of WWF's Arctic Programme may be reached at 
+47-22203777/4/5 or by e-mail at (peterp@oslonett.no).  WWF is known as World Wildlife Fund in the USA and Canada.  



 </table> <p> <a href="/graphics/toolbar.map">
<img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
