<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>ARABIAN ORYX NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>

 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
For Immediate Release: 4 April, 1995<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><CENTER><H2>Arabian Oryx Makes a Comeback</H2></CENTER></CENTER></B> <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Gland, Switzerland</B> -- The Saudi government has successfully
introduced 23 captive bred Arabian oryx, considered extinct in
the late sixties, into the animal's former habitat, WWF - World
Wide Fund for Nature has announced. Its previous home was the
unforgiving terrain of the Rub'al-Khali or Empty Quarter, the
largest and most uninhabitable desert in the Arabian Peninsula
with rocky escarpments and large sand dunes.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The release took place at an impressive ceremony in the recently
created 'Uruq Bani Ma'arid Protected Area of the Rub'al-Khali
on March 28, 1995. It was attended by Second Deputy Premier Prince
Sultan Bin Abdulaziz, numerous royalty, and Dr Claude Martin,
Director General World Wide Fund For Nature representing the international
conservation community.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The animals were the descendants of four oryx initially presented
by the then late King Abdulaziz to WWF in 1963, to strengthen
the world herd for breeding in captivity. Some sand gazelle (<I>Gazella
subguttorosa marica</I>) were also released simultaneously. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
In the parched, undulating sands of the Arabian desert, the Arabian
Oryx (<I>Oryx leucoryx</I>) has always been part of local culture
and mythology. Huge numbers ranged through what is present day
peninsular Saudi Arabia, especially in the Rub'al-Khali. But in
the last century, the animal fell upon hard times.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
With modernisation and industrialisation, the local people turned
their back on traditional customs which regulated their rights
to graze so that livestock was protected. They began overhunting
and overexploiting the limited resources in a harsh environment.
The effects on wildlife were devastating. As a result many animals
came close to extinction.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The Arabian Oryx was particularly hard hit. From a healthy population
in the middle of the nineteenth century, its numbers began to
rapidly diminish. By 1960 only about 100 to 200 individuals were
left in the Empty Quarter. By 1969 the animal was considered extinct.
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
That it didn't die out completely is a tribute to the Saudi royal
family. Several distinguished members made a determined effort
to breed at least a few animals in captivity. But it was a struggle.
Now perhaps the tide is turning.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
As Dr Martin remarked on the occasion, ''Today the world is faced
with environmental degradation on a global scale. We need more
examples of such successful schemes. It will send a message of
hope to those who are succeeding us on this planet, and are desperately
looking for solutions to the world's problems.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
''Such messages of hope are as important for the urban youth as
they are for the local communities whose livelihood directly depends
on fertile soils, freshwater resources, and wild plants and animals,''
he added. ''Without their involvement and active participation,
conservation has become unthinkable.''<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
......2<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The released animals went through a tough screening process. They
were selected from different genetic lineages to maximise the
genetic diversity of the oryx population. Any animals showing
showing strong physical or behavioural abnormality were excluded.
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
All the animals were vaccinated against a whole range of diseases.
Long acting tranquilisers were used to relax the animals while
loading and transporting them. Then the animals were airlifted,
finally trucked to their desert home, and set free. This was the
moment many people in Saudi Arabia had waited many years for.
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For some time, there has been a large scale, national level, captive
breeding programme for the oryx. Two Research Centres of the National
Commission for Wildlife Conservation and Development (NCWCD) have
succeeded in captive breeding. They are the King Khalid Research
Centre near Riyadh, and the National Wildlife Research Centre
(NWRC), Taif. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The oryx breeding programme at the NWRC was started with animals
from the late King Khalid's collection. Despite many difficulties,
it succeeded in establishing a sizeable breeding herd of over
two hundred individuals. They include third generation hand-reared
animals. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The reintroduction of the oryx is part of a much wider programme
to restore some of Saudi Arabia's diverse natural habitat and
wildlife populations. A System Plan of Protected Areas, established
with IUCN (World Conservation Union) assistance, is already in
place. This plan has identified 56 terrestrial and over 50 marine
reserves to be established in ten years.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The protected area where the oryx have been released is in the
western extension of the vast and unique Rub' al-Khali desert.
It is characterised by a variety of landscapes including valleys,
plains, besides sand dunes with interdunal corridors and mountains.
This 11,000 square kilometre area has an amazing diversity of
plant species. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The area's natural barriers provide a relatively inaccessible
habitat, well suited for the restoration of the target species.
Given that legislation to prevent hunting for five years in the
Empty Quarter has been passed, the combination of regulations
and inaccessibility should work towards restoration of the reintroduced
species and habitat.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For their part, ''international conservation organisations like
WWF will do their utmost to support Saudi Arabia in its process
to further conservation on the peninsula,'' according to Dr Martin.
''This may include the establishment of a regional strategy for
the conservation of migratory species, including the Houbara bustard
in its Asian range, and the adoption and implementation of CITES,
the Bonn Convention and the Biodiversity Convention.''<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The successful oryx project is fine proof of Saudi Arabia's determination
to restore and maintain its biological diversity. And is yet another
way of making the desert bloom. Ends. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For more information, please contact: Arun Chacko at WWF International.Phone:
41-22-3649566. Fax: 41-22-3648307.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

