<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Fisheries Crisis Overshadows World Oceans Day</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

 
 
<P>

<center>

<H2>
Fisheries Crisis Overshadows World Oceans Day
</H2>

<B><FONT SIZE=4>WWF Unveils Action Plan to Save Marine Fishes</FONT></B>
</center>

<P>

<B>GLAND, Switzerland</B> -- WWF-World Wide Fund for Nature today
released a 10-point action plan aimed at reversing the crisis
in marine fisheries and restoring abundant seas.  This prescription
could help revitalise the marine ecosystem and save millions of
jobs in coastal communities around the world.

<P>

<img src="/graphics/fisheriesbig.jpg" align=right>

On the eve of World Oceans Day, WWF published <U>Marine Fishes
in the Wild</U>, a status report that forecasts a grim future
for many of the world's most popular fish species.  The report
reveals that the world is in the grip of a fisheries crisis that
transcends political boundaries and affects North and South alike.


<P>
&quot;Nearly everywhere, fisheries that have sustained coastal
communities for generations have suffered catastrophic declines,&quot;
said Michael Sutton, Director of WWF's Endangered Seas Campaign.
 &quot;Gone forever are the estimates that marine catches could
top 500 million tonnes a year.  Without doubt, we have exceeded
the limit of the seas.&quot;

<P>
In some areas, chronic overfishing has driven staple species such
as Atlantic cod and Atlantic halibut commercially extinct, resulting
in the loss of hundreds of thousands of jobs.  Approximately 70
percent of the world's commercially-important marine fish stocks
are either fully fished, overexploited, depleted, or only slowly
recovering.

<P>
Increasingly volatile &quot;fish wars&quot; have erupted all over
the globe as fishing fleets clash over remnants of declining stocks.
 Governments worldwide pay US$54 billion in subsidies to an industry
that catches only US$70 billion worth of fish.

<P>
To make matters worse, fully one-third of the world's catch--between
18 and 40 million tonnes of unwanted fish, marine mammals, sea
turtles, and seabirds--is thrown back into the oceans dead or
dying each year.  The effect on marine ecosystems is devastating.


<P>
To help alleviate this global catastrophe, WWF recently launched
the Endangered Seas Campaign, an ambitious, three-year effort
to promote the conservation and sustainable use of marine fishes
worldwide.  The campaign's goal is to reverse the effects of overfishing
on marine fishes and the ocean ecosystems on which they depend.
 WWF has pledged more than $1 million per year to build the necessary
political will around the world to stop overfishing, restore devastated
fisheries, improve management regimes, and reduce the use of destructive
fishing practices.

<P>
In one innovative example, WWF is working with seafood companies
to set up a Marine Stewardship Council that will create market
incentives for fisheries conservation.  The organization will
establish a broad set of principles for sustainable fishing and
set standards for individual fisheries. Ultimately, fisheries
certified to these standards will be marked with a distinctive
logo. This will allow seafood consumers to select fish products
they know come from healthy, well-managed sources.

<P>
&quot;Our challenge is to save marine fishes--both as an important
source of food and a vital component of ocean ecosystems,&quot;
said Sutton. &quot;WWF will need strong public support to create
new social, economic, and political incentives for fishing that
is both sustainable and clean.  The stakes are high: the future
of world fisheries, their associated marine ecosystems, and the
millions of people around the world who depend on them for food
and employment.&quot;

<P>

<B>Note:</B> Attached is a brief summary of  
<a href="http://www.panda.org/news/press/news_51b.htm"><B>WWF's 10-point action
plan</a></B> that will help reverse the crisis in marine fisheries. For
more information, please contact Someshwar Singh at +41 22 3649553
or fax 3648307.
<P>



<br>

</blockquote>

<center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" 
border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For 
Nature</i></h6></center>
