<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>CLIMATE SCIENTISTS- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>

 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
For immediate release Thursday 30 November 1995<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><FONT SIZE=5><H2><CENTER>Climate Scientists Stick to Their Guns</CENTER></H2><BR>
</FONT></B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Madrid--</B>The world's leading climate scientists this week
fought off concerted efforts by Saudi Arabia and other oil producing
nations to weaken the text of the UN's Intergovernmental Panel
on Climate Change (IPCC) Second Assessment Report, due to be finalized
in Rome next month.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;The fossil fuel lobby came to Madrid determined to water
down the scientific evidence that human activities -- notably
burning oil and coal -- are having a direct influence on the earth's
climate,&quot; said Dr Merylyn McKenzie-Hedger, climate policy
officer at WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
On Wednesday, the last day of the meeting, delegates struggled
for eight hours to reach agreement on one small section on the
report -- on the detection of climate change.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
At the beginning of the meeting, the report contained a crucial
sentence stating that evidence pointed to &quot;a detectable human
influence on global climate&quot;. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Saudi Arabia battled long and hard to obscure this clear signal
that there is an urgent need to reduce carbon emissions. But the
tactics misfired. By 18.30 on Wednesday afternoon, the Saudi delegation
found itself isolated from the rest of the conference, and agreement
was reached that &quot;the balance of evidence suggests an appreciable
human influence on global climate&quot;.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Throughout the IPCC process -- it has taken five years to put
this report together -- a vociferous minority of oil and coal
producing countries has done its utmost to defy the scientists.
They have constantly tried to emphasize &quot;uncertainties&quot;
and to weaken the case for reducing oil and coal consumption.
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;The majority of governments accept the IPCC's findings,&quot;
7added McKenzie-Hedger. &quot;Now they and the scientific community
must stand by their beliefs and resist any last-minute oil lobby
attempts to alter the text at the final meeting in Rome.&quot;
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
ENDS
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For more information contact Sarah Russell +41 22 364 9554. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

