<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WWF GLOBAL FOREST MAP TO BE UNVEILED 9 SEPTEMBER
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>
<p>
<center>
<font size=4><b>
WWF GLOBAL FOREST MAP TO BE UNVEILED 9 SEPTEMBER
</b>
</font>
</center>
<p>
Geneva's Palais des Nations will host the unveiling of the first-ever
global forest area map by the international conservation organization
WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature.The map is the latest product of WWF's
Forests For Life initiative, a worldwide effort being carried out in
conjunction with business and government partners to halt and reverse the
loss and degradation of forests and woodlands by the year 2000. Forests For
Life will be a major focus of WWF 2000: The Living Planet Campaign, WWF's
new conservation action campaign.
<p>
The map release graphically illustrates the state of the world's forests
today, and highlights the urgent need for increased conservation action. It
demonstrates the shocking fact that, of the planet's 3.3 billion hectares
of forests, only six per cent is included in officially protected areas.
<p>
Forests For Life aims to increase that area to 10 per cent by the year
2000. It is also working on forest certification: a process which attempts
to link "green consumers" to producers who are seeking to improve forest 
management practices and obtain better market access and higher revenue by
providing an independent assessment of forest management operations.
<p>
The Forests For Life initiative focuses on protected areas, sustainable
forest management, forest restoration, protection of forests from climate
change, and reducing consumption of forest products.
<p>
WWF 2000: The Living Planet Campaign is a multi-year effort that aims to
conserve the diversity of life on Earth into the 21st century. WWF 2000
will be launched on 1 October  in a global teleconference broadcast live
from London to more than 30 countries around the world. The event will
feature the participation of worldwide political, business, conservation,
and entertainment figures.
<p>
<b>WHAT:</b><br>
<dd>Forests For Life Global Map Release<br>
<dd>A press conference to:<br>
<ul>
<li>unveil the first-ever map of the world's forests
<li>release new information about the state of the world's forests
</ul>
<p>
<b>WHERE:</b><br>
<dd>Palais des Nations, Geneva, Switzerland
<p>
<b>WHEN:</b><br>
<dd>10.30 AM Geneva time (8.30 GMT)<br>
<p>

<b>CONTACT:</b><br>
<dd>Javier Arreaza, WWF International
<dd>Tel: +41 22 364 9550, Fax: +41 22 364 8307
<dd>e-mail javier.arreaza@lan.wwf.ch
<p>
For more information about WWF-2000: The Living Planet Campaign, please contact:<p>
<center>The Campaign Operations Office, <br>
Tel: +31 20 520 7533, Fax: +31 22 520 7532<br>
e-mail 106204.3564@compuserve.com <br>
</center>



</table>
<p>
