<HEAD>
<TITLE>

Global Warming Makes Tropical Diseases Everyone's Problem
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>

<center>

<H2>
Global Warming Makes Tropical Diseases Everyone's Problem
</H2>

</center>
<p>
<B>GENEVA</B>--Incidences of insect-borne tropical diseases like malaria, dengue
fever, and hantavirus pulmonary syndrome are set to increase as the global
climate changes, according to a new World Health Organization report.
<P>
"Many countries and regions that have previously been immune from diseases
like malaria and dengue fever are laying out the welcome mat by doing
nothing to halt climate change," said Peter DeBrine, Climate Change
campaigner at WWF--World Wide Fund For Nature.
<P>
Infectious diseases currently kill more than 17 million people annually.
That number is set to rise rapidly, as populations of opportunistic species
such as mosquitoes and rats extend their territory. 
<P>
Scientists predict that malaria will spread to higher latitudes, increasing
those at risk to an estimated 60 per cent of the world's population. Malaria
is already turning up in places such as New Jersey and New York. Global
warming could cause another 1 million deaths from malaria per year in the
next century. 
<P>
Mosquitoes are not the only  problem. The deadly rat-borne hantavirus
pulmonary syndrome killed 60 people in America's Southwest in 1993. In 1994,
rodent populations exploded in Southern Africa, causing plague to break out
in Zimbabwe, Malawi, and Mozambique. The same year, plague resurged in India
following a blistering summer and unusually heavy monsoons.
<P>
"The incredible advances that have been made during the past century to
eradicate some of our most deadly infectious diseases could be dramatically
set back, unless governments take decisive action at this week's climate
negotiations in Geneva," said DeBrine.
<p>
Long-term ocean warming is also likely to harm marine life. In combination
with coastal pollution, warmer waters encourage the proliferation of toxic
"red tides". Recent die-offs of manatees off the coast of Florida are
thought to have been caused by a red tide enhanced by an oversupply of
nutrients and warm sea surfaces. 
<p>
"This is just one more alarm bell that should trigger global action against
climate change," added DeBrine. "How many more such bells do the world's
leaders have to hear before they move on from the starting block and get
going in the race against climate change?"
<p>
<font size=-1>
For more information, and copies of a new WWF report, Climate Changes...
our health, contact Peter DeBrine on +41 (0) 77 588 165 or Sarah Russell +41
22 362  9554.
</font>  

</blockquote>
<center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" 
border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
