<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Industrial Dispute on Climate Change
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>

<center>

<H2>
Industrial Dispute on Climate Change
</H2>

</center>
<p>
<B>GENEVA</B>--Next week industry groups will stand on opposite sides of the floor
at the Second Conference of the Parties to the UN Framework Convention on
Climate Change which takes place in Geneva, 8-19 July.
<p>
On one side stand the oil, power, and automobile companies, represented by
groups such as the Global Climate Coalition (GCC), a US lobby group. Last
month the GCC attacked the UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change
(IPCC) -- the ultimate authority on climate change. The panel had just
published its Second Assessment Report, which carries a key statement, that
there is a  discernible human influence on the global climate . The GCC
criticized the way the report was approved and claimed that it was not to be
trusted.
<p>
Considering governments went through the IPCC report last year with a
fine-toothed comb, approving it line by line, this is outrageous,  said Dr
Claude Martin, Director General of WWF International.  All the 100
governments participating in the approval process agreed the line about the
discernible human influence . 
<p>
 The fossil fuel lobby has finally exposed itself for what it is,  he
added.  The GCC pretends to work for the good of the environment. It clearly
does not. It is a total sham -- a desperate group of self-interested parties
obsessed with serving their own short-term commercial interests. Any member
of the coalition who purports to be environmentally responsible should
resign immediately. 
<p>
Ranked against the oil lobby will be another industry group: insurance
companies who come to Geneva to lobby for urgent action on climate change.
Insurance companies stand to lose billions of dollars as a result of
catastrophes associated with climate change. In May this year, insurance
groups met in London to agree on ways to improve management of environmental
risks. Among conference outputs was a paper calling for a  substantial
reduction in greenhouse gas emissions .
<p>
WWF--World Wide Fund For Nature will also attend the meeting. WWF wants
governments to agree on a protocol to the convention that will commit
industrialized nations to reduce carbon dioxide emissions by 20 per cent
from 1990 levels by 2005. If this meeting does not end with a clear action
plan on a protocol proposal, the parties to the convention will have failed
in the mission they were charged with at the first conference in Berlin last
April -- to agree on a protocol to be adopted at the third conference of
parties in Japan in 1997.
<p>										
Meanwhile, the latest update of a computer animation programme* developed
by the Climate Research Unit  at Britain s University of East Anglia (UEA)
reinforces scientific evidence that human activities are heating up the
global climate.
<p>
The programme looks at geographical patterns of climate change since 1900.
It shows that over the past century, warming has been occurring along the
lines contained in the models scientists have been using to predict future
climate patterns.
<p>
Last year was the warmest ever. The seven warmest years have all occurred
since 1980. On average, the world has warmed at a rate of between 0.1 C and
0.2 C per decade over the past 25 years. Warming is taking place at
different rates in different places, with the most consistent temperature
rises occurring in the southern hemisphere. Annual temperatures over central
England have increased by around 0.5 C since the mid-19th century.
<p>
Given what we know about the climate system, it seems highly unlikely that
these changes could be happening naturally,  said UEA climatologist Dr Mike
Hulme.
<p>
 The Geneva conference must ignore the oil lobby and accept that the
scientists are right,  said Martin.  Urgent action is vital. The longer
governments wait, the worse the problem will get, and the more it will cost
to set right. 
<p>
For more information contact Sarah Russell on +41 22 364 9554 or Merylyn
McKenzie-Hedger on +44 385 731 (mobile) or +41 22 731 6750 (Hotel Longchamp).
<p>
<FONT SIZE=-1>*The Surface Air Temperature Record from 1900 to 1995, a computer animation
produced by Phil Jones, Mike Salmon, and Mike Hulme, Climate Research Unit,
University of East Anglia, Norwich, UK. Tel: +44 1603 593 162.
</FONT>

</blockquote>
