<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Joint Statement on the Relationship between
the WTO and Multilateral Environmental Agreements
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/position.gif" alt="WWF Position Statement">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>
<CENTER>World Wide Fund For Nature, Greenpeace, and Friends of the Earth</center>
<br>

<CENTER><B> <FONT SIZE=5>Joint Statement on the Relationship between
the WTO and Multilateral Environmental Agreements<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>


<P>
<B>Introduction<BR>
</B>
<P>
<img src="/graphics/wwf_green.jpg" align=right>
The Committee on Trade and Environment (CTE) of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) is currently discussing the relationship between
the rules of this body and multilateral environmental agreements
(MEAs) which incorporate trade measures. These discussions are
a continuation of work on this issue that began nearly five years
ago in the GATT Working Group on Environmental Measures and International
Trade. It is not clear whether or not the CTE will produce substantive
recommendations by the time of the WTO Ministerial Meeting in
Singapore this December. However, given the length of time governments
have discussed this issue, the environmental community expects
the CTE to produce recommendations which remove any threat of
a WTO challenge to MEAs.<BR>

<P>
In the past few months Friends of the Earth (FoE), Greenpeace,
and the World Wide Fund For Nature (WWF) have been following these
CTE discussions with increasing alarm. Over this period the mandate
of the CTE has been turned on its head as the discussions have
shifted from considering whether WTO rules need amending to accommodate
trade measures in MEAs, to consideration of how more restrictive
rules might be applied to MEAs (and individual MEA members) which
use trade measures to secure the environmental objectives of these
agreements. Such changes in the interpretation of WTO rules could
dangerously weaken important international agreements such as
the Montreal Protocol on Substances that Deplete the Ozone Layer,
the Basel Convention on the Control of Transboundary Movements
of Hazardous Waste, the Convention on International Trade in Endangered
Species (CITES), and any future MEAs incorporating trade measures.
<BR>

<P>
Given the threat that such a proposed change in WTO rules could
pose to the global environment and biodiversity, WWF has commissioned
an ongoing legal analysis of the role of trade measures in MEAs
and of the formal proposals tabled in the WTO discussions. This
analysis is being conducted in consultation with FoE and Greenpeace.
The main environmental concerns emanating from this legal analysis
are summarized in the next section of this paper. The objectives
that any balanced and environmentally friendly reform of WTO rules
should achieve are laid out thereafter. Recommendations on how
WTO Members could achieve those objectives conclude this statement.
<BR>

<P>
FoE, Greenpeace, and WWF believe that anything less than these
actions will compromise the effectiveness of the above&#173;mentioned
MEAs, other existing ones that may have to develop trade measures
for effective implementation, and also future agreements, and
will thus endanger the global environment.<BR>
<P>
<B>Analysis of WTO/MEA relationship<BR>
</B>
<P>
The international negotiators who incorporated trade measures
into MEAs did so because they considered them to be essential
and effective implementation tools. The history of the implementation
of these agreements bears out this assessment. Trade measures
have, for example, been particularly effective in the rapid implementation
of the Montreal Protocol, and in securing the broad membership
necessary to make the agreement work. Trade measures proved to
be a key factor in persuading some countries producing or consuming
CFCs, such as Korea, Israel, and Myanmar, to join the agreement,
and to phase out production and use of these ozone&#173;depleting
substances.<BR>

<P>
As no formal GATT or WTO challenge has yet been filed against
trade measures taken to implement MEAs with WTO rules, one has
to presume that WTO Members do not consider such measures incompatible
with trade rules. It is nevertheless important legally to confirm
this compatibility, given the uncertainty about how the trade&#173;oriented
dispute settlement procedures of the WTO would operate in the
event that a formal challenge was brought against such a trade
measure. <BR>

<P>
These concerns have in some respects been heightened by the recent
ruling of the WTO Apellate Body on the Venezuela&#173;US Reformulated
Gasoline dispute. This underlines the fact that WTO rules are
a moving target on the issue of MEAs. The uncertainty may be impairing
effective implementation of existing MEAs. It will probably also
discourage negotiators of future environmental agreements from
using trade measures, even when controlling trade in environmentally
hazardous products or goods produced by environmentally hazardous
processes is vital to the effectiveness of any MEA. MEA negotiators
must have the certainty that if a trade measure is chosen as a
tool to deal with a multilaterally agreed environmental problem,
their decision will not be subject to challenge under trade rules.
 <BR>

<P>
Instead of positive environmental reform of the WTO, trade officials
in the CTE are now talking about applying unbalanced and inappropriate
trade disciplines to MEA negotiators and parties. Some of the
recommendations made in the formal proposals of WTO Members, notably
New Zealand and Korea, could if implemented undermine global efforts
to secure sustainable development.<BR>

<P>
In particular, the suggestion that WTO panels should apply &quot;effectiveness&quot;,
&quot;proportionality&quot; and &quot;least trade restrictiveness&quot;
tests to trade measures in MEAs is a very alarming one. It would
give the trade specialists on WTO dispute panels the mandate to
second&#173;guess the negotiators of and parties to MEAs, on environmental
issues, using criteria developed to liberalize trade, not safeguard
the environment. If implemented, such proposals could increase
rather than decrease conflicts between MEAs and the WTO, effectively
creating a hierarchy of policy objectives with trade at the top
and environment at the bottom.<BR>

<P>
As proposed by New Zealand in particular, these tests would place
a heavy burden of proof on members of MEAs taking trade actions
to implement their agreed commitments. Application of such tests
could thus reverse the widely accepted Precautionary Principle,
which requires that when any action or policy measure may have
a negative environmental effect, governments and policy&#173;makers
should give the environment the benefit of the doubt.<BR>

<P>
<B>Defining a sustainable WTO&#173;MEA relationship<BR>
</B>
<P>
FoE, Greenpeace, and WWF  believe that establishment of a mutually
supportive relationship between MEAs and the WTO is one of the
most urgent priorities for the international community. We further
believe that establishing such a relationship will depend on an
appropriate division of labour between MEAs and the WTO. MEAs
should retain full competence to judge the legitimacy of their
environmental objectives, and to select the means to achieve those
objectives. WTO dispute panels must not be able to redefine the
level of environmental risk deemed acceptable. Conversely, the
WTO should retain competence to prevent protectionist abuse of
trade measures through its dispute settlement mechanism.<BR>

<P>
The legal solutions which achieve these overarching objectives
will:<BR>

<P>
- not expand the scope for measures serving trade policy rather
than environmental policy objectives<BR>

<P>
- introduce an exemption in the WTO which will provide sufficient
flexibility for MEA negotiators to develop and parties to use
effective trade measures<BR>

<P>
- involve reform of the WTO dispute settlement system to sensitise
it to environmental concerns<BR>

<P>
- reward multilateralism by being based on a presumption that
trade measures taken pursuant to MEAs are compatible with all
WTO agreements.<BR>

<P>
<B>Conclusions and Recommendations<BR>
</B>
<P>
FoE, Greenpeace, and WWF believe that in moving towards a comprehensive
arrangement making the WTO and MEAs mutually supportive, WTO Members
should take the following actions and accept the following principles
by the time of the Singapore Ministerial Meeting.  <BR>

<P>
1. Acknowledge that a case&#173;by&#173;case waiver approach for
MEAs with trade measures is unacceptable as it creates a hierarchy
which places the WTO above MEAs, and even greater uncertainty
for environmental negotiators who consider trade measures a necessary
implementation tool.<BR>

<P>
2. Re&#173;evaluate the formal proposals tabled on the WTO&#173;MEA
relationship in the CTE, and in particular the European Commission's
non&#173;paper, in the light of the recent Apellate Body ruling
on the Venezuela&#173;US Reformulated Gasoline dispute.<BR>

<P>
3.   Accept that no necessity, effectiveness, or proportionality
tests should be applied by the WTO to trade measures taken pursuant
to MEAs.<BR>

<P>
4.   Confirm that WTO dispute settlement panels have no competence
to establish the environmental objectives of MEAs and how best
to achieve them, and ensure that whenever a trade dispute in the
WTO has implications for environmental policies or regulations,
advice is sought on these from independent environmental experts.
<BR>

<P>
5.   Ensure that measures pusuant to MEAs cannot be censured through
different parts of the WTO (e.g. GATT Article XX, the Technical
Barriers to Trade Agreement, General Agreement on Trade in Services,
Trade&#173;Related Intellectual Property Rights, etc.) once an
environmentally acceptable MEA exception is in place.<BR>

<P>
6.   Provide a broad definition of MEAs and allowable environmental
objectives of trade measures within MEAs, to ensure that there
is no &quot;WTO chill factor&quot; weakening implementation of
existing MEAs, or preventing negotiation of future effective ones.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
