<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WWF Plans Major Presence at Second World Fisheries Congress
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>

<center>

<H2>
WWF Plans Major Presence at Second World Fisheries Congress
</H2>
</center>
<p>
<b>WHAT:</b>
The Second World Fisheries Congress will focus on Developing and Sustaining World Fisheries Resources: The 
State of Science and Management.  Delegates will consider why many fisheries have collapsed and what is needed to manage fisheries 
sustainably.  With 900 delegates from 55 countries preregistered, the Congress will provide an opportunity for 
conservationists, scientists, managers, fishers and industry representatives to meet and discuss how to reverse the 
escalating crisis facing world fisheries.
<p>
WWF is an official sponsor of the Congress and served on its international steering committee.  Michael Sutton, Director of 
WWF's Endangered Seas Campaign, will present a paper entitled A new paradigm for managing marine fisheries in the next 
millennium. WWF will also present a poster paper on Mediterranean fisheries and share a booth in the Exhibition Hall with the 
Ocean Wildlife Campaign, a coalition effort to promote the conservation of large pelagic fishes such as sharks, tunas and 
billfishes.
<p>
<b>WHEN:</b>	29 July - 1 August 1996
<p>
<b>WHERE:</b>	Brisbane Convention & Exhibition Centre, Brisbane, Queensland, Australia.	
<p>

<b>WHO:</b>	An international team of  WWF marine conservation experts will  be attending the Second World Fisheries 
Congress.  It includes David Butcher and Ray Nias of WWF Australia, Michael Sutton, Laura Cooper and Demetres Karavellas of 
WWF's Endangered Seas Campaign,  Chris Tydeman and Indrani Lutchman of WWF UK, Romy Trono of WWF's Philippine Programme, Tundi 
Agardy of WWF US, Mariko Abe of WWF Japan, Shigeki Komori of WWF's South Pacific Programme,  and Bobbie Jo Kelso, Elizabeth 
Fleming and Glenn Sant from TRAFFIC.  David Wilmot, Director of the Ocean Wildlife Campaign, will also attend the Congress.
<p>
<b>WHY:</b>	The world is in the grip of a fisheries crisis that transcends political boundaries and affects north and south 
alike.  Nearly everywhere, fisheries that have sustained coastal communities for generations have suffered catastrophic 
declines.  In some areas, excessive fishing has driven staple species to commercial extinction.  If we are to save marine 
fishes, both as an important source of food and a vital component of marine ecosystems, we must reform contemporary fishery 
management, build public support for fishery conservation and create economic incentives for sustainable fishing.  This won't 
be easy, but the stakes are high:  the future of world fisheries, their associated marine ecosystems, and the millions of 
people around the world who depend on them for food and employment.
<p>
<center><a href="http://www.panda.org/news/press/news_60b.htm">Australian National Audit Office Audit Report</center>
<p></a>
<font size=-1>
For more information, please contact Someshwar Singh at +61 7 3846 3000 or fax 3846 3578.  From 28th July onward, please 
phone +61 7 32 55 0822 or fax 32 55 0899.
</font>

</blockquote>
<center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" 
border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
