<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>RUSSIAN ANTELOPE- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
For Immediate Release: May 17, 1995<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><H2>
<CENTER>Russian Antelope Threatened by Unregulated Trade</CENTER>
</H2><BR>
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>GLAND, Switzerland</B>.- An antelope species from the Russian
steppes is now the object of a massive trade that could have severe
repercussions in its ability to reproduce and survive in the long
run, according to a species report released today by Traffic International,
the wildlife trade monitoring programme of WWF-World Wide Fund
For Nature and IUCN-The World Conservation Union.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
According to the report <I>From Steppe to Store: The trade in
Saiga Antelope Horn</I> , the illegal trade in horns of male Saiga
antelopes (<I>Saiga tartarica</I>) was as high as 44 tonnes in
1994. Sales were reported in Asian states like China, Korea, Japan,
Hong Kong, Singapore, Thailand, Taiwan and Malaysia, and European
countries like Great Britain. Most of this trade originates in
the Russian Republic of Kalmykia and the Independent Republic
of Kazakhstan, but poaching may also be a problem in neighboring
Mongolia, whose population is very close to extinction.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
With a total population numbering about 1 million, the species
itself is not strictly endangered at the present time. But the
Traffic report states that &quot;in the past 50 years largely
irreversible changes have occurred to parts of the Saiga's steppe
environment, and within the last five years the governments of
Russia and Kazakhstan have all but lost the ability to apply and
enforce any [of the] management regime and harvest controls&quot;
necessary to use the species sustainably. Meanwhile, prices per
kilogram of Saiga horn hover around US$30. This by far exceeds
the minimum monthly wages in both Russia and Kazakhstan, which
now stand at US$5 and US$4, respectively, and creates a great
incentive for potential poachers.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
In addition to the segmentation of habitat by livestock breeding
and construction projects undertaken during the Soviet era, the
relaxation of border and trade controls between the former USSR
and its neighbors has boosted legal and illegal exports of Saiga
antelope products. In 1989 alone, the overall quantity exported
may have exceeded previous annual totals by five to seven times.
The greater part of the increase is due to illegal trade.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The trade in Saiga antelope products itself is not formally illegal.
The species was listed last November on appendix II of the Convention
on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Flora and
Fauna (CITES), which only requires parties to regulate and monitor
all international commerce in the Saiga Antelope and its derivatives.
Nevertheless, neither Kazakhstan (where the largest population
is found) nor Mongolia are parties to the Convention, and are
not required to abide by it.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The demand for Saiga horn has been driven by the relatively recent
adoption of the horn as an ingredient in Oriental medicines. Saiga
horn is now popularly interpreted to be <I>lingyang-jiao</I>,
an ingredient often quoted in ancient Chinese medical texts as
a cure for liver problems and fever. It is now used to treat convulsions,
headaches, vertigo and other problems.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>END</B> 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For more information, please contact Javier Arreaza at 41 22 364
9575, or fax 41 22 364 8307. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

