<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>SEA TURTLE- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>
 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>
For release: 14 June 1995<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>   
<H2>  
<CENTER> Tourism Threatens Endangered Mediterranean Sea Turtles</CENTER>
</H2>
<BR>

</FONT>GLAND. Switzerland</B>--WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature
is taking legal action over a new road down to one of the Mediterranean's
last remaining turtle nesting beaches -- the latest threat to
the endangered loggerhead turtle (<I>Caretta caretta</I>).<BR>
<BR>
Around one-third of the Mediterranean's known loggerhead turtle
population gathers to nest on the Greek island of Z&aacute;kynthos
every summer. But developments like this new illegal road to Sekania
Beach on the island's southern coast will open up the beach to
tourists and builders. WWF is anxious to prevent Sekania from
filling up with tavernas and discoth&egrave;ques whose bright
lights and music will frighten adult female turtles and stop them
coming ashore to lay their eggs.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The challenge is to find a balance between human activities
like tourism and conservation,&quot; said Paolo Guilglielmi, coordinator
of WWF's Mediterranean Programme.<BR>
<BR>
That equilibrium is a distant dream for Z&aacute;kynthos. One
by one the island's beaches are being overwhelmed by tourists
-- despite efforts by the Greek government to control developments.
On Daphni Beach, which also lies on the south coast, 13 illegal
buildings have appeared over the past five years. Over the same
period, the beach's turtle nest numbers have fallen by 40 per
cent.<BR>
<BR>
In 1992, WWF-Greece negotiated the purchase of 32 hectares of
land on neighbouring Sekania Beach, where more than 52 per cent
of the island's turtles lay their eggs. In a good season, nearly
1,000 nests  are packed into the 500-metre-long beach, the highest
loggerhead nesting density in the world. The turtles that nest
here will not nest anywhere else: female turtles always lay their
eggs on the same beach. If they cannot lay them here, they will
not lay them at all.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Protective measures like this are not enough,&quot; says
Vassilios Katsoupas of WWF-Greece. &quot;For the turtles to survive,
the Greek government must pass laws and make sure they are properly
carried out.&quot;<BR>
<I>                                                          
                        more....<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</I>                                        2<BR>
<BR>
Earlier this year the Standing Committee to the Berne Convention
(the Convention of Wild Fauna and Flora and Natural Habitats in
Europe), to which Greece is a signatory party, urged the Greek
government to demolish illegal buildings on Daphni and create
a marine park to protect turtle beaches. Failure to comply means
the Council of Europe can take Greece to the European Court, reducing
its chances of attracting EU development funds.<BR>
<BR>
In April, the Environment Ministry said it would resolve the problems
by  the end of the year. These good intentions are now being blocked
by local authorities' inaction. The Prefect of Z&aacute;kynthos
is clearly more concerned about safeguarding electoral  support
from local landowners who oppose restrictions on tourist development.
<BR>
<BR>
The Sekania road appeared only a few days after the Ministry's
announcement. Since then, local authorities have issued contradictory
statements, denying  the road exists while also claiming it has
been there since 1965. WWF is now taking legal action against
the road builders and local officials, accusing them of perjury.
The organization is also calling on the government to fulfill
its longstanding promise to set up a marine park. <BR>
                                        <BR>
                                        -ENDS-<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
For more information contact Sarah Russell at WWF International
on +41 22 364 9574 or Vassilios Katsoupas at WWF-Greece on +31
1 362 3342<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
