<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Theft of Endangered Tortoises a Severe Blow to Species, says WWF</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>
EMBARGOED until Wednesday 15 May 1996

<p>

<center>

<h2>
WWF Relieved by News of Hostage Release in Indonesia
</h2>

</center>

<P>
<b>GLAND, Switzerland</B> - WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature today
expressed deep relief at the release  of WWF employee Mark van der
Wal,  a Dutch national, and eight of the other ten hostages who have
spent the past four months in a remote part of the Indonesian province,
Irian Jaya, in the hands of the OPM (Free Papua Movement).
<p>
"We have waited a long time for this moment," said Dr Claude Martin,
Director General of WWF International. "It has been an ordeal for all
involved, particularly for Mark and his family, and at some points it
seemed it would never end. Now, thank God, it has. We are immensely
relieved, and enormously grateful to all those who have worked so hard
to secure the hostages' release. Our concern now is that the two
remaining hostages should also be set free as soon as possible."
<p>
Mark van der Wal, Martha Klein (a Dutch employee of UNESCO),  four
students from Cambridge University, UK, and three Indonesians were
rescued by the Indonesian army earlier today. The released hostages
are apparently still in the forest, where they are  being looked after by
the military. Bad weather is preventing  them from being airlifted out by
helicopter.
<p>
The Indonesian army took over last week when the International
Committee for the Red Cross  withdrew from negotiations to free the
hostages after talks broke down. The ICRC had worked long and hard to
mediate conditions that would be acceptable to all parties. In the earliest
stages of the 18-week long crisis, Christian missionaries had played a
leading role. The Indonesian army  coordinated the release operation
throughout the crisis, and stepped up its involvement on 9 May when
ICRC backed out. 
<P>
Twenty-four people were originally kidnapped on 8 January. Ten of
these, including WWF employee Frank Momberg, a German national, and
nine local Irianese were released in mid-January. Momberg subsequently
made a short trip to Germany and is now back working for WWF  in
Indonesia. Three Indonesian hostages were freed during March and
April.
<P>
"Now that the crisis seems to be over, our next task is to ensure that
WWF continues the conservation work it has started in the Lorentz
Nature Reserve," added Martin. This is an extremely important natural
area, with incredible biological and cultural diversity. We want to do all
we can to make sure that it is developed in ways that benefit local
communities and assure the long-term protection of its natural wealth."
<P>
WWF has been working in the area where the kidnapping occurred since
1990. Among its aims is to secure national park status for the area and to
ensure that it is listed as a World Heritage Site. WWF is keen to maintain
its long-term commitment to the Lorentz and its people. A key objective is
to establish a people-based conservation management regime for the
area.
<P>
At the time of the kidnapping, Mark van der Wal and Frank Momberg were
on a brief field liaison visit to discuss and plan future activities in
cooperation with local villagers. The four students from Cambridge
University were on an unrelated field research expedition. This group,
with their Indonesian counterparts, was kidnapped first. The WWF staff
members, plus their UNESCO companion, were taken shortly afterwards.
<P>
ENDS
<br>
<font size=-1>
For more information contact Sarah Russell on +41 22 364 9554
 </font>

<P>

<br>

