<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WORLD FISHERIES CONGRESS REAFFIRMS URGENT NEED FOR ACTION 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>

<P>
<center>
<h2><B>World Fisheries Congress Reafirms Urgent Need For Action <BR></h2>
</B>
</center>
<P>
<b>Brisbane</b>, Australia - At the conclusion of the Second World Fisheries
Congress, WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature called for major reductions
in fishing fleets, greater attention to small scale fisheries,
better enforcement, and a fundamental realignment of fisheries
management from production to ecosystem management in order to
avoid further destruction of world fisheries.<BR>

<P>
Keynote speakers at the Congress warned that many fisheries have
already collapsed and that 70 percent of world fisheries are either
fully-fished, overexploited, depleted or slowly recovering.  They
said that world fleets had far more fishing power than is necessary
to net the available catch and should be reduced by at least 50
percent.  An FAO official predicted rising prices and a global
shortfall of up to 40 million tons of fish if urgent conservation
measures are not adopted as a matter of priority.<BR>

<P>
&quot;We need to forge a new paradigm of fishery management that
is founded on conservation and sustainability instead of unbridled
development,&quot; said Michael Sutton, Director of WWF's Endangered
Seas Campaign.  &quot;Public concern and market forces must be
harnessed to provide powerful incentives for conservation.&quot;
<BR>

<P>
Innovative new approaches  such as the proposed Marine Stewardship
Council were welcomed by Congress delegates. Partnership with
industry was seen as essential to complement traditional government
management and regulation, much of which has fallen far short
of its goals.<BR>

<P>
&quot;We need to get over the notion that fisheries resources
 are the sole concern of the fishing industry,&quot; said David
Butcher, Chief Executive Officer of WWF Australia. &quot;Heavily-subsidized
fishing fleets have grown twice as fast as catches, and their
owners wield enormous political power. At the end of the day,
fisheries are a public resource and decision-making must therefore
take this public interest into account.&quot; <BR>

<P>
WWF warned delegates that aquaculture should not be promoted as
a solution to the growing crisis in world fisheries. Aquaculture
development should take into account the need to deal with the
huge problems of pollution, disease, introduction of exotic species,
and the destruction of coastal habitats.  The large scale destruction
of mangroves for shrimp farming in many countries in Southeast
Asia is typical of these serious environmental impacts.<BR>

<P>
Small-scale, subsistence and inshore fisheries, which involve
more than 90 percent of the world's fishers, need far more attention
from scientists and managers.  Northern fishing fleets continue
to push into the fishing zones of developing countries, further
threatening the livelihoods of coastal fishing communities and
the marine ecosystems on which they depend. <BR>

<P>

For more information, please call Someshwar Singh at +61 7 3255
0822 or fax 3255 0899





</blockquote> <center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
