<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Incentives for Conservation and Sustainable Use of Biodiversity: Implementing Article 11 of the CBD
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/position.gif" alt="WWF Position Statement">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>
<br>

<CENTER><B> <FONT SIZE=5>Joint Statement on Incentives for Conservation and Sustainable Use of Biodiversity: 
Implementing Article 11 of the CBD
<BR> </FONT></B></CENTER>


<P>
<P>
<img src="/graphics2/natvgirl.jpg" alt="girl in grass skirt" align=right>

<b>WWF calls on Parties at CoP.3 to</b>:
<p>
<ul type circle>
<li>adopt a programme of work on incentive measures and give the appropriate mandate to SBSTTA.3. 
</ul>
<p>
<b>Such a programme should aim at</b>:
<ul type circle>
<p>
<li>providing technical advice and support for Parties to design, select and implement national programmes of economically and 
socially sound incentives. Special attention should be given to the needs of developing countries. Guidance is urgently 
needed on the formulation and implementation of appropriate supportive policies in order to strengthen incentive programmes 
and remove legal barriers and disincentives.
</ul>
<p>
<b>The programme should include the following elements</b>:
<p>
<ul type circle>
<li>Review of  existing macro-economic measures, including systems of national accounting, that ensure the incorporation of the 
value of nature and remove disincentives for conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity
<p>
<li>Development of proposals for sectoral incentives encouraging conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity in forestry, 
fisheries and agriculture, in particular
<p>
<li>Development of incentives to promote effective private efforts for conserving and sustainably using biodiversity
<p>
<li>Assessment of ways in which institutions, and mechanisms at all levels, including locally based participative approaches, 
can be established to support the introduction and continued effectiveness of incentive measures
<p>
<li>Formulation of training and capacity building support programmes to develop and manage incentives projects
<p>
<li>Promotion at the local level of incentives aimed at conserving the traditional knowledge and culture of those indigenous 
people whose livelihoods are based on the sustainable use of biodiversity.
</ul>
<p>
In implementing this programme of work, Parties, SBSTTAs and CoPs should ensure that the experience accumulated by NGOs and 
other organizations are duly incorporated. They particularly need to guarantee:
<p>
<ul type circle>
<li>self-sufficiency and the phasing-out of dependency on external funding
<p>
<li>successful incentive schemes that include social, economic and macro-economic measures.
</ul>
<p>
<b>WWF urges CoP.3 to encourage Parties to</b>:
<p>
<ul type circle>
<li>report at CoP.4 on their efforts to implement Article 11, including a review of their existing policy and legal regimes, 
and of actions taken to remove the provisions that act as disincentives to conservation
<p>
<li>require that GEF establishes a fast-track programme, targeting practical and focused projects providing socio-economic 
incentives and removing disincentives at local, national and regional levels.
</ul>
<p>
<b>INTRODUCTION</b>
<p>
Article 11 states that: "Each Contracting Party shall, as far as possible and where appropriate, adopt economically and 
socially sound measures that act as incentives for the conservation and sustainable use of components of biodiversity".  
<p>
As well as recognizing the importance of economic measures, Article 11 stresses that social measures are equally important.  
<p>
WWF urges the Third Meeting of the Conference of the Parties to the Convention on Biological Diversity (CoP.3) to adopt a 
programme of work that ensures rapid and effective implementation of Article 11. This programme should address economically 
and socially sound incentive measures, particularly those which would be practical to implement immediately at local, 
national and regional levels. Recommendations should include action on incentives that specifically address the thematic 
issues contained in the medium-term work programme of the SBSTTA and the CoP. The role that the SBSTTA and the Convention 
Secretariat can play in providing support for national programmes of incentive measures should be examined.
<p>
As a contribution towards this effort, WWF has reviewed case studies that analyse a variety of incentive measures already 
being implemented by WWF and others in various parts of the world. 
<p>
Key lessons learned and recommendations from this review are summarized below.
<p>
<b>BACKGROUND</b>
<p>
Article 11 has a central role in the effective implementation of the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD). Information 
and education campaigns on conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity may not be sufficient to influence change in 
behaviour of civil society, including local communities, industry and consumers. Indeed the provision of economic and social 
incentives is fundamental to achieving the Convention's objectives in the long term.  Different instruments have been proposed 
for this endeavour and the debate on their merits will continue. Voluntary mechanisms could include encouragement, persuasion, 
ethical appeals, information access, and education campaigning.  Incentives can also be provided via legislation and regulatory 
systems, particularly by ensuring that regulatory agencies adopt integrated approaches for conservation and sustainable use of 
biodiversity in the planning and implementation of their actions. What is clear is that a combination of voluntary and regulatory 
instruments are required from the social to the economic and macro-economic levels.
<p>
Social incentives could include general measures to improve the quality of life; to reform land and resources tenure; to 
grant user rights over wildlife to local people and to enable them to participate in resource management; to help build 
community institutions; and/or to provide socio-economic infrastructures. 
<p>
Economic incentives include the generation of alternative economic activities and incomes, in combination with social 
incentives; establishment of direct fiscal schemes, such as credit and endowment funds; revenue sharing; and tax rebates or 
direct compensation payments and exemptions. 
<p>
On a macro-economic scale, incentives could include the introduction of taxes that incorporate the values of nature, and 
systems of national accounting and policy reforms that redirect public and private expenditure and change the use of external 
and internal funds. These policy reforms would reduce future dependence on external aid grants and set standards for private 
sector finance.
<p>
The central challenge facing the Convention and the Parties is the establishment of conditions whereby sustainable use reaps 
more benefits for the people concerned than unsustainable use; where the real values of nature are recognized; and where 
economic transactions support, rather than undermine, the conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity.  
<p>
The success or failure of conservation at any level is strongly influenced by national legislation and policies. Similarly, 
national policies may be affected by international policies, and by the actions of multilateral institutions. Even the best 
investments in, and policies for, conservation are likely to fail if the broader context in which they are set is not geared 
towards conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity. Policies at all levels need to provide consistent support if the 
goals and mechanisms of the Biodiversity Convention are to be achieved. Policies will have to be finely tuned at both 
national and local levels to respond to social, cultural, and environmental diversity, whilst maintaining biodiversity 
differences.
<p>
There are already many experiences of economic and social incentive measures being developed in different regions and 
countries, from which all countries can learn in implementing Article 11.
<p>
CoP.3 and future sessions of the SBSTTA can take steps to help spread the implementation of effective measures more widely. 
With respect to the precautionary  principle, action is needed now to conserve biodiversity, even though many global issues 
within the Convention and other fora have not yet been solved. 
<p>
<b>LESSONS LEARNED</b>
<p>
A variety of effective incentive measures for the conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity are already in use in many 
different countries. However, to achieve the objectives of the Convention on Biological Diversity, far more integral 
incentive schemes are needed.  Many of the existing schemes are pilot cases, and are at the community level only. It is 
essential to move on from these pilot phases, in order to learn lessons from these projects, and to take action to implement 
a much larger number of incentive programmes, including the reform required by macro-economic policy.
<p>
The following are some of the lessons learned and recommendations obtained from the experiences of WWF and others:
<ul type circle>
<p>
<li>Incentive measures, particularly those based on economic mechanisms, must be clearly linked to specific goals and 
targets for the conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity.
<p>  
<li>Socio-economic incentives for conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity must be designed and implemented on 
regional and landscape scales.
</ul>
<p>  
Some of the questions that should be asked during the planning, implementation and evaluation process of the 
incentive mechanism relate to:
<ul type circle>
<p>
<li>the effectiveness of the instrument in achieving the conservation target set in response to conservation threats
<li>the encouragement of innovation for developing or adapting technologies and practices
<li>the provision of continuing incentives and motivation, including capacity-building
<li>the level of political acceptability
<li>the required macro-economic policy context.
<p>
<li>Economic incentives alone are not enough to promote conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity. Additional 
measures, such as social incentives, and awareness building and empowerment of stakeholders, are also required in order to 
achieve successful incentive schemes.
<p>  
<li>Governments have a crucial role to play in creating an enabling macro-economic context, as well as policy and legal 
reforms that strengthen and complement incentive measures for biodiversity conservation. 
<p> 
<li>Government and partners should give special attention to providing appropriate institutional arrangements for local 
communities and stakeholders, including women, by controlling the process as equal partners during both the planning and 
implementation of  incentive measures. A process rather than a blueprint approach to project design must be employed.
<p>
<li>Encouragement of local entrepreneurs and development of innovative capacity can play a significant role in the 
success of incentive projects for the conservation and sustainable use of biodiversity.
<p>
<li>Training is needed to develop effective economic valuation techniques for structuring incentives mechanisms.
  <p>
<li>Incentive mechanisms, particularly those based on the promotion of alternative economic  activities, should build on 
indigenous knowledge, practices and institutions.
<p>
<li>Experience has shown that conservation organizations, funding agencies and other external partners can play an 
important role as catalysts and facilitators in the process. Incentive initiatives should be the product of consultation and 
dialogue and be responsive to the needs of stakeholders.
<p>
<li>Incentive programmes must plan for self-sufficiency and the phase-out of external support. It is important that 
initial funding is stable and allows for the establishment of the mechanism, but it must be oriented towards local capacity 
building and not create dependency. Training and support of local staff for long-term management and the building up of local 
institutional capacities will be crucial before and during the transitional period, in order to implement incentive schemes 
for biodiversity conservation, including revenue sharing. 
<p>
<li>Effective indicators must be identified and comprehensive monitoring systems put in place.
</ul>

</table> <p> <a 
href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
</BODY>
