<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> WWF Relieved at Peaceful End to Indonesian Hostage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>
FOR RELEASE:  9 May 1996
<p>

<center>

<h2>WWF Regrets Red Cross Withdrawal from Indonesian Hostage Negotiations</h2>

</center>

<P>
<b>GLAND, Switzerland</B> - WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature today expressed
profound regret at today's withdrawal of the International Committee
for the Red Cross (ICRC) from negotiations to free eleven hostages
being held by the Free Papua Movement (OPM)  in a remote part of the
Irian Jaya province of Indonesia.
<p>
"While we understand and sympathize with the ICRC's decision to
withdraw after long months of trying to reach a peaceful settlement
to this crisis, we are very sorry that they feel obliged to do so,"
said Dr Claude Martin, Director General of WWF International.
<p>
"No organization could have worked harder than they have, and we are
deeply grateful to them for all they have done," he added. "It is
reassuring to know that they will still provide medical assistance to
the hostages, should this become necessary. Meanwhile, we at WWF are
still hoping and praying for a peaceful conclusion."
<p>
The ICRC had hoped to secure the hostages' release earlier this week,
but negotiations broke down and the organization today announced that
it would discontinue its intermediary role in discussions with the
OPM.
<p>
One of the hostages, Mark van der Wal, a Dutch national, is a WWF
employee. He was kidnapped on 8 January 1996, along with another WWF
staff member, Frank Momberg from Germany; a Dutch employee of UNESCO;
four students from Cambridge University in the UK; and 17
Indonesians. Momberg and nine local Irianese were released in
mid-January. Three more Indonesians were released during March and
April.
<p>
-ENDS-
<p><font size =-1>
For more information, contact Sarah Russell on +41 22 364 9554.
</font>

<P>
<br>
</blockquote>
