<HEAD>

<TITLE>WILD PANDA LOAN- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For immediate release: April 10, 1995
<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><CENTER><H2>WWF Criticises Wild Panda Loan to Berlin</H2></CENTER> <BR>
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Gland, Switzerland</B> -- The WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature
has criticised the move to bring a wild-born female panda to the
Berlin zoo. The female panda &quot;Yan Yan&quot; is due to arrive
in Berlin on April 14, following an agreement between the city
and the Chinese government. WWF said the action was wrong and
detrimental to the integrated breeding programme for this endangered
species. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The Berlin loan follows the US Interior Department's approval
in January to import a pair of pandas for the San Diego Zoo, despite
a US moratorium on panda loans. One of these was also caught in
the wild. Other US zoos are expected to negotiate similar loans.
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The 9-year-old Yan Yan was removed from the wild when she was
just three months old in the belief she had been abandoned by
her mother. Bur research has shown that female pandas regularly
leave their cubs to search for food for up to 50 hours without
any ill effects. Yan Yan will be a mate for Bao Bao, the surviving
panda of a pair China gave to Germany in 1980. She has already
failed to reproduce despite several attempts at different Chinese
zoos.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;Panda loans should only be for breeding or research,&quot;
according to Mr Dawood Ghaznavi, WWF International's Asia/Pacific
Programme Director. &quot;These loans should help conservation
of the wild population and be part of a well planned, integrated
international breeding programme. They should only involve captive-bred
animals and must generate funds for conserving wild pandas in
China.&quot; <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
WWF fears that approval of these loans could set a dangerous precedent
and lead to a further depletion of an already fragile wild panda
population. Around 1,000 surviving wild pandas are confined mostly
to the bamboo forests of southwestern China, and are threatened
mainly by habitat destruction.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The giant panda is listed on CITES Appendix I, which strictly
prohibits all international trade in the species. WWF has called
on the CITES Standing Committee, which oversees the wildlife trade
treaty, to tighten controls on panda loans and stop all loans
involving wild-caught pandas. WWF has also urged the CITES Secretariat
to issue a strong directive on panda loans. Last year, China made
two loan agreements involving captive-bred pandas with zoos in
Japan and South Korea.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;Given the number of captive-born pandas in China, there
is no justification for using wild-caught pandas to service the
loans,&quot; Mr Ghaznavi added. &quot;China recently had encouraging
success in the captive breeding of pandas. Between 1992 and 1994,
30 panda cubs were born in captivity with more than half surviving.&quot;
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
However, WWF recognizes the efforts of the US Department of Interior
and the American Zoological Association to ensure that panda loans
actually embrace panda conservation in the wild. But until the
new framework and San Diego's loan agreement are tested, WWF strongly
feels that other loans should not be approved. ENDS <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For more information, contact Arun Chacko in Switzerland at tel.
+41 22 364 9566 or
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
fax +41 22 364 8307. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

</BODY>
