<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Global Warming Threatens Bird Migration, Report Warns
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Relaese">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>
<P>
<center><font size=5><B>Global Warming Threatens Bird Migration, Report Warns</B></font></center>
<P>
<img src="/graphics/stork.gif" align=right>
<b>Washington, Sept. 19</b>  -- One of nature's most spectacular sights -- the annual migration of millions of birds throughout 
the 
world -- is seriously threatened by global warming, says a new report from World Wildlife Fund.  The report, which names the 
world's 15 most critically affected sites, details a widespread disruption in migratory patterns as prime feeding and 
breeding grounds are lost to sea level rise, changes in the timing of seasons, and drier weather.
<p>
"The effect of global warming on bird migrations is like a family setting out on a cross-country road trip only to discover 
that all of the gas stations, hotels and restaurants are closed," said Adam Markham, director of WWF's Global Climate Change 
Campaign.  "You wouldn't get too far and you might not even survive."	
<p>
Birds rely on relatively stable weather patterns and the availability of food sites and food resources to complete their 
migratory strategies.  Long-distance migrants may travel hundreds or even thousands of miles without stopping and must often 
double their weight in food before leaving to build up fat deposits.  Global warming will wreak havoc with the migratory 
cycle, affecting many species' chances of survival during every part of their journey:  at the breeding grounds, the 
wintering grounds, and the stops in-between.
<p>
"Coastal sites such as the Chesapeake Bay or the Mediterranean Sea are so important for the bird species that use them every 
year as stop-overs for "refueling," that any threat could put millions of birds at risk," Markham said.  "If any of these 
so-called "critical" sites are lost, the whole balance of the migratory process can be thrown off."
<p>  
That balance will be thrown off by three of the main consequences of global warming:
<p>
*Coastal flooding --  caused by sea level rise, this may result in the most serious impacts as essential feeding areas such 
as low lying marshes and mudflats are lost.  
<p>
Studies show that some of the world's most valuable bird areas could be partially  or totally lost to sea level rise, 
including the Chesapeake Bay, parts of the Danube Delta in Romania, Port Philip Bay in Australia and the Wash in the U.K. 
<p>
*Changes in the timing of the seasons -- global warming could cause the more than one million shorebirds such as the Red Knot 
and Ruddy Turnstone who stop at the Delaware Bay to feed during their trip north to leave a week earlier, thereby missing the 
emergence of the millions of Horseshoe crabs from the Atlantic on whose eggs they rely to survive.
<p>
*Drier weather -- this could be particularly severe for birds in the Plains states of  Canada and the U.S., the Mediterranean 
Basin of Europe, and parts of southern Africa.  Half of all North
American ducks breed in prairie pothole wetlands that could disappear as a result of global 
warming.                                  
<p>
The species affected read like a Peterson's Field Guide of the world's most famous birds -- mallard, pintail, plover, 
warbler, bittern, snipe and oriole.  Jeff Price of the American Bird Conservancy has run computer models that show a 
climate-induced loss of numerous songbirds around the Great Lakes and the loss of the Baltimore Oriole from most of its 
current range in the southern and mid-Atlantic states, possibly including Baltimore.
<p>
"Baltimore without orioles is like Canada without geese," Markham said.  "Even if many of these bird species shift their 
range to accommodate global warming, there is no guarantee of suitable habitat in the new areas.  Many species return to the 
exact same spot year after year for the very reason that conditions there are perfect for them."
<p>
So what can be done?
<p>
Markham suggests the developed world look closely at its fossil fuel emissions.  The US recently agreed to binding agreements 
on carbon emission reductions; the auto industry is taking a look at alternative fuels vehicles, and builders and insurers 
are revisiting solar energy and reevaluating the cost to society of increasingly violent weather patterns.  
<p>
"Individuals can look at how much they consume, and how efficient are their houses," Markham added.  "Telecommuting is 
becoming more popular, and many individuals are discovering  that not only do compact fluorescent light bulbs save the 
environment, but they save money as well. When you combine saving money and saving the environment, everyone comes out a 
winner."
<p>
For more inforamtion, please contact  Lee Poston at +1  (202)778-9536. Bird-call audiotape and slides are also 
available.                   

 </table> <p> <a href="/graphics/toolbar.map">
<img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
