</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>MARINE AREA- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>

 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
For Release: 6 November, 1995<BR>
 

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><H2>
<CENTER>WWF Calls for a Global Network of Marine Protected Areas</CENTER>
</H2>
<BR>
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>GLAND, Switzerland</B> -- WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature urges
governments at the second meeting of the Biological Diversity
Convention in Jakarta (6-17 November) to establish a global network
of Marine Protected Areas. Such a network will be essential to
conserve the world's marine and coastal ecosystems.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;The challenge for governments at Jakarta is to start the
process for a global network of Marine Protected Areas (MPAs),&quot;
said Nancy Vallejo, WWF's Coordinator of International Treaties.
&quot;These MPAs could serve as spawning and nursery areas for
the world's declining commercial fish stocks, and as models for
conflict resolution and eco-tourism. Most importantly, MPAs can
be crucial links in preserving the overall biological processes
of the marine environment.&quot;<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
WWF believes that a chain of integrated Marine Protected Areas
can be effective in promoting sustainable use of resources in
the marine environment, which envelopes 70 per cent of our planet.
The importance of the MPAs extends beyond their worth as fisheries
management areas, sanctuaries for endangered whales and turtles,
or recreational parks. In fact, MPAs can act as insurance against
unpredictable environmental trends, including global climate change.
They can also serve as control areas for scientific research and
monitoring. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
In a series of papers prepared for the Conference, WWF outlines
some of the essential first steps that need to be taken at international,
regional and national levels, to restore the health of the marine
and coastal environment. The recommendations include the setting
up of experts panels, adopting an integrated approach to marine
and coastal zone management, selecting MPA sites and national
biodiversity planning. WWF has also proposed mechanisms to address
global and regional fisheries crisis through international and
regional fisheries bodies. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The present loss of marine biological diversity is unprecedented
and alarming. The most direct threats to marine ecosystems and
biological diversity come from overexploitation of marine resources,
destructive resource extraction practices, land-based pollution,
toxic discharges and ocean dumping. A dramatic example is the
killing of coral reef fishes using explosives: a single blast
can decimate hundreds of years of cumulative reef development
and can preclude regeneration of reefs in the vicinity of the
explosion. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
......<I>more<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</I>-2-<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Other destructive practices include mining live coral, the use
of poison for fishing, long lining, drift netting, bottom trawling,
and the disposal of hazardous wastes. Moreover, coastlines are
being altered by growing urban and industrial landscapes, and
mangrove forests cleared for agriculture and shrimp farming. Over
70 per cent of the world's population lives in the coastal zones.
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;On land, we have finally realized the destructive effects
of our activities and are moving towards more ecologically sustainable
practices. Unfortunately, we have not really begun to make this
transition in the marine environment,&quot; said Ms Vallejo. &quot;The
Convention on Biological Diversity is the best place to trigger
national actions. The sooner that is done, the better.&quot; 
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Other WWF papers for the Jakarta Conference focus on Biosafety,
Protected Areas, Forests, Toxic Threats, Air Pollution, Land-based
Sources of Marine Pollution , Intellectual Property Rights, and
Benefit-sharing Agreements and Transfer of Technology.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
-End- <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For more information, please call Someshwar Singh at +41 22 364
9553 and during Conference at +62 21 570 3600 or fax +62 21 573
3089. For requests for WWF documents, please call Delwyn Dupuis
at +41 22 364 9517 or fax +41 22 364 8219.<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
