<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EXTINCT" PHEASANT FOUND IN VIETNAM
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>
<p>
<center>
<font size=4><b>
"EXTINCT" PHEASANT FOUND IN VIETNAM
</b>
</font>
</center>
<p>
<b>GLAND, Switzerland</b> -- A pheasant species scientists
thought extinct in the wild has been found in central Vietnam.
WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature project staff working in
Bach Ma National Park and local officials confirmed that two
Edwards's pheasants (Lophura edwardsi) were caught just
days ago. Villagers found a male and a female, and brought
them to the Forest Guard Station in Phong Dien District.
Unfortunately, the female has since died due to injury
sustained while being caught.
<p>

The last known collection of a live specimen was in 1928.
Three scientific expeditions conducted between 1988 and
1994 failed to find any specimen nor even sight them.  This
latest find comes close on the heels of the scientific
discoveries of the saola (Pseudoryx nghetinhensis) and giant
muntjac (Megamuntiacus vuquangensis) in northern
Vietnam's Vu Quang Nature Reserve in 1992 and 1994
respectively.
<p>

"This is yet another feather in the cap for conservation in
Vietnam," says Dawood Ghaznavi, Asia/Pacific Programme
Director at WWF International. "Rediscovering this pheasant
after 70 years means mankind has a second chance to save
this exquisite bird and its habitat." 
<p>
	
The Edwards's pheasant is found only in Vietnam. It was
already considered rare in 1923 when French ornithologist
Jean Delacour brought 15 back to Paris. Until then, the
species had only been known to science from four skins sent
in 1895 to the National Museum of Natural History in Paris.
<p>

The bird's habitat is very wet forest, much of which has been
destroyed. Bach Ma, with Vietnam's wettest and lushest
forests, is considered to be the only protected area where
some population of the species could exist. The park is also
said to harbour seven pheasant species, out of a total of 12
in Vietnam and 23 in Southeast Asia. The search for the
Edwards's pheasant was renewed recently after local
villagers reportedly sighted the pheasant. Earlier this year,
villagers found a threatened species of pheasant, the
Siamese fireback (Lophura diardi). 
<p>

"We are elated the Edwards's pheasants were found as this
signifies that the probability of an existing wild population is
high," says WWF Bach Ma project executant Roland Eve.
"The find is mainly thanks to the good cooperation between
project staff and the local provincial network of forest guards."
 
<p>

We now have plans to increase the number of forest guards
who will be patrolling the area," adds Hoang Ngoc Khanh,
Director of the Thua Thien-Hue Province Forest Protection
Department. "This, along with the public awareness
campaign, should increase the chances that the pheasant
will survive in the wild."
<p>

Bach Ma National Park was a favourite summer resort during
the French colonial period. Portions of the 22,000-hectare
park were severely affected by defoliants sprayed during the
Vietnam war and logging. These are now slowly recovering
with concerted planting programmes and reforestation efforts.
Over 500 floral species, including several valuable timber
species, at least 55 mammal species, and some 300 bird
species have been recorded here. A recent WWF-sponsored
survey by the Vietnam Russian Tropical Centre has so far
identified 176 species of butterflies. Several are likely to be
new to science and some newly recorded in Vietnam.
<p>

Nearly 78,000 people live around the park. Many still depend
on  forests for subsistence. WWF's project, funded by the
European Commission, involves the local communities in
conserving the park's resources. Project activities include
helping the authorities develop an ecotourism plan and
sustainable community development schemes, training park
protection staff, and collecting data on the park's rich animal
and plant life. 
<p>
More information with David Hulse at Hanoi +84-4 822 0640
or Chng Soh Koon  at Gland +41-22 364 9326  
<p>
<font size=-1>
In the US and Canada, WWF is referred to as the World Wildlife Fund.
</font>

</table>

<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
