<HEAD>
<TITLE>Harpoons Not the Only Threat to Whales</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>

<center>

<H2>
The International Whaling Commission (IWC) 1996
<br>
Harpoons Not the Only Threat to Whales
</H2>

</center>

<P>
It is ten years since the International Whaling Commission imposed a moratorium on commercial whaling. WWF and a majority of 
IWC member governments believe that the moratorium must be maintained and respected. However, the pro-whaling lobby - 
spearheaded by just two countries: Japan and Norway - is not  yet  losing steam.  Meanwhile, evidence is growing of 
additional  threats to whales -- from marine pollution , habitat degradation, depleted stocks of prey species, ozone 
depletion and climate change. Of concern is the threat to whales from persistent organochlorine chemicals such as PCBs and 
DDT.    
<ul>
WWF will be presenting the following documents at IWC:
<p>

1. <a href="http://www.panda.org/news/press/news_53b.htm">Position Statement: on Whaling and the IWC: 1996 IWC Annual Meeting</a>
<br>
2. <a href="http://www.panda.org/news/press/iwc2.htm">A paper on Protecting Cetaceans from Toxic pollutants.</a>
<br>
3. <a href="http://www.panda.org/research/fishfile2/frontpg.htm">The new report  Marine Fishes in the Wild.  </a>
<br>
4. <a href="http://www.panda.org/research/w-whales/page1.htm">Species Status report  Whales in the Wild </a>
<br>
5. <a href="http://www.panda.org/news/press/page6.htm">Prospective climate change impacts on cetaceans and its
            implications for the conservation of whales and dolphins</A>
  <br>
6. A new report by TRAFFIC on whale-meat trade in SE Asia. 
</ul>

A 25-minute Video News Release entitled  "Whales Polluted To Death?" has been prepared for the IWC 1996. 		
<p>
	The annual meeting of the International Whaling Commission lasts from June 24 until June 28. The WWF opening press 
statement for the IWC 1996 is embargoed for 20 June, 1996 while the Video News Release is  <b>embargoed until the inaugural day 
of the IWC meeting  - 24 June, 1996.</b>
<p>

	The WWF team members include Cassandra Phillips, Gordon Shepherd, Anne Marie Mikkelson, Stig Hvoslev, James 
Martin-Jones, Ginette Hemley, Lucy Farmer,  Dana West and Someshwar Singh.
<p>
	The IWC 96 will meet at Aberdeen, Scotland. The WWF team can be contacted  in Aberdeen at +44 1224 827 672 or fax +44 
1224 827 491.
<p>
	Though one third of the world's oceans in the southern hemisphere provide a  sanctuary to all whales, large-scale 
Japanese "scientific" whaling continues in those waters. This is despite two 1995 IWC Resolutions which recommended that 
scientific whaling should only be permitted in "exceptional circumstances", and that 
it should not be permitted in sanctuaries. Meanwhile, Norway has almost doubled the                      
number of whales it permits to be hunted, in defiance of IWC regulations.
<p>



For more information, please call Someshwar Singh at +41 22 364 9553 or fax 364 8307.  
<P>


<br>

</blockquote>

<center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" 
border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For 
Nature</i></h6></center>
