<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Last Whalers Still Holding Out</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>

<center>

<H2>
The Last Whalers Still Holding Out
</H2>

</center>

<P>
<b>GLAND, Switzerland </b>-- The annual meeting of the International Whaling Commission this year in Aberdeen (June 24-28) 
marks a 
full decade of the international ban on commercial whaling. But Japan and Norway are still holding out - the only two 
countries still engaged in large-scale killing of whales. Between them, they will have killed almost 1000 minke whales this year.
<p>

"For the IWC, the challenge is to enforce its own decisions," said Cassandra Phillips, WWF's Whale Coordinator. "If that was 
done, Japan could not possibly continue large-scale `scientific' whaling in the Antarctic region (declared a whale sanctuary 
since 1994), nor Norway announce big minke whale kill-quotas in defiance of the IWC moratorium ."
<p>

In the name of "scientific whaling", Japan is hunting 440 minke whales from the Antarctic and 100 from the North Pacific this 
year. This is despite a 1995 IWC resolution which recommends that scientific whaling should only be permitted in "exceptional 
circumstances", and that it should not be allowed in sanctuaries.
<p>

Norway, on the other hand, gave its whalers a quota of 425 for this season early last month even before the IWC could examine 
the population estimates. Only last year, the IWC's Scientific Committee ruled that the Norwegian estimate of the NE Atlantic 
minke whale stocks were not valid and therefore provided no scientific basis for setting any whaling quota. In 1995, an IWC 
resolution called on Norway to "halt immediately all whaling activities under its jurisdiction."
<p>
 
Other rules are also being flouted by the whalers. For instance, trade in whalemeat is illegal under both Norwegian and 
Japanese law. But only recently, Japanese customs authorities seized a 6-ton shipment of whalemeat smuggled from Norway, 
passing under the label of mackerel.
<p>

"Harpoons, however, are not the only threat to whales," continued Ms. Phillips. "The mysterious series of mass die-offs of 
marinal mammals, including whales, which started in the 1980s continues. But the mystery may be close to being solved. 
Autopsies of dead whales have revealed high levels of chemicals such as PCBs (polychlorinated biphenyls)."
<p>

The evidence is growing of additional threats to whales. These include marine pollution, habitat degradation, ozone 
depletion, and climate change. Of particular concern is the evidence that even extremely low levels of persistent 
organochlorine chemicals such as PCBs and DDT are increasing disease and decreasing fertility. If that continues, apparently 
stable whale populations could crash with very little warning. 
<p>

"The IWC Aberdeen meeting will be another battle in the long war to bring whaling under control," Ms. Phillips stated. WWF 
and a majority of the IWC member governments strongly believe that the moratorium on commercial whaling must be maintained 
and respected.

<p> 
For more information, please call Someshwar Singh at +41 22 364 9553 or fax 3648307. During the IWC meeting, please call WWF 
office at +44 1224 827 672 or fax +44 1224 827 491.
<p>


<br>
</blockquote>

<center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" 
border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For 
Nature</i></h6></center>
