<HEAD>
<TITLE>
BIRTH OF SEVEN NEW MOUNTAIN GORILLAS AN ENCOURAGING SIGN
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>
<CENTER><B>
<h2>Birth of Seven New Mountain Gorillas an Encouraging Sign, Says WWF</h2> 
</B></CENTER>
<P>
<b>GLAND, Switzerland</b> -- The birth of seven baby mountain gorillas
in the last three months in Rwanda is a hopeful sign of stability
and recovery for one of Africa's most endangered animal species,
WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature said today.<BR>

<P>
Officials from the International Gorilla Conservation Programme
(IGCP) -- a conservation initiative jointly supported by the African
Wildlife Foundation, Fauna and Flora International and WWF --
have registered the births of seven young gorillas at Rwanda's
Volcano National Park, bordering with Za&iuml;re's Virunga National
Park and Uganda's Mgahinga Gorilla National  Park. <BR>

<P>
The infants were born to two different groups designated with
the names of &quot;Pablo&quot; and &quot;Susa&quot;. Both groups
have been habituated and studied for several years.   <BR>

<P>
&quot;It is very encouraging to register such a high number of
births, given all the bad incidents that took place last year
in this area,&quot; said Annette Lanjouw,  Regional Coordinator
for IGCP.  It is believed that 8 mountain gorillas were killed
during 1995 by poachers  using spears and military fire weapons,
following a 10-year period in which no gorillas had been poached.
<BR>

<P>
Since last April, four young gorillas -- &quot;Tamu&quot; (meaning
&quot;sweet&quot; in the local language, Kinyarwandan), &quot;Bikereri&quot;
and &quot;Mitimbili&quot; (locations were these two were found),
and &quot;Gusangira&quot; (meaning &quot;sharing&quot;) -- were
born to the &quot;Pablo&quot; group, one of three groups habituated
for study by the late pioneer researcher Dian Fossey.<BR>

<P>
In the same period, three new babies were born to the &quot;Susa&quot;
group, the largest of the groups habituated for tourism since
the 1980's.  These were named &quot;Muganga&quot; (meaning &quot;doctor&quot;),
&quot;Kwiyunga&quot; (meaning &quot;reconciliation&quot;) and
&quot;Getty&quot;, in reference to the J. Paul Getty Wildlife
Conservation Prize, awarded earlier this year to the wardens at
the Parc National des Volcans for their courage and dedication
during the Rwandan Civil War.<BR>

<P>
&quot;Fortunately, all mothers and infants seem to be in good
condition&quot;, added Lanjouw.   In spite of the destruction
related to the civil war, gorilla research efforts in Rwanda have
been restored almost to their pre-war levels.  A new park headquarters
now stands where the old office -- destroyed during the war --
 used to be, and land mines are being painstakingly searched at
Volcano National Park by the Rwandan Patriotic Army, with financing
from IGCP.<BR>

<P>
For more information, please contact Annette Lanjouw in Nairobi,
Kenya, at +254 2 710 0367 or Javier Arreaza in Gland, Switzerland,
at +41 22 364 9550.





</blockquote> <center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
