<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>COMMERCIAL LOGGERS IN GUYANA- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>

 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
For release 27 February 1995 <BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><CENTER><H2>Commercial Loggers Threaten Guyana's Wilderness</H2></CENTER><BR>
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>GLAND, Switzerland</B> -- WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature warned
today that commercial logging schemes in Guyana threaten to destroy
some of the world's most unspoiled forests and rob indigenous
people of their birthright.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Guyana is in debt, and the only way it can see to solve its financial
problems is to cash in its natural assets. The government has
therefore started to sell off huge logging concessions. Of the
country's 16 million hectares of forest cover, 9.4 million hectares
have been licensed for logging. Half this area has gone to foreign
companies.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Barama is a Malaysian and South-Korean owned-timber company which
has been granted a concession half the size of Belgium. Guyana
itself benefits little from the deal -- last year the country
earned just US$50,000 in royalties on the millions of dollars
worth of timber Barama exported. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The story is much the same in neighbouring Suriname, where foreign
loggers await government approval for massive 1-million-hectare
concessions.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Some of the harshest criticism comes from local Amerindians,who
are outraged by the sell-outs. Many have only recently discovered
that the forest lands they have farmed and hunted for generations
have been licensed to foreign companies.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;We are on the verge of a major economic, social, and ecological
crisis,&quot; said Henk Reichart, a WWF consultant working in
Suriname. &quot;These are major companies and they are looking
for new areas to exploit. Guyana and Suriname have been very easy
victims.&quot;<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
-Ends-<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For further information, contact Sarah Russell on tel +41 22 364
9574. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

