<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Theft of Endangered Tortoises a Severe Blow to Species, says WWF</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>
EMBARGOED until Saturday, 11 May, 0800 GMT
<p>

<center>

<h2>Theft of Endangered Tortoises<br> 
 A Severe Blow to Species, says WWF</h2>

</center>

<P>
<b>GLAND, Switzerland</B> - The campaign to save a rare tortoise from extinction has suffered a grave setback with the theft 
of nearly half the hatchlings from the only breeding group in captivity, the World Wide Fund For Nature (WWF) announced today.

<p>

The ploughshare tortoise of Madagascar is the target of a species recovery programme mounted by the Jersey Wildlife 
Preservation Trust and the Department of Waters and Forests of Madagascar with the support of WWF.  The only breeding centre, 
established in northwest Madagascar ten years ago, has produced 162 young to date.  During the night of 6 May, 74 youngsters 
and two adult females were stolen from their locked compound surrounded by a chain-link fence.

<p>

It is believed that the animals are destined for the international blackmarket trade in endangered species.  The Department 
of Waters and Forests has alerted its agents in the main shipping ports and airports of Madagascar and TRAFFIC International 
(the wildlife trade monitoring unit of WWF and IUCN-The World Conservation Union) has alerted customs agents in 18 countries 
around the world.

<p>

"This is a major blow to the chances of survival of this species", said John Newby, Director of the WWF Africa/Madagascar 
Programme.  "We hope that customs authorities worldwide will do their utmost to help recover these priceless specimens."

<p>

The ploughshare tortoise is found only in a remote part of Madagascar and only a few hundred are left in the wild.  The 
components of the recovery programme include captive breeding, field research and environmental education campaigns.  

<p>

Adult ploughshare tortoises are easily recognised by the plough-shaped projection extending from the bottom shell under the 
chin.  They are the size of a small footstool and the shell is marked in dark brown and pale yellow.  At hatching, the 
tortoises are the size of a pingpong ball and their colours are similar to that of the adult, but the ploughshare does not 
become evident until they are about five years old.  The exact age of the stolen youngsters is not yet known, but the colony 
at the breeding station ranged from five months to seven years old.

<p>

Mr Mamy Razandrimamilafiniarivo, the Malagasy head of the breeding station, who is currently attending courses at the 
International Training Centre for the Breeding and Conservation of Endangered Species in Jersey, was shocked by news.
<p>
'I am devastated,' he said, 'that half the work of ten years could be wiped out so suddenly.'
<p>
-ENDS-
<p><font size =-1>
Lee Durrell, Jersey Wildlife Preservation Trust, Channel Islands (G.B.)
<br>Telephone: +44 1534 864 666
<br>Fax:       +44 1534 865 161
<br>E-mail:    ldexec@itl.net
<br>
<br>John Newby, Africa/Madagascar Programme, WWF International, Switzerland
<br>Telephone: +41 22 364 9261
<br>Fax: +41 22 364 4238

</font>

<P>
<br>
</blockquote>
