<HEAD>

<TITLE>NUCLEAR TESTING BY FRANCE- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>

 
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For release on Friday 4 August 1995<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Impact">
<H2><CENTER>WWF Urges France to Drop Nuclear Test Plans</CENTER></H2>
<BR>
</FONT>GLAND, Switzerland</B>--Fifty years after the world's first
nuclear bomb dropped on Hiroshima, WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature
calls on President Chirac of  France to reverse his decision to
conduct nuclear tests around the coral atoll of Mururoa in the
South Pacific.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The proposal is outrageous,&quot; said Dr Claude Martin,
Director General of WWF-International. &quot;France's international
status -- from both a political and environmental standpoint --
is at stake.  To regain credibility, the government  must drop
its plans to carry out dangerous experiments in this politically
vulnerable and biologically unique part of the world.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Anxiety  about the effects of nuclear radiation have haunted people
since the first atom bomb fell on Japan half a century ago. But
the international community has still not worked out how to deal
with the problem. Countries continue to argue about the best way
to dispose of waste from peaceful uses of radioactive material:
the products of these submarine tests are much less stable conditions
than any civil nuclear waste, and are therefore potentially far
more dangerous.<BR>
<BR>
The precise ecological impacts of the new tests are uncertain,
but conservationists are concerned that they  will affect deep-sea
and coral atoll ecosystems, marine life and birds, and the lives
of local people. Some scientists are concerned that radiation
could leak out, be absorbed by fish, and get passed into the foodchain,
threatening the health of the ecosystem, and  jeopardizing the
livelihoods of local people, many of whom support themselves and
their families by fishing.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Over the past decades, there has been a growing international
effort to help the small island countries in this region conserve
their natural environments, safeguard their wildlife, and develop
in a sustainable manner,&quot; said Peter Hunnam, WWF's South
Pacific Programme Representative. &quot;The nuclear tests will
make a mockery of this work.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
WWF's Fiji-based South Pacific programme  is involved in conservation
projects throughout the region, working to maintain fragile ecosystems
such as rainforests, mangroves, lagoons, and coral reefs. WWF
also supports local people's land rights claims, and helps communities
work out the best way to use natural resources such as shellfish,
seaweeds, and sea cucumbers without damaging the environment.
<BR>
<BR>
                                        -ENDS-<BR>
<BR>
For more information, contact the WWF International Press Office,
+41 22 364 9550 or +41 22 364 9552.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

