<HEAD>

<TITLE>SINO-INDIAN AGREEMENT TO SAVE TIGERS- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
3 March 1995
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><H2>
<CENTER>Unprecedented Sino-Indian Agreement to Save Tigers</CENTER>
</H2><BR>
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>GLAND, Switzerland</B> -- The Governments of the People's Republic
of China and India have agreed to work together in the fight to
save the world's dwindling tiger population. In addition, they
have vowed to share research and training facilities to improve
management of wild tigers and their shrinking habitats.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
This unprecedented agreement, signed in Beijing on Thursday, March
2, commits the two countries to put in place more internal controls
to stem the lucrative but illegal trade in tiger parts that is
helping to bring the species to the brink of extinction. As few
as 5000 tigers remain in the wild. Some tiger species are unlikely
to outlast the end of the century.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
China's participation is particularly important since, along with
other south east Asian countries, it has historically been the
world's largest consumer of tiger parts for medicinal purposes.
The country's own tiger population is down to about 80, mainly
in southern and northeast China. India, on the other hand, with
less than 4000 is home to the world's largest remaining wild tiger
population. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;This agreement is particularly important because China has
agreed to crack down on poaching, smuggling and illegal use of
tiger derivatives,&quot; said Judy Mills, Director of TRAFFIC
East Asia, a monitoring programme of WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature
and IUCN-The World Conservation Union. &quot;While China has made
sales of tiger products illegal, it is important that it now focus
on the black market within its borders.&quot;<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Small tiger populations exist in some other Asian countries. But
as a IUCN and WWF workshop held this week in Hanoi for specialists
from Cambodia, Laos, and Vietnam revealed, the animal's secretive
nature makes it very difficult to determine exact numbers. However,
trends in deforestation and illegal hunting in the area lead specialists
to believe that there may be fewer than 500 tigers in these countries.
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;The only real hope lies in the ability of all these countries
to crack down on illegal hunting and trade in tiger parts, as
well as in their will to protect tiger habitat,&quot; Dr Claude
Martin, Director General of WWF, declared. &quot;We also have
a long way to go to prevent the trade in tiger parts that takes
place elsewhere in the world. The agreement by India and China
is an important step in the right direction.&quot;<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
However, WWF and TRAFFIC are apprehensive about a clause in the
joint Sino - Indian protocol that encourages captive breeding
of tigers with a view towards releasing them into the wild. &quot;Tigers
are large carnivores that learn how to hunt wild game from their
mothers,&quot; observed Joanna Ruxton, senior conservation officer
for WWF Hong Kong. &quot;It is doubtful that captive-bred tigers
could be taught to hunt for food as they would in the wild. We
would prefer that China and India put their efforts into conserving
the tigers that remain in the wild.&quot;
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>-END-</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For more information, contact: Margaret Chan, Joanna Ruxton or
Judy Mills, at 2526-1011. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

