<HEAD>
<TITLE>MARINE FISHES ADDED TO LIST OF WORLD'S THREATENED ANIMALS - NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>
FOR RELEASE:  2 May 1996
<p>

<center>

<h2>Marine Fishes Added to List of World's Threatened Animals</h2>

</center>

<P>
<b>GLAND</b> - A workshop of 32 leading scientists has recommended adding more than 100 species of marine fishes to the 
global list of the world's most threatened animals. The workshop, jointly sponsored by the IUCN-The World Conservation Union, 
WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature, and the Zoological Society of London, ended yesterday in London.

<P>
 Participants in the workshop  examined 152 fishes and classified 131 as threatened. Of these, 15 species are considered 
'critically endangered'  and face imminent extinction unless  conservation action is taken immediately. The 1996 IUCN Red 
List of Threatened Animals will be released at the World Conservation Congress in Montreal in October.

<P>
The workshop's findings contrast sharply with the widely held view that marine fishes are inherently less threatened than 
terrestrial animals. The participants examined a wide range of fishes and found examples of threatened species throughout. 
For example, 26 of the world's 27 sturgeon species are threatened by the caviar trade and habitat loss. 

<P>
The great white shark, which is protected by only three countries (Australia, South Africa and the United States), is 
threatened by chronic overfishing for its fins--an ingredient of shark fin soup--and other products. 

<P>
Seahorses are considered vulnerable because of rapidly growing demand for traditional medicines in the Far East , the 
aquarium trade, and curios. Certain commercially-fished species such as Nassau grouper and southern bluefin tuna are 
considered threatened as a result of chronic overfishing.
<P>

"This is a very significant step," said Michael Sutton, director of WWF's Endangered Seas Campaign. "We are finally beginning 
to recognize that some fishes are as threatened as rhinos, tigers and elephants."

<p>
For more information, please call Michael Sutton at +44 1483 426444 or Mariano Gimenez-Dixon, IUCN at +41 22 999 0001, or 
Peter Cotgreave, Zoological Society of London at +44 171 449 6686 or Someshwar Singh at WWF International -+41 22 364 9553.

<p>
<br>
</blockquote>
<center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" 
border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For 
Nature</i></h6></center>
