<HEAD>
<TITLE>
ISO AND THE ENVIRONMENT: STORM CLOUDS GATHER
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>
<p>
<center>
<font size=4><b>
ISO AND THE ENVIRONMENT: STORM CLOUDS GATHER
</b>
</font>

<p>
</center>
<img src="/graphics/storm.jpg" align=left>A new report by WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature, entitled "ISO inside out - ISO and 
Environmental Management," says it is time 
for the Geneva-based  International Organization for Standardization (ISO) to settle the controversy it is fuelling with 
regards to the setting of environmental standards.
<p>
ISO's foray into the setting of environmental standards  is generating confusion. The WWF report highlights the 
following areas of concern:
<p>
<ul>
<li>The ISO 14001 standard on Environmental Management Systems (EMS) does not evaluate environmental impacts of the 
product, nor those of the process and production methods by which it was been created. Instead, it simply deals with the 
environmental management system of the producing company.
<p>
<li>Elements in the forest industry lobby have been pushing hard for the ISO to develop a sector-specific standard for 
application of the 14001 standard to the forestry sector.  
<p>
<li>ISO has no adequate mechanism to control the use or misuse of its own logos and marks of conformity (such as 14001 
standard).  This can lead to consumer confusion between EMS labels and product-based eco-labels (which do evaluate the 
environmental performance of a product or its production process).
<p>
<li>Developing countries are seriously under-represented, as are social and environmental NGOs in ISO meetings.  ISO 
standard-setting thus tends to be driven by the industry concerned. 
<p>
<li>The lack of transparency in the ISO process was recently enhanced by the adoption in June 1996 of a very 
restrictive policy which effectively bans media access to its meetings.     
</ul>
<p>
Though the international standardization movement (ensuring some uniformity in things like film sensitivity, the height 
of car bumpers or the size of screws) dates back to 1906, the ISO itself has a creditable track record since it was set 
up in 1947. The World Trade Organization (WTO) and the European Commission, among others,  recognise the ISO as a 
competent body for setting international standards.
<p>
However, WWF believes that ISO must address the above concerns to maintain its credibility.
<p>  
For more information, please call Charles Arden Clarke at +41 22 364 9513 or Someshwar Singh at +41 22 3649553.
</table> <p> <a 
href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
</BODY>
