<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EU Must Break Climate Change Paralysis
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">

<table width=580>
<td>
<br>

<CENTER><B> <FONT SIZE=5>
EU Must Break Climate Change Paralysis
<BR>
 
</FONT></B></CENTER><br>
<img src="/graphics/euclimate.jpg" align=right alt="winter sunset" hspace=5>
<b>Brussels, Belgium</b> - The EU must urgently develop a coherent Climate
Protection Strategy and implement measures to reduce CO2 emissions from the beginning of 1998 if
it is to meet its international obligations to combat climate change, WWF warned today.
<p>
A new WWF report, "Policies and Measures to Reduce CO2 Emissions by
Efficiency and Renewables" shows sector-by-sector how the EU can reduce its CO2 emissions.
By starting in 1998 with a range of proven policies and measures, the EU could cut these
emissions to 14% below 1990 levels by 2005. WWF is encouraging the EU to build on these
findings in order to meet a 20% reduction target by 2005 and satisfy demands for action by
nations which are most threatened by climate change.  
<p>
"The EU has a depressing record of missed opportunities on climate change
and no clear idea how it is going to tackle this problem in the future," says Andrew Kerr,
European coordinator of WWF's Climate Change Campaign. "Without Ministerial backing for an EU
climate protection strategy and firm emission targets, the EU will be unable to
combat the causes of climate change at home. And it will lose its ability to exert any leverage
on the international negotiations."
<p>
At their Council meeting on 9 and 10 December 1996, EU Environment Ministers
will decide the mandate for European Community negotiators involved in agreeing
legally-binding limitations in climate change gases from industrialised countries. More than
150 government will sign an agreement in Kyoto, Japan, in one year's time. 
<p>
The WWF report identifies how many millions of tonnes of CO2 can be avoided
in each sector of the European economy, primarily by introducing specific policies and
measures which were effective in one or more countries. Many of the measures should be
financially attractive for businesses. WWF therefore hopes to gain support from businesses for its
proposals.
<p>
The largest CO2 reductions are made in the residential sector, followed by
heavy industry, the transport sector, and the service sector. Just over two thirds of the
overall CO2 reduction comes from improving energy efficiency. Measures include energy performance
standards, economic incentives and subsidies, voluntary agreements, labelling and
information programmes, improved tariffs for certain goods and reductions in VAT. 
<p>
Contact: Martin Hiller, WWF European Policy Office, tel +32 2 743 8806


<p> </table> <p> <a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
</BODY>
