<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WWF Calls for Complete Overhaul of Commonwealth Fisheries Management
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>

<center>

<H2>
WWF Calls for Complete Overhaul of Commonwealth Fisheries Management
</H2>
</center>
<p>
At the start of the Second World Fisheries Congress being held in Brisbane, World wide Fund for Nature (WWF)-Australia has 
called for a complete overhaul of Commonwealth fisheries management in the light of a damning report by the 
Australian National Audit Office (ANAO).
<p>
"The ANAO report on the Australian Fisheries Management Authority (AFMA) released  in July makes disturbing 
reading", said WWF Australia CEO, Dr. David Butcher. "It is clear that Commonwealth fisheries management are in 
urgent need of reform - from the legislation right through to the complete overhaul of AFMA and its operations. The 
implication of the ANAO report is that  AFMA is unable to guarantee the sustainable management of Commonwealth 
fisheries as a result of serious structural, management and operational impediments."
<p>
"We are urging the Commonwealth Government to act immediately to implement measures to achieve sustainable 
fisheries practises in the lead up to a UN debate on marine issues scheduled for December.  There is an 
international imperative to address the problems of over-fishing and degradation of the marine environment 
following the signing of the UN Convention on the Law of the Sea and Australia must be at the forefront of these 
efforts."
<p>
"WWF is very concerned that no Environmental Impact Assessments have ever been carried out on commonwealth 
fisheries.  For example, experimental trawls for the extremely depleted Eastern Gemfish are being carried out 
without an Environmental Impact Assessment, contrary to advice received from the Commonwealth EPA. Similarly, a 
developmental fishing operations near Macquarie Island -- recently nominated by the Commonwealth Government for 
World Heritage Status -- have also been allowed to go ahead without an EIA. While we accept the need for research, 
the reasons for not carrying out an EIA should be made public."
<p>
WWF Australia has received more than 1000 signed postcards from concerned Australians calling on the Minister for 
Primary Industry to carry out massive changes in Commonwealth fisheries. These will be delivered to the Minister 
during the World Fisheries Congress. The postcards urge the Commonwealth to immediately ratify and implement the UN 
Fisheries Agreement.
<p>
"There is no doubt that fisheries will be one of the world's most important issues of the next decade for they not 
only imping dramatically upon the health of the marine environments but also upon the ability of the world to feed 
ever expanding population  and increased consumption patterns. At present, the state of Australia's fisheries as 
reported by the ANAO could fairly be described as a disgrace and international embarrassment", Dr. Butcher 
concluded.
<p>
<center><a href="news_60b.htm">ANAO Report on Commonwealth Fisheries Management</a></center>
<p>
<font size=-1>

For more information  please contact David Butcher, WWF Australia CEO on (0414) 917 297 or Desiree Sheehan, WWF 
Communications Manager on (02) 9299 6366.
<p>
The full name of the agreement is the UN Agreement for the Implementation of the Provisions of the United Nations 
Convention on the Law of the Sea of 10 December 1982 relating to the Conservation and Management of Straddling Fish 
Stocks and Highly Migratory Fish Stocks. There are well over 30 signatories to date. Australia has signed, but not 
yet ratified the Agreement.
</font>
</blockquote> <center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
</BODY>
