<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Australian National Audit Office Audit Report
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>

<center>

<H2>
Australian National Audit Office Audit Report

</H2>
</center>
<p>
The recently  released ANAO Performance Audit (the Report) on the Australian Fisheries Management Agency (AFMA) is highly 
critical of the Agency and its management of Australia's fisheries. With close to 40 substantive recommendations the report 
evidences the need for a major overhaul of the country's management regime and in doing so identifies six main areas in which 
AFMA's failings must be addressed as a matter of priority:
<p>
<ol>
<li>  The development of appropriate management policies and the criteria upon which such policies are to be guided.
<p>
<li>Formal assessment of the new and proposed Offshore Constitutional Settlement (OCS) Arrangements.
<p>
<li>  Review and revision of the now dated 1989 Fisheries Policy statement in the context of current and future 
requirements.
<p>
<li>  The need to ensure a conservation orientated decision making fisheries policy , through legislative amendment.
<p>
<li> Address the existing failings in the determination of catch and stock levels and the assessment of risks to 
individual fisheries.
<p>
<li> A review of the involvement of industry representatives and other interest groups in ensuring compliance with and 
enforcement of the fisheries management regime.

</ol>
<p>

In light of these findings and the recommendations laid down by the report, WWF Australia and Traffic (Oceania) require and 
urgent and complete overhaul of Australia's fisheries policy. In addressing the ANAO priorities the Commonwealth governments 
must:
<p><ol>
<li>  Recognise the severity of the findings of the ANAO and the urgent need to take action in order to protect 
Australia's national fisheries.
<p>
<li> Undertake a comprehensive review of all Australian legislative and policy arrangements, and in particular the new and 
proposed OCS agreements, with a view to ensuring the maximum level of coordination and efficiency in national management. 
This will include a review of the  role and abilities of AFMA and state based management agencies. 
<p>
<li> Establish  a clear ecologically sustainable framework for determining national fisheries policy and management direction 
that reflects international standards, expectations and commitments     for the protection and management of fish stocks 
including such instruments as the UN Fisheries     Agreement and its parent UNCLOS , as well as other international 
conservation principles.
<p>
<li>  Adopt measures and procedures to manage Australia's fishing industry in accordance with this framework that :
<ul>
<li>  Ensure an accurate assessment of stock levels and safe levels of exploitation based upon a precautionary approach;
<p>
<li>  Account for short, medium and long term needs and are capable of responding immediately to environmental threats 
or declines in stock levels.;
<p>
<li> Include mandatory procedures to ensure that all appropriate management decisions and             activities and subject 
to Commonwealth Environmental Impact Assessment; and 
<p>
<li>   Implement realistic mechanisms and controls to ensure compliance and where necessary         enforcement of fisheries 
policy. 
</ul>
<p>
<li> Ensure that all management decisions particularly with respect to the designation of research       priorities and 
enforcement requirements are made on an independent basis. This will further       require:
<ul>
<p> 
<li>   Reviewing the role to be played by industry in the determination of national management to        remove the potential 
for conflicts of interest and the potential for MAC's to place short term        interests over long term objectives; and 
<p>  
<li>  Ensuring that the views  of all stakeholders are adequately represented.  
 </ul>
</ol>
</blockquote> <center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
