<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WORLD TRADE ORGANISATION DEADLOCK THREATENS VITAL GLOBAL CONSERVATION AGREEMENTS
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF Position Statement">

<table width=580>
<td>
<br>

<CENTER><B> <FONT SIZE=5>
World Trade Organisation Deadlock Threatens Vital Global Conservation Agreements
<BR> </FONT></B></CENTER>

<P>
<img src="/graphics/building.jpg" alt="Indonesian girls" align=right>
<b>GENEVA, Switzerland</b> -- The World Trade Organisation's failure to confirm that its rules allow the use of trade 
measures to 
support international environmental agreements is now threatening the effectiveness of those agreements and, consequently, 
the global environment, WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature said on Tuesday.
<p>
Charles Arden-Clarke, Senior Policy Analyst at WWF International, accused the Committee on Trade and Environment of the WTO, 
of "having nothing to show" after more than two years of intensive work on this specific issue.  "There is a deadlock in the 
committee which threatens 30 years of progress on protection of the global environment," said Mr Arden-Clarke.  "This is 
simply unacceptable."
<p>
The Committee on Trade and Environment, which holds its last official meeting in Bern on October 24-25,  was formally set up 
in 1994 to tackle a range of trade and environment issues.  A specific priority was to define how the WTO relates to 
environmental agreements which call for trade measures in their implementation, such as the Convention on International Trade 
in Endangered Species (CITES) and the Montreal Protocol, which protects the ozone layer.
<p>
"Environmental NGO's present in meetings of existing conservation agreements and negotiations of new ones are now seeing a 
'chilling factor' emanating from the WTO," said Mr Arden-Clarke.  "Government delegations are refusing to discuss trade 
measures until the WTO has confirmed that trade measures are a legitimate tool for protecting the global environment."
<p>
The lack of progress of the committee is more regrettable, given that it first started work as a working group of the then 
General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs in 1991, following the US-Mexico tuna-dolphin dispute.  This showed clearly that GATT 
rules were too inflexible to take account of the environmental damage caused in the production of traded goods.  Tuna caught 
in a net killing large numbers of dolphins was exactly the same to the GATT as tuna caught in fishing lines, killing few, if 
any, dolphins.
<p>
At the present, trade measures in CITES and the Montreal Protocol specifically address environmental damages caused in the 
production of traded goods.  Without such trade measures, these agreements wouldn't work.
<p>
"We ask the WTO negotiators to break this dangerous deadlock before the WTO Ministerial Meeting in December in Singapore," 
said Arden-Clarke.  "The continuing uncertainty over trade measures is now damaging environmental agreements.  Neither our 
planet nor the global trading system can afford this."
<p>
For more information, please contact Connie Sidler at +41 1 297 2121, Javier Arreaza at  +41 22 364 9550 or fax +41 22 364 8307.



</table> <p> <a 
href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
</BODY>
