<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WWF PLANS OCT. 1ST LIVE TELEVISION LAUNCH
OF GLOBAL CAMPAIGN

</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF Media Advisory">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>WWF PLANS OCT. 1ST LIVE TELEVISION LAUNCH
OF GLOBAL CAMPAIGN</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B>POLITICAL AND BUSINESS LEADERS, CELEBRITIES TO PARTICIPATE</B></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=2>RELEASE OF THREE REPORTS IN SEPTEMBER
FRAMES URGENCY<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
On October 1st, some of the world's foremost environmental leaders,
political figures, business leaders and well-known celebrities
will take part in the launch of a major global environmental campaign,
in a television news conference broadcast live from London via
satellite around the world.  WWF - the world's most respected
environmental organization - will unveil <B>WWF 2000: The Living
Planet Campaign</B>, a multi-year initiative aimed at preserving
the diversity of life on earth into the 21st century.<BR>

<P>
WWF 2000 represents the most ambitious undertaking ever planned
by the global environmental organization, which is marking its
35th anniversary this year.  The campaign will link individuals
from all walks of life, and from countries in every hemisphere,
to a specific set of actions and activities aimed at reversing
the degradation of  the environment.  WWF has identified specific,
science-based goals for the three most critical areas of environmental
protection by the year 2000: protecting vital endangered spaces,
saving cherished endangered species, and changing global markets
that threaten earth's biodiversity.<BR>

<P>
<B>WHAT</B>:      <B>WWF 2000:  The Living Planet Campaign</B>
<P>
 A press conference to:
<UL>
<LI>launch the landmark campaign,
<LI>unveil the specific campaign goals,
<LI>mark announcement of major WWF 2000 commitments by several
world government leaders, international corporation executives,
and well-known figures from the entertainment industry; and
<LI>premiere a new music video by an international rock music
legend.
</UL>

<P>

<P>
<B>WHERE</B>:<br>
      British Academy Of Film and Television Arts
(BAFTA)
<br>
  195 Piccadilly<br>
<FONT SIZE=6 COLOR=#FFFFFF> </FONT>London W1
<p>
<B>WHEN</B>:<br>
 October 1, 1996<br>
 11:00 AM GMT<BR>

<P>
<B>WORLDWIDE TELECAST</B> <BR>

<P>
The press conference will be broadcast live via satellite to the
nearly 30 WWF national organizations around the world.  Plans
are underway for simultaneous press conferences around the world,
focusing on how the WWF national organizations will implement
the campaign's goals.<BR>

<P>
<B>CAMPAIGN COUNTDOWN<BR>
</B>
<P>
During the month of September, WWF will release three major environmental
reports that help to underscore the need for the Living Planet
Campaign:<BR>

<P>
Sept. 9th <U>World Forests at Risk</U>: study and worldwide map
showing the  
<P>
  increasing percentage of the world's forest that is unprotected.
<P>
 A Geneva press conference is scheduled; material available via
fax worldwide, and through WWF's World Wide Web page (www.panda.org).
 <I>Interview opportunities</I>.<BR>

<P>
Sept. 19th <U>No Safe Landing</U>: study showing the effects of
climate change on the patterns of migratory birds.  A Washington,
DC, press conference is scheduled; material available via fax
and on WWF's Web page.  <I>Interview opportunities</I>.<BR>

<P>
<I>Interview opportunities</I>. <BR>

<P>
<B>CONTACT<BR>
</B>
<P>
For more information, call the WWF 2000 Campaign Operations Office
at  
<P>
+31 20 520 7533<BR>

<P>
<B> </B>


