<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>CONSERVATION OF VU QUANG- NEWS RELEASE</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
For release on 12 June 1995 <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><H2><CENTER>Boost for Conservation of Vu Quang</CENTER></H2><BR>
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>HANOI, Vietnam</B> -- WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature today
welcomed the joint commitment made by the Vietnamese and Dutch
governments for forest protection in Vietnam, in particular the
Vu Quang Nature Reserve. The Reserve is home to the recently discovered
<I>sao la</I> (<I>Pseudoryx nghetinhensis</I>) and giant muntjac
(<I>Megamuntiacus vuquangensis</I>).<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Vietnam's Minister of Forestry Nguyen Quang Ha and Netherlands
Ambassador to Vietnam D.A.V.E. Ader, today signed a statement
to the effect in the presence of both countries' Prime Ministers.
Dutch Premier Mr Wim Kok is on a ??-day visit to Vietnam. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The signing formally initiates the Vu Quang Nature Conservation
Project, to be implemented by WWF in collaboration with Vietnam's
Ministry of Forestry. It will be funded by the Netherlands's Directorate
General for International Cooperation (DGIS). <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The five-year project aims to provide a balance between conservation
and development in Vu Quang. It recognizes that protecting the
reserve also means addressing the needs of the 20,000 people living
in and around the reserve. Most of these people are farmers, who
supplement their income with hunting mainly wild pigs and the
common muntjac, besides the giant muntjac. Although the <I>sao
la</I> is not commonly hunted, it occasionally falls into the
hunter's trap. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The Conservation Project activities will include developing sustainable
economic schemes David, maybe we should give one or two egs? If
so, can you please provide? for the local communities and formulating
land-use plans for the seven local communes within Vu Quang. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Located in northern Vietnam, Vu Quang has one of the country's
richest and most pristine forests. It made world headlines in
May 1992 when a team of WWF and Ministry of Forestry scientists
discovered the goat-like <I>sao la.</I> Again in April 1994 a
similar team discovered the giant muntjac, called that because
it is twice the size of the Indian muntjac (<I>Muntiacus muntjak</I>),
till then the world's largest. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Since the <I>sao la</I>'s discovery, the Vietnamese Government
has enlarged the reserve from 16,000ha to almost 60,000ha, and
imposed logging and hunting bans. WWF has been helping to protect
the reserve by setting up guard posts, training protection staff,
and promoting conservation awareness among the local communities.
It has also helped develop a management plan for the reserve.
The Vu Quang Nature Conservation Project will supplement these
conservation efforts. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
-End-<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For more information and/or a copy of the joint statement, please
contact David Hulse, WWF Indochina Office in Hanoi at tel: (+84-4)
266 368. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

