<HEAD>
<TITLE>Norway's Subsidised Whale Hunt is Out of IWC Control</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>

<P>

<center>

<H2>
Norway's Subsidised Whale Hunt is Out of IWC Control
</H2>

</center>

<P>
<b> ABERDEEN, Scotland</b>-- As the International Whaling Commission's 1996 annual meeting opens in Aberdeen Scotland today, Norway, conducting commercial whaling against the wishes of the IWC, is preparing for further increases in their self-awarded hunt
ing quota.

<p>

In February this year, long before the IWC's Scientific Committee considered population estimates for the North East Atlantic minke whales, Norway's Commissioner promised his whalers an increase in quota. The whalers had a quota of 232 in 1995, which was 
almost doubled to 425 in May this year.

<p>

The IWC Scientific Committee has now reluctantly agreed that the Norwegian estimate of 118,000 based on their 1995 survey is "adequate" for use in the Revised Management Procedure (part of the Commission's most recent management plan, which is not being i
mplemented because the IWC's moratorium is in force), although they say a number of points still need to be resolved. However, the Committee has also accepted as adequate an estimate of 67,500 for the same population of whales based on a 1989 survey. 

<p>

"The difference between these estimates has not yet been explained. Whale populations cannot possibly grow at such a rate" said Cassandra Phillips, WWF's whaling coordinator. "It seems clear that the Committee does not really know how many whales there ar
e in this population. These are entirely Norwegian estimates; the data were collected by observers paid by Norway, three quarters of whom were whalers, calculations were done by the Norwegian computer centre and the computer programme needs more tests" sa
id Phillips. 

<p>

Before these latest figures, Norway had put forward no fewer than seven estimates in the last 15 months, ranging from 69,600 to 112,000.

<p>

Last year's Scientific Committee dismissed Norway's long-standing estimate of 86,700 because bugs were found in the computer programme. Norway had used this estimate to justify their return to commercial whaling in 1992.  Since the errors were revealed, N
orway has poured several million dollars into a new survey and an improved computer programme.
<p>
"The IWC's Revised Management Procedure (RMP) does not simply use the latest estimate" said Vassili Papastavrou, a member of the IWC Scientific Committee. "It averages the estimates fed into it from successive surveys, so in order to return to the region 
of 86,700 Norway needed a new higher estimate of well over 100,000." As long as the moratorium is in force, no one is authorised to use the IWC's RMP for calculating quotas.

<p>

The whale meat market in Norway has now collapsed. Norwegian news reported two weeks ago that only 56 of 202 whales caught this year had been sold. Meat from last year's hunt equivalent to at least 30 whales was still in cold storage when the 1996 hunt be
gan.

<p>

Norway's Fish Sales Association is subsidising purchase of whale meat in order to keep the hunt alive. They have also announced a million kroner marketing drive to increase domestic acceptance of whale meat. As well as the several million dollar 1995 whal
e survey the Norwegian government has spent several more million dollars on public relation firms in the US, UK and elsewhere.

<p>

"Norway is spending much more than it is making" said Phillips.  "We are afraid they  want a return to the high catch levels of before the moratorium - the levels which depleted this population."

<p>
 
Norway's whalers are demanding that they be allowed to export whale meat to the lucrative Japanese market and are also demanding further increases in their quota, up to 1,800 whales a year. 

<p>

Norway rightly promotes international solutions to international problems, but apparently not when its own interests are involved" said Phillips. "Norway should agree to abide by the decisions of the International Whaling Commission and halt its whaling."



<p>


For more information please call Cassandra Phillips or Lucy Farmer or Dana West or Someshwar Singh at +44 1224 827 672 or fax +44 1224 827 491.

<p>


<br>
</blockquote>

