<HEAD>
<TITLE>EU To Push Green Timber Certification</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases">
</center>
<blockquote>


<P>

<center>

<H2>
EU To Push Green Timber Certification
</H2>

</center>

<P>

<B>BRUSSELS, Belgium</b> -- The European Union should publicly support independent
certification of sustainably managed forests within and outside its fifteen Member States,
WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature said today. 
<p>
The forests of the world are rapidly disappearing. Between 1980 and 1990, 17 million
hectares of tropical forests alone were destroyed annually, an area almost five times the
size of Belgium. Worldwide, the biggest individual cause for the destruction of forests rich
in biodiversity is commercial timber exploitation.
<p>

"Many European timber companies have joined with WWF, other NGOs and indigenous
peoples to create the Forest Stewardship Council as a tool to counter this enormous
threat," says Claude Martin, Director General of WWF International. "But we need the
support of the EU to help get certified wood into the shops."
<p>

WWF supports independent forest certification under the control of the Forest Stewardship
Council (FSC), as this creates an incentive for improved forest management and gives the
customer accurate environmental information.
<p>

"The EU is one of the world's largest markets for timber, and the public in Europe is very
concerned about the destruction of forests," said Claude Martin.  To meet its
responsibilities, the EU should support activities which enhance supply and demand of
certified wood within and outside the Union. WWF believes that the legal instruments
necessary are already in place. What is needed is the commitment and financing to bring
these projects into reality. 
<p>

Since 1990, principles and criteria for good forest management have been established
through a worldwide consultative process. On this basis, the FSC was set up in 1993 as an
independent organisation. It accredits certification programmes worldwide on a voluntary
basis. To date, four certifiers have been accredited and  2.3 m hectares certified.
<p>

To promote FSC-approved certification, WWF and FSC cooperate with retailers (eg. in
UK, Netherlands), with private forest owners (Germany, Sweden), with importers and
traders (Belgium), and with governments and aid agencies (EU, Poland).- ends -
<p>

CONTACT:  Martin Hiller, tel +32 2 347 3612, or at the seminar, +32 2 274 7009
<P>



<br>

</blockquote>

<center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" 
border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For 
Nature</i></h6></center>
