<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WWF TO RELEASE GROUNDBREAKING MIGRATORY BIRD STUDY 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" 
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">

<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF Position Statement">

<p>
<table width=580>
<td>
<CENTER><B> <FONT SIZE=5>
WWF TO RELEASE GROUNDBREAKING MIGRATORY BIRD STUDY 
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
A breakthrough study identifying 15 migratory bird sites around the world - ranging from the United States to China - which 
are severely threatened by global climate change will be released by WWF - World Wide Fund for Nature, the international 
conservation organization.  The study highlights the potential consequences of ignoring the imminent threats of global 
climate change to migratory birds and their habitats.  Release of the study by WWFs Global Climate Change initiative sets a 
precedent for future exploration into specific climate changes which threaten the existence of migratory birds worldwide.  
The Global Climate Change initiative will be a major focus of WWF 2000: The Living Planet Campaign, WWFs largest ever 
conservation action campaign. 
<P>
The study will be released during a Washington, D.C. briefing on 19 September by WWF and a panel of experts on global 
warming, bird migration and sea-level rise.  The panel will include: Adam Markham, Director, WWF Climate Change initiative; 
Dr. Stephen Leatherman, Director, University of Maryland Laboratory on Coastal Research; Brian Harrington, Manomet 
Observatory and author of "Flight of the Red Knot;" and, Jeff Price, American Bird Conservancy.
<P>
WWF 2000: The Living Planet Campaign is a multi-year initiative aimed at conserving the diversity of life on Earth into the 
21st century.  WWF 2000 will be launched on 1 October in a global teleconference broadcast live from London to more than 30 
countries around the world. The televised launch event will feature the participation of worldwide political, business, 
conservation and entertainment figures.  It will be available live via satellite to media worldwide.
<P>
<b>WHAT:</b>Global Climate Change Migratory Bird Study Release<br>
A breakfast briefing to:<br>
<li>Announce WWFs breakthrough migratory bird study<br>
<li>Release a full colour map and report with detailed information on the 15 critical sites identified by the study.<p>

<b>WHERE:</b>	Old Ebbitt Grill - Cabinet Room<br>
		675 15th Street, NW<br>
		Washington, DC  20005<p>		

<b>WHEN:</b>	September 19, 1996<br>
		9:45 AM - 11:00 AM (EDT)<br>

<b>CONTACT:</b><br>
Lee Poston, WWF Global Climate Change, +001 202 778 9536 for more information on the migratory birds study.<br>
For more information on WWF 2000: The Living Planet Campaign, contact the Campaign Operations Office at +31 20 520 7533.<p>

<b>NOTE:</b> 
Global Climate Change and WWF 2000: The Living Planet Campaign information will be available on the WWF Web page at http://www.panda.org.


</table> <p> <a 
href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img 
src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><h6><i>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
