<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>JAPANESE WHALING- NEWS RELEASE </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif">
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif" BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center><img src="/graphics/tit_nwr2.gif" alt="WWF News Releases"></center>
For Immediate Release: April 13, 1995<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><H2><CENTER>Japanese Whaling Ship Returns with 330 Minke Whales Today</CENTER> </H2>
<BR>
<BR>
</B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>GLAND, Switzerland</B> -- As Nisshin Maru, the Japanese whaling
ship docked today at a Tokyo port with 330 minke whales hunted
in the Antarctic Ocean, WWF-World Wide Fund For Nature once again
deplored Japan's insistence on carrying out large-scale whaling
for scientific purposes.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The Nisshin Maru set out in December 1994 to hunt for minke whales
in the Antarctic region south of New Zealand. The main whaling
ship was accompanied by three catcher-boats. The whales brought
on board are normally cut and processed on board the main factory
ship. The whale meat is sold in the local Japanese market. <BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Only recently, in a letter addressed to the Japanese Prime Minister
and representatives of the Japanese Parliament, Dr. Claude Martin,
Director General of WWF International, pointed out that the Japanese
scientific whaling programme was a pretext, designed to provide
results that were just not needed.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Japan's scientific whaling programme in the Southern Ocean, has
always been based on the assumption that commercial catch limits
for whaling in that region would at some stage be set by the International
Whaling Commission (IWC). However, the reality is that now the
Southern Ocean Whale Sanctuary is in place, the IWC will not set
quotas for this region.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
Since the 1987-88 hunting season (December to March) in the Antarctic,
Japan has been catching between 270 to 330 whales each year. The
international moratorium on commercial whaling went into effect
in 1985-86. Japan's commercial catches then numbered 1,941. It
was only in 1987-88 that Japan withdrew its objection to the moratorium
and resorted to scientific whaling.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;In the decades since the 1950s, all the big whaling nations
of the world, except for Japan and Norway, have stopped whaling
one after the other,&quot; said Cassandra Phillips, WWF's Cetaceans
Officer. &quot;The world looks to Japan now to cease its large-scale
lethal scientific whaling programme.<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
&quot;The coming into effect of the Southern Ocean Whale Sanctuary
last December heralds a new future for the world's great whales,&quot;
added Ms Phillips. &quot;But that landmark decision in conservation
is being partially undermined by Japan continuing to hunt whales
in such large numbers, ostensibly for the benefit of science!.&quot;
<BR>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
The Sanctuary will stay in place for at least ten years and even
then its status can only be revised by a three-quarters majority
vote in the IWC. Moreover, the IWC has noted that any calculation
of a minke whale quota would not depend in any way on the results
of the current Japanese scientific whaling programme.
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
-End-
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
For more information, please call Cassandra Phillips at +44 386
882055 or Someshwar Singh at +41 22 364 9573.<BR>
<BR><BR>
<center><br clear=all>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6>
</center>

