<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Vietnam</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="/graphics/back.gif" text="#000000" link="#bb0000" alink="#bb0000" vlink="#bb0000">

<center>
<table width=580 border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<td valign=top>
<P>
<a href="http://www.panda.org/thefield/thefield.htm"><font size=2><b>Return to the Main Menu</b></font></a>

<P>
<B>VN0005 Vietnam: Biodiversity Conservation Studies</B><!--VN0005 Vietnam Biodiversity Conservation Studies-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
Less than 10% of Vietnam is covered by primary forest, but these
remaining natural forest and grassland areas still hold viable
populations of many valuable species. This project works to expand
the information base on mammals and other important species and
ecosystems in Indochina, and to strengthen Vietnam's system of
protected areas and ecological reserves.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     100</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
With less than 10% of Vietnam covered by primary forest, it is
of great international significance that Vietnam still has viable
populations of several threatened mammals and other important
plant and animal species. The government of Vietnam is willing
to set aside significant land areas to protect these important
species. Assessments of Vietnam's current system of protected
areas (PAs) undertaken by WWF, the Food and Agriculture Organisation
(FAO), and the Vietnam Ministry of Forestry (MOF) commend the
extensive reserve system, but point out that the system is only
a starting point for the conservation of biological diversity.
Many reserves are small, isolated, and degraded, or contain only
historical and cultural sites of little value for biodiversity
conservation. Gaps exist in habitat coverage for the protection
of mammal species of particular importance, and there is scope
for valuable extensions to some existing reserves and PAs. A major
increase in the reserve system has been proposed, which would
almost double the area under protection to 2 million ha. Numerous
field surveys and much protected area planning is needed for the
completion of this exercise, and MOF welcomes WWF's technical
expertise in the collection of information through surveys, and
in preparing species management plans. Extensions to existing
PAs, supported by field surveys, are essential for the long&#173;term
survival of several important species in Indochina, including
the tiger, Asian elephant, Javan rhinoceros, and the sao la.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To produce survey reports of major reserves.
<P>
2.  To research reports of important species populations.
<P>
3.  To provide technical support for management plans for major
reserves.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0005.1: Large Mammal Surveys (Nov. 90 - Jun. 99</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
Despite the rich array of species found in Vietnam, particularly
among large mammals and birds, many areas of the country either
remain unsurveyed or have not been surveyed in the past two decades.
Little up&#173;to&#173;date information is available about the
present distribution of large mammals in the remaining forest
fragments. This information is urgently needed as the MOF continues
its review of the present PA system. The scientific surveys are
planned as follow&#173;up activities to previous field surveys
undertaken under this project. The positive results of the status
survey of the Asian elephant in Vietnam in 1992&#173;1993 have
prompted the Country Team coordinator and the MOF to suggest further
activities under this project, which will supplement the present
information base.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To undertake a follow&#173;up survey of Asian elephants in
areas of the country not previously surveyed, to supplement information
gathered in the previous 1992-93 survey.
<P>
2.  To undertake a more extensive elephant census in one or two
forest areas found to be critical to the long&#173;term survival
of the elephant in Vietnam, most likely in Nghe An, Ha Tinh, and
other provinces which border Laos.
<P>
3.  To present the findings of the elephant surveys and census
to the MOF as a means of directing their protected area planning
and management work.
<P>
4.  To make all information gathered through field surveys carried
out under WWF project VN0005 accessible (in the Vietnamese language
if possible) to all scientists in Vietnam who may benefit from
the up&#173;to&#173;date information.
<P>
5.  To encourage the participation of young scientists and fieldworkers
in all surveys, as a means of providing solid field experience
for the next generation of Vietnamese biologists and protected
area managers.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Biomes:</B></I></U>
<P>
Tropical Dry Forest; Tropical Moist Forest; Tropical Woodland.
<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Protected Area Establishment; Protected Area Management; Programme
/ Project Development; Research and Monitoring; Species Management;
Training.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Species:</B></I></U>
<P>
Asian elephant (Elephas maximus); Clouded leopard (Neofelis nebulosa);
Gaur (Bos gaurus); Javan rhinoceros (Rhinoceros sondaicus); Tiger
(Panthera tigris).<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>VN0006 Vietnam: Coordination of the Indochina Programme</B><!--VN0006 Vietnam Coordination of the Indochina Programme-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
This project seeks to coordinate WWF conservation activities in
Vietnam, Laos, Myanmar, and Cambodia. The Indochina programme
has initially focused on Vietnam and is based in an office in
Hanoi. It tackles pressing conservation concerns, strengthens
regional conservation capabilities, implements land&#173;use planning,
and ensures conservation is included in regional development practices.
<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  100</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
