<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
In the early 1990s WWF perceived the need for a greatly enlarged
programme in Vietnam, Laos, Myanmar, and Cambodia. Little activity
had been undertaken in this region for security and political
reasons but changing conditions have offered good opportunities
to increase the level of WWF involvement. The initial focus has
been principally on Vietnam; new initiatives will be developed
in the other three countries as circumstances allow.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To ensure representation of WWF in discussions and negotiations
with local conservationists and government officials.
<P>
2.  To develop a national conservation programme in Vietnam, and
keep a watching brief for opportunities in Myanmar, Laos, and
Cambodia.
<P>
3.  To oversee and supervise the implementation of the agreed
WWF Indochina Programme, as approved by the WWF Programme Committee.
<P>
4.  To coordinate activities of consultants and project executants,
and ensure that projects within the Indochina Programme proceed
according to contractual conditions and terms of reference.
<P>
5.  To further develop a coherent programme and new projects for
submission to the WWF Programme Committee.
<P>
6.  To strengthen WWF's presence in Indochina through field projects
and policy activities, to ensure sound environmental practices
are included in the development of the region, and to strengthen
long&#173;term conservation capabilities.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0006.1: Coordination of the Indochina Programme (Jul.
91 - Jun. 99</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
The programme formalized its position in Vietnam and Indochina
when it established a representative office in Hanoi in 1991 and
appointed an official Vietnam country representative in 1993.
Following this appointment, two WWF project staff were hired to
fulfil coordination and project administration duties. Shortly
thereafter the WWF office moved to a larger and more prominent
location in the Ministry of Forestry (MOF). This office served
WWF very well through to mid&#173;1994 when WWF opened its own
independent representative office in Hanoi. The new WWF funding
mechanism takes over the primary core costs of operating the WWF
Indochina Programme office in Hanoi. Additional activities leading
to WWF activities in other countries of Indochina are still at
the planning stages. The programme continues to work towards strengthening
its relationship with the Vietnamese MOF and other conservation
research institutes. <BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To develop a strong office administrative system by hiring
and training Vietnamese staff, including one programme officer
and one or two administrative assistants.
<P>
2.  To widen the scope of the WWF Indochina Programme, so as to
cover the whole country of Vietnam, focusing on training at Cuc
Phuong, Bach Ma, and Cat Tien National Parks.
<P>
3.  To study the viability of a second WWF presence in Vietnam,
in Ho Chi Minh City, as needed for project coordination in southern
Vietnam.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Institutional Support and Development; Programme / Project Development;
Research and Monitoring.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0006.2: Development of Strategic Plan for WWF Indochina
Programme (Apr. 95 - Jun. 97</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
In 1993 a strategic plan for the Indochina region was developed
with input from the WWF Indochina Country Team. This plan sets
the goals for the WWF Indochina Programme until the year 2000.
The goals include developing protected areas; sustainable management
of forest, freshwater and marine resources; reducing the impact
of industrial development; environmental education; and promoting
treaties and conventions. In view of the large scope of the plan,
WWF will have to seek a significant amount of outside resources
to implement the wide range of activities called for. WWF is therefore
building partnerships with bilateral and multilateral government
aid agencies to promote the implementation of the strategic plan.
The Indochina Programme has already established productive relationships
with a large number of development agencies, including ODA, USAID,
EC, World Bank/GEF, UNDP, DGIS, and GTZ/BMZ. Although the Indochina
Programme may not itself implement every element of the plan,
it is important to have access to a small amount of unplanned
catalytic funding to be able to seize opportunities as and when
they arise. Most of these opportunities involve providing advice
and participating in strategic planning missions of funding partners.
One of the key activities of this project is to support the conservation
planning efforts of the Ministry of Forestry.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To promote the development of the strategic plan for Indochina
by seeking input from consultants/advisors from specialized disciplines
(e.g. development of Environmental Education Strategy for Vietnam).
<P>
2.  To respond to ad hoc requests from the government of Vietnam
and/or special opportunities which are unplanned but likely to
have an important conservation impact (e.g. providing ad hoc advice
on government conservation policies).
<P>
3.  To participate in strategic planning and project development
missions of multilateral or bilateral aid agencies to promote
the implementation of the WWF strategic plan for Indochina.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Programme / Project Development.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>VN0007 Vietnam: Remote Sensing Monitoring of Natural Habitats
in Protected Areas</B><!--VN0007 Vietnam Remote Sensing Monitoring of Natural Habitats in Protected Areas-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
This project monitors changes in forest cover in selected protected
areas through time series analyses of remote sense images. This
helps to evaluate reserves, prepare management plans, monitor
progress, and increase monitoring capabilities on the part of
the Forest Inventory and Planning Institute (FIPI), a primary
counterpart agency of WWF in Vietnam.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  100</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
The Vietnamese Ministry of Forestry (MOF) has declared a system
of 87 protected areas (PAs) in Vietnam. Ten of these have been
designated national parks (NPs) and there are several other reserves
of high international significance. Rates of forest loss have
been very high in all forest categories and most reserves are
threatened by logging, shifting cultivation, agricultural encroachment
and/or fires. Forest cover maps for Vietnam tend to be out of
date and come from a variety of sources. Consequently, the true
extent and quality of forests in some areas remain uncertain.
There is a severe backlog in surveying, preparing, and approving
Vietnam's PA management plans. The use of remote sensing analysis
of priority areas prior to survey work can substantially reduce
the time needed to carry out field surveys, and can also greatly
increase the accuracy and reliability of the survey findings and
recommendations. In particular, the use of time series techniques
developed by the WWF Xishuangbanna project in China can provide
vital information on the extent of remaining habitats, key areas
for conservation, realignment of reserve boundaries, planning
of buffer zones, and identification for priority protection measures.
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To assist the WWF Indochina Programme's protected area management
and forest conservation projects by providing thematic forest
maps based on satellite imagery.
<P>
2.  To increase capacity at the FIPI Remote Sensing Section in
the areas of digital image processing, and Geographic Information
System (GIS) analysis for the purpose of forest mapping, multi-temporal
forest cover monitoring, and management planning, in order to
ensure FIPI's capacity to fulfil the WWF Indochina Programme's
conservation planning needs.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0007.1: Remote Sensing Monitoring of Natural Habitats
in Protected Areas (Aug. 91 - Jun. 97</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
FIPI, WWF, and Gent University agree that monitoring forest cover
in Vietnam, focusing on specific protected areas and biologically
rich special&#173;use forests, is necessary in order to promote
effective protection and conservation. Providing baseline data
in the form of remote sensed images and maps aids management planning
and implementation within those PAs and special&#173;use forest
areas which fall within WWF's workplan. Significantly, this project
(VN0007) is an output-oriented project. Capacity building activities,
equipment purchase, training, and field surveys are all aimed
at the production of forest status maps, the primary project output,
which assists the conservation programme planning process of WWF
and FIPI.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To increase capacity of the FIPI Remote Sensing Unit to produce
accurate and up&#173;to&#173;date maps which will assist forest
and conservation planners.
<P>
2.  To produce and share maps with other units of FIPI, WWF, and
protected area officials, which will assist their daily work.
<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Biomes:</B></I></U>
<P>
Tropical Dry Forest; Tropical Moist Forest; Tropical Woodland.
<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Protected Area Management; Research and Monitoring.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>VN0011 Vietnam: Marine Conservation</B><!--VN0011 Vietnam Marine Conservation-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
Rich coastal and marine habitats occur along Vietnam's extensive
coastline of over 1,000km. In light of the clear overutilization
of coastal and marine resources and the absence of an overall
plan for their conservation, this project aims to initiate a marine
conservation programme for the Vietnamese coastline, based on
a survey identifying conservation problems, required actions,
and protection needs.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  80</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     20</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Vietnam has an extensive coastline of over 1,000km, together with
a large marine territory of disputed size which includes the Paracel
Islands and the Spratly Islands. Coastal and marine habitats include:
northern dwarf mangroves; southern tropical mangroves; coral reefs;
sandy beaches; rocky coastline; coastal brackish lagoons; marine
atolls; deep sea; and continental shelf areas. Vietnam exploits
its marine resources, without any limits, for fish, prawns, coral,
clams, turtles and their eggs, seaweeds, birds' eggs, mangroves,
and other products. Some resources are clearly being overutilized,
such as turtles, clams, and coral, and almost no conservation
activities have been initiated. A few marine areas are included
inside protected areas such as Halong Bay, Cat Ba, Son Tra, Con
Dao, along with some mangrove areas. However, there is no overall
plan for conservation of coastal and marine resources, and the
Ministry of Forestry (MOF) which runs the national nature reserve
system, has no clear mandate to protect marine areas. Both the
Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO) Tropical Forest Action
Plan and the National Plan for Environment and Sustainable Development
point out this weakness, and recommend that the nature reserve
system should be broadened to include marine areas. However, almost
no documentation on the marine environment of Vietnam is available.
It is urgent that this gap be filled. The lack of substantive
conservation measures in the marine and coastal areas of Vietnam
is critical, particularly since Vietnam relies heavily upon these
resources for the greater part of its food and economic inputs.
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To train Vietnamese scientists in underwater survey techniques.
<P>
2.  To provide basic equipment for two survey teams to operate
in coastal areas.
<P>
3.  To complete the survey of the national coastline.
<P>
4.  To identify conservation problems, actions, and protection
needs.
<P>
5.  To design a follow&#173;up marine conservation programme.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0011.1: Marine Conservation Phase I - Coastal Survey (Sep.
92 - Jul. 96</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
Under this activity, a marine expert was stationed in Vietnam
with the Ministry of Science, Technology, and Environment and
the Institute of Oceanography with the following terms of reference:
(a) compile a resource description of the marine environment of
Vietnam; (b) assemble a survey team to travel the length of Vietnam
by car with diving equipment, inspecting the coast and offshore
islands at various points; (c) identify the main conservation
problems and issues; (d) identify which government agencies should
be responsible for different aspects of marine conservation, protected
areas, controls on production, pollution controls, and monitoring;
and (e) develop a number of priority projects or subprojects for
inclusion in a WWF/Vietnam Phase II marine programme/project as
part of the Vietnam Biodiversity Action Plan.<BR>

<P>
This activity has now closed but is retained in the WWF List of
Projects as the basis for future survey work.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To train two marine survey teams, one based in the north,
one based in the south of the country.
<P>
2.  To complete an initial survey of 1,200 km of coastline.
<P>
3.  To collate existing data of coastal resources, habitat conditions,
levels of exploitation, threats, and conservation value.
<P>
4.  To publish the &quot;Coastal Zone Resources Report&quot;,
including the plan for coastal protected area system.
<P>
5.  To design project documents for priority projects.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Biomes:</B></I></U>
<P>
Littoral Zones.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Fisheries Management; Research and Monitoring.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0011.2: Marine Conservation, Phase II &#173; Marine Reserve
Establishment (Sep. 92 - Jul. 99</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
Phase II of the Marine Conservation project (Marine Reserve Establishment)
extends the marine conservation surveys (completed under Phase
I) into the establishment and implementation of marine protected
areas. This will require closer involvement of the Vietnamese
government at the decision-making and management level. Financial
inputs from local and central government for labour, equipment
maintenance, and research is considered essential for project
success. Local research institutes, such as the Institute of Oceanography
at Nha Trang and the Institute of Tropical Biology in Ho Chi Minh
City, should be actively involved, along with communities. Proposals
on the establishment of marine protected areas in Hon Mun, Nha
Trang District, Khanh Hoa Province, and Phu Quoc Island, Kien
Giang Province should be prepared by the WWF Indochina Programme
in consultation with the local provincial governments. Additional
areas could also be considered for protected area proposals after
the results of the Phase I surveys are fully analysed. The WWF
Indochina Programme and its government counterparts lack the experience
and human resources to undertake this proposal preparation activity
without outside technical assistance. In 1994-95 WWF Indochina
Programme hired the WWF Philippines Programme as consultants to
assist in the preparation of one or two project proposals for
marine sanctuary establishment at Hon Mun and Phu Quoc. <BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To design a system of marine protected areas in Vietnam based
on the Activity 1 survey results, focusing initially on Hon Mun
(Khanh Hoa Province) and Phu Quoc (Kien Giang Province), with
other sites to be considered, including Cu Lao Cau (Binh Thuan
Province) and Con Dao (Ba Ria&#173;Vung Tau Province).
<P>
2.  To provide technical and financial assistance for building
nature reserve infrastructure at initially one or two sites (Hon
Mun and/or Phu Quoc), install basic equipment, and train marine
reserve staff.
<P>
3.  To assist in research and experimental projects, including
the restocking and culture of depleted species in the reserves.
<P>
4.  To promote local awareness of marine conservation and coordinate
with local government officials.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Biomes:</B></I></U>
<P>
Open Oceans and Seas.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>VN0012 Vietnam: Participatory Development of Bach Ma National
Park</B><!--VN0012 Vietnam Participatory Development of Bach Ma National Park-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
This conservation and sustainable development project is designed
to involve local communities in a &quot;stakeholder&quot; approach
in the planning and management of Bach Ma National Park in the
central highlands of Vietnam. The park and the adjacent forest
reserve are under pressure from illegal logging, mining, and population
growth. Special attention will be given to the traditional land&#173;use
patterns of the ethnic minorities who have long been living in
the area. An ecotourism plan will also be developed.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    60</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 40</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Bach Ma National Park protects the forested coastal highlands
of central Vietnam at the point where the mountains jut into the
South China Sea between Hue and Danang. The mountainous central
region is a hotspot of local endemism, constituting the natural
divide between the tropical rainforest systems of southern Vietnam
and the seasonal forest systems to the north. The highlands of
Bach Ma, with their stunning waterfalls and deep forest gorges,
were a favourite summer resort during the French colonial period.
Although containing some of Vietnam's wettest and lushest forests,
the 22,000ha area of the park was severely affected by defoliants
sprayed during the American War. However, the forests are now
slowly recovering following concerted planting programmes and
reforestation efforts instituted by the local and central authorities.
<BR>

<P>
Bach Ma's forests still contain over 500 species of flora, including
several valuable timber species such as the &quot;Shorea thorellii&quot;
and &quot;Fokienia hodginsii&quot;. Some of these trees have diameters
of 12m and heights of over 40m. There are at least 55 species
of mammal present in the park, including leopard (&quot;Panthera
pardus&quot;) and gibbon (&quot;Hylobates concolor gabriellae&quot;).
There is a rich bird life, with some 300 species occurring, including
seven pheasant species. Of particular note is the occurrence of
the endemic Edwards' pheasant (&quot;Lophura edwardsi&quot;).
<BR>

<P>
Nearly 78,000 people, a mix of lowland Vietnamese and two ethnic
minorities, live in the communes next to the park. Many still
depend on the forests for subsistence. Consequently the park is
faced with problems of uncontrolled collection of firewood, cutting
of vegetation for construction materials, logging, hunting, and
livestock overgrazing. In addition, the forests are threatened
by clearance for farming purposes. <BR>

<P>
WWF's project at Bach Ma seeks to involve local communities and
other affected parties in protecting the park. The primary goal
is to develop and implement a participatory model natural resources
management programme, aimed at improving the quality of life for
people living in or near the park. As a start, WWF is helping
local authorities review the management plan they prepared in
1990. WWF is also developing an ecotourism plan, to be completed
by October 1996, sustainable community development schemes, training
park protection staff, and collecting data on the park's animal
and plant life. <BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To develop and implement a participatory model of natural
resources management in Vietnam.
<P>
2.  To ensure that the natural resources management model produces
a significant improvement in the quality of life for communities
living in or near Bach Ma National Park. 
<P>
3.  To ensure that the model promotes long&#173;term sustainable
management of Bach Ma National Park.
<P>
4.  To develop the model so that it can be replicated elsewhere
in Vietnam.<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0012.1: Participatory Development of Bach Ma National
Park (Oct. 92 - Feb. 99</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
This conservation and sustainable development project is designed
to involve local communities and all other affected parties in
the planning and management of Bach Ma National Park. The project
will adopt a &quot;stakeholder&quot; approach in which current
use patterns are identified and dialogue established between all
users of the park environs and national authorities, in order
to determine an equitable and sustainable utilization strategy.
Special account will be taken of the historical use patterns of
long&#173;term ethnic minority residents. An ecotourism plan will
be developed that seeks to involve or compensate existing stakeholders
and thereby secure the long&#173;term viability of this important
and biologically rich forest area.<BR>

<P>
EC funding for the pilot phase of the project will cease in January
1997. Most of the planning work will have been completed by then,
but additional resources would be needed for park management,
implementing community development, ecotourism activities, institution
building, etc. CHF 2 million would sustain the implementation
phase for a period of four years.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To develop and implement a participatory model of natural
resources management that will result in significant improvements
in the quality of life for communities living in or near Bach
Ma National Park, as well as to provide long&#173;term sustainable
management of the park.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Biomes:</B></I></U>
<P>
Temperate Rainforest; Tropical Moist Forest.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Community Conservation; Ecotourism Development; Forest Management;
Natural Resource Economics; Protected Area Management; Research
and Monitoring.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>VN0017 Vietnam: Conservation Training and Biodiversity Action
Plan (GEF)</B><!--VN0017 Vietnam Conservation Training and Biodiversity Action Plan (GEF)-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
This WWF project links with GEF implementation of the UNDP project
to assist countries in the Asia/Pacific region to prepare proposals
which strengthen national conservation training programmes. It
complement the GEF conservation training initiatives with WWF's
ongoing field programmes in sustainable protected area management.
The project has two components: preparing a Biodiversity Action
Plan (BAP), and training professional staff in biodiversity conservation.
<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  100</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

