<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
The GEF proposal for Vietnam was initially prepared by WWF&#173;US
under UNDP project RAS/86/158, and was later submitted and approved
by GEF. The purpose of the UNDP project was to assist countries
in the Asia/Pacific region to prepare proposals which strengthen
national conservation training programmes. WWF remains actively
involved in training and other conservation initiatives in Vietnam
through its Hanoi office. Linking GEF implementation to the WWF
office in Hanoi will complement the GEF conservation training
initiatives with WWF's ongoing field programmes in sustainable
protected area management. It will also help to accelerate WWF's
own conservation programme since much groundwork and collaborative
planning has already been undertaken with the MOF and the State
Committee for Sciences.<BR>

<P>
There are two distinct project components: (i) preparing a Biodiversity
Action Plan (BAP); and (ii) training professional staff in biodiversity
conservation. The BAP will be prepared during the first two years
of project implementation. It will action&#173;oriented with specific,
costed projects and presented in a time&#173;frame indicating
the lead and cooperating agencies and prior requisites for each
activity. It will include: (a) a review and prioritization of
protected areas (terrestrial and coastal/marine), identifying
necessary investments in terms of infrastructure, research, and
extension to buffer zones; (b) identification of necessary research,
education, and extension activities; and (c) identification of
conservation activities outside protected areas, e.g. agricultural
germplasm, zoos and botanical gardens, restoration of degraded
lands.<BR>

<P>
Training programmes will be designed and conducted both in Vietnam
and abroad throughout the five-year project period. Three levels
of in&#173;service conservation field training courses (for park
guards, protected area and community&#173;level managers, and
biological specialists) will be designed to offer training for
up to 350 people annually. In&#173;service field conservation
training centres will be set up at Cuc Phuong, Bach Ma, and Nam
Cat Tien National Parks to provide practical field training in
environment and conservation management. Two biological survey
teams, trained in practical techniques, will be formed and become
operational. Senior staff from MOF and related institutions will
receive higher degrees through overseas education and training.
Staff from MOF and the State Committee for Sciences will attend
short overseas training courses. Park directors, tourist officers,
information officers, and MOF staff will visit prominent national
parks in the region to study effective management techniques.
Equipment and materials for course development will be provided
for the Forestry College and the MOF Refresher Training Centre.
A project management core of professionals will be trained and
will assist with the implementation of this international project
and coordinate ongoing in&#173;service training.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To strengthen the capacity of the government of Vietnam to
implement programmes which protect areas of high biodiversity
importance through a broad range of training activities for forest
guards and rangers, protected area managers, technicians, scientists,
and senior government officials, both in&#173;country and through
overseas fellowships and study tours.
<P>
2.  To build on existing plans and strategies (National Conservation
Strategy, Tropical Forestry Action Plan, and the National Plan
for Environment and Sustainable Development) to develop a specific
Biodiversity Action Plan, which outlines a time-frame of costed
actions necessary to preserve Vietnam's precious biodiversity,
to reduce forest loss, and to safeguard water catchments.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0017.1: Conservation Training and Biodiversity Action
Plan (GEF) (Jun. 92 - Jun. 97</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Background.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To complete the Biodiversity Action Plan, including a review
of the protected area system and recommendations for conservation
projects and specific costed actions.
<P>
2.  To provide field training facilities at Cuc Phuong, Bach Ma,
and Nam Cat Tien National Parks.
<P>
3.  To conduct in&#173;service training courses in field conservation
techniques designed and delivered to at least 800 Vietnamese conservation
fieldworkers.
<P>
4.  To provide advanced degrees (PhD and MSc) for at least 12
Vietnamese conservation professionals; participation in diploma
and short courses for at least eight Vietnamese officials; and
two study tours undertaken for up to 30 mid and upper level staff
of the MOF.<BR>
