<P>
<B>VN0021 Vietnam: Conservation of Vu Quang Nature Reserve</B><!--VN0021 Vietnam Conservation of Vu Quang Nature Reserve-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
This five-year project aims at promoting sustainable development
in the buffer zones of the Vu Quang Nature Reserve, to ensure
the long&#173;term security of the reserve and the viability of
its wild fauna and flora. Management of the reserve will be strengthened
and a number of projects will be implemented to improve agricultural
productivity, and to provide better health care, education and
employment opportunities.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    40</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 60</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
The Vu Quang Nature Reserve conservation and development programme
focuses on the sustainable development of the local communities
in the vicinity of the reserve. Vu Quang is an area of spectacular
natural beauty that has tremendous tourism potential. It is largely
a mountainous area, sharing its border along the western side
with Laos. The diversity of vegetation and habitat types found
in Vu Quang is reflected in the diversity of the fauna. Given
the relative isolation of the area and largely mountainous terrain,
Vu Quang is also rich in endemic species, as well as a number
of new species hitherto unknown to science. Of the 720 species
of birds recorded in Vietnam, Vu Quang holds about 250 resident
and 50 migrant species. Of the large mammals the most important
are Asian elephant, gaur, tiger, leopard, Asiatic black bear,
Malayan sun bear, serow, wild boar, white&#173;cheeked gibbon,
sambar, and barking deer. Several other mammals, including otter,
civet, Douc langur, Phayre's leaf monkey, at least two species
of macaque, leopard cat, porcupine, and mouse deer, make Vu Quang
an extremely rich area in terms of biological diversity. However,
numbers of all these species appear to be low. <BR>

<P>
Vu Quang Nature Reserve has assumed global importance from the
recent discoveries of two large mammal species new to science:
the sao la and the giant muntjac. Unfortunately, poaching, by
using snares, poses a serious threat to the long&#173;term survival
of these newly discovered species. The government of Vietnam,
in recognition of the significance of the discovery of the sao
la, has banned all logging activities within Vu Quang. The project
also addresses the development of the proposed Pu Mat Nature Reserve
in the adjoining Nghe An province, where the presence of the Vu
Quang ox has also been confirmed. The project recommends the retention
of forested areas between Vu Quang and Pu Mat as a corridor linking
the two conservation areas and thereby ensuring the free movement
of wildlife in general and the more mobile mammals and birds in
particular.<BR>

<P>
The reserves buffer zone is occupied by seven communities, while
areas that were originally logged (selectively) are being allowed
to recover in a so-called regeneration zone. The communities comprise
farmers and almost all of them supplement their income from the
sale of non&#173;timber forest produce. Poor roads are often cited
by the villagers as the most serious impediment to their ability
to market their agricultural products. Rice cultivation is at
present limited to once a year, but in many areas it could be
increased to twice a year if an assured supply of water is made
available (e.g. through the construction of small dams). One activity
that appears promising in substantially improving the local economy
is deer farming, which has paid dividends to a number of enterprising
local inhabitants around the reserve. Other activities recommended
in the project for the buffer zone include controlled grazing,
stall feeding, establishment of cinnamon plantations, apiculture,
butterfly farming, and the development of carefully controlled
nature tourism. Natural forests have traditionally been the only
source of fuel-wood for local communities. In order to mitigate
the effect of fuel-wood extraction on the remaining natural forests
and other vegetation types in Vu Quang, the project advocates
the establishment of fuel-wood plantations using appropriate fast-growing
tree species along the degraded slopes of the hills bordering
the communities in the buffer zone. <BR>

<P>
The project has an initial life span of five years, during which
the Vu Quang Nature Reserve management will be strengthened through
the provision of appropriate training opportunities to the reserve
staff, and improved protection of the area by a trained guard
force. Simultaneously, a number of projects will be implemented
to improve the agricultural productivity of the communities, thereby
enhancing the living standards of the people through the provision
of better health care, education, and employment opportunities.
The project recognizes and recommends the need to rely on the
expertise of the Vietnamese instead of expatriate staff in implementing
this long&#173;term, integrated project for conservation and community
development in Vu Quang. Funding for this major protected area
and community development project is from DGIS (Netherlands Development
Assistance Agency).<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
Short&#173;term objectives:
<P>
1.  To conserve the remaining primary forest and rehabilitate
the secondary forest in the Vu Quang area, while at the same time
conserving its biodiversity and improving the balance between
the human population and the natural resources.
<P>
2.  To raise the living standards of the local communities of
Vu Quang.
<P>
3.  To prepare a concept management plan and project identification
proposal for the proposed Khe Thoi Nature Reserve.<BR>

<P>
Long&#173;term objectives:
<P>
4.  To ensure the survival of the unique fauna and flora of Vu
Quang and Pu Mat Nature Reserves through the protection of their
habitat and the mitigation of human&#173;wildlife conflicts.
<P>
5.  To ensure the agricultural productivity of the human population
in the lowlands of Ha Tinh and Nghe An Provinces that are dependent
on the Truoi river and those rivers flowing from Pu Mat, by safeguarding
the integrity of the rivers' catchment area in Vu Quang.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0021.1: Development of an implementation plan (Preparatory
Phase) (Jul. 95 - Jun. 00</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
The first phase of the Vu Quang project will be a preparatory
phase of one year. During this period the project will gather
information to plan the socio&#173;economic activities of the
implementation phase. Support from all members of the local population,
as true stakeholders in the protection of Vu Quang, is essential
to the success of the project. Apart from preparing social and
environmental impact assessments and studies of the local farming
and economic systems, the project will also plan for the infrastructure
components and equipment procurement. At the same time the project
will implement some urgent measures to protect the reserve and
to limit poaching activities. Following an evaluation, in November
1996, of the first year of project implementation, the first phase
of the project will begin in earnest, focusing on all aspects
of community development and nature conservation at the Vu Quang
Nature Reserve and among the 21,000 residents of the buffer zone
area.
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To gather information to plan the socio&#173;economic activities
of the implementation phase; includes stakeholder analysis and
preparing social and environmental impact assessments, as well
as information on gender issues, resource uses, local farming,
and economic systems.
<P>
2.  To plan for the infrastructure components and equipment procurement.
<P>
3.  To implement urgent interim measures to protect the reserve
and to limit poaching activities.
<P>
4.  To review and evaluate the findings of the preparatory phase
and to prepare detailed implementation plans, including realistic
workplans and budgets for the two implementation phases (FY1997&#173;FY2001).
<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Biomes:</B></I></U>
<P>
River Systems; Tropical Moist Forest.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Protected Area Management; Programme / Project Development.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Species:</B></I></U>
<P>
Asian elephant (Elephas maximus); Giant muntjac (Megamuntiacus
vuquangensis); Indochinese tiger (Panthera tigris corbetti); Saola
(Pseudoryx nghetinhensis).<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>VN0022 Vietnam: Cat Tien National Park Conservation Project</B><!--VN0022 Vietnam Cat Tien National Park Conservation Project-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
Cat Tien National Park is an area of high biodiversity in southern
Vietnam covering two distinct biogeographical zone. The park is
known to harbour several endangered species including the Javan
rhinoceros. However, the area is facing various threats through
human encroachment and uncontrolled exploitation. To address there
threats this project will engage in an active programme to upgrade
the management and protection of the park. Simultaneously the
project will assist the local people with alternative sources
of income through the implementation of an integrated conservation
and development programme (ICDP).<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     80</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  20</TD><TD WIDTH=28>
</TD><TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  10</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    30</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     10</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 50</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
The proposed Cat Tien National Park covers an area of approximately
74,000ha and is situated 150km north-east of Ho Chi Minh City
in southern Vietnam. The park will be administratively divided
in three provinces: Lam Dong, Song Be, and Dong Nai Provinces.
The area is a biodiversity &quot;hotspot&quot; located at the
transition of two biogeographical zones. The northern part of
the proposed park (currently known as Cat Loc Nature Reserve)
is famous for its small population of Javan rhinoceros, probably
the most endangered large mammal species in the world. The southern
area (the original Nam Cat Tien National Park) harbours a large
seasonal swamp which contains a population of the endangered Siamese
crocodile. Other interesting areas are the more or less undisturbed
tropical rainforests of lagerstroemia/dipterocarp. The entire
area is rich in bird, mammal, and tree species. <BR>

<P>
Cat Tien suffered from the heavy spraying of herbicides (notably
Agent Orange) during the American war. As a result, large tracks
of dipterocarp forest died and species composition changed. Bamboo
became the dominant species over large areas. After the war, the
New Economical Zone (NEZ) policy of the Vietnamese government
led to an influx of people from elsewhere in Vietnam, especially
from the overpopulated deltas of the Mekong and Red Rivers. Other
migrants, mainly ethnic minority peoples from the north, have
arrived as well and encroached upon the Nam Cat Tien National
Park and its extension into Song Be Province. Cat Loc has also
suffered serious encroachment. Apart from these newer settlers,
several indigenous groups live inside the proposed park as the
Cat Tien region is their traditional homeland. Large areas outside
the proposed park expansion become flooded during the rainy season,
forcing people to depend heavily on the park's resources as harvests
are lost and/or agriculture is impossible. In these instances,
the park's resources provide alternative income.<BR>

<P>
The proposed park is an important part of the water catchment
are for the Dong Nai river system, which is the second major river
of southern Vietnam. The whole area is under serious threat as
a result of encroachment, overexploitation of its natural resources,
transformation and conversion into cashew fields, shifting cultivation,
and the construction of dams. This project sets out to reverse
a number of threats by actively protecting the area. At the same
time the project will assist the people living inside the park
and those who are mostly effected by restrictions put on the use
of this area by providing technical inputs, and developing alternative
agricultural systems and income-generating activities by following
a participatory approach. Active protection will be improved by
demarcating the area and by recruiting, equipping and training
guards. Research into the parks' natural dynamics, tropical rainforest,
biodiversity and tourism development will be undertaken. Development
of some tourist infrastructure will be studied and carefully implemented.
All of these activities in the protection&#173;oriented component
will follow a project approach. The community component will mainly
follow a process approach. Since this will make management more
complicated, a good monitoring system will be implemented and
a high degree of flexibility maintained. The government of Vietnam
intends to relocate and/or settle the people illegally living
inside the park. The project will assist these people when settled
elsewhere and will also work with the ethnic minority communities
remaining inside the park. The Cat Tien National Park Conservation
Project is planned for five years, split into two phases, each
of two-and-a-half years. For the community and socio&#173;economic
component of the project, the first phase will be used especially
for feasibility studies, PRAs, and EIAs. The second phase will
focus on implementation. For the conservation and protection component,
clear targets are set for the first phase. Following the first
phase, a mid&#173;term review will be held in order to assess
the progress of the project, the commitment of the Vietnamese
government, and to determine any necessary adjustments.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
Main objective:
<P>
1.  To conserve the Cat Tien National Park to maintain its biodiversity
values and its services as the water catchment area of the Tri
An reservoir.<BR>

<P>
Short-term objectives:
<P>
2.  To establish effective park management.
<P>
3.  To conserve important forest types, habitats, and a rich assembly
of plants and animals, some of which are threatened by extinction.
<P>
4.  To establish wildlife research and habitat monitoring programmes.
<P>
5.  To enhance public awareness of the physical and biological
values of the park and its environs.
<P>
6.  To increase income-generating opportunities for the park and
the local human population through the development of tourism.
<P>
7.  To reduce the dependency of the local human population upon
park resources.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0022.1: Cat Tien National Park Conservation Project (Jan.
