<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
WWF and co&#173;sponsors Bank of America, MacArthur Foundation,
and Vietnam's National Environmental Agency held a &quot;Business
for Biodiversity&quot; symposium in Ho Chi Minh City in late 1995.
The 40 invited guests included representatives of prominent international
companies, key Vietnamese government officials, and leaders of
the Vietnamese business community. The symposium heard papers
on inovative financing mechanisms, lending practices, environmental
quality management, technolgy transfers, and environemntally sustainable
business. It provided a forum for business leaders to express
openly their views and concerns about the environment and environmental
regulations. The aim of the symposium was to encourage the formation
of a Vietnam Environmental Business Council, a body which would
help guide business investment to more environmentally sustainable
practices by establishing industrial standards and clarifying
and enhancing Vietnam's environmental legal framework. Over time,
the Council will establish a funding mechanisms for environmentnal
projects and clean&#173;ups. Although the Council will be an autnomous
entity, WWF will maintain an advisory, technical role. The Secratariat
offices for the Business Council will be established in Hanoi
and Ho Chi Minh City. <BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To conduct a full&#173;day symposium consisting of prospective
Business Council participants. The group of participants will
include foreign business interests, Vietnamese joint venture partners,
representatives from the Vietnamese government, and WWF.
<P>
2.  To establish further appropriate objectives subject to the
participants of the first meeting consensually agreeing to support
the Business Council concept.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0851.1: Vietnam Environmental Business Council (Jun. 95
- Jul. 97</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Background.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Objectives.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>(Concept) VN0020 Vietnam: Protected Areas for Resource Conservation
(PARC)</B><!--VN0020 Vietnam Protected Areas for Resource Conservation (PARC)-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
This project is a demonstration model which will show that biodiversity
conservation integrated with community development is feasible
even in a difficult combination of circumstances. The project
seeks to protect and enhance the potential for conservation of
the remaining primary forests of Vietnam, as well as regenerating
degraded areas. The issue directly addressed by these activities
is the effective conservation of biodiversity. The project also
calls for the establishment of multiple&#173;use areas to fill
the economic and livelihood needs of nearby communities. These
areas will involve traditional forestry activities, such as tree
plantations and agroforestry, as well as assisted natural regeneration.
<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     50</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   50</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    50</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 50</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
In Vietnam, as in many other tropical countries, the remaining
centres of biodiversity are under increasing stress to provide
sustenance to an expanding population. During the last few decades,
the frontiers of the biologically rich wildlands have been retreating.
What fragmented natural areas remain are often too small and too
isolated to maintain unique habitats, species assemblages, or
viable populations. The urgent need is to seek a fair balance
between the provision of ecologically sound livelihoods and conservation.
In order to meet this challenge protected areas (PAs) should address
not only the goal of biodiversity conservation but a multitude
of other development objectives. In general, PAs should maintain
ecological functions vital to the economy of the rural communities
and the nation as a whole; provide opportunities for sustainable
rural development by promoting more efficient and ecologically
sound use of natural products; guide establishment of land tenure
systems that are compatible with cultural traditions of indigenous
communities and ecological sustainability; maintain the environmental
stability of the surrounding region by sound watershed management
and sound land-use planning; ensure the sustainable use of biodiversity
which support indigenous communities, the agricultural economy,
and major industries; provide opportunities for education in ecology
and natural history for academic institutions, policy-makers,
and the general public, and contribute to scientific research
on natural habitats, wild species, and their relationship with
human development; protect endemic genetic resources and preserve
distinctive ethno&#173;biological forms and values; and provide
habitats for viable populations of important flora and fauna species.
<BR>

<P>
This project aims to achieve these multiple objectives by developing
and implementing the new Protected Areas for Resource Conservation
(PARC) concept in Vietnam. The project also expects to involve
extensive re&#173;afforestation and assisted natural regeneration
in the secondary growth areas and buffer zones. PARC expands the
function of conservation to mean wise preservation and use of
natural resources to ensure sustainability. The PARC concept is
based on a modified landscape ecology approach, which is a recent
development in conservation science. The approach deals with the
fragmentation of habitats and the multiplicity of objectives that
must be met. Instead of focusing conservation efforts on a small
PA, the need is to plan and manage entire landscapes that include
ecosystems in varying intensity of human uses.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
Main objective:
<P>
1.  To establish, over the course of the five-year project, a
nationally and regionally replicable model of biodiversity conservation
through community&#173;based management. The project will introduce
and test the new PARC concept (Protected Areas for Resource Conservation),
which is based on the need for a modified landscape ecology approach
to conservation in Vietnam. This will be accomplished by:<BR>

<P>
Specific objectives:
<P>
2.  To select and design two PARC sites in biologically, environmentally,
socially, and economically critical regions of the country.
<P>
3.  To implement management plans and community programmes for
the two PARC sites, and to monitor progress and impact.
<P>
4.  To evaulate implementation and, based on these assessments,
modify the PARC concept for replication in other sites.<BR>

<P>
Because of the emphasis on local capacity building and two PARC
demonstration sites, the finalization of project activities required
to meet the immediate objectives will be made during the ongoing
project preparation activities in Phase I of the project.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0020.1: Protected Areas for Resource Conservation (PARC)
(Jan. 94 - Jan. 99</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
The five-year project will be divided into three phases: a one-year
survey and design phase; a three-year operation and monitoring
phase; and a one-year evaluation and assessment phase, allowing
for modifications to the PARC model.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
<B>Phase I (Year 1) - Two PARC sites in biologically, environmentally,
socially, and economically critical regions selected and designed:</B>
<P>
1.  To formulate criteria for selection of the two PARC sites.
<P>
2.  To survey and select, through a consultative process with
all stakeholders, two priority protected areas to be developed
as models for resource conservation (PARC sites) for integrated
protection of biodiversity and sustainable forest&#173;based economic
and community development.
<P>
3.  To design management plans for the two PARC sites and analyse
sustainable financing of the two PARC sites beyond the project
period.
<P>
4.  To conduct socio&#173;economic appraisals of the selected
sites for the purpose of designing community resource projects
and sustainable livelihood systems which are sensitive to women
and local ethnic communities, including recommendations on land
tenure concepts and a fair and equitable incentive system.
<P>
5.  To plan re&#173;afforestation of corridors and buffer zones,
tree plantations in multiple&#173;use areas, assisted natural
regeneration, and other agroforestry activities.<BR>

<P>
<B>Phase II (Years 2&#173;4) - Management plans and community
programmes for two PARC sites implemented with ongoing monitoring
for progress and impact:</B>
<P>
1.  To implement management plans for PARC sites and monitor progress
and impact.
<P>
2.  To implement community resource development projects, coordinating
closely with local communities and creating linkages with existing
local, district, and provincial extension programmes.
<P>
3.  To pilot&#173;test sustainable financial mechanisms, including
ecotourism and sustainable harvest and value&#173;added production
of non&#173;timber forest products.
<P>
4.  To implement re&#173;afforestation, tree plantations, assisted
natural regeneration, and other agroforestry projects.<BR>

<P>
<B>Phase III (Year 5) - PARC implementation evaluated, and modified
for replication in other areas based on the evaluation assessments:</B>
<P>
1.  To conduct field surveys to evaluate impact of the project
on biodiversity conservation in the two sites.
<P>
2.  To conduct socio&#173;economic surveys to assess impact of
the community development projects and, based on these evaluations
and assessments, modify the PARC concept for replication at other
sites.
<P>
3.  To evaluate effectiveness of the PARC concept.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>(Concept) VN0852 Vietnam: Indochina Biodiversity Forum</B><!--VN0852 Vietnam Indochina Biodiversity Forum-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
Numerous attempts have been made to combat subregional loss of
biodiversity in recent years by forging better subregional cooperation.
Unfortunately, these initiatives have not yet been successful.
Recurring problems include inadequate funding, personnel lacking
the appropriate level of training, and uncoordinated information
systems management. Transfrontier protected areas (PAs) are a
popular topic in the subregion, but a coordinating body is essential
to making such discussions a reality. This project proposes the
establishment of a subregional biodiversity forum which will serve
as a catalyst for biodiversity information exchange and cooperative
land&#173;use planning among the countries of Cambodia, Laos,
Thailand, and Vietnam. To accomplish these objectives, a series
of annual forum meetings, a joint training programme, and the
development of an electronic forum via Internet for data and information
exchange are needed. <BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  50</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    20</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  30
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
In 1991, WWF opened a country office in Hanoi to manage its burgeoning
activities in Vietnam and the rest of the Cambodia&#173;Laos&#173;Vietnam
subregion). WWF's activities in Laos and Cambodia have largely
encompassed capacity building and training programmes. In Laos,
international training has been provided for staff of the National
Office for Nature Conservation (NONC) of the Department of Forestry
and the Dong Dok Superior Forestry Technical School. Fieldwork
and ground-truthing have concentrated on forested regions which
contain important flagship species such as the kouprey and elephant.
In 1991, WWF worked with the Department of Forestry to design
the GEF portion of the Forest Management and Conservation Project,
which began implementation in 1995. In Cambodia, international
training has been provided for staff of the Ministry of Environment
and the Wildlife Protection Office of the Department of Forestry.
<BR>

<P>
In Vietnam WWF is working with the Ministry of Forestry at various
protected areas (PAs), including Vu Quang Nature Reserve (home
of the recently identified sao la), Bach Ma National Park, Cuc
Phuong National Park, and Cat Tien Nature Reserves (home of the
last population of wild Javan rhinos). WWF's involvement in these
PAs started with wildlife surveys and has progressed to assisting
the government of Vietnam establish integrated conservation development
projects which will include park&#173;level use of GIS. Capacity
building activities have included study tours, a graduate degree
fellowship programme, and provision of GIS equipment and training
(including remote sensing training) for the Forestry Inventory
Planning Institute (FIPI). A noteworthy benefit has been the establishment
of a strong network of local officials at the central, provincial,
and district levels. Along with FIPI and subcontractor Asian Bureau
for Conservation, maps were prepared for the entire country, including
five PAs. These maps have been included in the Biodiversity Action
Plan, prepared under projecVIE/91/G31 and written in close coordination
with the Ministry of Science Technology and Environment (MOSTE)
and IUCN. The plan, which will guide Vietnam's biodiversity policies
for the next decade, identifies priority areas in Vietnam by comparing
areas of biodiversity and endemism with degradation from land
use. It will be essential to allowing Vietnam to carry through
with its obligations under the Convention on Biological Diversity.
WWF continues to work closely with MOSTE in obtaining government
approval for the Biodiversity Action Plan at the highest level.
WWF hopes to use this experience to assist Cambodia, Laos, and
Thailand address issues related to UNCED, especially in connection
with the Convention on Biological Diversity. WWF's presence in
Thailand began with institutional support for the Wildlife Fund
Thailand (WFT), a local NGO founded in 1983. WFT was first internationally
recognized by its pioneering community incentives approach to
buffer zone management at Sup Tai village near Khao Yai National
Park. This work led to a series of community development projects
at Huay Kha Khaeng&#173;Thung Yai and other important forest areas
of Thailand. In 1987, WWF also linked with the Centre for Conservation
Sciences at Mahidol University in creating a species and ecosystem
database which was shared between Mahidol, WFT, and the Royal
Forest Department. Most recently, the WWF Thailand Project Office
moved to the campus of the Asian Institute of technology (AIT)
to facilitate a closer working relationship with the numerous
international agencies based there. <BR>

<P>
With WWF offices in Bangkok and Hanoi and good relations with
Laos and Cambodia, WWF maintains a subregional perspective and
has good working relationships with many potential project subcontractors.
For example, the WWF office in Hanoi worked with the Cat Specialist
Group of the IUCN Species Survival Commission to host a Subregional
Tiger Action Plan meeting in March 1995 which brought together
representatives from Cambodia, Laos, and Vietnam to develop a
subregional plan for tiger conservation. A planned tiger survey
of Vietnam's Yok Don National Park, which borders Cambodia, will
allow Cambodian, Lao, and Vietnamese conservation officials to
work together in the field. Transfrontier protected areas are
a popular topic in the subregion, but a coordinating body is essential
to making such discussions a reality. Establishment of a subregional
biodiversity forum will serve as a catalyst for biodiversity information
exchange and cooperative land&#173;use planning among the countries
of Cambodia, Laos, Thailand, and Vietnam. To accomplish these
objectives, a series of annual forum meetings, a joint training
programme, and the development of an electronic forum via Internet
for data and information exchange are needed. <BR>

<P>
Ideally, the Biodiversity Forum should be comprised of technical
officers from the national level and from local areas of high
transfrontier conservation value. The main function of the forum
will be to discuss subregional solutions to common problems and
to make project evaluations and recommendations. Regular dialogue
between the lead NGO, collaborating subcontractors, and forum
participants will be essential. The objective of the initial forum
will be to arrive at consensually agreed project objectives, communication
procedures, database structure, and data collection methods. To
arrive at project objectives, the forum first will assess the
current state of subregional cooperation. Forum participants will
arrive with prioritized lists of what each country deems the most
viable sites for cooperation on land management decisions. Using
a biodiversity database with a common interface and an email link,
the electronic forum will allow further technical exchange and
relationship building. <BR>

<P>
Training in biodiversity inventory, database management, GIS,
and other identified natural resource management techniques will
accommodate the varying needs of each country's participants.
Database management and GIS training will occur at one of several
possible sites: Subic Bay Conservation Training Centre, FIPI,
AIT, and several in&#173;country locations. Training in other
field level conservation techniques, such as biodiversity inventory,
will occur at GEF&#173;Cuc Phuong Field Conservation Training
Centre or Dong Dok Forestry Technical School in Laos. Later meetings
of the forum will review progress and make recommendations for
enhancement of the project, for example concerning the framework
for subregional and site&#173;specific land&#173;use plans. By
the end of the project the subregional transfrontier land&#173;use
master plan will be finished, as will management plans for specific
areas of consensually agreed importance. At the final forum, proposals
will have been developed for important sites and presented to
a round table of international and national donors. However, the
forum should not cease at the end of the project period, so methods
for sustaining the forum must be a high priority in the early
design phase of the forum.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To create a functional, user friendly database and a cadre
of natural resource professionals trained in its use.
<P>
2.  To prepare subregional land&#173;use plans for border areas
and plans for specific protected areas.
<P>
3.  To foster increased cooperation between Cambodia, Laos, Thailand,
and Vietnam on issues of common conservation importance.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>VN0852.1: Indochina Biodiversity Forum (Jun. 95 - Jun. 98</B>)
<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Background.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Objectives.<BR>

