<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>WWF Position Statement April 1996 Whaling and The IWC</TITLE>
</HEAD>
 
<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif" background="/graphics/back.gif"
BGCOLOR="#ffffff"  link="#215e21"  vlink="#215e21" alink="#a67d3d">
<center>
<blockquote>
<h2>WWF Position Statement April 1996
<p>
Whaling and The IWC:
<br>
1996 IWC Annual Meeting</h2>
<p>
</center>

<b>WWF and whaling</b>

<p>

<dd>	WWF's mission is to conserve nature and ecological processes and to help build a future in which humans live in 
harmony with nature.  One important way of achieving this goal is to ensure that any human exploitation of the planet's 
renewable resources, such as wild species of animals, is sustainable in both the short and the long term.  This does not, 
however, mean that <u>all </u>renewable resources<u> must </u> be exploited by humans.  On the contrary, our care for, and 
responsibility to, the rest of life on earth and future human generations implies that we should make the minimum use of 
renewable resources consistent with fulfilling human needs.
<p>
<dd>	There are a number of particular conservation concerns which must be taken into account in the case of whaling. 
Especially important are:
<p>
<ul>
	<li> The increasing evidence of additional threats to whales apart from whaling, including marine pollution, habitat 
degradation, depleted stocks of prey species, ozone depletion, and climate change. Of especial concern is the evidence that 
even extremely low levels of persistent organochlorine chemicals such as PCBs and DDT are increasing susceptibility to 
disease and decreasing fertility by interfering with the hormonal systems of many animals including whales and dolphins. If 
this continues apparently stable whale populations could crash with very little warning.
<br>
   <li>  The deplorable record of the whaling industry throughout history and its total failure to operate in a sustainable 
way. The question remains whether regulations on any future whaling can ever be fully enforced. This is currently illustrated 
by the evidence of continuing illegal trade in whale-meat. WWF welcomes the efforts of IWC members to monitor stockpiles of 
whale-meat, but the frozen stocks of meat from various whale species resulting from past whaling and from research whaling 
make it virtually impossible to distinguish legal from illegal whale-meat, so that the "laundering" of illegal catches is 
facilitated. 
<BR>
  <li>The fact that whale-watching can provide an alternative, non-consumptive, sustainable use of whales. In many cases 
whale-watching can provide higher economic returns than whaling on a particular population of whales, as well as giving an 
incentive for whale conservation. WWF is involved with promoting whale-watching projects in many countries including Japan, 
Norway, the Caribbean, South Africa and New Zealand.  
 <BR>
  <li>The fact that whales are currently being killed only for a small meat market and no longer for oil and other products 
formerly derived from whales which are now obtained from other sources or manufactured synthetically.
</ul>
	<dd>In addition, WWF sees no benefit to the conservation of whales from commercial whaling, and therefore does not 
support its resumption. 
<p>

<b>The IWC and the commercial whaling moratorium </b>
<p>
<dd>	All whales are highly migratory species, so that no whale population belongs to any one country, and any whaling is a 
matter of international concern.  The IWC is the only international organisation with the authority to regulate whale 
conservation worldwide, and is recognised as such in both UNCLOS and UNCED's Agenda 21. 
<p>
<dd>	In 1982, recognising that the then current "new management procedure" for regulating whaling was seriously flawed, 
the IWC decided on an indefinite moratorium on all commercial whaling (to take effect from the 1985/86 whaling season), 
pending a comprehensive assessment of the effects of this moratorium on whale stocks and the replacement of the "new 
management procedure". 
<p>
	<dd>A series of critical issues remain to be addressed before the IWC could even consider reviewing the moratorium on 
commercial whaling. These include: 
<ul>
 <li>  The development, formal adoption  and incorporation into the Schedule of a comprehensive Revised Management Scheme 
(RMS), as agreed by the IWC in 1992 and 1994. This would have to include a comprehensive system of supervision and control, 
as well as rigorous standards for whale surveys and catch data accuracy and analysis, including independent validation of the 
original sources of historical catch data. 
<br>
  <li> Being able to assess the effects of the moratorium on whale stocks, as specified by the IWC in paragraph 10(e) of the 
Whaling Convention Schedule. 
<br>
 <li> Full investigation and consideration of the growing impacts on whales of all the threats other than whaling.
</ul>
<p>

<b>Aboriginal Subsistence Whaling</b>
<p>
	<dd>WWF recognises the legitimate human need for aboriginal subsistence whaling, provided that:
<ul>	
<li>such whaling is carried out by aboriginal, indigenous or native peoples who share traditional strong  social or cultural 
ties to a continuing dependence on whaling and on the use of whales; and
<br>
<li>the whale-meat and other products are used exclusively for local consumption within the whaling community; and 
<br>
<li>the whaling is sustainable, and highly endangered whale populations are not targeted. 
</ul>

<b>The Southern Ocean whale sanctuary and "scientific" whaling</b><p>
<dd>	WWF warmly welcomes the establishment of the IWC's Southern Ocean whale Sanctuary, which together with the contiguous 
Indian Ocean Sanctuary covers approximately one third of the world's oceans.  The combined sanctuaries give long-term 
protection from pelagic whaling to nearly all the whales of the southern hemisphere, and should finally put an end to the 
shameful history of Antarctic whaling. Together with the Antarctic Treaty and its Environmental Protocol, and the Convention 
on the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources (CCAMLR), the Southern Ocean sanctuary opens the way for 
comprehensive conservation and rehabilitation activities in the region. 
<p>
<dd>The sanctuary should now be dedicated to non-lethal scientific research and monitoring on undisturbed and recovering 
whale populations and the ecosystems of which they are part.  WWF believes that large-scale "scientific" whaling can not be 
justified anywhere, and above all should not be conducted in sanctuary areas. WWF urges all IWC member states to enforce 
immediately the two 1995 IWC Resolutions which recommended that scientific whaling should only be permitted in "exceptional 
circumstances", and that it should not be permitted in sanctuaries.
<p>


For further information contact:<br>
WWF International<br>
CH-1196 Gland<br>
Switzerland<br>
Tel: + 41 22 364 9111<br>
Fax: + 41 22 364 5829<br>

<p>

<a href="http://www.panda.org/news/press/news_53.htm">BACK</a>


</blockquote>

