<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Asia General</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="/graphics/back.gif" text="#000000" link="#bb0000" alink="#bb0000" vlink="#bb0000">

<center>
<table width=580 border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<td valign=top>
<P>
<a href="http://www.panda.org/thefield/thefield.htm"><font size=2><b>Return to the Main Menu</b></font></a>

<P>
<B>9S0012 Asia general: Asian Elephant Conservation</B><!--S0012 Asia general Asian Elephant Conservation-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
This project supports the bi&#173;annual journal entitled &quot;GAJAH&quot;,
produced by the IUCN Species Survival Commission's Asian Elephant
Specialist Group (AESG). The journal's aim is to highlight the
plight and promote the conservation of Asian elephants. It also
provides a forum for communication amongst all members of the
specialist group.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  100
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
The Asian elephant, which once ranged from Syria to eastern China,
is now restricted to India and South-East Asia, where human interference
has greatly reduced its forest habitat. This has led to a serious
conflict between elephants and humans, with deaths and injuries
on both sides. In Indonesia, most elephants are confined to the
island of Sumatra, although some survive in parts of Kalimantan,
along the border with Sabah. In 1981, the Sumatran population
was estimated at only 350, but according to more recent surveys
there may be as many as 4,800 in the region. There are also problems
in Malaysian oil palm plantations and in Sri Lanka, where elephants
are being moved from areas being developed around the vast Mahaweli
River Basin to special reserves elsewhere. One of the greatest
problems facing the Asian elephant is fragmentation of its habitat.
When this happens, elephants can often find themselves stuck in
the middle of agricultural land and, hungry, they will raid croplands.
Even when large areas of forest remain, elephants often invade
fields, for example of sugar cane and rice. As a result of the
translocation of hundreds of thousands of people from Java, Madura,
and Bali to Sumatra, new settlements have been created in marginal
forest areas where elephants also live. This has led to serious
conflicts between people and elephants. Many elephants bear the
scars of wounds caused by the muzzle&#173;loaders used to drive
them away. This project facilitates communication between elephant
managers and scientists with the aim of enhancing elephant conservation
in Asia.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To promote the conservation of the Asian elephant throughout
its range by supporting the work of the IUCN Species Survival
Commission's Asian Elephant Specialist Group.
<P>
2.  To provide better coordination and increased efficiency of
IUCN/WWF efforts to conserve wild populations of elephants throughout
the region.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0012.1: Asian Elephant Conservation (Jun. 80 - Jun. 99</B>)
<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
This activity has funded a range of initiatives to support the
operations of the AESG. Since 1993-94, WWF funding has been focused
on the production &quot;GAJAH&quot;, the AESG newsletter.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Objectives.<BR>

<P>
<B>Major targets for FY1998 and beyond:</B>
<P>
1.  To maintain efforts to facilitate communication and exchange
between Asian elephant experts. <BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Communications; Policy Development; Programme / Project Development;
Research and Monitoring; Training.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Species:</B></I></U>
<P>
Asian elephant (Elephas maximus).<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>9S0018 Asia general: Training on Wetland Survey and Evaluation
in South-East Asia</B><!--S0018 Asia general Training on Wetland Survey and Evaluation in South-East Asia-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
Given the fast pace of economic development in the Asian region
and the rapidly increasing human population, considerable environmental
destruction is occurring. In wetlands, many of the problems arise
from an ignorance of wetland values and functions and an inadequate
knowledge of sustainable wetland management. This project coordinates
a series of workshops/training courses within Asian countries
to train local biologists and environmental planners in wetland
techniques. A manual detailing wetland survey and assessment methods
will be produced. Trainees will be encouraged to develop long&#173;term
wetland conservation programmes in their countries, especially
for threatened wetlands.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  80</TD><TD WIDTH=28>
</TD><TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  100</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   20</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Wetland areas throughout the world, particularly in Asia, are
severely threatened by exploitation, conversion to alternate land
use, and basic neglect. The value of these wetlands to the economy
of Asian countries and to local people has been highlighted in
recent years. The WWF-sponsored Asian Wetlands Inventory has been
remarkably successful in identifying wetland areas of high conservation
priority in South-East Asia. This work has been largely based
on existing data, with little or no fieldwork carried out, to
determine the present status of some areas. It is imperative for
sound conservation planning that the Asian Wetland Inventory be
followed up with more detailed surveys of areas where information
is currently inadequate. This will yield high&#173;quality information
of value to both natural resource managers and development planners.
In order to achieve this, natural resources personnel of government
agencies and non&#173;governmental organizations (NGOs) throughout
Asia need to be trained in wetland assessment and management methodologies.
<BR>

<P>
Since 1984, the Asian Wetland Bureau (now Wetlands International)
has organized numerous training courses and workshops for Asian
biologists, on subjects such as techniques of wetland assessment,
and migratory and waterbird identification and monitoring in Asia.
These courses and other training and professional development
initiatives have been undertaken with the particular objective
of meeting and building up local capacity to meet previously unfulfilled
training needs. Such courses have been organized on a collaborative
basis, either with regional agencies or national agencies, and
thus have had the additional benefit of strengthening ties with
the agencies concerned. The first stage of this project, undertaken
between 1988 and 1992, was jointly funded by WWF and the UK Overseas
Development Administration. Results from the project have been
encouraging. Follow&#173;up surveys indicate increased capability
in wetland assessment and management at government level, and
an increase in the availability of local language manuals on study
techniques. Many workshop participants and other institutions
in the region have been involved in further training in their
own country.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To assist governmental and non&#173;governmental environmental
agencies at national level in the development of training programmes
and to promote professional development and institutional strengthening
in the field of wetland assessment and management, based on systematic
needs analyses. Emphasis will be placed on training in methods
of raising public awareness of wetland functions and values, and
in the concept of &quot;wise use&quot; of wetland resources.
<P>
2.  To mobilize the resources of key institutions in Asia (government
research bodies, universities, non&#173;governmental and regional
organizations) and to provide high quality training in response
to the needs of government and non&#173;governmental bodies in
the fields of wetland promotion and wise use.
<P>
3.  To provide, where necessary, expertise in training and wetland
ecology by developing and/or running professional development
courses in wetland assessment and management.
<P>
4.  To establish links between existing institutions involved
in wetland training in order to maximize efficiency in the delivery
of wetland assessment and management training services in Asia.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0018.1: Organizing Workshops on Wetland Training Issues
(Nov. 88 - Jun. 97</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
A workshop on Public Awareness of Biodiversity in Wetlands took
place in Thailand in September 1994, in conjunction with Mahidol
University and the Ramsar Centre, Japan. See also Project Background.
<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To liaise with user agencies and individuals in order to improve
content and future use of the training modules developed.
<P>
2.  To liaise with cooperating agencies (and specifically those
in the Indo&#173;China and South-East Asian regions) with regard
to further training needs and development of wetland training
programmes.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Biomes:</B></I></U>
<P>
Lake Systems; Littoral Zones; Mangrove; Marshes/Swamps; Mudflats;
River Systems.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Education; Training.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0018.2: Training Courses/Workshops at National level (Nov.
88 - Jun. 97</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
Wetlands International will develop national training initiatives
as follow&#173;up to the regional workshop on training needs held
in South-East Asia in November 1993, and the Oceanian regional
workshop on conservation needs held in June 1994.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To further develop and facilitate wetland training courses
and wetland policy and management courses throughout the region,
in cooperation with the relevant agencies in the Wetlands International
network.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Biomes:</B></I></U>
<P>
Lake Systems; Littoral Zones; Mangrove; Marshes/Swamps; Mudflats;
River Systems.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Education; Training.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0018.3: Developing and Disseminating Training Materials
(Nov. 88 - Jun. 97</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
Training materials on wetland assessment and management will continue
to be developed and made available to the relevant organizations
in the region. Efforts will be made to translate existing materials
into various local languages.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To complete all outstanding modules of the training manual.
<P>
2.  To continuously update current modules following feedback
from users.
<P>
3.  To continue to seek funding and cooperation on translation
of training materials into local languages.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Biomes:</B></I></U>
<P>
Lake Systems; Littoral Zones; Mangrove; Marshes/Swamps; Mudflats;
River Systems.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Education; Training.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0018.4: Providing Support to Local Organizations and Support
Networking (Nov. 88 - Jun. 97</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
Wetlands International will continue with the preparation of &quot;Asian
Wetland News&quot; and support dissemination to a wider range
of agencies in the Asia/Pacific region.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To encourage cooperating agencies to use the training materials
to organize self&#173;training workshops, and to encourage partner
organizations to seek further training.
<P>
2.  To investigate the options available (in liaison with IIED
of the UK) for electronic networking and information dissemination,
particularly with respect to training materials.
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Biomes:</B></I></U>
<P>
Lake Systems; Littoral Zones; Mangrove; Marshes/Swamps; Mudflats;
River Systems.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Institutional Support and Development.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>9S0019 Asia general: Environmental Input to Wetland Planning</B><!--S0019 Asia general Environmental Input to Wetland Planning-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
Coastal and inland wetlands are among the most productive ecosystems
in Asia. They support at least 100 mammals and 200 migratory bird
species and are an important resource for people. However, high
population density and rapid economic growth in Asia are leading
to the widespread loss and degradation of wetlands. This project
aims to influence wetland planning and management in Asia, firstly
by monitoring the input of development assistance projects on
key wetlands and intervening where necessary to prevent or reduce
loss of wetland values, and secondly by assisting national governments
and other agencies to develop and implement regional, national,
local, and site&#173;based wetland conservation action plans and
policies.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  80</TD><TD WIDTH=28>
</TD><TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  10</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   20</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    50</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 40</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Coastal and inland wetlands are among the most productive ecosystems
in Asia and, as such, they are exploited intensively for food,
materials, water supplies, and many other useful natural products.
They also have many other ecological functions critical to human
life support systems, as well as supporting a unique and diverse
flora and fauna. In spite of their importance, wetlands in Asia
cover a relatively small proportion of the land surface. Asia
represents 14% of global land area, yet it supports over 55% of
the total human population. This population is increasing by 55
million per year. Furthermore, economic growth in Asia, and associated
development, is greater than in any other region of the world.
As a result, natural ecological processes and specific wetland
sites and habitats have come under severe pressure. Wetlands are
being destroyed through reclamation for development at an increasing
rate. A recent review by Wetlands International estimated that
of the internationally significant wetlands in Asia for which
information was available, almost half were moderately or severely
threatened by factors such as pollution, siltation and erosion,
logging, reclamation for urban development and agriculture, and
encroachment by human settlement. This project represents a fundamental
part of Wetlands International's medium to long&#173;term strategy
to achieve the protection and sustainable use of wetland resources
in the region. In particular, it seeks to influence the policies,
activities, and practices of development assistance agencies and
of national governments.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To monitor the impact of development assistance projects on
key wetlands in Asia and to disseminate this information to assist
effective intervention by Wetlands International and other environmental
groups, in order to minimize or eliminate impacts on wetlands.
<P>
2.  To provide assistance to national governments and other relevant
agencies in the development and implementation of regional, national,
local, and site&#173;based wetland conservation policies and action
plans.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0019.1: Environmental Input to Wetland Planning (Nov.
88 - Jun. 97</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
Wetlands International (formerly Asian Wetland Bureau) offices
in South Asia, South-East Asia and Indonesia, together with Wetlands
International headquarters, will continue to monitor activities
of development assistance agencies which may impact upon wetlands.
<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To prepare for a workshop on, and to formulate guidelines
for, the environmentally sound management of river basins in Asia,
utilizing wetland functions and maximizing wetland benefits; to
be done in conjunction with UNEP and regional experts.
<P>
2.  To hold a workshop on incremental costs in conjunction with
GEF.<BR>

