<P>
<I><B>9S0019.2: Assistance with Wetland Conservation Policies
and Action Plans (Nov. 88 - Jun. 97)<BR>
<BR>
</B></I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
Wetlands International (Asia region) is one of the key sources
of technical information on wetland ecology, assessment, and management
in the Asia/Pacific region. It is frequently asked for advice
on wetland policy formulation, site management, and environmental
impact assessment. Recognizing the great importance of developing
sound wetland policies and wetland action plans at a national
level, for the successful implementation of wetland conservation
programmes at all levels, Wetlands International (WI) has started
a programme of national and subregional workshops to assist this
process. The first national wetland action plan was produced for
the Philippines in 1992. Workshops are also believed to be the
best way of bringing together all of the agencies in a country
likely to require technical support from WI. They allow needs
to be assessed so that WI can develop a programme of technical
support, involving both its own technical staff and experts from
other relevant institutions in the Asia/Pacific region and internationally.
These are supported, where required, by specialist consultants.
<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Objectives.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Biomes:</B></I></U>
<P>
Lake Systems; Littoral Zones; Mangrove; Marshes/Swamps; Mudflats;
River Systems.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Policy Development; Training.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>9S0021 Asia general: Support to TRAFFIC Southeast Asia, Petaling
Jaya, Malaysia</B><!--S0021 Asia general Support to TRAFFIC Southeast Asia, Petaling Jaya, Malaysia-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
South-East Asia is one of the world's most important regions involved
in the legal and illegal trade in live wild animals and plants,
as well as animal and plant derivatives. The South-East Asia office
of Trade Records Analysis on Flora and Fauna in Commerce (TRAFFIC)
was set up to monitor this trade. It also provides assistance
to local government efforts to regulate wildlife movements by
conducting trade studies and maintaining contacts with all parties
liable to be involved in either side of the trade. This includes
government officials, traders, scientists, conservation non&#173;governmental
organizations, and international organizations.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     50</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  10</TD><TD WIDTH=28>
</TD><TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   20</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  20</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  100
