<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
International and local demand for live wild animals and plants
(and products derived from them) is threatening the continued
existence of many species. Trade Records Analysis on Flora and
Fauna in Commerce (TRAFFIC) provides a valuable wildlife trade
monitoring and analysis function, playing an important role in
reducing threats to wildlife. South-East Asia is one of the world's
major wildlife exporting, importing, and consuming regions, and
has numerous problems with illegal trade. To investigate and solve
these problems, controlling imports is not enough; monitoring
must also take place from within the area of export. One of the
best ways of doing this is to establish a regional office whose
staff can make and maintain the necessary contacts with state
authorities, dealers, scientists, and conservation NGOs. The existence
of the South-East Asia TRAFFIC office not only benefits the region,
it plays an essential role in the geographical coverage of the
TRAFFIC network in one of the world's most important and critical
wildlife trade regions.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To monitor trade in wild plants and animal utilization. This
includes monitoring in relation to the Convention on International
Trade in Endangered Species (CITES), and monitoring of non&#173;CITES
listed species, domestic trade, and local utilization.
<P>
2.  To liaise with government agencies, wildlife traders, and
other appropriate organizations and individuals, to collect data
on species in trade.
<P>
3.  To identify areas of trade which may be detrimental to any
species, and determine the impact of trade on wildlife and their
habitats.
<P>
4.  To assist the CITES secretariat, governments, and other appropriate
bodies in facilitating trade control, and in curtailing possible
threats to species.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0021.1: Support to TRAFFIC South-East Asia, Petaling Jaya,
Malysia (Oct. 91 - Jun. 99</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
This activity monitors the trade in wildlife by collecting and
analysing data and information from as many sources as possible.
Additional information and data is provided to governments and
NGOs on a wide range of topics. The TRAFFIC office is also responsible
for the publication of bulletins and special reports. TRAFFIC's
regional office for the ten countries of South-East Asia is based
in Petaling Jaya, Malaysia and is currently staffed by two people
assisted by consultants as necessary. <BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To ensure that adequate information about illegal trade in
plant and animal species is available to TRAFFIC, governments,
international bodies, and to all other concerned parties with
power to curtail the illegal trade in and threats to certain species.
<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Institutional Support and Development; Policy Development; Research
and Monitoring; Wildlife Trade Monitoring.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>9S0027 Asia general: Small Grants Fund</B><!--S0027 Asia general Small Grants Fund-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
This project provides small grants to allow Asian conservationists
and organizations to carry out low costs conservation activities.
Particular emphasis is given to applied research on plant biodiversity
conservation, training in environmental education and a &quot;conservation
action&quot; category, which covers a wide variety of other initiatives
with conservation merit.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     60</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  30</TD><TD WIDTH=28>
</TD><TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  20</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   10</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     40</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 40</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Since June 1990 the Asia/Pacific programme has supported several
small-grant projects aimed at promoting conservation action in
the region: e.g. 9S0027 Small Grants Fund, 9S0028 Small Grants
for Plant Conservation, and 9S0053 Support for Environmental Education.
At the 1994-95 Asia/Pacific Subcommittee meeting in Kao Yai, Thailand,
it was decided that these projects should be merged as components
of one overall grant project (9S0027). <BR>

<P>
Small grants can be received or originated from any part of the
world and normally involve budgets ranging between CHF2,000&#173;5,000.
Grant requests are subject to quick review by relevant country
teams and by experts from specialized disciplines, depending on
the nature of the initiative. For example, small grants for plant
conservation are normally reviewed by the WWF Plants Conservation
Officer, who will particularly favour: surveys for the identification
of centres of plant diversity; initiatives which lead to germplasm
conservation of economically important plants (including wild
crop relatives and locally utilized species); investigations in
traditional plant usage, especially the development of sustainable
harvesting methods; proposals linked to existing WWF projects
concerned with the management of protected areas or with sustainable
development; projects which control invasive plant species which
threaten the maintenance of biodiversity; and actions which raise
awareness among local people of the conservation value of the
plants concerned.<BR>

<P>
Small grants for training in environmental education (EE) are
normally reviewed by WWF International's Environmental Education
and Conservation Capacity Building (EE&amp;CCB) department. Education
has been identified as critical for promoting sustainable development
and improving the capacity of people to address environment and
development issues. Training is one of the most important tools
to develop human resources and facilitate the transition to a
more sustainable world (&quot;Agenda 21&quot;, Chapter 36). However,
many developing countries lack the funds for such training programmes.
Grants will help train key people who can then play an important
role in the development of EE in both the formal and non&#173;formal
education sectors. Priority will be given to initiatives which
promote South&#173;South cooperation. Small grants for conservation
action may cover a variety of activities ranging from, for example,
NGO campaigning against the construction of a dam, to translating
an important book on conservation into an Asian language. <BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To provide EE training for key people from developing countries
in the Asia/Pacific region, to enable and encourage them to play
a catalytic role in regional EE development.
<P>
2.  To research and identify centres of plant diversity, engage
in germplasm conservation of economically important plants, investigate
traditional plant usage, and control invasive plant species which
may threaten biological diversity.
<P>
3.  To promote conservation action in the widest sense in the
Asia/Pacific region.<BR>
<BR>

