<P>
<B>9S0033 Asia general: ASEAN Environment Programme</B><!--S0033 Asia general ASEAN Environment Programme-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
WWF's ASEAN Environment Programme (AEP) coordinates WWF's efforts
in the ASEAN (Association of South East Asian Nations) region
to conserve nature and ecological processes. The programme aims
to strengthen the links among members of the WWF Network in the
ASEAN region, as well as to enhance their capacity and capability
to deal with pollution prevention and control issues and initiatives
effectively and efficiently. As well as assisting with follow&#173;up
on existing WWF activities and in developing new activities, AEP
also assists with networking between WWF and other NGOs and environmental
protection agencies.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     60</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 10
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  10</TD><TD WIDTH=28>
</TD><TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  20</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   30</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    20</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     20</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 20</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  10
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
The rapid pace of economic growth in the ASEAN countries during
the past two decades has, in many cases, been achieved without
adequate concern for the environment. If left unchecked, this
trend will lead to serious, perhaps insurmountable, environmental
problems, such as the depletion of the natural resource base and
the degradation of fragile ecosystems upon which the economies
of the ASEAN countries are largely dependent. The ASEAN Environment
Programme (AEP) is designed to survey, document, and analyse the
range of existing and emerging pollution&#173;related environmental
issues, institutions, and instruments. This it does with a view
to identifying critical points of intervention for WWF and to
facilitate the formulation, implementation, and monitoring of
effective pollution prevention and control strategies and measures
in the ASEAN region. The AEP addresses issues and initiatives
on pollution prevention and control, as well as on wasteful consumption
patterns, within the overall framework of promoting sustainable
development.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To help coordinate the development and implementation of the
third part of the WWF mission in the ASEAN countries.
<P>
2.  To act as a focal point for liaison between WWF International's
Resource Consumption &amp; Pollution team and the WWF Network
in ASEAN countries. 
<P>
3.  To review and analyse the range of pollution&#173;related
environmental issues in the ASEAN region; to identify and prioritize
specific areas for WWF's intervention and involvement; to formulate
a strategic programme of activities that could be undertaken or
facilitated by WWF to address these issues, with specific reference
to atmospheric and coastal pollution. 
<P>
4.  To develop a programme to maintain environmental quality in
the region.
<P>
5.  To provide technical expertise to WWF NOs and Programme Offices
in ASEAN countries to help them develop activities on pollution.
<P>
6.  To liaise with relevant research institutions and key intergovernmental
bodies working on pollution&#173;related environmental issues
in the ASEAN region, including the ASEAN Secretariat, United Nations
Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (UNESCAP),
United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), ROAP, the Asian Development
Bank (ADB), the Asia/Pacific Development Centre, the Asian Institute
of Technology, and the Institute for South East Asian Studies.
<P>
7.  To help build up a network of NGOs working on pollution issues
in ASEAN countries.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0033.1: ASEAN Environment Programme (Jul. 92 - Jun. 97</B>)
<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
There exists a wide range of pollution problems, varying in scope
and severity, in the ASEAN region, with the major ones being air
pollution; freshwater, coastal and marine water pollution; industrial
emissions and effluents; domestic and municipal wastes, including
sewage and solid waste; toxic chemicals and hazardous wastes;
energy&#173;related pollution; and tourism&#173;related pollution.
However, few of the activities currently being carried out by
WWF in the ASEAN region are designed to address pollution problems
comprehensively, although some of the ongoing WWF conservation
field/policy and education programmes in the ASEAN region do contain
some pollution&#173;related elements. It is logical therefore
that the main emphasis of WWF's AEP should include: enhancing
the capability and capacity of WWF Programme Offices to deal with
pollution problems effectively and efficiently; increasing awareness
and demonstrating the sectoral and cross&#173;sectoral linkages
concerned; facilitating cooperation, collaboration, and networking
at all levels, both within the WWF Network as well as with other
NGOs and environmental protection agencies; making appropriate
interventions at relevant national, subregional, regional, or
international fora; promoting the use of pollutant release and
transfer registers (PRTRs), low cost pollution monitoring kits
and other innovative approaches towards integrated pollution prevention
and control; developing generic subregional or regional strategies
and specific national action plans which take into account the
diversity of local priorities, pressures, perspectives, and practices;
documenting and disseminating relevant reports and information
packages, including materials in local languages; ensuring the
incorporation of national, subregional, and regional views into
the formulation of WWF Network-wide policies and positions at
the international level; soliciting and securing the funds required
for both the long&#173;term sustainability of the AEP and for
the recruitment and training of full&#173;time pollution prevention
and control officers in all WWF offices in the ASEAN region.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To liaise with and support other environmental groups, to
prepare WWF project proposals, and to follow up on existing projects
where necessary.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Communications; Lobbying; Policy Development; Research and Monitoring.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>9S0047 Asia general: Indochina Regional: CITES Membership Consultancy</B><!--S0047 Asia general Indochina Regional CITES Membership Consultancy-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
This project provides advice and technical assistance to the governments
of Laos, Vietnam, Cambodia, and Myanmar regarding joining the
Convention on International Trade of Endangered Species (CITES)
convention and its implementation and control of wildlife trade.
<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     50</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  20</TD><TD WIDTH=28>
</TD><TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   30</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  100
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Three countries of the Indochina region have not yet joined CITES:
Laos, Cambodia, and Myanmar. Vietnam became a member in January
1994. All three countries have expressed support for the convention,
but are having difficulty in understanding the documentation,
legal implications, and procedures for joining. Meanwhile, uncontrolled
trade in these countries is a very serious problem for conservation,
both internationally and domestically. Laos exports a great deal
of wildlife and forest products through Vietnam. Recent examples
are Douc langurs, ivory, primates, snakes, and crocodiles. Large
quantities of wildlife trophies, ivory, and crocodile skins are
also exported or smuggled through Thailand. Vietnam has laws banning
the capture and sale of many species, but the wildlife markets
are full of endangered and protected species. Large trading companies
and breeding farms front as official outlets for animals that
are claimed to be bred in captivity. Myanmar has been severely
criticized for allowing large&#173;scale export of elephants and
other wildlife. Smuggling of animal products and wildlife is common
across the borders with Thailand, China, and Assam. Cambodia is
struggling to get conservation established as an active sector
again after decades of warfare, and is keen to establish international
relations through such conventions as CITES. This project aims
to assist these countries to become active members of CITES by
providing a consultant to lead them through the application process
and advise them on implementation.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To encourage and assist Laos, Cambodia, and Myanmar to become
members of CITES.
<P>
2.  To draft regulations, suitable for each country, for the domestic
control of wildlife trade as a precondition to joining CITES.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0047.1: CITES Membership Consultancy (Apr. 94 - Jun. 99</B>)
<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
This project supports, and builds on the previous work of, the
Trade Records Analysis on Flora and Fauna in Commerce (TRAFFIC)
Southeast Asia in providing assistance to the governments of Laos,
Vietnam, Cambodia, and Myanmar in their attempts to improve the
control and monitoring of illegal wildlife trade. Although principally
focused on the issue of CITES membership and implementation, the
project also aims to provide technical and legal advice on the
development of national administration legislation, enforcement
measures, and training. These activities reflect concern about
the growth of largely uncontrolled wildlife trade throughout the
Indochina region and resulting threats to wild animal and plant
populations. Previous work funded by IUCN and TRAFFIC Southeast
Asia's core budget has been carried out in Vietnam and Laos. As
a result, Vietnam acceded to CITES in January 1994 and Laos is
currently considering membership. Follow&#173;up activities are
needed in both countries. In Cambodia and Myanmar, the top priority
should be given to initiating a dialogue with appropriate government
departments. Owing to the difficulty of communication and other
administrative sensitivities and complications, it is necessary
to retain a certain level of flexibility in setting a timetable
for action during the project period. Activities will be coordinated
by TRAFFIC Southeast Asia in close consultation with the CITES
Secretariat and the WWF Indochina Programme Office.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  Vietnam: To assist with training, development of national
legislation, preparation of public awareness materials, and production
of technical assistance to support CITES implementation.
<P>
2.  Laos: To conduct a follow-up mission to determine progress
made since TRAFFIC Southeast Asia's March 1993 consultancy visit,
which provided guidance on the accession to CITES.
<P>
3.  Cambodia and Myanmar: To establish contacts with the appropriate
government departments; to arrange an exploratory mission to each
country; to offer assistance in developing wildlife trade controls,
with the intention of agreeing to further detailed consultations
following the successful steps taken in Vietnam and Laos.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Institutional Support and Development; Policy Development; Training;
Wildlife Trade Monitoring.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>9S0049 Asia general: Indochina Conservation Action Grants</B><!--S0049 Asia general Indochina Conservation Action Grants-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
Conservation outreach is a vital complement to the overall biodiversity
conservation programme of WWF in Indochina. The Indochina Conservation
Action Grants programme supports action&#173;oriented projects
of grass roots conservation groups, young conservation researchers
and scientists, and public awareness activities in rural areas.
<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  100</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307></TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28>
</TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Vietnam is facing serious environmental problems, such as deforestation,
soil erosion, overexploitation of coastal resources, threats to
ecosystems, and depletion of genetic resources. Although the government
has been aware for some years that the problem of increasing wastelands
(caused by deforestation) is a matter of considerable concern,
the country is not well equipped to tackle such an enormous task.
This is not only because the country is poor and lacks financial
resources, but also for want of experienced manpower in the environmental
field. While considerable training investment and land management
changes will be difficult for Vietnam to finance, they are nonetheless
vital to the restoration of a stable, productive environment for
the future welfare of the country. Grass roots conservation efforts
in Vietnam are almost non&#173;existent. It is therefore imperative
that WWF provides immediate attention to this important conservation
need in Vietnam and the neighbouring nations of Indochina.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To provide action grants with a funding range of CHF4,000
and less per grant to grass roots groups, young conservation professionals,
and for public awareness and outreach programmes.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0049.1: Conservation Awareness and Action Grants Programme
(Jul. 92 - Jun. 99</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
Small grant opportunities for funding will be solicited and selected
as part of the operations of the WWF Indochina office in Hanoi,
following the procedures of the Thailand Conservation Action Fund
for project reporting and accounting.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1. To support at least 10-15 small projects to be identified by
the WWF Indochina Office, with a target budget of CHF800-3,000
per project. Anticipated projects include a continuation of the
elephant surveys in Laos, printing posters on Javan rhino and
kouprey conservation in local languages (Vietnamese, Khmer, and
Laos), and supporting other survey activities in Vietnam and the
region.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Communications; Research and Monitoring.<BR>
