<P>
<B>9S0059 Asia general: Strategic Development and Support Project</B><!--S0059 Asia general Strategic Development and Support Project-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
The main objective of this project is to provide a fund which
allows strategic growth, or change, to take place within the WWF
Asia/Pacific Programme. This will be achieved by setting aside
part of the programme's available resources which can be used
to enable growth in specific and pre&#173;determined areas. <BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  100
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Until the early 1990s there was ample opportunity for strategic
development within the Asia/Pacific Programme because of the rapid
growth of programme funding. Each year budget growth allowed the
funding of new projects, as well as of exploratory development
work. More recently private sector funds available to the programme
have slowed and even dropped. As a result, the development of
new projects has fallen behind. At the same time, government and
aid agency (GAA) sources of funding for WWF work have continued
to expand. However, a certain investment in project formulation
and design is necessary before funding from such sources is achievable.
The purpose of this project is to provide private sector funds
for specific activities that will allow the programme to expand
into new areas of work. Emphasis will be placed on issues that
involve strategic growth or a change of direction of the programme.
The new fund created under this project will allow the programme
to overcome budgetary constraints. Since new activities resulting
from this will most likely have to be funded from GAA sources,
a secondary purpose is to provide a source of funds for preparatory
work by WWF staff. <BR>

<P>
Guidelines for the project have been set by the Asia/Pacific Subcommittee
and are as follows: Expenditure on this project will be subject
to the approval of a core group of the subcommittee. Activities
can be submitted for consideration from any country, with following
areas marked as priorities for receiving support: projects in
Pakistan, India, Vietnam, and the Pacific region; policy positions
with multilateral lending institutions; staff training workshops
or training programmes; institutional development initiatives,
including transitions to National Organization (NO) status and
nationalization of country offices; logical framework analysis;
improving field project and policy integration; strategic studies;
field staff participatory programmes (to enable field staff to
meet and share experiences and expertise); and education in China.
Other subject areas may be considered at the discretion of the
core group.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To provide a source of funds for activities which will bring
about strategic development within the Asia/Pacific Programme.
<P>
2.  To enable preparatory work on proposals of strategic significance,
for subsequent submission to GAA sources of funding.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0059.1: Strategic Development and Support Project (Jul.
93 - Jun. 99</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
