<P>
<I><B>9S0059.6: Strategic Planning for the Asia/Pacific Region
(Oct. 94 - Dec. 96</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
The WWF Asia/Pacific region contains seven WWF National Organizations
(NOs), located in Australia, Hong Kong, India, Japan, Malaysia,
New Zealand, and Pakistan. WWF also runs conservation programmes
in Bhutan, China, Indonesia, Nepal, Philippines, Thailand, Vietnam,
and the South Pacific. Most of these programmes are guided by
strategic plans of varying quality and sophistication. The absence
of an overall strategic plan for Asia/Pacific has made it difficult
to allocate resources within the region in a systematic and rational
manner. In fact such decisions are often based on a historical
involvement of WWF and on a desire to maintain the status quo
to prevent conflict situations. In During the 1990s WWF's private
sector income has steadily decreased, leading to some hard decisions
to reduce budgets of individual country programmes. The absence
of a regional strategic plan has made such decisions subjective
and arbitrary, and frustrations and frictions have arisen. A regional
strategic plan would provide a rational framework for allocating
resources within the region and also help determine priorities
for future institutional and programmatic development. Moreover,
a strategic plan would help in identifying specific areas in need
of support from the WWF Network; in turn this could lead to the
formulation of &quot;sourcing plans&quot; which would enhance
continuity by securing long-term commitments from the WWF Network
for specific programme interventions. <BR>

<P>
This activity covers the organization of strategic planning workshops
for the Asia/Pacific region, to be guided by outside facilitators
with a good understanding of the region. To date, workshops have
taken place in Malaysia (November 1994) and in Nepal (February
1995), and have set about mapping out biodiversity priorities
in the region, overlaying them with other parameters such as political
and socio&#173;cultural conditions, and WWF's history and institutional
presence. It is hoped that this brainstorming exercise will identify
geographical priorities for WWF, as well as specific programme
interventions needed to achieve WWF's mission in Asia. In March
1996 the status of the strategic planning process was discussed
at the Asia&#173;Pacific Subcommittee meeting in Bali and it was
agreed that an outside log&#173;frame specialist should be hired
to lead the final stages of the strategic planning process. This
plan should apply to the region as a whole and should be used
as a monitoring and evaluation tool to assess international programmatic
activities both in the region and at country or subregional level.
<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To develop a strategic plan for the WWF Asia/Pacific Programme,
based on conservation priorities as determined by biological,
political, socio&#173;cultural, and other criteria. The strategic
plan will also address priorities for the development of WWF's
institutional presence in the region.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Institutional Support and Development; Policy Development; Programme
/ Project Development.<BR>

<P>
<B>9S0065 Asia general: Establishment of TRAFFIC East Asia, Hong
Kong</B><!--S0065 Asia general Establishment of TRAFFIC East Asia, Hong Kong-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
This project supports the establishment and operation of a TRAFFIC
office in Hong Kong which will focus on trade issues in the Chinese
Economic Zone, notably in Hong Kong, Taipei, and China.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     40</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  10</TD><TD WIDTH=28>
</TD><TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   10</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  20</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     60</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  20</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  40
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
In January 1993 a TRAFFIC office was re&#173;established in Taipei,
Taiwan, and quickly built up strong relations with key government
departments and law enforcement agencies in Taiwan. The primary
focus was on the trade in rhino horn and other products of endangered
species used in traditional Chinese medicine. It is increasingly
apparent that the wildlife trade in Taiwan is but one part of
a regional trade involving all of Greater China, including Taiwan,
Hong Kong, and mainland China. It is therefore considered essential
that TRAFFIC monitor the trade in the East Asia region as thoroughly
as possible, rather than focus on just a part of it.<BR>

<P>
With the Chinese Economic Zone now the world's fourth-largest
economy, the greatest threat to endangered species in trade now
comes from mainland China, where rising incomes and consumer demand
for wildlife products as both food and medicine could have the
most severe impacts on already rare plants and animals. As yet
this market is poorly understood. A vital role for TRAFFIC's is
to establish baseline market intelligence which will allow appropriate
policy options to be formulated. The centre of wildlife trade
in Greater China is Hong Kong, which is important both as a consumer
market and as an entrep&ocirc;t. Although WWF has an office in
Hong Kong and wildlife trade there has been one of its focuses,
this area of work lacks staff and resources. <BR>

<P>
This project recommends that the next step towards securing a
comprehensive wildlife trade monitoring capability in Greater
China is to establish a permanent TRAFFIC presence in Hong Kong,
located within the premises of WWF-Hong Kong. This would place
TRAFFIC at the heart of the region's most important trading hub
and centre for the import and re&#173;export of wildlife products.
It would also give TRAFFIC the capacity to undertake research
and investigations in Hong Kong itself, an important market for
wildlife and wildlife products in its own right and provide a
base from which to make forays into the mainland, either using
consultants or permanent TRAFFIC staff, to carry out investigations
or project work. It would also strengthen the work of the Taipei
office by providing logistical support and direct communication
with Taiwan's major trading partner.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To establish a TRAFFIC office in Hong Kong to monitor regional
wildlife trade issues involving all of Greater China, including
Taiwan, Hong Kong, and mainland China.
<P>
2.  To consolidate and develop work initiated by TRAFFIC Taipei,
with an additional focus on trade in some species and wildlife
products which have been little studied of late, e.g. live birds,
aquarium fish, shark fins, edible birds' nests, musk and saiga
antelope, reptiles and amphibians.
<P>
3.  To establish a permanent investigation and research capacity
in Hong Kong, in particular on trade related to traditional Chinese
medicines that make use of rhino horn, tiger bone, bear gall,
shark fins, and birds' nests.
<P>
4.  To develop a trade monitoring capability in mainland China,
which represents the largest Asian market for many wildlife products,
by conducting baseline monitoring through regular and frequent
surveys and investigations. This will provide the fundamental
market intelligence on which to base policy analysis and to develop
and propose methods of control.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0065.1: Establishment of TRAFFIC East Asia, Hong Kong
(Jul. 94 - Jun. 99</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
This project was developed from a proposal submitted to the TRAFFIC
Committee in October 1993, which agreed on the need to establish
TRAFFIC East Asia. Hong Kong was selected as the most logical
location for this office because of its infrastructure and communication
facilities, and the offer of office space and logistics by WWF-Hong
Kong. Moreover, Hong Kong is seen as a regional hub for wildlife
trade and as a favourable location for maintaining a high degree
of political independence.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Objectives.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Communications; Lobbying; Policy Development; Research and Monitoring;
Treaties; Wildlife Trade Monitoring.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>9S0066 Asia general: Strengthening of Conservation and Development
Programmes</B><!--S0066 Asia general Strengthening of Conservation and Development Programmes-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
It has become apparent in recent years that biological conservation
cannot be achieved in the long term without the active support
and participation of local communities. This has led to an expansion
in the number of Integrated Conservation and Development Projects
(ICDPs), which aim to meet development needs while managing and
conserving natural resources. Within the Asia/Pacific region,
there are a large number of ICDPs being carried out by international
and local NGOs, as well as by governments and donor agencies.
In many cases, organizations and individuals are embarking on
ICDPs without the requisite knowledge and skills to successfully
implement these complex programmes. This project aims to strengthen
ICDPs in the region by addressing training, capacity building,
and information dissemination needs. <BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     50</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  25</TD><TD WIDTH=28>
</TD><TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  50</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   25</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    20</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 30</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Increasing numbers of Integrated Conservation and Development
Projects (ICDPs) are being designed and implemented by conservation
NGOs. It is therefore essential that those involved have the necessary
skills to design and implement them. In recent years, WWF has
become concerned that the chances of a large number of community-based
conservation projects achieving their objectives may be hindered
by a limitation of sufficient skills and knowledge. Recognizing
that effective implementation can only occur in the long term
through building local capacity and facilitating information exchange,
the Asia/Pacific Programme, with the help of WWF-US, organized
two regional workshops in 1993. The success of these initial workshops
highlighted the need to try and address the requirement for training,
capacity building, and information dissemination in the Asia/Pacific
region in a systematic and long&#173;term manner, such that the
full potential of ICDPs as a conservation strategy can be realised.
This project aims to establish a programme that will use participatory
approaches to: identify and assess ICDP training needs in the
region; design and implement a training programme that will help
develop a core of ICDP trainers in the region; develop and disseminate
training materials and information on ICDPs; and initiate an ICDP
network to further facilitate information flow and exchange.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To improve capacity of WWF in&#173;country offices and partners
in the Asia/Pacific region to design, implement, monitor, and
evaluate ICDPs through establishment of a long-term training programme.

<P>
2.  To develop a core of trainers in the region who are capable
of undertaking future ICDP-related training.
<P>
3.  To increase information exchange and enable transfer and adoption
of new training approaches and methodologies on ICDPs.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0066.1: Strengthening of Conservation and Development
