<P>
<B>9S0074 Asia general: Indochina General: CITES Enforcement Training
Seminar</B><!--S0074 Asia general Indochina General CITES Enforcement Training Seminar-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
Indochina's tigers and other species, some of which exist nowhere
else in the world, are seriously endangered because of the illegal
and growing trade in wildlife. This project provides training
of trainers (customs officials and scientists) by the CITES Secretariat
and TRAFFIC Southeast Asia. Initially, 90 customs officials will
be trained.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     50</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     50</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  50</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  50
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Indochina is one of the richest areas of biodiversity in South-East
Asia. Over the last 100 years, and in the last two years in particular,
species unknown to western and Vietnamese scientists have been
discovered living near the Laotian and Vietnamese border. For
over 30 years the region was in a constant state of war and much
habitat was destroyed as a direct result of massive bombing, napalming,
and defoliation. In the past 10 years, since the war in Vietnam
ended, scientists have been assessing the status of habitat and
restoring it, and attempting to assess the distribution and status
of species in Vietnam. <BR>

<P>
WWF has been documenting the wildlife trade in Vietnam since 1985
and in recent years has supported monitoring and investigation
of this trade. Following recommendations from WWF and TRAFFIC,
Vietnam acceded to CITES in February 1994. However, the illegal
wildlife trade, particularly in tiger bones and tiger derivatives,
continues and appears to be escalating. Elephants are also being
poached for ivory, skins and other parts, while wild cats (including
clouded leopard, black panther, and spotted leopard), bear and
bear parts including gall bladders are also being hunted and exported
illegally. In March 1995 WWF and IUCN's Cat Specialist Group convened
a workshop with Vietnam's Ministry of Forestry (the CITES Management
Authority in Vietnam) on conservation of the tiger; participants
came from Vietnam, Cambodia, and Laos. Reports at the workshop
and subsequent reports from Vietnam indicated that Indochina is
losing at least one tiger per week to hunters and the illegal
wildlife trade. A June 1995 WWF-supported workshop on elephants
revealed that in one province alone 48 elephants had been killed
in the previous two years. Duty-free tiger bone wine, seahorses,
and other wildlife parts from threatened or endangered species
are openly on sale in markets and in Duty Free shops at airports.
With the influx of visitors and businessmen from Hong Kong, China,
South Korea, Taiwan, and Japan, this illicit trade has been stimulated
and is flourishing both overtly and underground.<BR>

<P>
In March 1995, MOF appealed for help in stemming this trade and
proposed that CITES conduct a training workshop in Vietnam. CITES
agreed to train the trainers and customs officials in cooperation
with TRAFFIC Southeast Asia, Vietnamese scientists, and the Ministry
of Forestry. The first workshop, in October 1995, included two
members of the CITES Secretariat, a representative from the Vietnamese
Ministry of Forestry, CRES (the CITES Scientific Authority), IEBR,
FIPI, and trainers from three key border areas of Vietnam, including
Hanoi, Danang, and Ho Chi Minh City. This project seeks to continue
this training.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To train customs officials at key border points in identification
techniques for species and species parts and medicine, particularly
tiger and tiger parts and deriviatives.
<P>
2.  To build capacity for Vietnamese CITES Managment and Customs
authorities to train customs authorities in other border areas,
particularly remote ones.
<P>
3.  To eliminate the sale of tiger bone products or medicines
containing or purporting to contain tiger bone and other parts
from all airports in Vietnam, both domestic and international,
by early 1996.
<P>
4.  To reduce and eliminate as soon as possible the sale of other
CITES-listed species.
<P>
5.  To stimulate strengthening of national and international legislation
which regulates or prohibits the trade in wildlife.<BR>
<BR>

