<P>
<B>(Concept) 9S0063 Asia general: &quot;People and Plants&quot;
in the Asia Programme</B><!--S0063 Asia general &quot;People and Plants&quot; in the Asia Programme-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
The project aims to build capacity within certain Asian countries
to work with local communities on conservation issues relating
to the use of wild plants. Methodology includes demonstration
projects. Particular attention will be paid to requests for assistance
by WWF field projects. The project is part of a wider &quot;People
and Plants&quot; initiative. Support for an Asian coordinator
is requested.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     60</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  10</TD><TD WIDTH=28>
</TD><TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   10</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  20</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     20</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 80</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
This project forms part of the &quot;People and Plants&quot; joint
initiative of WWF in association with UNESCO and the Royal Botanic
Gardens, Kew. The purpose of the initiative, which began in July
1992, is to raise the capacity within certain countries, notably
some of those with tropical forest, for work with local communities
on conservation issues arising from the use of wild plants. Methods
include: (a) a limited number of demonstration projects; (b) support
for advice to, or visits between, projects to share experiences;
(c) workshops; (d) writing and provision of manuals on practical
techniques; (e) provision of working papers and other information.
The need to augment the capacity to work with local people on
conservation issues relating to the use of wild plants is evident
in Asia; for example in connection with the wide&#173;scale overharvesting
of medicinal plants (e.g. in the Himalayas and China) and of rattans,
leading to reduction in available resources, lower rural incomes,
and probably erosion of genetic diversity.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
Main objective:
<P>
1.  To raise the capacity in selected Asian countries for work
with local communities on conservation issues relating to the
use of wild plants.<BR>

<P>
Specific objectives:
<P>
2.  To continue work on the demonstration project at Kinabalu-
<P>
3.  To appoint a &quot;People and Plants&quot; coordinator for
Asia, to develop and implement an efficient strategy for Asia.
<P>
4.  To exchange experiences through visits to, and between, projects.
<P>
5.  To provide manuals and other literature.
<P>
6.  Workshops in connection with the international meetings.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0063.1: People and Plants (Jul. 94 - Jun. 99</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
Work at Kinabalu National Park, Malaysia, will continue. This
is a major component in which Sabah Parks works with local communities
to study the uses of plants, to identify conservation issues and,
when found, search for solutions. There is a strong training component
through provision of research and training grants. This project
has received support from the MacArthur Foundation for 1993&#173;96,
with &quot;People and Plants&quot; involved in project formulation
and submission. The MacArthur grant is administered by Sabah Parks.
A coordinator for Asia will develop a strategy for Asia, based
on an assessment of existing WWF strengths in ethnobotany and
plant resource use within Asia, and identification of priority
actions to most effectively meet project objectives. A list of
key contacts within WWF for involvement is requested from the
Asia team. Workshops at local levels and exchanges between projects
are likely to be major components, including compilation of a
list of key people for provision of information. It is hoped that
the Kinabalu project can be used as a resource centre for visits
by staff from other WWF projects or reciprocal movements. <BR>

<P>
<B>Proposed source of funding: </B>WWF own funds - Asia Programme
Budget: CHF 75,000 (field expenses) are requested to cover the
costs of the Asia coordinator (salary, travel, subsistence, and
other project running expenses). This amount (subject to revision
on experience) is requested for each of three years, 1994&#173;1997;
Multiregional Programme: Project WWF 9Z0556 (promotion of ethnobotany
and sustainable use of plant resources) will meet some costs of
the project, including the salary of the &quot;People and Plants&quot;
coordinator who initiated the project at Kinabalu, where he will
continue to be involved (this money will now come to WWF 9Z0556
from the Darwin Initiative).<BR>

<P>
<B>Aid agencies or external foundations:</B>
<P>
1.  MacArthur Foundation (Kinabalu; grant to Sabah Parks for 1993&#173;96),
US$350,000.
<P>
2.  Darwin Initiative (UK grant). Support for &quot;People and
Plants&quot; 1993&#173;96. Mainly for salaries and expenses of
two coordinators and project components in Africa, &#163;368,500.
<P>
3.  A grant of US$20,000 was made for the work at Kinabalu in
1992&#173;93 from the Tropical Forestry Programme (US) but no
further funding from this source is anticipated at present.
<P>
4.  UNESCO will provide some financial and other support for &quot;People
and Plants&quot; (from July 1994) but details await finalization.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>(Concept) 9S0069 Asia general: The Ivory Trade in Selected
Consuming Countries in Asia</B><!--S0069 Asia general The Ivory Trade in Selected Consuming Countries in Asia-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
As the ivory trade ban under CITES enters its fifth year, there
is a need to assess the state of Asia's traditional ivory manufacturing
industries and to determine whether past markets persist or new
ivory markets have developed. This project will compare the current
situation with the findings of the comprehensive Ivory Trade Review
Group studies undertaken in 1989. Detailed analyses will be made
of ivory markets in key consumer countries. The results will be
compiled as a report for consideration in the context of continuing
calls by certain African elephant range states to reopen the trade
and to assist in the development of WWF policy in this issue.
<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     30</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 10</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  60
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
For centuries, enormous economic and cultural value has been attached
in Asia to ivory from both Asian and African elephants. Soaring
demand and prices in the 1970s and 1980s drove drastically damaging
uncontrolled elephant harvests in many range countries, and various
international measures were introduced under CITES in the hope
of reducing threats to elephant populations through the regulation
of the international ivory trade. Several countries in Asia played
key roles in the ivory trade, as centres of ivory carving, range
states of Asian elephants, and as consumers of ivory products.
With the listing of the African elephant in CITES Appendix I in
1989, legal international trade in elephant ivory ceased. Trade
monitoring prior to the ban, including the comprehensive studies
carried out in 1989 in Japan, China, Hong Kong, Taiwan, and India
by the Ivory Trade Review Group, confirmed the crucial role played
by Asian countries during the boom years of the trade. After the
ban, many Asian governments introduced strict controls on the
domestic trade of ivory and the use of stockpiles, some huge,
held in the region. Though TRAFFIC has continued to monitor trends
in the ivory trade in Asia, particularly through the tracking
and analysis of ivory seizures, no comprehensive studies of Asian
processing centres and markets have been carried out since 1989.
Available evidence indicates that some Asian countries continue
to feature as destinations of illegal ivory shipments. Furthermore,
pressure continues from certain African elephant range states
in support of the reopening of ivory trade and in these and other
countries stockpiles are increasing. With these factors in mind,
the TRAFFIC Network identifies a growing necessity to carry out
some comprehensive reviews of the ivory market in key consuming
countries in order to be in a position to predict any related
problems and to provide advice to the CITES Parties in their future
deliberations on ivory trade controls.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To carry out comprehensive assessments of the ivory trade
in key consuming countries.
<P>
2.  To compare the findings of these assessments with the results
of studies carried out prior to the international ivory trade
ban.
<P>
3.  To evaluate policy and legislation in those consuming countries
and capacity for law enforcement.
<P>
4.  To interpret results of the above as they relate to the effectiveness
of the CITES ban on trade in elephant products.
<P>
5.  To provide the CITES Parties with up&#173;to&#173;date information
on the status of the ivory trade in key consuming countries prior
to the 10th meeting of the Conference of the Parties to the Convention
to be held in 1997.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0069.1: The Ivory Trade in Selected Consuming Countries
in Asia (Jul. 95 - Jun. 99</B>)<BR>
