<P>
<B>(Concept) 9S0070 Asia general: Chemical Pollution and Biodiversity
- Promoting Scientific Networking</B><!--S0070 Asia general Chemical Pollution and Biodiversity - Promoting Scientific Networking-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
This project aims to begin work on endocrine disrupters in the
ASEAN region, with the primary focus being on the development
of a scientific network. The recently established Institute for
Environment and Development (IED), based at the National University
of Malaysia, has expressed its interest and willingness to coordinate
the proposed scientific networking in consultation with WWF-Malaysia,
WWF&#173;US, and WWF International. The data thus generated, and
the experience thus gained, will not only further the scientific
evidence on the impacts of endocrine disruptors on human health
and wildlife, but could also play a major role in raising awareness
and initiating action for appropriate remedial measures.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 50
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  25</TD><TD WIDTH=28>
</TD><TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   25</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  25</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     25</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  25</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  10
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  15
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
WWF&#173;US has been playing a significant role over the past
few years in highlighting the adverse effects of chemical contamination,
including the impacts of endocrine disruptors in our environment
on human health and wildlife. The issue of endocrine disruptors
has not only received worldwide media attention, but has also
triggered considerable public concern, as well as attracting the
attention of decision makers, researchers, NGOs and the chemical
industry. WWF's Resource Consumption &amp; Pollution Advisory
Group (RCPPAG) has already expressed its interest in pushing forward
the issue of endocrine disruptors at various national, regional,
and international fora. Given its existing level of interest and
the significance, at the 1995 WWF&#173;US Asia/Pacific Programme
and Policy Planning Meeting held in Washington, Rich Liroff of
WWF&#173;US and Martin Abraham of WWF International/AEP, drafted
a preliminary project concept, outlining the beginnings of a process
for scientific networking in the ASEAN region on endocrine disruptors.
The preliminary project concept was subsequently submitted to
the WWF&#173;US Asia/Pacific SE Asia Subregional Team, and the
WWF RCPAG Envpol Subgroup for discussion and endorsement. <BR>

<P>
The newly established Institute for Environment and Development
(IED), located at the National University of Malaysia, was identified
as a possible focal point for coordinating the scientific network
in the ASEAN region for the following reasons: one of the project
originators, Martin Abraham, Project Director of the WWF International/AEP,
is outposted at WWF-Malaysia, and has been working closely with
WWF International and WWF&#173;US on endocrine disruptors; both
the Institute for Environment and Development and the National
University of Malaysia have had long-standing and strong links
with WWF-Malaysia, as well as other international/regional national
research institutions, including several universities, the Institute
for Medical Research and the International Medical College, based
in Malaysia and elsewhere in the ASEAN region; the Institute for
Environment and Development is a multidisciplinary scientific
institution, focusing primarily on research (rather than on broad&#173;based
policy or advocacy); the ASEAN region is witnessing rapid industrialization,
rapid urbanization, and rapid increase in the use of chemicals,
all of which make it a suitable region for commencing the kind
of scientific networking on endocrine disruptors currently being
proposed. WWF-Malaysia has agreed to the process and scope of
the project concept on endocrine disruptors, with the Institute
for Environment and Development acting as the implementing agency.
The Executive Director of the Institute for Environment and Development,
Prof. Mohd. Nordin Hj. Hasan, has also agreed to the proposed
project in writing, reiterating that subject to the availability
of funds the IED is interested in participating in the proposed
scientific networking on endocrine disruptors; the IED has contacts
with several researchers working on environmental health at the
National University of Malaysia, University of Malaya, and the
University of Michigan.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To develop a network, within two years upon commencement of
the proposed project, of scientists in the ASEAN region actively
engaged in exchanging information and experience on the impacts
of endocrine disruptors on human health and wildlife.
<P>
2.  To provide a counterpart scientific forum in the ASEAN region
for scientists working on endocrine disruptors in the US (including
WWF&#173;US) and Europe.
<P>
3.  To create awareness among the scientific community in the
ASEAN region on the full significance of endocrine disruptors
in the environment to human health and wildlife. 
<P>
4.  To promote a scientific basis for addressing chemical pollution
issues related to endocrine disruptors in developing countries,
particularly in the ASEAN region.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0070.1: Chemical Pollution and Biodiversity - Promoting
