<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 50</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  50
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Tourism is a fast growing industry, in particular in the Asia
region, with very significant impact on people and the environment.
Mobility and tourism are realities of our modern society and this
trend is not likely to change within the foreseeable future. However,
alternative forms of tourism can be developed which have a minimum
impact on social, cultural, and environmental values and which
must preempt less respectful commercial developments. &quot;Ecotourism
is environmentally responsible travel and visitation to enjoy
and appreciate nature (and any accompanying cultural features)
that promotes conservation and sustainable development, has low
visitor impact, and provides for beneficially active socio&#173;economic
involvement of local populations&quot; (IUCN definition by Ceballos&#173;Lascurain,
1992). <BR>

<P>
In the past many ecotourism project initiatives have failed due
to lack of good marketing knowledge or unfavourable pricing conditions
imposed by tour operators. Many WWF project contain ecotourism
components. Over the past five years WWF has commissioned several
studies which have enhanced our understanding of the subject,
e.g. &quot;Ecotourism: The Potentials and Pitfalls&quot; by Elizabeth
Boo, and &quot;Beyond the Green Horizon&quot; by WWF-UK. Many
other organizations have published valuable documents, many of
which highlight successes and failures of various ecotourism initiatives
and provide guidelines for sound ecotourism development. <BR>

<P>
Two types of ecotourism may be distinguished, each dealing with
different audiences and markets. The first type is &quot;high
cost exclusive adventure and nature tourism&quot;, well known
from Tiger Tops in Nepal. The tourists get high quality guidance
and service and pay high rates accordingly (up to US$200 per day).
If properly organized, local people benefit from hosting, catering,
guiding, etc. This type of enterprise is not normally managed
by local communities but by an entrepreneur who pays a concession
fee to the government for using the services of protected areas.
This project aims to develop structures and ways to ensure that
most of this exclusive income flows back to the local community.
<BR>

<P>
The second type is &quot;low cost community based ecotourism&quot;.
WWF is supporting many Integrated Conservation and Development
Programmes (ICDPs) which promote low-cost and low-impact tourism
as a means of generating income for local communities living near
protected areas. Most of the community based ecotourism projects
have only modest facilities and are located in remote areas with
difficult means of communication. As a result the fees are low
and this kind of tourism generally attracts unorganized backpackers.
Tour operators are less interested in promoting this form of tourism
because there are little financial incentives for them. This project
aims to promote these small-scale community based tourism sites
through means of media. The Asia Ecotourism project intends to
capitalize on the past work done by WWF and other organizations
and intends to eliminate a few remaining obstacles, in particularly
in the area of promotion and marketing.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
Main objective:
<P>
1.  To establish a resource centre for ecotourism which should
promote ecotourism in Asia as an economically viable means of
empowering local people, generating income for local communities
and protected areas, and achieving conservation. <BR>

<P>
Specific objectives:
<P>
2.  To identify potential ecotourism sites and assist local communities
in developing ecotourism business plans.
<P>
3.  To provide information and advisory services to WWF NOs, POs,
field level programmes, other environmental NGOs, and tourist
offices in the region concerned with ecotourism.
<P>
4.  To develop ecotourism site marketing plans and specific ecotourism
packages for promotion via tour operators, publishers of travel
guides, Internet, press and other media.
<P>
5.  To organize regional seminars and workshops for promoting
ecotourism.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0075.1: Promoting Ecotourism in Asia (Jul. 96 - Jun. 01</B>)
<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Background.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To set up an ecotourism centre for Asia within the Asia region
in collaboration with environmental organizations and national
tourist offices, identifying (a) ecotourism sites for high cost
promotion and (b) ecotourism sites for low cost promotion; 
<P>
2.  To establish ecotourism business plans in collaboration with
local communities.
<P>
3.  To create ecotourism databases in each country.
<P>
4.  To develop generally recognized ecotourism labelling standards
for tour operators, hotels and lodges, together with tourism organizations.
<P>
5.  To establish a database of nature tour operators, hotels and
lodges worldwide willing to adhere to ecotourism standards and
codes of conducts.
<P>
6.  To initiate and promote ecotourism through annual seminars
and workshops and through the establishment of regional and national
networks.
<P>
7.  To establish a marketing and promotion plan to make the centre
economically viable.<BR>

<P>
The activities will initially focus on the country of operation
and gradually expand to neighbouring countries so as to create
exemplary approaches for replication elsewhere.
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Methods:</B></I></U>
<P>
Ecotourism Development.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>(Concept) 9S0079 Asia general: SE Asia Campaign for Coral Reef
Protection and Sustainable Fishing</B><!--S0079 Asia general SE Asia Campaign for Coral Reef Protection and Sustainable Fishing-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
The central aim of this project is to stop dynamite and cyanide
fisheries in Indonesia and the Philippines and to promote sustainable
ways of fishing. WWF-Netherlands has recently agreed to allocate
funding to jointly design, set up and implement a major policy
initiative that will especially focus on the international dimension
of dynamite and cyanide fishing in Indonesia. The establishment
of a project coordinator in Jakarta would coordinate work with
TRAFFIC SE Asia and other WWF offices in the region, such as the
Philippines, Hong Kong and Malaysia. For the European market in
ornamental fish and coral products a link would be made with WWF&#173;Netherlands.
<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  100
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Over 30% of the world's coral reefs occur in SE Asia. Philippines
and Malaysia have major reef systems but Indonesia, with 81,000
sq km of coastline and over 17,000 islands, is of critical importance
as the centre of coral reef ecosystem biodiversity (Wells, 1993).
Current major threats to the reefs are the rapid spread of overfishing,
the ornamental fish trade and trade for consumption, and the use
of destructive fishing methods such as dynamite and cyanide. WWF
Indonesia Programme Office has two large field projects in progress
which demonstrate how unsustainable fishing can be avoided, along
the lines of the ICDP approach. The WWF Philippines Programme
Office has developed a concept for a similar field project. <BR>

<P>
One of the objectives of the bilateral cooperation between WWF&#173;Netherlands
and WWF in Indonesia is to complement marine field projects with
policy activities that would address destructive fishing methods.
The international dimension of the problem means that investors
and consumers can be found in Hong Kong, Taiwan, and other states
in the region. Over the past six years WWF in Indonesia has worked
for coral reef protection and initiated Bunaken Park, which was
later developed further by USAID. The large pristine reef area
in Irian Jaya, the Teluk Cendrawasih NP, was established and is
managed with the help of local communities and the government.
A third field project is Taka Bona Rate in South Sulawesi. A visitor
centre was established in the Bay of Jakarta and regular information
is shared with the public from the Jakarta office. WWF Philippines
Programme Office takes the lead at a regional level in developing
various approaches to managing the dynamite and cyanide problem.
El Nido Marine Reserve in Palawan, and Turtle Island are two WWF
Philippine Programme Office projects. The country plan focuses
on marine and small island ecosystems dealing with the prevention
of cyanide fishing. Funding for this programme is still pending.
<BR>

<P>
Hong Kong plays a major role in driving the live reef fish trade.
WWF-Hong Kong's objectives are to include live reef fish in the
Hong Kong trade statistics; push the Hong Kong government to establish
a cyanide detection lab; increasing fines for possessing and using
cyanide/dynamite. The TRAFFIC network, comprised of Hong Kong,
Japan, Taiwan, and the SE Asia office, plan preliminary research
into the live reef fish trade, pending funding. WWF's &quot;Endangered
Seas Campaign&quot; has a regional campaign against dynamite and
cyanide fishing based on the integration of fieldwork, trade monitoring,
and policy work. In order to develop this initiative into a major
campaign with fundraising possibilities for SE Asia, the campaign
will provide policy support and input additional funding so as
to enable WWF in the Philippines to fully participate in this
project. <BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To raise the issues to a higher level in government and private
sector agendas.
<P>
2.  To communicate a better alternative for dynamite and cyanide
fishing in the fishery sector, involving local fishermen and redefining
the role of middlemen, based on models in Indonesia and the Philippines.
<P>
3.  To develop and implement a model governmental policy and test
it in at least two countries, from national down to district level.
<P>
4.  To ensure that a model government policy is adopted by the
ASEAN.
<P>
5.  To enable two or three major actors in the chain to demonstrate
how their business can contribute to a solution, such as a cyanide
company banning cyanide, a navy contributing to patrolling, a
trader receiving certification, consumers groups banning certain
products, or diving tour operators building awareness.
<P>
6.  To ensure the listing and/or uplisting by CITES of some key
species.
<P>
7.  To encourage the European Union to ensure compliance to CITES
with regard to the trade of coral products and ornamental fish.
<P>
8.  To attract one or two major donors to support and follow this
campaign.
<P>
9.  To secure funding for a coral reef protection project that
complements COREMAP and other existing projects in the region.
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0079.1: SE Asia Campaign for Coral Reef Protection and
Sustainable Fishing (Jul. 96 - Jun. 97</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Background.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Objectives.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Biomes:</B></I></U>
<P>
Coral Reefs.<BR>

<P>
