<P>
<B>(Concept) 9S0705 Asia general: Philippine&#173;Sabah Turtle
Islands Transboundary Protected Area</B><!--S0705 Asia general Philippine&#173;Sabah Turtle Islands Transboundary Protected Area-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
The Proposed Regional Marine Turtle Conservation Programme for
ASEAN gives direction for future actions towards the conservation
of these endangered species (six of the seven sea turtles are
reported to occur within the region). Notable among the recommendations
is the establishment of transboundary protected areas (PAs) which
support important aggregations sea turtles. Areas proposed include
the Philippine&#173;Sabah Turtle Islands, Sipadan Island, and
Berau Islands which support the region's largest breeding aggregation
of green turtles (&quot;Chelonia mydas&quot;). Whilst the proposed
programme goes through the ASEAN decision-making process, critical
actions are necessary in the interim to establish the first transfrontier
PA in the region, involving three of the six member nations (Philippines,
Malaysia, and Indonesia). This project will enable the preparation
of strategies for the establishment and eventual joint management
of these islands. It will also provide a forum for involving local
communities and agencies, such as the local government in the
Philippines Turtle Islands, as well as the Departments of Wildlife
and National Parks in Sabah.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    100</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
The Philippine&#173;Sabah Turtle Islands is an area high in conservation
value whose productivity is facing multiple threats. It is an
ideal site for WWF to demonstrate Integrated Coastal Management
(ICM) as an effective tool for conserving coastal areas of high
biological importance. Existing development plans for the area
indicate a trend towards increasing pressure on the marine resources.
Although soon to be managed as a priority site under the Philippines'
Integrated Protected Areas System (IPAS), the lack of an ICM plan
may jeopardize the conservation goals. Ecotourism, for example,
if not planned within the context of an ICM may cause profound
negative impacts on the population of sea turtles, as well as
on the environment in general. Although the marine waters of the
area have great potential for fisheries development, fishing activities
should be properly managed and monitored in order to avoid overfishing
and the collapse of fish stocks. Marine pollution prevention is
another important component of an ICM for the transboundary management
area. Siltation from the Sabah mainland and the resultant high
turbidity of the waters around Turtle Islands are adversely affecting
organisms such as coral polyps and sea&#173;grasses by limiting
light penetration, and in some cases smothering them altogether.
There is also a loss of aesthetic and recreational qualities.
An ICM plan for the conservation area would consider these various
threats and impacts.<BR>

<P>
Nine islands straddling the Philippine&#173;Sabah Treaty Limits
require serious efforts to conserve sea turtles in the ASEAN Region.
This group of islands, together with the Berau Islands of Indonesia,
is regarded as the only remaining major green turtle rookery in
the entire region, with a combined annual nesting population of
1,953 to 5,440. Over 14 million turtle eggs were produced between
1984 and 1992, with the islands on the Philippine side contributing
about 72% and the remaining 28% laid on the three nesting islands
on the Sabah side. Approximately 10% of the eggs transplanted
and hatchlings released from the Sabah hatcheries were hawksbill
turtles, making the area an important hawksbill nesting site.
Although divided by the treaty limits, data on tag recoveries
gathered by the Pawikan Conservation Project (PCP) and the Sabah
National Parks (SNP) have demonstrated that this group of islands
is a single well-defined rookery. Successful conservation of these
important nesting islands therefore requires a concerted effort
by both the Philippine and Malaysian governments. The establishment
of the group of islands as the first ASEAN Transboundary Marine
Turtle Sanctuary will ensure effective and successful conservation
of a significant population of green and hawksbill turtles for
the benefit of the region.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To determine and agree on critical actions required to pursue
the establishment and eventually the joint management of the first
ASEAN Transboundary Protected Area for the conservation of sea
turtles.
<P>
2.  To prepare a work plan and budget for establishment of the
PA. 
<P>
3.  To conduct consultations with concerned local communities.

<P>
4.  To conduct consensus building seminars with the local communities
and provide them with information regarding the need for the establishment
of the PA and the long-term benefits which may be derived from
the successful management of the PA. 
<P>
5.  To determine possible options to increase the number of turtle
eggs to 70% of the total egg production, and to formulate a monitoring
scheme to document market flow and volume of legal egg harvesting
from the Philippines. 
<P>
6.  To determine the feasibility of declaring a Treaty Area for
the Philippine&#173;Sabah Turtle Islands, similar to the one established
between Papua New Guinea and Northern Australia, which allows
for indigenous people to continue to practice their traditional
wildlife collection and hunting activities, including the local
marketing and consumption of their catch/harvest. <BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0705.1: Transboundary Marine Turtle Conservation Area
(Jul. 94 - Jun. 99</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Background.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
1.  To formally establish and manage the first Transboundary Sea
Turtle Sanctuary in the region.
<P>
2.  To develop and implement an Integrated Coastal Management
Plan for the transboundary sanctuary.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>(Concept) 9S0717 Asia general: Biodiversity Studies of the
Mekong River and Watersheds</B><!--S0717 Asia general Biodiversity Studies of the Mekong River and Watersheds-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
The project will have three phases: 1) Project Development (year
1): a survey of the existing information on the Mekong River and
its watershed, as well as a preliminary field investigation. The
major output will be the preparation of a bibliography, compilation
of existing maps, and a proposal for the next phase of the project;
2) Ecological Inventory (ca. 2-3 years): a broad ecological survey
of the watershed using remote sensing and GIS, and a more detailed
survey of riverine biota. The major output will be a book on the
ecology of the river and watershed and a proposed biodiversity
conservation programme for the Mekong; 3) Institutionalization
of the programme within the Mekong Secretariat: the project will
assist the Secretariat carry forward the conservation programme
for at least a year.<BR>

