<P>
<B>(Concept) 9S0718 Asia general: Model Legislation Suite for
Biodiversity Conservation</B><!--S0718 Asia general Model Legislation Suite for Biodiversity Conservation-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
In many Asian countries legislation on natural resources, such
as forests, national parks, water, and minerals, are not consistent
with the promotion of the sustainable use of resources and the
conservation of biodiversity. This project is aimed at developing
a framework for natural resources conservation that meets the
goals of conservation. The framework will serve as a model for
examining the consistency of legislation on natural resources
in Asian countries.<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Forests     0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    25</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  75
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
Durung the execution of the IPAS1 programme in the Philippines
(under which 10 national parks were created and in which WWF was
the major player), one of the major outputs was draft legislation
for protected areas (PAs) in the country. In 1992, the bill based
on that draft legislation was enacted into law. The law has been
praised by many as technically sound and socially progressive,
especially in the treatment of indigenous communities. On the
basis of the IPAS experience, the WWF Asia/Pacific Programme developed
a model legislation for PAs. The model is now being used by some
countries of the region in formulating new, or amending existing,
legislation. Building on these experiences, the Asia/Pacific Programme
would like to move forward by developing a framework for all legislation
relevant to the sustainable use of natural resources.<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
1.  To conduct a survey of natural resource legislation for biologically
important countries of the region.
<P>
2.  To examine selected legislation for consistency with biodiversity
conservation and sustainable use.
<P>
3.  To draft a set of framework legislation for natural resources
that promote conservation.
<P>
4.  To conduct a workshop for the purpose of vetting the framework
legislation.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0718.1: Model Legislation Suite (Jul. 96 - Jun. 99</B>)
<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Background.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Objectives.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>(Concept) 9S0720 Asia general: ASEAN Regional Sea Turtle Conservation
Programme</B><!--S0720 Asia general ASEAN Regional Sea Turtle Conservation Programme-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
The overall aim of the programme is to ensure the survival of
sea turtles for their ecological, cultural, and economic values
for the continued benefit of the peoples of the ASEAN region.
The programme will develop and implement six major components.
WWF will prepare and package a funding proposal in consultation
with participating agencies and NGOs. The programme proposal will
be submitted to potential funding bodies such as GEF, USAID, etc.
<BR>

<TABLE>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Priority Biomes</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307></TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307><U><B>Strategies</B></U><B>    <U>%</U></B>Forests     0
</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Consumption &amp; Pollution 0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Freshwater Ecosystems  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>EE &amp; Capacity Building  0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Oceans and Coasts   100</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Protected Areas    0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Biomes  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Species     100</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Biome Specific  0</TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD>
<TD WIDTH=307>Sustainable Resource Use 0</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Treaties &amp; Legislation  0
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=307></TD><TD WIDTH=28></TD><TD WIDTH=307>Non-Priority Strategies  0
</TD></TR>

</TABLE>

<P>
<U><B>Project Background:</B></U>
<P>
In an effort to develop a comprehensive regional sea turtle conservation
programme, the First ASEAN Symposium Workshop on Sea Turtle Conservation
was held in December 1993. The proposed programme passed through
the ASEAN decision-making process and has already been approved
by the ASEAN Working Group on Nature Conservation and subsequently
by the ASEAN Senior Officials of the Environment. <BR>

<P>
Since the Regional Sea Turtle Conservation Programme will be a
major and comprehensive regional initiative, funding negotiations
are anticipated to be lengthy before full funding is secured.
The programme is planned to be implemented in two phases: Phase
1 will be concerned with initial programme development, institution
building (organizing an ASEAN Marine Turtle Specialist Group),
and fundraising. During this interim phase, WWF will fund and
implement selected activities which will pave the way for the
smooth implementation of subsequent component activities. In support
of programme development and to achieve a strong commitment from
member states of ASEAN, WWF has drafted an agreement on the Regional
Sea Turtle Programme to be signed by government representatives.
An important output of this phase will be a detailed five&#173;year
conservation action plan which will provide the basis for activities
under Phase 2. Phase 2 will cover the final development and implementation
of the programme. This will set in motion the major programme
components, e.g. institution building, conduct of management&#173;oriented
and basic research, capacity building and public awareness campaigns,
international linkaging, resource management and protection, and
the development of a sustainable financing mechanism. <BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Objectives:</B></U>
<P>
<B>On information systems:</B>
<P>
1.  To develop a regional information system for marine turtles
in the ASEAN region.
<P>
2.  To review the work carried out on marine turtles in the region
with the aim of determining the trend in population, and status
of research and management efforts.<BR>

<P>
<B>On institution building:</B>
<P>
3.  To create and formally organize an ASEAN Marine Turtle Specialist
Group. This would function as an advisory group to the ASEAN Working
Group on Nature Conservation (AWGNC) and would formulate and recommend
policies and programmes for marine turtle conservation in the
region.<BR>

<P>
<B>On research and monitoring</B>:
<P>
4.  To conduct scientific investigations on the population status
and distribution of marine turtles in the region.
<P>
5.  To conduct studies on current rates of harvest and recommend
management interventions where required.
<P>
6.  To conduct relevant studies on all aspects of the life-cycle
of sea turtles in order to generate the information needed to
update or formulate management strategies.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>On capability building and awareness</B>:
<P>
7.  To coordinate training and education activities for appropriate
personnel involved in sea turtle conservation in the region.
<P>
8.  To develop an educational programme promoting marine turtle
conservation in the region.
<P>
9.  To facilitate sharing of successful information and educational
programmes.
<P>
10.  To promote community involvement by local NGOs, religious
groups, etc. in the development of local or community projects
involving marine turtles.<BR>

<P>
<B>On international efforts/linkages:</B>
<P>
11.  To encourage countries to accede to international species
conservation agreements (e.g., CITES, Bonn Convention).
<P>
12.  To participate in international efforts promoting the conservation,
management, and wise use of marine turtles.
<P>
13.  To encourage exchange of information and development of joint
conservation programmes between range countries within the region.
<BR>

<P>
<B>On resource management and protection</B>:
<P>
14.  To establish regionally and globally significant areas as
ASEAN Natural Heritage/Conservation and Transboundary Protected
Areas.
<P>
15.  To encourage joint management schemes in significant turtle
areas that share common boundaries or international borders.
<P>
16.  To discourage the use of commercial fishing methods which
contribute to high mortalities or destroy turtle habitats.<BR>

<P>
<B>On sustainable financing and other support measures</B>:
<P>
17.  To develop professional administrative and technical support
staff based in the Philippines for the immediate and long-term
implementation of the project by WWF and other appropriate institutions
in the ASEAN region.
<P>
18.  To develop and institutionalize a sustainable financing plan
for a long-term conservation programme of marine turtles in the
ASEAN region and in other range countries.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<I><B>9S0720.1: ASEAN Regional Sea Turtle Conservation Programme
(Jul. 95 - Jun. 99</B>)<BR>
<BR>
</I>
<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Background:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Background.<BR>

<P>
<U><I><B>Activity Objectives:</B></I></U>
<P>
See Project Objectives.<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<B>(Concept) 9S0721 Asia general: Model Agreement on Transborder
Reserves</B><!--S0721 Asia general Model Agreement on Transborder Reserves-->
<BR>
<BR>

<P>
<U><B>Project Summary</B></U><B>:</B>
<P>
This project is aimed at developing a model multilateral agreement
on transborder protected areas (PAs). The model will address issues
on sustainable financing, governance and management, protocols,
and technical considerations of transborder PAs. A workshop will
be convened to vet the draft model agreement, after which the
final version will be published and circulated in the region.
<BR>

