<HEAD>

<TITLE> UN Framework Convention on Climate Change</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/graphics/back.gif">

<blockquote>

<CENTER><FONT SIZE=+2><b>WWF Position Statement<br></b>
                                                        June 1996<p>

UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, <br>
Geneva, 8 - 19 July 1996<p></center></font>

<a name="1"><B>Intensifying Efforts on the Berlin Mandate</B></a>

<p>
Time is running out if the Berlin Mandate is to be fulfilled. There is an urgent need at AGBM4 for governments to identify a 
course of action to accelerate completion of the negotiations which can then be endorsed by Ministers at COP2.
<p>
<ul>
<LI>	The new science underlines the validity of the Toronto target, of a 20 per cent cut in anthropogenic emissions of 
CO<SUB>2</SUB> by 2005, which was envisaged as &quot;the initial global goal&quot; for industrialized countries and which is 
embodied in the AOSIS protocol. 
<p>
<LI>	The IPCC SAR shows that early action is required to start sending greenhouse gas emission curves on a manageable, 
smooth downward path. A more recent study by RIVM has demonstrated that it is already extremely difficult to avoid rates of 
temperature change which can be tolerated by many ecosystems. WWF is aware that even 0.10 degrees/decade temperature increase 
is too much for some species. 
<p>
<LI>	The earlier the emissions are lower, the more flexibility future generations will have in selecting climate goals and 
emission pathways. Allowing countries flexibility in the timing of reductions will not ensure cost reductions, and comes at 
the price of increased environmental damage in all countries. Credible, fixed timetables are needed to stimulate global 
investment and research into clean technologies; hesitation will lead to the irreversible adoption of polluting development 
paths, and thus larger mitigation costs in the future. The focus has to be on HOW to stimulate investment decisions in 
environmentally sound energy technologies NOW and not delay until later.
<p>
<LI>	The IPCC SAR shows that significant no regrets measures are feasible in most countries, and that 10&#173;30 per cent 
energy efficiency gains above present levels are possible at negative to zero cost in each sector. Some studies show that 40 
per cent gains can be achieved in the short term.
<p>
<LI>	The appropriate instrument for strengthening the Climate Convention is a protocol. WWF does not support the option of 
an amendment and finds proposals for selecting the amendment route based on the argument that this circumvents the unresolved 
issue of the Rules of Procedure particularly unacceptable. The Rules of Procedure can and must be resolved.
<p>
<LI>	The success of the Berlin Mandate process rests with the industrialized countries which have to assume their 
responsibilities and make cuts so that there is environmental space for raising living standards in developing countries. 
Only commitments  by the industrialized countries can lead the world into action which will prevent dangerous anthropogenic 
interference with the climate system.
<p></ul>
Yet, whilst governments indicated at AGBM3 they were considering the substance of the problems, few countries indicated that 
they had devised a timetable to produce results. WWF considers it is time to carve out a manageable package of actions which 
will lead to a successful conclusion for the Berlin Mandate. WWF therefore suggests that:
<p>
<ul>
a) 	The AGBM process focuses on the 2005 time&#173;frame: the 2010 and 2020 time&#173;frames are examined in more detail 
by SBI which can report back at AGBM7, prior to COP3. SBI can also work with SBSTA using the IPCC Technical paper on the 
Modelling of Stabilization Scenarios to develop targets and timetables for the &quot;safe emissions reduction corridor&quot;.
<p>
b) 	The discussions of policies and measures and the 2005 target are integrated through an Intersessional Working Group 
which will identify, in outline, a broad menu of policies which can contribute to the achievement of the 20 per cent target 
by 2005 and which will report back to AGBM5 with the first results. This group can examine in detail the emerging 
in&#173;depth reviews of national communications, the forthcoming IPCC Technical Report on Policies and Measures, and the 
data in the Second round of National Communications as they become available.  
<p>
</ul>
	The Group should also review Articles in the draft protocols which have been tabled which relate to policies and 
measures, such as proposed coordination mechanism in the AOSIS Protocol and the Annexes in the EU Structure Protocol.
<p>

<a name="2"><B>Taking Stock</B></a>
<p>
COP2 has a central agenda item, &quot;taking stock and intensifying efforts&quot;. AGBM4 therefore has a responsibility to 
move beyond distinct debates to seek a way in which they can be integrated. There were many encouraging signs of progress at 
AGBM3. Most obvious was the fact that those intent on delay for its own sake will not receive attention. More substantively, 
most governments revealed more clearly their views on aspects of the Berlin Mandate so the process was advanced.  However it 
was also clear that already there is more information within the process than there is time for negotiators to respond to.  
But according to the Berlin Mandate, analysis and assessment was only to form a part of the early stages of the negotiations.
<p>
This suggests that new mechanisms and processes are needed so that all relevant information can now be synthesized and used 
to decide action paths. It is also clear that the inter&#173;relationships of the Conventions' Subsidiary Bodies are not yet 
fully resolved and there is an uneven distribution of work between them. 
<p>
In order to expedite progress WWF therefore suggests that SBI be asked to undertake central review work on the longer 
time&#173;frames of the Berlin Mandate (2010 and 2020) and with a view to the starting to envision the action required beyond 
the Mandate, so that global emissions are safely reduced to 50&#173;70 per cent of current levels (which the IPCC has shown 
to be necessary for stabilization of ghgs at all levels of atmospheric concentrations.) 
<p>
<a name="3"><B>IPCC SAR </B></a>
<p>
The Publication of the IPCC's Second Assessment Report has marked a new stage in the negotiations on the FCCC. The IPCC 
unanimously agreed that it is now possible to detect a discernible human influence on climate. The Second Assessment Report 
was produced as a result of a substantial process of analysis and assessment of the major recent developments in science 
relating to climate change. It took two&#173;and&#173;half years and involved 2,000 leading scientists. Its key findings were 
exhaustively reviewed by governments in a series of meetings which took 23 days altogether, often involving evening sessions. 
No longer must we proceed on the precautionary principle alone. Furthermore, with the increased confidence in the climate 
models, their projections for future climate change must galvanize action.
 <p>
The publication of the SAR has been a crucial turning point for policy&#173;making. It has opened up new debates on levels of 
stabilization targets for concentrations, and the EU led the way and became the first group to suggest figures at AGBM3. 
Governments now openly acknowledge the need for cuts of more than 50 per cent in current levels of emissions. 
<p>
There is no way in which all these issues can be resolved by 1997. Nor is that necessary. The Berlin Mandate had its origins 
in the recognition that the industrialized country commitments were not adequate and that there was a need to take 
appropriate action for the period beyond 2000. What is necessary is that legally binding reduction targets are started for 
the post 2000 era through a flexible evolving protocol.
<p>
<a name="4"><B>A flexible protocol</B></a>
<p>
The appropriate instrument for strengthening the Climate Convention is a protocol. WWF does not support the option of an 
amendment and finds proposals for selecting the amendment route based on the argument that this circumvents the unresolved 
issue of the Rules of Procedure particularly unacceptable. The Rules of Procedure can and must be resolved.
<p>
WWF believes that the Climate Convention should be strengthened by the adoption, at COP 3, of a flexible &quot;shell&quot; 
protocol. This would enable the immediate incorporation of a CO<SUB>2</SUB> reduction target of 20 per cent in the year 2005 
for Annex 1 countries, with some other elements, and provide the basis for further development of the protocol. 
<p>
WWF does not rule out the option of a system of protocols, but at the moment there seems to be stronger support for one, 
integrated protocol.
<p>
There is clear agreement that the fulfilment of the Berlin Mandate by the adoption of a legally binding stringent reduction 
target for Annex 1 countries will only be a first step. The process of agreeing on and adjusting the international response 
to climate change will need to be a step&#173;by&#173;step process and WWF believes an evolutionary approach is required to 
strengthening the Convention.
<p>
WWF envisages a protocol which would be continuously developed and which would be flexible enough to incorporate new targets 
and other commitments in the future. The Convention should continue to provide for related decisions and activities, 
including much of the institutional structure.
<p>
<a name="5"><B>The protocol and the review processes of the Convention</B></a>
<p>
Parties should recall that the review processes of the Climate Convention are ongoing. Art.4.2(d), which required COP 1 to 
undertake the review of the adequacy of the commitments in Art.4.2(a) and (b), requires a second review &quot;not later than 
31 December 1998, and thereafter at regular intervals determined by the Conference of the Parties, until the objective of the 
Convention is met&quot;.
<p>
WWF has proposed that a protocol should be closely linked to the review processes of the Convention. It should be designed to 
house targets determined through these processes.
<p>
WWF notes that a critical decision for the COP will be the determination of the &quot;regular intervals&quot; at which 
reviews of the commitments in the Convention will take place after the second review, to take place not later than 31 
December 1998.
<p>
<a name="6"><B>An Early Target Date</B></a>
<p>
The first protocol to the Climate Convention should focus on the year 2005. It is extremely important that a first&#173;step 
strengthening of the Convention, creating new commitments for Annex 1 parties only, is achieved as soon as possible.
<p>
Whilst WWF believes that longer&#173;term reduction targets will have to be set for several greenhouse gases, the focus of 
negotiations should now be the short term, to put in place an unambiguous reduction target rapidly for Annex 1 parties and to 
avoid drawn&#173;out negotiations. A clear signal is needed for investment decisions on less&#173;carbon intensive 
technologies. Take&#173;up of even mature technologies involves short time delays: to develop new supply configurations takes 
more time. The development and diffusion of technology is a complex process which proceeds incrementally both in terms of 
hardware development and its adoption. It is clear that opportunities to achieve timely reductions have already been lost. A 
sudden re&#173;interpretation of the climate impacts assessments, which no longer seems a remote possibility, might require 
punitive early action if first steps are not taken soon.
<p>
<a name="7"><B>GHG Concentration Targets</B></a>
<p>
For achievement of the ultimate objective of the treaty, a target for stabilizing concentrations of greenhouse gases will 
have to be set. WWF's own analysis and assessment reveals that rates of change associated with all but the lowest targets are 
likely to cause serious disturbance to many ecosystems, and will not permit them to adapt naturally to climate change. WWF 
therefore considers that greenhouse gas concentrations in the atmosphere should be stabilized at below 450 ppmv 
CO<SUB>2</SUB> equivalent by 2100. It supports the concept of setting legally binding targets and timetables which achieve a 
&quot;safe emissions reduction corridor&quot; to this stabilization target, taking account of rates of temperature change and 
sea&#173;level rise. 
<p>
However, WWF accepts that negotiation on this cannot be completed by 1997, although it considers that more serious reflection 
of the long&#173;term issues should be accelerated in SBSTA and SBI to inform the AGBM. However, that is not a reason to 
defer first stage action to reduce greenhouse gas emissions. Indeed all informed parties are agreed that the need for 
substantial reductions of emissions is earlier, the lower the concentration target. Those who wish to defer early action are 
implicitly seeking higher stabilization targets. It is of grave concern that high targets (750 ppbv and 1000 ppbv) have even 
been mentioned. A proportionate raising of the impacts would involve temperature increases in the range of 3&#173;9<FONT 
FACE="Symbol">&#176;C for the 1000 ppbv scenario. It is probable there would also be additional, unexpected aquatic and 
biotic feedbacks. The associated impacts would be catastrophic and totally disrupt life on earth.
<p>
<a name="8"><B>Policies and measures</B></a>
<p>
Discussions on policies and measures should have clear boundaries within the FCCC, and be undertaken to meet 
pre&#173;specified targets and timetables, if parties are serious in seeking to achieve progress. Debates should focus on 
policies and measures which would benefit from international coordination, or those which would be more effective through 
coordinated action.
<p>
The National Communications have revealed some 1,000 different policies operating. It is very doubtful, however, if the full 
supporting information is available on the operation of these measures at national or international level, to undertake 
comparative, systematic assessment, during the AGBM process. There are other fora where the difficult task of tackling the 
main priorities has been started, ranging from the EU, OECD/IEA to academic conferences, and the Internet. The IPCC has also 
given clear messages about the scope for policy changes and identified the possible policy portfolio and is due to review 
material in the SAR on this issue in a Technical Report. Mechanisms should therefore be devised for sharing and exchanging 
information outside the mainstream process which can then inform the FCCC negotiations.
<p>
Studies already undertaken have shown that there needs to be coordination on such measures as progressive efficiency 
standards; economic instruments; removal of subsidies on fossil fuels and subsidies on production practices which promote 
greenhouse gas emission, such as in agriculture; and providing incentives for renewable energy during market build up. 
Coordinated action will be necessary to establish the provisions of the Berlin Mandate as an excepted multilateral 
environmental agreement under WTO rules. 
<p>
Above all it is vital to start to link the policies and measures discussions more closely to the achievement of targets in 
timetables, and that is why WWF is proposing accelerating action on this. 
<p>
<a name="9"><B>Differentiation within Annex 1</B></a>
<p>
It is clear that some developed countries are preparing information to justify special treatment during the Berlin Mandate 
process as to why flat rate reductions should not apply to them. Many different approaches have already been suggested to 
vary commitments with &quot;concrete&quot; differentiation.  Most aim to reduce the obligations of the proponent. WWF 
believes that for the long term this issue has to be resolved to the satisfaction of all parties. Ultimately WWF considers 
that permissible emissions should be based on per capita allowances<SUP>1</SUP> rather than as reductions from an arbitrary base.
<p>
However, WWF does not consider that this issue need inhibit the agreement of the envisaged Protocol which essentially will 
use &quot;no regrets&quot; measures, and is concerned that some parties are using differentiation as a means of delaying 
agreement of a protocol in 1997. The possibility of contextual differentiation as a means of reaching flat&#173;rate 
reduction targets would seem to be entirely different and reflects the need for individual countries to use varying means 
which match national circumstances, to reach the same ends.
<p>

<SUP>1</SUP>  As was outlined in <I>Caring for the Earth</I> (1991) IUCN, UNEP, WWF.
<p>

<B>For further information contact:</B>
<p>
Merylyn McKenzie Hedger<br>
