<TD ALIGN=LEFT>


<H2><CENTER>WWF's Europe/Middle East Programme<BR></CENTER></H2>

<p>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<a name="programme"><tt><B>The regional Programme</B></tt></a>


</TD>

</TABLE>




<TABLE CELLPADDING=8 WIDTH=500>

<TR><TD ALIGN=lef>



<IMG align=left SRC="wwf.gif" alt="WWF">

<P>


WWF's Europe and Middle East Regional Programme stretches from

Portugal to the Bering Strait, and from the Arctic Ocean to the

Persian Gulf. WWF has National Organizations (NOs) in 14 countries

within the region, and supports conservation projects in another

18. In all, the programme supports around 120 projects. Set up

to link WWF's various European activities within a regionwide

framework, and to transfer funds from west to east and from north

to south within the region, the programme contains five geographical

subregions: Central and Eastern Europe, the Mediterranean, the

Baltic, the North Sea, and the Arctic. Staff from NOs and WWF

International form subregional teams which coordinate WWF activities

within these programme areas. 


<p>


Meanwhile, a Brussels-based team concentrates on pan-European

policy issues, such as working to influence European Union (EU)

policies on agriculture and development.


<p>


Like other WWF Regional Programmes, the Europe and Middle East

Programme focuses on the organization's Global Priorities to the

Year 2000*, devoting most of its efforts to conserving freshwater

wetlands, oceans and coasts, and forests. In June 1994, WWF embarked

on a three-year European Forest Campaign, to protect and restore

forests throughout the region..

<P>

