<HEAD>



<TITLE>Tiger</TITLE>



<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z Beta">

</HEAD>


<BODY  bgcolor="#ffffff" background="graphics/back.gif" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000000" VLINK="#000000">

<center><table width=570 cellpadding=0><tr><td width=390 valign=left align=left nowrap> 

<br><br>

<img src="graphics/tiger1.jpg" align=top>


<p>

<center><img src="graphics/tigerhd2.gif" alt="header: Tiger"></center>

<br>

</td><td width=180 nowrap valign=top align=right>

<table width=170><td width=160 align=center bgcolor="#cccc99" nowrap>

<table width=125><td align=left bgcolor="#cccc99" nowrap>

<center><img src="graphics/logo1.gif" alt="WWF logo"></center>

<p><br>

<center><img src="graphics/subhd.gif" alt="header: Threatened Species"></center><br>

<img src="graphics/line130.gif" alt="line">

<BR>

<center><font size=1>C O N T E N T S</font></center>

<p>


<a href="page1.htm"><font size=2>Introduction</font></a>
<br>
 <a href="page2.htm"><font size=2>Distribution</font></a>
<br>
 <a href="page3.htm"><font size=2>Population</font></a>
<br>
 <a href="page4.htm"><font size=2>Threats</font></a>
<br>
 <a href="page5.htm"><font size=2>Conservation &<br> Research Activities<br></font></a>

 <a href="page6.htm"><font size=2>Legal Status</font></a>
<br>
 <a href="page7.htm"><font size=2>Captive Breeding</font></a>
<br>
 <a href="page8.htm"><font size=2>References</font></a><p>

<br>

</td></table></center></td></table></center>


</td></tr><tr><td colspan=2>


<p>

The Tiger has a distinctive reddish orange coat striped with black, and is the largest of the cats. Populations occur in a wide
        range of habitats from the evergreen and monsoon forests of Indo-Malaysia to the birch woodlands of Siberia and the
        mangrove swamps of the Sundarbans.13 In areas of prey abundance, such as Chitwan National Park in Nepal, territories
        range from 10 to 20 km2 for females and 30 to 70 km2 for males. In the Russian Far East where prey is scarce, territories
        vary in size from 200 to 400 km2 for females and 800 to 1,000 km2 for males.13 . . .

<p>

<img src="graphics/line2.gif" alt="line">

