<html>
<head>
<title>Saving The Siberian Tiger</title>
</head>
<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link+"#0000ff">
<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=10 width=510>
<td align=left>

<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=12 width=480>
<tr><td align=left>

<h2>Saving the siberian tiger</h2>

<p>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>
<br>

"Vehicles with well-armed poachers are common in the Amur region," reports Dr Ilse Storch of WWF's Russian Far East project office, "As they can get CHF7,500 (US$5,000) for a tiger pelt or CHF4,500 per kilo for tiger bones, they are taking tigers, and wild boars and bear."

<p>

The region is home to many species found nowhere else: Siberian tigers, Amur leopards and Himalayan black bears are all found here,<img align=right src="tiger.jpeg" alt="Picture of a Siberian tiger"> alongside reindeer, sable, wild boar, brown bear, lynx, and salmon. The forests contain Siberian pine nuts, wild ginseng, and numerous other edible and medicinal plants and mushrooms. But the wildlife is now declining rapidly.

<p>

The pace of economic deregulation and the lack of long-term resource management plans threaten the whole region. The remaining 200 to 300 Siberian tigers are not only threatened by poachers. Timber harvesting, mining, and other unplanned industrial development are destroying their habitat. Unless these animals are properly protected they may become extinct. 

<p>

WWF is providing emergency support, as well as equipping and training anti-poaching brigades and community game guards. "Our long-term aim," says Dr Storch, "is to conserve enough of the natural habitat for the tigers to thrive."

<p>

WWF has also conducted a number of workshops, canvassing opinion for the development of a regional conservation strategy. "If we are to succeed," concludes Dr Storch, "we must include plans for local development as well as conservation. Of course there will have to be areas completely set aside for conservation, and corridors between them to allow the tigers and their prey to move from one to another. But we must also establish areas where local people can exploit the forest's rich natural resources in sustainable ways."

<p>
<br>

<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>
<a href="page8-13.htm#strategy3">Back to the previous page</a>

</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>

</td>
</table>
</center>
<p>
<center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
<i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center></body></html>
