<html>
<head>
<title>More Than Fundraising</title>
</head>
<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link+"#0000ff">
<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=17 width=510>
<td align=left>

<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=17 width=500>
<tr><td align=left valign=top width=155>

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>

<img src="birdy.jpeg" alt="Picture of a parrot">

<br>
<font size=2>Orange - bellied parrot, Tasmania.</font>

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>


<tt>"Most conservation projects require a long-term commitment. In these times of international financial uncertainty, it is remarkable that WWF has been able to increase its investment in conservation 
year on year. This requires careful
planning, the prudent deployment of our financial and human resources and, 
wherever possible, the use of these 
to attract additional funding from
governments, corporations, and other NGOs."</tt>

<p>
<br>


<pre>   <tt>DR Jorgen Randers 
Deputy Director 
General WWF
International</tt></pre>

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>


<img src="shunter.jpeg" alt="Picture of a bulldozer">

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>




<img src="dolfins.jpeg" alt="Picture of dophins">


</td>
<td align=left>

<p>
<br>

<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>
<font size=5><b>MORE THAN FUNDRAISING</b></font>
<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>

"Many of WWF's fundraising activities achieve other goals as well", says Ken Phillips, WWF International Development Director, "such as improving efficiency, communicating conservation messages, or reducing resource use."
<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>
<font size=4><b>Improving efficiency</b></font>
<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>

WWF's ability to send conservation information around the world has recently been enhanced by two communications giants. Novell Inc. donated state-of-the-art computer networking systems while Computer Associates International has provided accounting software for WWF's offices in 52 countries. These gifts-in-kind will help WWF improve its operations and release more than CHF720,000 (US$500,000) for direct conservation.
<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>
<font size=4><b>Educating pet owners</b></font>
<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>

For the past five years Uncle Ben's, the Australian subsidiary of Mars, has joined WWF in reminding pet owners of the effect that their animals can have on wildlife. These messages are carried by the company's TV advertising, in-store promotion materials, and on petfood packaging. The company makes a donation for every label returned to WWF and the funds are used to protect endangered native Australian species. And many of those who return the labels become regular WWF supporters.
<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>
<font size=4><b>Reducing resource use</b></font>
<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>

In the Netherlands WWF is encouraging government offices and companies with more than 50 employees to reduce their normal paper use by 10 per cent through such means as photocopying on both sides of a sheet, using e-mail, or by increasing their use of recycled paper.

<p>

Participants donate one third of their resulting financial savings to WWF. In the first few months of the campaign, more than 100 organizations, including Polygram, 10 hospitals and 18 local administrations, have joined, and WWF plans to sign up another 150 before the scheme is a year old.

<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>
<font size=4><b>Picture caption</b></font>
<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>

At Paris' Orly and Roissy airports volunteers maintain 11 WWF collecting boxes into which travellers are encouraged to drop their unwanted small change. Special arrangements with a group of banks ensure that nature benefits from the best possible exchange rates.


<br>
<br>


</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>


<center>
<table cellpadding=10 width=500>
<td align=left>
<hr size=1 noshade>

