<DOCHDR>
http://www.panda.org:80/research/save_myjob/sum.htm 204.243.96.56 19970217024902 text/html 12527
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 17-Feb-97 02:44:50 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 09-May-96 21:22:43 GMT
Content-length: 12341
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Summary</title> 
</HEAD>
<body background="http://www.panda.org/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#FF3333" alink="00ff00" vlink="509920">
<center><font size=+3>Summary</font></center>
<p><br>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<P>
Two major problems that society faces today are the enhanced greenhouse
effect and unemployment. In general, policy directed towards the
reduction of greenhouse gases like carbon dioxide (CO2) has been
seen as a threat to employment. This idea, however, is highly
questionable. For this reason it is of great importance that studies
are performed to investigate the employment effects of climate
policy.
<P>
<B>Aim of the study</B>
<P>
This study investigates the potential employment effects of achieving
the 'Toronto target' for the Netherlands, that is: 20% cuts in
Dutch carbon-dioxide emissions from fossil-fuel burning by 2005
(based on the 1988 level of 180 Mton).
<P>
As the study aims to present an overall picture, potential employment
effects <I>outside the Netherlands</I> due to the Dutch measures
are also included in the analysis.
<P>
<B>Points of departure</B>
<P>
The employment effects are evaluated compared to a base scenario
with `frozen' technology. Thus, employment effects of energy conservation
that would take place anyway (autonomously or because of already
planned government policies) are included in the analysis. The
reason for this is that in this study we are interested in the
total number of jobs involved in climate policy and not only in
the extra number of jobs involved in <I>intensifying</I> climate
policy.
<P>
It is assumed that the necessary CO2 reduction is achieved solely
by measures to improve energy efficiency and conservation and
substituting sustainable energy for fossil fuels. Moreover, we
assume that this is done in the most cost-effective way.
<P>
In the base scenario real gross national product grows by 1.5%
a year between now and 2005. Because of this assumption of relatively
low economic growth it is possible to achieve the Toronto target
via measures to improve efficiency. With higher economic growth,
these measures would not be sufficient to achieve the target.
<P>
In that case other options would become necessary, such as the
shrinking (or even closing down) of energy-intensive sectors in
favour of energy-extensive sectors. Such structural shifts in
the economy do not imply a net employment loss: only a restructuring
of the economy. However, if it is necessary to force these structural
shifts too fast, these shifts could give rise to a temporary loss
of jobs.
<P>
Making assumptions concerning energy prices is notoriously tricky.
Partly because of a recent study by the Dutch Department of Economic
Affairs we assume them constant at the 1990 level. There are reasons
to believe that the volume of the calculated employment effects
becomes (somewhat) higher if the energy price turns out to be
higher, and vice versa.
<P>
<B>Measures to improve energy efficiency</B>
<P>
The various measures available for improving energy efficiency
to achieve the Toronto target are obtained from the ICARUS data
base for the Netherlands. Given the assumed energy levels most
of the measures appear profitable. In Figure 1 the cost effectiveness
is given of the various measures to improve energy efficiency:
the costs to avoid an additional ton of CO2 rises with the amount
of CO2 already avoided. Measures to avoid CO2 on top of about
70 Mton per year cost money. In the figure eight dots are drawn
to show as an example the cost effectivity of a few measures out
of the more than 900 included in the ICARUS data base. It is noted
that there are reasons to believe that not all costs are accounted
for in the ICARUS data base. To the extent that this is true the
measures seem to be more profitable than they really are. We will
discuss this issue at the end of the summary.
<P>
All the measures to improve energy efficiency together involve
an avarage cost of approximately 5.5 billion guilders a year.
Because of these measures fuel bills would be approximately 17
billion guilders lower. Thus, in effect 11.5 billion guilders
would be saved. However, the government would receive 2.5 billion
guilders less in income because of foregone gas revenues. Assuming
that these foregone revenues were compensated by higher taxes,
the private sector saves 9 billion guilders.
<P>
<B>Economic methodology</B>
<P>
To get a clear insight into the potential employments effects
on a sectoral level an input-output analysis has been used. Thus,
we investigate how the output of the various sectors of the economy
is changed by measures to improve energy efficiency. In first
order, three major changes occur:
<P><ol>
<li> Increase in output in the sectors that provide the goods related
to energy conservation and sustainable energy.
<P>
<li> Decrease in output in the energy sectors because of the energy
saved.
<P>
<li> The actors that introduce the measures incur extra costs for
implementation and extra benefits through lower energy bills.
As most of the measures considered will appear profitable, in
effect money is saved. It is assumed that this money is respent
over the economy, in such a way that all sectors experience an
equal increase in output (in terms of percentage).
</ol>
<P>
<P>
<b>Table 1 Potential employment effects of achieving the Toronto
target.</b><HR>

<PRE WIDTH=132>
         Cause of employment          direct:  indirect:     total: 
         effects:                                                   

         Investments in                17 000     21 000     38 000 
         efficiency                   (2 000)   (11 000)   (14 000) 
         improving measures                                         

         Lower turnover of energy     -17 000    -27 000    -44 000 
         sector:                     (-2 000)  (-11 000)  (-13 000) 

         Respending saved money:       40 000     38 000     77 000 
                                      (8 000)   (13 000)   (22 000) 

         TOTAL                         39 000     32 000     71 000 
                                      (9 000)   (14 000)   (23 000) 


</PRE>
<HR>
<P>
The figures between brackets denote the fraction of the employment
that is generated abroad.
<P>
Subsequently, the employment effects of these three categories
of output changes are calculated. Direct and indirect effects
can be distinguished. The direct effects involve the employment
effects in the sectors that directly experience a change in output
(the sectors are mentioned above). The indirect effects involve
the employment effects in the sectors that supply inputs for these
sectors.
<P>
<B>Potential employment effects</B>
<P>
In Table 1 the potential employment effects in jobs per year in
2005 are shown as a result of achieving the Toronto target for
the Netherlands. The employment reached in 2005 is permanent,
since investments have to be repeated and respending of money
saved on energy bills is permanent.
<P>
The following points are noteworthy:
<P>
<ul>
<li> The projected volume of the labour force for the Netherlands
in 2005 is about 7 million. Thus, the total potential net employment
effect comes down to approximately 1% of the labour force.
<P>
<li> The employment effects due to the respending of saved money
dominate. The reason is of course that the measures involved appear
to be (very) profitable. The costs of the necessary investments
are approximately a factor 2 lower than the money saved by these
measures.
<P>
<li> The importance of calculating the indirect effects become clear.
They involve approximately half of the total employment effects.
<P>
<li> The job creation in the sectors supplying goods for measures
to improve energy efficiency is in the same order as the loss
of jobs in the energy sector. This, despite the fact that the
decrease in output of the energy sector is about a factor three
larger than the increase of the former sectors. The reason for
this, is of course that the energy sector is much more labour
extensive than the other sectors.
<P>
<li> About 20% of the employment generated by the Dutch measures
to achieve the Toronto target for the Netherlands, is actually
generated outside the Netherlands. Vice versa, it is plausible
that to the extent that other countries also try to achieve the
Toronto target, these foreign measures would create extra jobs
in the Netherlands (for example, substitution from coal to gas
in Germany could be profitable for the Netherlands because of
the involved higher export possibilities of gas). However, such
possible extra employment effects are not calculated.
<P>
<li> As a direct result of energy conservation typically more industrial
engineers, building constructors, mechanics, factory workers and
electricians will be employed. Thus, the bulk of the newly created
jobs do not involve revolutionary new developments.
</ul>
<P>
<B>Government policies</B>
<P>
As mentioned above, most of the measures to improve energy efficiency
involved appear to be profitable. In the literature a wide variety
of `hidden' costs are suggested, among which: transaction costs,
usage of higher discount rates, informational costs, welfare costs
because of `annoyance'. Therefore, it is still necessary that
government devices policies to get them implemented.
<P>
Suggested government policies to overcome these hidden costs are:
<P>
<ul>
<li> direct regulation;
<P>
<li> subsidies on energy-conservation measures;
<P>
<li> creation of energy services. The electricity and gas companies
can help agents with energy analysis (scanning the conservation
potential), advising, implementation (project management), taking
over the risks involved with implementation and lending money
(see, e.g., Moor <I>et al</I>., 1995).;
<P>
<li>tax shift from labour to energy. It is plausible that the obstacles
mentioned are only of relative importance. If energy conservation
becomes profitable enough, the obstacles mentioned are overcome.
</ul>
<P>
Presently, it remains an open question to what extent the above
policy options (or others) are able to bring about all energy
improving measures mentioned in this study. More research is needed,
although it seems self-evident that present government policy
is not sufficient to overcome the obstacles.
<P>
However, extra government policies will generally have extra side
effects on employment. Below we discuss two possibilities.
<P>
<ul>
<li> Extra government policies will in general cost extra money.
One can think of the extra costs involved with extra government
workers to implement the policy, extra advisers, extra people
to facilitate implementation, and so on. These extra `policy'
costs would eventually decrease the net profits for the private
agents. Thus, less money is saved in effect and the employment
effect because of the net savings would be smaller. However, this
effect is compensated by more jobs for people involved in the
implementation policy. So, it is plausible that the net employment
effect would be the same. Only the sort of jobs would be different:
more jobs in `implementation policy', less jobs spread out over
the whole economy.
<P>
<li> If the government chooses to achieve (part of) the CO2 reduction
via a tax shift from labour towards energy/CO2, the shift in the
relative prices of energy and labour could have independent positive
employment effects. From the literature we conclude that one should
not be too optimistic about the volume of this positive effect.
<P>
A final caveat concerning the study seems in order. As explained
above there are all sorts of `hidden' financial and non-financial
costs involved in implementing measures to improve energy efficiency.
The existence of these costs do not in particular endanger the
volume of the employment effects. However, there is a possibility
that these costs appear so high that from an economic point of
view other ways to achieve the Toronto target are more preferable.
With the present state of knowledge this is an open question.
<P>
</ul>
<br>
<align=right><a href="contents.htm">Back ||........></a>
<br><p>


<align=right><a href="contents.htm"><center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p><i><h6>Copyright 1996, The World Wide Fund For Nature</i></h6></center>
