<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN">
<html>
<head>
<title>If The Earth Is A Bank Account</title>
</head>
<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link+"#0000ff">
<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=10 width=510>
<td align=left>

<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=17 width=510>
<tr><td align=left valign=top>

<hr size=1 noshade>
<b><font size=4><tt>If the earth is a bank account</tt> ....</font></b>
<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>

its natural resources are the capital and the output of goods and services produced (Gross Domestic Product, or GDP) the interest. As the capital decreases, through the overexploitation or pollution of irreplaceable natural resources, so the interest must eventually diminish. WWF is challenging the international community, whose accounting systems ignore this erosion of capital, to factor it into a new and true measurement of cost, wealth and development.	
<p>	
<br>			

<hr size=1 noshade>
<b><font size=4><tt>Local effects</tt></font></b>
<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>

Loggers, for instance, often do not have to calculate the cost of the trees they fell, let alone the effect that their activities have on local communities. When rubber plantation managers in Nigeria wanted to extend their operation into the Okomu Forest Reserve, the first calculations showed that the expansion would generate a turnover of CHF2.28 million (US$1.58 million) against a direct investment of just CHF648,000. But when consideration was given to the potential loss of fuelwood and building materials, food and clothing from wildlife, and tourism and traditional medicine, the overall costs rose to CHF2.36 million, exceeding turnover by more than CHF86,500.
<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>
<b><font size=4><tt>National reality</tt></font></b>
<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>

Japan's economic success has apparently made it one of the richest countries in the world per capita. But when researchers from the University of Tsukuba corrected the Gross National Product (GNP, a variation of GDP) over a 30-year period by taking into account social and environmental costs, the picture changed dramatically. The new figures showed sustained growth to 1980, but then slumped by more than 90 per cent over the next five years. While the Japanese may have a lot of cash, the research confirmed, their quality of life was falling.
<p>

In the United Kingdom, national income rose by 230 per cent between 1950 and 1990. But in the same period the cost of water, air, and noise pollution was reckoned to be CHF51 billion. In Brazil, the inclusion of timber depletion costs reduces the value of agricultural output by 20 per cent; in Indonesia, GDP goes down by 17 per cent when net changes in petroleum, forestry, and soil resources are taken into account; while if the United States' GDP is adjusted for the costs associated with resource depletion, pollution, and accidents, the net income per person drops by 75 per cent.
<p>

It is clearly neither sustainable nor economically prudent to continue ignoring these real environmental costs. Natural resources need to be given a value in the economic indicators used for planning. WWF is urging governments and international organizations to switch to "true GDP" accounting by 31 December 1999.

<p>
<br>
<hr size=1 noshade>

<a href="page2.htm#account"><tt><b>Back to the previous page</b></tt></a>


</td>
<td align=left valign=top  width=135>

<p>
<br>

<img src="Lumber.jpeg" alt="Picture of exploited trees">

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>

<pre>   <img src="cars.jpeg" alt="Picture of a traffic jam"></pre>

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>

<img src="riberboat.jpeg" alt="Picture of a riverboat">

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>

<pre>   <img src="sewage.jpeg" alt="Picture of a sewage dump"></pre>

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>


WWF believes that the cost of resource degradation should be included in accounting systems (from top): logging in Brazil; air pollution in Bangkokand Mexico City; water pollution in Bombay. 

</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

</td>
</table>
