<title>
Pollution Prevention: Better Safe Than Sorry!
</title>

<body background="graphics/bk.gif" link="#ffffff" vlink="#ffffff" alink="#bb0000">

<table width=570 border=0 cellpadding=5>
<tr><td colspan=3>

<img src="graphics/pollutionmainhd.gif" alt="Pollution Prevention">&nbsp;&nbsp;<img src="graphics/smog1.jpg">

</tr></td>
<tr><td width=125 valign=top>
<table width=125 border=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td align=center>
<p>
 
<p>
<br>
<font color="#ffffff">
<a href="impa1.htm"><b>The Impacts of Pollution on the Environment</b></a><p>
<A HREF="impa2.htm"><B>Fighting pollution worldwide</B></A><P>
<A HREF="impa3.htm"><B>Can any chemical be considered "safe?"</B></A><P>
<A HREF="impa4.htm"><B>POPs</B></A><P>

___<BR><BR>
<A HREF="index.htm"><B>Table of Contents</B></A>
</font>
</tr></td>
</table>
</td>


<td width=10>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</td>

<td width=450 align=left valign=top>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=6><B>WWF targets endocrine disruptors</B></FONT>
<P>
At the international level, WWF is working to raise awareness
about endocrine disruptors in various intergovernmental fora.
It is lobbying for toxics use reduction and better information,
as well as for bans and phase-outs of the most persistent toxic
chemicals. Scientific conferences are planned with the focus on
endocrine disruptors, such as the ongoing series of &quot;Wingspread&quot;
conferences, initiated in 1991 by WWF-US expert Dr Theo Colborn,
when many prominent scientists first called attention to the danger.

<P>
For the layperson, fact-sheets and other educational material
is available. WWF-Canada has produced a new video, Hormone Copy-cats,
with Dr Colborn as its lead presenter. This explains the phenomenon
of endocrine disruptors and the dangers they pose, and explores
the options for addressing the issue. Ideal for lectures and discussion
groups, the video is available free on a returnable basis from
WWF-Canada.
<P>
Spearheading the popular-awareness campaign is a new book on endocrine
disruption, aimed at the general reader, by Colborn, Dianne Dumanoski,
and John Peterson Myers. Already Our Stolen Future (Dutton Signet,
1996) is having an impact similar to Rachel Carson's Silent Spring.
<BR>
<BR>


<br>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar_small.map" alt="toolbar"><img src="/graphics/toolbar_small.gif" alt="toolbar" border=0 ismap></a>

</td></tr>
