<head>
<title>Victory In South America</title>
</head>
<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ff">
<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=10 width=510>
<td align=left>

<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=12 width=480>
<tr><td align=left>

<h2>Victory in South America</h2>

<p>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>
<br>

WWF won a significant tactical victory in its efforts to save the world's largest wetland, Brazil's Pantanal. The area, considered to have one of the greatest concentrations of bird life in the world, was threatened by the Hidrovia Project, a US$1 billion scheme to enlarge the waterway link between Brazil, Bolivia, Paraguay, Uruguay, and Argentina.

<p>

WWF launched a video news release on the damage the scheme might cause, simultaneously holding a workshop in Asuncion, Paraguay, with other NGOs, the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), and the Intergovernmental Commission on the Hidrovia (CIH). To "dissipate the heat" after heavy and unfavourable press coverage, the CIH then called an emergency meeting in Buenos Aires, Argentina, of high - level government officials, UNDP, and a number of national and international NGOs, led by WWF.

<p>

"WWF did not negotiate, and there was no quid pro quo," emphasizes Gonzalo Castro, WWF's Freshwater Ecosystems Coordinator for Latin America. "We raised issues which the CIH accepted."

<p>

<img align=right src="lilly.jpeg" alt="Picture of a giant lilly">

Following the meeting, the CIH announced that :

<p>
<br>

<ul>

<li>the Pantanal will have special status and be protected

<p>

<li>no engineering work should proceed before an environmental impact assessment (EIA) of the project is completed

<p>

<li>the EIA should be technically sound, transparent, and open to public participation

<p>

<li>the public should be included in the decision-making process.

</ul>
<p>
<br>
	
"WWF is particularly pleased with the understanding of the crucial importance of the Pantanal, and congratulates the CIH on taking these important steps to avoid compromising this critical ecosystem," says Castro. "This success shows how powerful WWF can be when field research, policy development, and communication come together. However, WWF now faces the challenge of monitoring the results of the EIA very closely indeed."

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>

