<head>
<title>Results In Tanzania</title>
</head>
<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ff">
<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=10 width=510>
<td align=left>

<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=12 width=480>
<tr><td align=left colspan=2>

<h2>Results in Tanzania</h2>

<p>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>
<br>

"We have worked long and hard for this," said Meg Gawler, WWF's Programme Officer for Marine Conservation Projects, when the Tanzanian parliament passed legislation to create the Mafia Island Marine Park. "Along with the islanders and the Ministry of Fisheries, WWF has lobbied for three years to establish Tanzania's first marine park."

</td></tr>
<tr><td align=left>

<p>

Mafia is one of the most biologically diverse areas in East Africa, with spectacular coral reefs, seagrass beds, intertidal flats, and adjacent islands, all of which act as important breeding and nursery grounds for fish and other marine species. Fishing is a major source of food for the islanders, and they had been facing serious problems from mainland fishermen who ransacked fish stocks with dynamite - indiscriminately destroying fish and the coral reefs.

</td>
<td align=left>

<img src="raft.jpeg" alt="Picture of a fishing boat">

<br>

<font size=2>Traditional fishing vessel, Tanzania.</font>

</td></tr>
<tr><td align=left colspan=2>

<p>

WWF, working with government officials and marine experts, developed a plan for the sustainable management of the island's resources, and launched a campaign to gain park status for the island, its surrounding waters, and six smaller islands.

<p>

WWF has supported reef patrols and marine guards since 1993 and will now increase the park's enforcement capability. Islanders will continue to live in the park, which includes their traditional fishing grounds, but the multizonal management system will be carefully 
monitored and evaluated together with the park's inhabitants and users.

<p>

"This is a great step forward," concludes Gawler, "and will, hopefully, prove to be a major victory in our attempts to eradicate dynamite fishing in Tanzania."

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>


<a href="page18-20.htm#two">Back to the previous page</a>


</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

</td>
</table>
</center>
