<DOCNO>WT24-B34-213</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA013-000133-B026-102</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.panda.org:80/research/save_myjob/point.htm 204.243.96.56 19970217024925 text/html 9921
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 17-Feb-97 02:45:14 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 09-May-96 21:32:38 GMT
Content-length: 9736
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Points of departure</title> 
</HEAD>
<body background="http://www.panda.org/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#FF3333" alink="00ff00" vlink="509920">
<center><font size=+3>Points of departure</font></center>
<p><br>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<P>
<b>2 Points of departure<!--2 Points of departure--></b>
<P>
The results of a study of employment effects are highly dependent
on the points of departure from which the calculations are made.
To calculate the employment effects of achieving the Toronto target
in particular a reference scenario (if no measures are taken)
and the nature of the measures to reduce CO<sub>2</sub> emissions have to
be chosen. These points of departure will be discussed in this
chapter.
<P>
<B>2.1 The reference scenario<!--2.1 The reference scenario--></B>
<P>
In this study we choose the following reference (or base) scenario
for the period 1994 - 2005<br> (see also Table 2.1).
<P>
<ol>
<li> In the base scenario we assume an economic growth of 1.5 % per
year. This economic growth figure is deduced from the scenario
named 'Global Shift' of the Dutch Central Planning Bureau (CPB,
1993a). Note that we assume in this way a relatively low economic
growth. In the scenario `European Renaissance', for example, the
economic growth figure would have been higher: 2.8 % a year.
<P>
<li> In the base scenario we assume that no improvement of energy
efficiency takes place. That is, we assume a `frozen technology'.
<P>
 Therefore, employment effects of the following measures are included
in our analysis:
<P>
<ul>
<li> energy conservation that would take place anyway (so called
autonomous energy conservation);
<P>
<li>energy conservation that is already planned by the government
for the next years.</ul>
<P>
 The reason for including these employment effects is that in
this study we are interested in the total number of jobs involved
in climate policy and not only in the extra number of jobs involved
in <I>intensifying</I> climate policy.
<P>
<li> In the base scenario it is assumed that some sectors grow slower
than others. For example, in the Global Shift scenario energy-intensive
industries grow more slowly than the service sectors. Because
of this, the growth figure of CO<sub>2</sub> emissions will be lower than
1.5 %, the assumed figure for economic growth. In fact, CO<sub>2</sub> emissions
grow by 0.2 % less. This effect is referred to as CO<sub>2</sub> reductions
because of `structural shift'.</ol>
<P>
In the base scenario, which is used from hereon, CO<sub>2</sub> emissions
increase by 1.3 % a year. This seems a reasonable assumption given
the fact that between 1988 and 1993 (the most recent years for
which data is available) this was also the average growth in these
emissions (see also Table 2.1).
<P>
<b>Table 2.1</b><i> Development in CO<sub>2</sub> emissions</i><HR>

<PRE WIDTH=132>
                      1988-1993      1994-2005      1994-2005      
                                     base scenario  Toronto        
                                                    scenario       

growth rate             1.3 %          1.3 %         -2.6 % 
CO<sub>2</sub> emission                                                

growth rate             2.6 %          1.5 %          1.5 % 
GDP                                                         

efficiency                - <sup>a</sup>            0 %         -3.9 % 
improvement                                                 

structural                - <sup>a</sup>         -0.2 %         -0.2 % 
shift                                                       


</PRE>
<HR>


<sup>a</sup> Although we are unable to give the specific numbers for the
efficiency improvement and the structural shift for the period
1988-1993, we know the sum of the two is -1.3 %
<P><br>
<B>2.2 Measures to achieve the Toronto target<!--2.2 Measures to achieve the Toronto target--></B>
<P>
To calculate the employment effects of achieving the Toronto target,
we have to decide <I>how</I> the emission reduction is to be achieved.
There is a number of options available: energy conservation, sustainable
energy, carbon management, CO<sub>2</sub> removal, and cutting in energy-consuming
activities (Okken <I>et al</I>., 1991).
<P>
In this study we assume that the necessary CO<sub>2</sub> reduction is achieved
solely by measures to improve energy efficiency and conservation,
and substituting sustainable energy for fossil fuels. Moreover,
we assume that this is done in the most cost-effective way.
<P>
This decision has been made because of the following reasons.
<P>
<ol>
<li> Most of the selected measures to improve energy efficiency appear
profitable (that is, the investments involved are more than compensated
by the reduced energy bills). In chapter 7 we discuss possible
obstacles for implementation.
<P>
<li> The option of CO<sub>2</sub> removal, for example by storage in depleted
natural gas fields, is uncertain before the year 2005.
<P>
<li> Other options are politically troublesome, such as shrinking
certain energy-intensive sectors of the economy and the use of
nuclear energy. Nuclear energy has also been omitted as an option
because of the fact that it is hardly possible to increase the
amount of nuclear energy before the year 2005. Finally, it is
doubtful whether CO<sub>2</sub> emissions can be avoided more cost effective
by nuclear energy than by energy conservation (Boels <I>et al</I>.,
1994).</ol>
<P>
So, in this study the Toronto target is achieved solely by efficiency
improvement and not by additional structural shifts in the importance
of sectors (which would have been the case if the CO<sub>2</sub> reduction
is achieved by shrinking some energy intensive sectors). From
Table 2.1 it appears that an improvement in energy efficiency
has to be achieved between 1994 and 2005 of almost 4% a year.
<P>
Of course, there is a limit to the amount of reductions that can
be made by efficiency improvement alone. However, it will appear
that within the base scenario chosen it is possible to achieve
the Toronto target in this way. If the economic-growth figure
in the base scenario would have been somewhat higher, then this
would no longer be possible. Then other measures would become
necessary as well: slowing down some sectors of the economy or
even slowing down the economy as a whole.
<P>
As will become clear in chapter 4, in the chosen reference scenario
it is <I>technically</I> possible to achieve the 20% CO<sub>2</sub> reduction
by the year 2005 solely with measures which improve energy efficiency.
However, the question can be posed whether it is reasonable from
an <I>economic</I> point of view to implement these measures within
the next ten years. More precisely, won't this relatively fast
implementation lead to destruction of capital? In order to check
to which extent this could be the case, we make the following
crude reasoning.
<P><ol><ul>
<li> The bulk of the measures involved appear to have a technical
life time in between 10 and 20 years, thus 15 years on average.
Assuming that the age cohorts of the present capital stock are
evenly distributed with respect to age, this means that about
one third of the present capital stock could be still present
in 2005 from a technical point of view.
<P>
<li> Generally speaking, the economic life time is shorter than the
technical life time of capital. Thus, it is plausible that because
of this more than two third of the present relevant capital stock
will be replaced in 2005.
<P>
<li> Part of the measures involve so-called add-on technology, thus
technology that can be added to existing capital. Of course, the
implementation of such technologies do not cause destruction of
capital.</ul></ol>
<P>
Summarizing we conclude that it is plausible that the proposed
measures will not lead to a high degree of capital destruction.
<P>
<B>2.3 Other points of departure<!--2.3 Other points of departure--></B>
<P>
In this study no special attention is paid to government policies
needed to bring about the efficiency improvements. So in a way
only the employment <I>potential</I> of these measures is calculated.
Policies (such as a tax shift from labour to energy) can involve
specific extra (positive or negative) employment effects. In chapter
7 we shall discuss which governmental policies would be needed
to reach the Toronto target and the possible impacts of these
policies.
<P>
In the base scenario constant energy prices (at the 1990 level)
are assumed. This assumption of non-increasing energy prices seems
the most plausible given the recent study by the Dutch Department
of Economical Affairs (Berg et al., 1994), in which it is stated
that because of technological improvements energy prices will
not go up for the next 10 years.
<P>
Furthermore, it is assumed that energy prices will remain the
same with respect to the base scenario despite the assumed energy
saving. If it is assumed that only the Netherlands will make work
of achieving the Toronto target, it is self-evidident that this
will not influence the level of the energy price. However, if
it is assumed that the extra energy saving will be done world
wide, it is probable that the energy price will go down because
of the decreased demand for energy. Such a decrease in energy
prices compared to the base scenario would cost employment in
the energy producing sectors. However, it would enable households
to spend more money on other things thereby creating employment.
<br><p>
<align=right><a href="contents.htm">Back ||........></a><p>

