<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Introduction</title> 
</HEAD>
<body background="http://www.panda.org/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#FF3333" alink="00ff00" vlink="509920">
<center><font size=+3>Introduction</font></center>
<p><br>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<B>1.1 Reason for the study<!--1.1 Reason for the study--></B>
<P>
The enhanced greenhouse effect is one of the major global environmental
problems today: the large-scale burning of fossil fuels is increasing
the concentration of carbon dioxide (CO2) in the earth's atmosphere,
which in turn results in more of the sun's radiated energy being
trapped. The consequences of the enhanced greenhouse effect can
be far reaching for the earth's climate and for life on earth.
<P>
To limit the changes in the earth's climate the UNEP conference,
held in 1988 in Toronto [UNEP, 1988], advised the developed countries
to reduce their CO2 emissions by 20% in 2005 in respect to 1988.
At present, there are reasons to assume that the government policy,
which the various countries delineated so far, is insufficient
to reach the Toronto target.
<P>
The attention for the greenhouse effect has to compete with one
of the most pressing <I>social</I> problems society faces today:
unemployment. In general, policy directed towards reduction of
greenhouse gases has been seen as a threat to employment. Since,
in addition, the problem of unemployment is manifesting itself
more directly, governments have been reluctant to implement far-reaching
measures to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases. The idea that
climate policy is a threat to employment, however, is highly questionable
(see e.g. Jacobs, 1994, De Wit, 1994). For this reason it is of
great importance that studies investigate the employment effects
of climate policy.
<P>
<B>1.2 Goal of the study<!--1.2 Goal of the study--></B>
<P>
In this study we try to gain an insight into the net employment
effects of climate policy. More specifically, we investigate the
employment effects of achieving the Toronto target for the Netherlands,
that is: 20% cuts in Dutch carbon dioxide emissions from fossil
fuel burning by 2005 (based on 1988 levels).
<P>
The study considers the contribution of activities in various
industrial, manufacturing, service and other sectors to overall
CO2 reductions. For each activity the means, costs and net employment
effects of achieving the CO2 reductions are identified.
<P>
The employment effects of the measures taken to achieve the Toronto
target in the Netherlands alone, are calculated. However, part
of these employment effects would take place <I>outside</I> the
Netherlands because of increased imports into the Netherlands.
These employment effects outside the Netherlands are also included
in our study.
<P>
The methodology which is used in this report is intended to be
applicable in other case studies for other countries.
<P>
<B>1.3 How to read the report<!--1.3 How to read the report--></B>
<P>
To answer the questions raised above, we first specify the points
of departure for our calculation in chapter 2. In chapter 3 we
shall discuss the methodology. In chapter 4 the measures are determined
which are necessary for achieving the Toronto target. Also the
investments in the various parts of the Dutch economy are given.
By means of these results, in chapter 5 the employment effects
are calculated. A comparison is made in chapter 6 with other literature.
Finally, in chapter 7 the results are evaluated.
<P>
<br>

<align=right><a href="contents.htm">Back ||........></a><p>
<p><br>
<center>
<a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 
ISMAP></a><p>
