<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Potential employment effects</title> 
</HEAD>
<body background="http://www.panda.org/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#FF3333" alink="00ff00" vlink="509920">
<center><font size=+3>Potential employment effects</font></center>
<p><br>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<P>
For the calculation of the potential employment effects in the
various sectors of the economy (calculated for 2005) we used the
input-output table from the Statistics Netherlands (CBS, 1994)
for the Dutch economy in the year 1991. To obtain results for
the year 2005, we made the following correction. Using the total
employment and economic growth in the year 2005 from the 'global
shift' scenario of the Dutch Central Planning Bureau (CPB, 1993a)
(see section 2.1), we deduced an average decrease in labour intensity
of 1.2.
<P>
Since the Netherlands has an open economy, the increase and decrease
of returns of the various sectors does not only take place in
the Netherlands, but also abroad. Therefore, we included in our
analysis the competitive imports of goods and services from abroad.
In our approach we assumed that the competitive imports are produced
with the same input and labour intensity as in the Netherlands.
Although this assumption is not always valid, it is sufficient
to obtain a rough estimation of the employment generated abroad
(noted that it is small compared to the employment generated in
the Netherlands).
<P>
As an example, in Table 5.1 we give the number of jobs (directly
and indirectly) generated by an investment of 1 million guilders
in a number of sectors of the Dutch economy.
<P>
<b>Table 5.1</b><i> Employment in various sectors of the economy as a result
of an increased output of 1 million guilders (in the year 2005,
in the Netherlands and abroad)</i><HR>

<PRE WIDTH=132>
change in output in:          direct   indirect       total 

mechanical engineering           3.8        4.6         8.4 

electrical engineering           3.8        3.8         7.6 

transport industry<sup>a </sup>             2.7        5.5         8.3 

construction and                 4.2        5.3         9.5 
installation                                                

business services                6.2        2.4         8.6 

petroleum industry               0.4        1.5         1.8 

electricity (public              1.9        2.1         4.0 
utility)                                                    

gas (public utility)             0.8        1.1         1.9 

average output change<sup>b </sup>          3.8        3.6         7.4 


</PRE>
<HR>

<P>
<sup>a </sup> This is the average over the sectors car industry and transport
equipment.
<P>
<sup>b</sup> This is the average employment due to a proportionally-distributed
increase in consumption of<br> 1 million guilders by the Dutch households.
<P>
In Table 5.2 the employment effects in jobs per year in 2005 are
shown as a result of achieving the Toronto target for the Netherlands.
<P>
<b>Table 5.2</b><i> Potential employment effects of achieving the Toronto
target.</i><HR>

<PRE WIDTH=132>
Cause of employment          direct:  indirect:     total: 
effects:                                                   

Investments in measures       17 000     21 000     38 000 
to improve energy            (2 000)   (11 000)   (14 000) 
efficiency                                                 

Lower turnover of energy     -17 000    -27 000    -44 000 
sector                      (-2 000)  (-11 000)  (-13 000) 

Respending saved money        40 000     38 000     77 000 
                             (8 000)   (13 000)   (22 000) 

TOTAL                         39 000     32 000     71 000 
                             (9 000)   (14 000)   (23 000) 


</PRE>
<HR>

<P>
The figures between brackets denote the fraction of the employment
that is generated abroad.
<P>
The following points are noteworthy:
<P><ol><ul>
<li> The projected volume of the labour force for the Netherlands
in 2005 is about 7 million. Thus, the total potential net employment
effect would be approximately 1% of the labour force.
<P>
<li> The employments effects due to the respending of saved money
are predominant. The reason is of course that the measures involved
appear to be (very) profitable. The costs of the necessary investments
are approximately a factor 2 lower than the money saved by these
measures.
<P>
<li> The importance of calculating the indirect effects become clear.
They involve approximately half of the total employment effects.
<P>
<li> The job creation in the sectors supplying goods for measures
to improve energy efficiency is of the same order as the loss
of jobs in the energy sector. This, despite the fact that the
decrease in output of the energy sector is about a factor three
larger than the increase of the former sectors. The reason for
this, is of course that the energy sector is much more labour
extensive than the other sectors.
<P>
<li> About 20% of the employment generated by the Dutch measures
to achieve the Toronto target for the Netherlands, is actually
generated outside the Netherlands. Vice versa, it is plausible
that to the extent that other countries also try to achieve the
Toronto target, these foreign measures would create extra jobs
in the Netherlands (for example, substitution from coal to gas
in Germany could be profitable for the Netherlands because of
the involved higher export possibilities of gas). However, such
possible extra employment effects are not calculated.
</ul></ol>
<P>
To gain more insight into which sectors employment effects take
place we present in Table 5.3 the direct employment effects of
the investments and the lower turnover of the energy sector.
<P>
<b>Table 5.3</b><i> Potential employment gains and losses as a direct result
of energy conservation</i><HR>

<PRE WIDTH=132>
Direct employment in                 
jobs per year in:                    

mechanical engineering         5 700 

electrical engineering         1 300 

transport industry             2 400 

construction and               5 800 
installation                         

business services              1 300 

petroleum industry            -2 100 

electricity (public           -8 900 
utility)                             

gas (public utility)          -4 200 

mining                        -1 700 


</PRE>
<HR>

<P>

<P>
As a direct result of energy conservation typically more industrial
engineers, building constructors, mechanics, factory workers and
electricians will be employed. In the Appendix a detailed table
is shown which gives the employment of all sectors of the economy
generated in the Netherlands and abroad as a function of the various
types of investment.
<P>
It should be noted that the level of employment which has been
calculated, is the potential employment in the year 2005. The
employment which is the result of respending of money saved on
energy bills would only reach the full potential when all measures
are applied. However, the employment which is reached in 2005
is permanent: measures to improve energy efficiency have to be
reimplemented after a while and energy saved on energy bills is
respended as long as energy is saved.
<P>
<br>
