<head>
<title>Involving Corporations In Conservation</title>
</head>
<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ff">
<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=10 width=510>
<td align=left>

<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=12 width=480>
<tr><td align=left>


<h2>Involving corporations in conservation</h2>

<p>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>
<br>

WWF-UK has pioneered a partnership with 54 companies, who together account for more than 10 per cent of all wood and wood products sold in Britain -- worth more than US$1.6 billion a year. The companies, which include the country's leading supermarkets an
d home improvement chains, are all committed to phasing out, to an agreed timetable, the sale of wood and wood products that do not come from independently certified, well-managed forests. 

<p>

<img align=right src="trees.jpeg" alt="Picture of a Swiss forest">

The companies have all agreed to buy a proportion of their supplies from FSC-approved forests. "The agreement covers not just wood, furniture, and products like 
charcoal," says Alan Knight of B&Q, the leading home improvement chain, "it also encompasses things like brushes with wooden handles, paper, and packaging, as well as the materials we buy for our internal use."

<p>

The group is spreading the FSC's reach by launching its own projects to ensure that forests from which its companies regularly obtain supplies are certified. Members have projects under way in Australia, Belgium, Croatia, Germany, Ghana, Hungary, Poland, 
Portugal, Spain, and the United States.

<p>

"The standards are exacting," says Knight "but they have helped increase general environmental awareness throughout the company and its suppliers."

<br>
<pre>                                                    <font size=2>Temperate forest, Switzerland.</font></pre> 
<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<a href="page15-17.htm#one">Back to the previous page</a>


</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

</td>
</table>
</center>
