<DOCNO>WT24-B34-246</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA013-000133-B026-162</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.panda.org:80/research/save_myjob/measure.htm 204.243.96.56 19970217024943 text/html 9177
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 17-Feb-97 02:45:30 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 09-May-96 21:35:31 GMT
Content-length: 8992
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Measures involved</title> 
</HEAD>
<body background="http://www.panda.org/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#FF3333" alink="00ff00" vlink="509920">
<center><font size=+3>Measures involved</font></center>
<p><br>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<P>
In this chapter we discuss the specific set of measures which
is necessary for achieving the Toronto target and the changes
in cash flows which are the result of those measures.
<P>
<B>4.1 The Toronto target<!--4.1 The Toronto target--></B>
<P>
In 1988, the base year for the Toronto target (UNEP, 1988), 180
Mt CO<sub>2</sub> was emitted in the Netherlands (Okken <I>et al</I>., 1991).
To achieve the Toronto target, 20% less should be emitted in the
year 2005, which implies a total emission of 144 Mt CO<sub>2</sub>.
<P>
Between 1988 and 1993 CO<sub>2</sub> emissions grew at about 1.3% per year.
In our base scenario this emission growth continues until the
year 2005. Thus, the emission of CO<sub>2</sub> in 2005 would be about 224
Mt. See also Table 4.1.
<P>
Combining these figures, we see that in order to achieve the Toronto
target 80 Mt less CO<sub>2</sub> should be emitted in the year 2005 compared
to the base scenario with `frozen technology'.
<P>
<b>Table 4.1 </b><i>CO<sub>2</sub> emissions (Mt)</i><HR>

<PRE WIDTH=132>
1988                           180                       

1993                         &#177; 192                        

2005, base scenario          &#177; 224<sup>a </sup>                      

2005, Toronto scenario         144<sup>b       </sup>               


</PRE>
<HR>

<P>
<sup>a</sup> + 1.3 % a year starting from 1994
<P>
<sup>b</sup> - 20% compared to the emission in 1988
<P>
<B>4.2 Icarus data base<!--4.2 Icarus data base--></B>
<P>
To gain an insight into the options for energy efficiency and
sustainable energy we have used the ICARUS data base of energy-conservation
techniques, containing both energy-efficiency potentials and cost
data for the various economic sectors of the Dutch economy (De
Beer <I>et al</I>., 1994). In this data base only energy-efficiency
improvement measures are included. That means measures which lead
to a decreased consumption of fossil fuels (thus less emission
of CO<sub>2</sub>) but which do not reduce the magnitude of the activity
for which the energy is used. Included are:
<P><ol><ul>
<li> end-use efficiency improvement (e.g. wall insulation, heat recovery,
more efficient cars, more efficient industrial processes, etc.);
<P>
<li> more efficient conversion of fuel (e.g. combined heat and power
(CHP) and more efficient power plants);
<P>
<li> the use of renewable energy sources like solar energy;
<P>
<li> good house keeping.
</ul></ol>
<P>
The ICARUS data base gives the conservation potential up to the
year 2000 and 2015. For this reason we made an interpolation,
assuming a linear increase in conservation potential between the
year 2000 and 2015. In this way we obtain a potential emission
reduction in the year 2005 of 93 Mt.
<P>
The ICARUS data base calculates the total yearly costs, using
the investment costs, operation and maintenance costs, costs of
avoided fuel and electricity consumption, and interest rate. Out
of the potential 93 Mt CO<sub>2</sub> reduction we looked at the most cost
effective 80 Mt CO<sub>2</sub>. Using a real interest rate of 4.7% (VROM,
1994) and constant energy prices (at the 1990 level) in our calculations,
the lower energy bill recovers the costs of investment for most
reduction measures. In Figure 4.1 the cost effectiviness is given
for the various measures as a function of the amount of avoided
CO<sub>2</sub>. The measures at the right-hand side of the arrow are superfluous
for achieving the Toronto target and therefore not included in
our calculation of the employment effects. In the figure eight
dots are drawn to show as an example the cost effectivity of a
few measures out of the more than 900 included in the ICARUS data
base.
<P>
The option of nuclear energy, which has been excluded for reasons
expressed in section 2.2, would be situated somewhere between
the options of wind and hydro energy. The costs per ton of avoided
CO<sub>2</sub> is estimated to be between <i>f</i> 25,- and <i>f</i> 300,- (Boels
<I>et al</I>., 1994).
<P>
In Table 4.3 the avoided CO<sub>2</sub> and the percentage of reduction in
respect to the base year 1988 is listed for various sectors of
the economy.
<P>
<b>Table 4.3</b><i> Division of CO<sub>2</sub>-emission reduction over the various
sectors</i><HR>

<PRE WIDTH=132>
                   avoided CO<sub>2</sub> (Mton,  reduction           
                   year)               percentage          
                                       relative to sector  

agriculture        7                   30 %                

industry           26                  18 %                

services           10                  28 %                

dwellings          15                  23 %                

transport          10                  19 %                

energy sector      12                  15 %                

total              80                  20 %                


</PRE>
<HR>

<P>

<P>
<B>4.3 Avoided energy costs<!--4.3 Avoided energy costs--></B>
<P>
In this section the yearly costs of avoided natural gas, oil,
coal and electricity are calculated. The results are given in
Table 4.4. The lower consumption of energy results in a lower
turnover of the energy supply sector.
<P>
<b>Table 4.4</b><i> Avoided energy (in Petajoules (=10<sup>15</sup> J) and energy costs
(in billions of guilders)</i><HR>

<PRE WIDTH=132>
avoided    gas      oil      coal     elec-     TOTAL     
                                      tricity             

energy:    548      312      228      131                 

costs:     5.37     6.07     0.98     4.79      17.21     


</PRE>
<HR>

<P>

<P>
<B>4.4 Investment costs<!--4.4 Investment costs--></B>
<P>
The investments to which the selected measures give rise, are
made in the following six sectors of the economy: 1. mechanical
engineering, 2. electrical engineering, 3. car and transport industry,
4 construction and installation, 5. business services, 6. other/internal.
The yearly operation and maintenance costs are in the last category
6.
<P>
The various measures differ in lifetime of the investment. We
divided the investment costs by the lifetime of the investment
to obtain a mean investment per year (without interest). It should
be noted, however, that to reach the Toronto target the investments
have to be made in a shorter time than the average lifetime: before
the year 2005 the employment effects would be larger than the
average yearly effect that is calculated. In Table 4.5 the results
are given.
<P>
<b>Table 4.5</b><i> Average yearly investment in various sectors.</i><HR>

<PRE WIDTH=132>
investment in:               in billions of   
                             guilders per     
                             year             

mechanical engineering             1.51       

electrical engineering             0.35       

car and transport industry         0.87       

construction and                   1.40       
installation                                  

business services                  0.20       

other sectors and internal         0.40       

additional costs of                0.76       
interest                                      

TOTAL INVESTMENT                   5.48       


</PRE>
<HR>

<P>

<P>
As can be seen, the avoided costs are much higher than the investment
costs. The returns of avoided energy consumption are used to compensate
the initial investments, costs of operation and maintenance.
<P>
Because of the international character of the economy it is assumed
that the capital necessary for investment is attracted from outside
the Netherlands. Therefore, the interest is also spent abroad.
<P>
We assume that the remainder of the avoided costs finds it way
to the households through higher wages. Since a lower turnover
of the energy sector results in a lower income for the government
of about 2.5 billion guilders, the government has to raise the
level of taxation. If the remainder of the avoided costs is diminished
by the taxation, the households have 9 billion guilders to spend.
It is assumed that this results in an equally-distributed increase
(in terms of percentage) of their consumption. Part of this consumption
is met by imports.
<P>
Since most of the means of transportation in the Netherlands are
produced abroad, it is assumed that investments made in the car
and transport industry are also made abroad. The lower consumption
of coal, all of which is imported, results in a reduced investment
abroad.

<br><p>
<align=right><a href="contents.htm">Back ||........></a><p>
