</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN">
<html>
<head>
<title>Introducing Environmental Awareness In Madagascar</title>
</head>
<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link+"#0000ff">
<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=10 width=510>
<td align=left>

<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=12 width=480>
<tr><td align=left>

<h2>Introducing environmental awareness in Madagascar</h2>

<p>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>

<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=12 width=480>
<tr><td align=left valign=top width=180>

<img src="flowers1.jpeg" alt="Picture of flowers">

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>

<font size=2>Drugs derived from the rosy periwinkle, found only in Madagascar, have increased the chances of recovery from childhood leukaemias to 80 per cent. </font>

</td>
<td align=left valign=top>

WWF's educational activities in Madagascar stretch from a child's first day in school to the training of postgraduate researchers. "We want to raise awareness of the island's environment and its value," says John Newby, Director of WWF's African-Madagascar Programme, "and help the Malagasy to develop ways of conserving it."

<p>

WWF introduced environmental education throughout the school curriculum and has run courses for educational administrators and more than 1,400 teacher-trainers, who have in turn trained 20,000 other teachers for such things as tree-planting and setting up school nature reserves. 

<p>

To back this up, WWF opened two environmental education centres, in Antananarivo -- Madagascar's capital -- and Fianarantsoa, offering in-service training to teachers and environmental information to students and the public. Based on the success of the first two, four further centres are planned.

<p>

"Eighty per cent of Madagascar's 10,000 plant species are found nowhere else," says Nat Quansah, WWF's Plants officer in Madagascar, "and it has five times as many tree species as the whole of North America. There is an urgent need to study and conserve the island's natural environments, but for that, there needs to be an even larger pool of skilled nationals who understand and care about this unique place."

</td></tr>
</table>

<br>

To build such a pool, WWF runs a programme to train students and researchers, linked to the island's universities and research institutes but supplemented with highly specialized scientists from outside. One subject currently being studied is the indigenous use of medicinal plants. "There is a wealth of knowledge among local people," explains Quansah, "but little has been documented, and few plants studied scientifically. We have built a team of students, doctors, botanists, and chemists to investigate these plants and develop a parallel health care system that draws on them. This project is providing valuable information, but it also helps train local scientists, and demonstrates to the Malagasy that their environment is well worth conserving."


<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<a href="page8-13.htm#strategy6">Back to the previous page</a>

</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>

</td>
</table>
</center>
<p>
