</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Comparison with other literature</title> 
</HEAD>
<body background="http://www.panda.org/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#FF3333" alink="00ff00" vlink="509920">
<center><font size=+3>Comparison with other literature</font></center>
<p><br>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<B>6.1 Introduction<!--6.1 Introduction--></B>
<P>
In this chapter we set our results in perspective by comparing
them to some other results that are arrived at in the literature.
In particular, two comparisons are made.
<P>
First, in section 6.2 a comparison is made with calculations of
the Dutch Central Planning Bureau (CPB). In particular, a comparison
is made with CPB (1992 and 1993b), in which the CPB investigates
the effects of a tax shift from labour to energy using macro models.
These studies can be seen as the most thorough studies concerning
the employment effects of energy conservation for the Netherlands.
<P>
Secondly, in section 6.3 we compare our results with calculations
made for other countries in which a similar input-output approach
is used as in our study.
<P>
<B>6.2 Studies of the CPB for the Netherlands<!--6.2 Studies of the CPB for the Netherlands--></B>
<P>
Recently, a number of studies have been done by the CPB to evaluate
the consequences of a tax shift from labour to energy. In these
studies the CPB evaluates the consequences of the tax shift with
two models which are used iteratively, namely:
<P><ol><ul>
<li> the sector macro model Athena which mainly models economic relationships;
<P>
<li> the energy demand model Ceneca which mainly models the energy
demand of the different sectors to a (highly) detailed level.
</ul></ol>
<P>
The CPB (1992) examines the economic and energy effects of a shift
in taxation for diverse variants. In the so-called A and B variant
they deal with a shift in taxation roughly characterised by an
energy levy on all forms of energy consumption which increases
energy prices by 50% or 100% respectively. In the A variant the
shift is carried out within the OECD; in the B variant it occurs
only in the Netherlands.
<P>
In both variants both levies lead to a decrease in the level of
employment in the Netherlands. This can be explained by the complete
dominance of relocation effects: the departure of energy-intensive
businesses to places outside the levy area. In this respect, the
study differs from our analysis. In our approach it is assumed
implicitly that the (unspecified) government policy is such the
relative competitive position of the energy-intensive businesses
is not affected. As a result, the employment effects are incomparable
with our study.
<P>
As far as the reduction of CO2 emissions is concerned, in the
CPB variants the Toronto target is achieved for the Netherlands
because of the mentioned departure of energy-intensive businesses
out of the Netherlands.
<P>
The CPB (1992) also considers a variant, the so-called C variant,
in which the energy-intensive industry is exempted from the energy
levy. In this way, it is prevented that energy-intensive businesses
move abroad. As a result, the CPB now finds - both for a 50% and
for a 100% levy  moderately positive effects on employment for
the short and medium term (up to 2005) and no effects on employment
worth mentioning in the longer term.
<P>
The positive effects on employment for the short and medium term
are due to the combined effects of (i) extra investments in energy
conservation and (ii) lower labour costs because of the tax shift.
In the short and medium term these effects apparantly dominate
feedback mechanisms on the labour market. In the longer term these
feedback mechanisms (more technically speaking: the strong Phillips
curve effect) take over, which results in neglegible employment
effects in the long term.
<P>
The above results are not directly comparable with the results
of our study because of the following points.
<P>
<ol><ul>
<li> The reference scenario of the CPB includes energy conservation
which takes place autonomously and which is already planned by
the government. Thus, the employment associated with this energy
conservation is <I>not</I> included in the analysis of the CPB.
Furthermore, a higher economic growth is assumed.
<P>
<li> The CPB focuses on the level of employment in the Netherlands.
Employment that is created abroad, is not taken into account.
<P>
<li> The positive employment effects in the study of the CPB is not
only due to investments in energy conservation (which is the driving
force in our study) but also to the lower labour costs which are
the result of the considered tax shift. In the study of the CPB
the relative importance of these factors cannot be distinguished.
<P>
<li> Because of the macro approach of the CPB multiplier and feedback
mechanisms play a role in their analysis. The feedback mechanisms
on the labour market play certainly a role in the long term, especially
in a reference scenario with a relatively low rate of unemployment
due to a well functioning labour market.
</ul></ol>
<P>
 It is not clear to which extent they play a role in the short
and medium term, although it is plausible that their influence
is limited due to the mal functiong of the labour market nowadays.
<P><ol><ul>
<li> The tax shift appears not sufficient to achieve the Toronto
target in 2005. In particular, the CPB predicts - notwithstanding
the energy levy - an increase in CO2 emissions of 6% (50% energy
levy) and 2% (100% energy levy) in 2005 compared to the 1988 level.
</ul></ol>
<P>
Summarizing, we conclude that because of different points of departure
the results of CPB (1992) are not directly comparable with our
study. Nevertheless, it can be concluded that feedback mechanisms
on the labour market become more dominant on the long term, especially
in a reference scenario with a relatively low rate of unemployment
due to a well functioning labour market.
<P>
Thus, if such a reference scenario were assumed in our study,
the negligence of feedback mechanisms in our study leads to an
overestimation of the net number of jobs created in the long term.
For, in such a reference scenario the extra employment because
of energy conservation leads to a higher wage rate, so that part
of the extra employment is countered by a loss of employment elsewhere
in the economy. However, in such a reference scenario the unemployment
rate is already low, so that this does not seem much of a problem
from a policy point of view.
<P>
<B>6.3 Similar input-output analyses for other countries<!--6.3 Similar input-output analyses for other countries--></B>
<P>
For the US and the UK studies have been done to the employment
effects of energy conservation programmes that largely consist
of building insulation, particularly in the domestic sector, and
upgrading of heating systems. Although these studies are therefore
more limited in character, it is nevertheless useful to compare
the results of these studies with our study in broad lines, because
a similar input-output approach is used.
<P>
Krier and Goodman (1992) find in the US case a positive net effect
of the investigated energy conservation programme. Just as in
our study they find that the loss of employment in the energy
sector is somewhat larger than the direct gains in employment
due to the investments in efficiency improving measures. Again
just as in our study, the net employment effect is nevertheless
positive due to the respending effect.
<P>
Taylor (1992) finds for the UK similar results. However, in her
study the employment gains due to the direct investments are larger
than the loss of employment in the energy sector. The resulting
positive net effect is enlarged further by the employment gains
due to the respending effect.
<P>
Summarizing, we conclude that similar approaches for other countries
confirm our conclusion that stimulating energy conservation can
have positive employment effects.
<P>
<br>
