<head>
<title>Promoting Sustainable Forestry</title>
</head>
<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ff">
<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=10 width=470>
<td align=left>

<h2>Promoting sustainable forestry</h2>

<p>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>
<br>

<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=12 width=480>
<tr><td align=left valign=top>

<img src="leafyLad.jpeg" alt="Picture of a greenhouse">

<p>

<font size=2>Mahogany tree seedlings ready for planting, Brazlian Amazon.</font>


</td>
<td align=left valign=top>



Deforestation in Brazil, which slowed down during the early 1990s, is once again increasing. In 1995, a record number of forest fires was recorded throughout the Amazon region. The Brazilian Amazon is believed to have lost up to 12 per cent of its cover, while most of the lesser known Atlantic forest has already disappeared.

<p>

WWF's Programme Office in Brazil is promoting sustainable forestry, and trying to ensure that current legislation is actually respected. WWF has, for example, joined a coalition of NGOs which aims to stamp out illegal and unsustainable mahogany extraction. The group is helping local communities develop the necessary skills to defend themselves against timber dealers as well as producing training materials for government officials and park rangers. In parallel, WWF has just embarked on a research programme to discover if the volume of mahogany already extracted has caused genetic erosion in the species. 

</td></tr>
<tr><td align=left colspan=2>

Another two-pronged conservation programme has been launched in Paragominas, the most intensively logged area of the Amazon. Under current rules, loggers and sawmills must plant six saplings for every cubic metre of timber 
harvested -- or pay an equivalent fee for the authorities to do so. Most elect to pay, and are frustrated because bureaucracy has hampered the establishment of viable replanting projects. WWF encouraged the companies to found a not-for-profit reforestation association, and is supporting the production and distribution of a manual on how to set up and manage such an operation. Simultaneously, WWF is working with IMAZON, a local NGO, to demonstrate how sustainable forest management and timber extraction are both possible and profitable -- and has produced a video to spread the message.

<p>

"Our programme is ambitious," says Paulo Lyra of the Brazilian office, "and we have a wealth of experience to draw on through the WWF Network. But the canvas of conservation in Brazil is vast, so we have to use both our human and financial resources cooperatively and catalytically."

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<a href="page15-17.htm#two">Back to the previous page</a>

</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

</td>
</table>
</center>
<p>
<center><a href="/graphics/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a><p>
