<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Economic methodology</title> 
</HEAD>
<body background="http://www.panda.org/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#FF3333" alink="00ff00" vlink="509920">
<center><font size=+3>Economic methodology</font></center>
<p><br>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<B>3.1 Introduction<!--3.1 Introduction--></B>
<P>
There are various approaches conceivable for calculating the potential
employment effects of achieving the Toronto target. In our calculation
we have used a static input-output analysis. Although a static,
partial analysis has drawbacks compared to using macro models,
it also has its advantages.
<P>
First, it is possible to achieve more specific information about
what sectors are involved in the creation of employment. In macro
models a higher aggregation level is necessary. As mentioned earlier,
specific information about the various sectors is one of the goals
of the study.
<P>
Secondly, macro models involve necessarily so many specific assumptions
(e.g. about the working of the labour market) that these specific
assumptions often become more dominating for the employment effect
than the measures involved.
<P>
Finally, the analysis can be seen as a first step towards macro
modelling and the results obtained in our approach can be used
as input data for macro models. In chapter 6 a global comparison
is made between our results and findings of the Dutch Central
Planning Bureau (CPB) using macro models.
<P>
In the next two sections we explain the methodology which is used
for the calculation and shortly discuss the assumptions underlying
our methodology.
<P>
<B>3.2 Qualitative description of I/O-analysis<!--3.2 Qualitative description of I/O-analysis--></B>
<P>
To evaluate the employment effects of the measures that are necessary
to achieve the Toronto target, we investigate how the output of
the various sectors of the economy is changed by the measures.
Primarily, three changes occur:
<P>
<ol>
<li> Increase in output in the sectors that provide the goods related
to energy conservation and sustainable energy.
<P>
<li> Decrease in output in the energy sectors because of the energy
saved.
<P>
<li> The actors that introduce the measures incur extra costs for
implementation and extra benefits through lower energy bills.
As most of the measures considered will appear profitable, in
effect money is saved. It is assumed that this money is respent
over the economy, in such a way that all sectors experience an
equal increase in output (in terms of percentage).
<P></ol>
The employment effects of these three categories of output changes
are calculated with an input-output analysis. Roughly, this works
as follows:
<P>
<I>Direct employment effects</I>
<P>
Calculation of the direct employment effects requires a knowledge
of the labour intensity (employment per unit output) of the sectors
which experience a change in output. On the assumption that this
labour intensity remains constant, the employment generated by
the change in investment can then be calculated for each sector.
<P>
<I>Indirect employment effects</I>
<P>
Indirect employment is that generated by the change in inputs
from supplier industries, i.e. the sectors supplying the intermediate
goods or services to the sectors producing energy or energy-saving
measures. The change in output of these supplier industries is
estimated on the basis of an input-output analysis. The employment
spin-off of the change in intermediate supplies can then be calculated
from data on the labour intensity of the supplier industries in
question.
<P>
<B>3.3 Crucial assumptions underlying the analysis<!--3.3 Crucial assumptions underlying the analysis--></B>
<P>
As mentioned, the analysis described above can be characterized
as static and partial. Thus, it lacks dynamic, feedback mechanisms
that are present in macro models. Below we make a more specific
inventory of the more crucial assumptions that are made implicitly
in this study.
<P>
We assume that no relative changes in export and import occur.
This is reasonable when it is assumed that the climate policy
is implemented world wide. If the implementation of measures to
improve the energy efficiency is done only at a national level,
the following can be said concerning the competitive position
of the Netherlands.
<P><ol><ul>
<li> Most of the proposed measures appear to be profitable. Thus,
by imposing them the competitive position of the Netherlands would
become better.
<P>
<li> However, there are reasons to believe that some costs are neglected
in our analysis (see section 7.4). This is disadvantagaeous for
the competitive position.
<P>
<li> If the Netherlands take a lead in implementing measures concerning
energy conservation, this could result in a technological lead
as well. This effect, the so called first mover advantage, could
strengthen the competitive position.</ul></ol>
<P>
All in all, it seems implausible that implementing the measures
only on a national level would worsen the competitive position
of the Netherlands.
<P>
We do not take into account a possible loss of employment because
of countervailing powers on the labour market. More specifically,
it could in principle be possible that the extra employment created
would push up the wage level, thereby decreasing employment elsewhere
in the economy. However, given the present case of relatively
high unemployment, it is unlikely that this would happen on the
short and medium term.
<P>
If it is assumed in the base scenario that in the long run the
unemployment rate goes down because of a better functioning of
the labour market, the mentioned countervailing powers cannot
be neglected anymore. However, in a situation of low unemployment
the employment issue becomes relatively unimportant anyway from
a policy point of view.
<P>
Although some sectors profit more because of the measures to be
taken than others, it is assumed that there are no changes in
relative prices because of this.
<P>
We assume that the respending of the money saved on energy bills
takes place in such a way that all sectors of the economy experience
an equal increase in output (in terms of percentage).
<br><p>
<align=right><a href="contents.htm">Back ||........></a><p>
<center>
