<DOCHDR>
http://www.panda.org:80/research/save_myjob/evaluate.htm 204.243.96.56 19970217025035 text/html 13924
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 17-Feb-97 02:46:24 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 23-May-96 15:12:51 GMT
Content-length: 13738
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Evaluation</title> 
</HEAD>
<body background="http://www.panda.org/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#FF3333" alink="00ff00" vlink="509920">
<center><font size=+3>Evaluation</font></center>
<p><br>
<blockquote><blockquote>
<P>
In this chapter the results are evaluated. In section 7.1 we give
a short summary of the results, after which in section 7.2 a discussion
follows of the points of departure and the more crucial assumptions
underlying the analysis in order to set these results in perspective.
In section 7.3 it is shown how climate policy also helps reducing
emissions of sulphur dioxide (SO<sub>2</sub>) and nitrogen oxides (NO<sub>x</sub>),
important contributors to acid rain and urban air pollution. Finally,
in section 7.4 we discuss the question why the measures necessary
for achieving the Toronto target are not yet implemented and which
governmental policies would be needed to facilitate implementation.
<P>
<B>7.1 Summary of results<!--7.1 Summary of results--></B>
<P>
By means of input-output analysis we have shown that implementing
the measures necessary for achieving the Toronto target for the
Netherlands results in a potential permanent increase in employment
of about 71 000 jobs, of which 48 000 in the Netherlands. This
comes down to approximately 1% of the labour force in 2005.
<P>
The employment effects due to the respending of saved money dominate.
This is due to the fact that the measures involved appear to be
(very) profitable. The costs of the necessary investments are
approximately a factor 2 lower than the money saved by these measures.
<P>
The indirect employment effects (the employment created in the
supply sectors) appear substantial. They involve approximately
half of the total employment effects.
<P>
The job creation in the sectors supplying goods for measures to
improve energy efficiency is in the same order as the loss of
jobs in the energy sector. This, despite the fact that the decrease
in output of the energy sector is about a factor three larger
than the increase of the former sectors. The reason for this is
that the energy sector is much more labour extensive than the
other sectors.
<P>
<B>7.2 Points of departure and assumptions<!--7.2 Points of departure and assumptions--></B>
<P>
The employment effects are evaluated compared to a base scenario
with `frozen' technology. Thus, employment effects of energy conservation
that would take place anyway (autonomously or because of already
planned government policies) are included in the analysis. The
reason for this is that in this study we are interested in the
total number of jobs involved in climate policy and not only in
the extra number of jobs involved in <I>intensifying</I> climate
policy.
<P>
It is assumed that the necessary CO<sub>2</sub> reduction is achieved solely
by measures to improve energy efficiency and conservation and
substituting sustainable energy for fossil fuels. Moreover, we
assume that this is done in the most cost-effective way.
<P>
In the base scenario real gross national product grows by 1.5%
a year between now and 2005. Because of this assumption of relatively
low economic growth it is possible to achieve the Toronto target
via measures to improve efficiency. With higher economic growth,
these measures would not be sufficient to achieve the target.
<P>
In that case other options would become necessary, such as the
shrinking (or even closing down) of energy-intensive sectors in
favour of energy-extensive sectors. Such structural shifts in
the economy do not imply a net employment loss: only a restructuring
of the economy. However, if it is necessary to force these structural
shifts too fast, these shifts could give rise to a temporary loss
of jobs.
<P>
We have argued in section 2.2 that it is plausible that the implementation
of the proposed measures before 2005 will not involve a high degree
of capital destruction. Thus, in the calculation of the employment
effects we assumed that no capital destruction occurs. Involving
capital destruction in our calculation would change our results
in the following way.
<P><ol><ul>
<li> As the capital destruction occurs only once, possible changes
are only temporarily. Thus, the permanent employment effects would
remain the same.
<P>
<li> The volume of the calculated effects would also temporarily
not change much because of the following compensating effects.
(i) Capital destruction would lead to a higher demand for new
capital and thereby more employment in the sectors supplying the
capital. (ii) Capital destruction would make measures less profitable,
thus leading to less employment due to the respending effect.
</ul></ol>
<P>
Making assumptions concerning energy prices is notoriously tricky.
Partly because of a recent study by the Dutch Department of Economic
Affairs we assume them constant at the 1990 level.
<P>
If we would have assumed higher (lower) energy prices, this would
probably increase (decrease) the volume of the employment effect.
For, the measures to improve the energy efficiency become more
(less) profitable by this, thus more (less) money is saved and
the employment because of the respending effect increases (decreases).
However, the forgone revenues of the energy sector will be also
larger (smaller), which will have extra negative (positive) employment
effects. As the latter effect is probably somewhat smaller, the
expected net effect is positive (negative).
<P>
In this study we use a static input-output approach. Although
a static, partial analysis has drawbacks compared to using macro
models, it also has its advantages. First, it is possible to achieve
more specific information about what sectors are involved in the
creation of employment. In macro models a higher aggregation level
is necessary. As mentioned earlier, specific information about
the various sectors is one of the goals of the study. Secondly,
macro models involve necessarily so many specific assumptions
(e.g. about the working of the labour market) that these specific
assumptions often become more dominating for the employment effect
than the measures involved.
<P>
In our calculations no special attention is paid to government
policies needed to bring about the efficiency improvements. So
in a way only the employment <I>potential</I> of these measures
is calculated. Policies (such as a tax shift from labour to energy)
can involve specific extra (positive or negative) employment effects.
See section 7.4 for a further discussion.
<P>
<B>7.3 Joint reductions of SO<sub>2</sub> and NO<sub>x</sub><!--7.3 Joint reductions of SO<sub>2</sub> and NO<sub>x</sub>--></B>
<P>
Climate policy not only gives rise to desirable side effects with
respect to employment, it also helps achieving other goals of
environmental policy.
<P>
The most obvious side effect is the conservation of non-renewable
sources. In table 4.4 it was shown that 550 PJ of gas, 310 PJ
of oil, 230 PJ of coal and 130 PJ of electricity are saved when
the Toronto target is achieved. So possible depletion of these
exhaustible resources is postponed.
<P>
Another direct effect of saving fossil fuels is a reduction in
emissions of SO<sub>2</sub> and NO<sub>x</sub>. The formation of these gases, mainly
during the burning of fossil fuels, contribute for example to
the problem of acid rain. While at the moment the formation of
CO<sub>2</sub> is almost directly proportional to the amount of used fuel,
this is not the case for SO<sub>2</sub> and NO<sub>x</sub>. The formation of these gases
can be avoided to a large extent. Therefore, it is difficult to
predict the amount of avoided SO<sub>2</sub> and NO<sub>x</sub> emission when the Toronto
target is achieved. However, if we assume a 'frozen technology'
between the period 1994-2005 with respect to the reduction in
SO<sub>2</sub> and NO<sub>x</sub> emission, the reduction percentage in the emission
of these gases is roughly the same in the year 2005 as the reduction
percentage in CO<sub>2</sub> emission.
<P>
<B>7.4 Government policies<!--7.4 Government policies--></B>
<P>
As has already been mentioned, no special attention is paid in
this study to which government policies would be necessary to
implement the measures to improve energy efficiency. We will discuss
this issue in this final section.
<P>
In chapter 4 it appeared that most of the measures involved to
improve energy efficiency are profitable. This is a well known
fact from the literature. Many explanations have been offered
why these profitable measures are not implemented in the absence
of further government policies (see for an overview e.g. Gillissen
and Opschoor, 1994).
<P><ol><ul>
<li> It could be that in our analysis some costs are omitted, like
transactions costs: in particular in the case of 'add-on technology'
agents have to spend time to find out how the technology fits
in the existing situation.
<P>
<li> There is an uncertainty both in the profit and the reliability
of new technology. Therefore, in reality agents require higher
discount rates than the one used in our calculation.
<P>
<li> Agents have only a limited amount of money to invest. If they
can make investments that are more profitable, they would do so.
<P>
<li> In many cases, the possibilities are unknown to agents. In economic
terms: there are information costs.
<P>
<li> If old equipment is not yet fully depreciated, agents will not
replace it.
<P>
<li> Implementation of the measures costs time and effort, which
agents can consider as annoying. Although the total amount of
money saved on the energy bill for all agents is large, for many
agents the energy bill is small compared to overall costs and
therefore does not have a high priority.
</ul></ol>
<P>
 In economic terms: the measures are not implemented because the
financial profit does not compensate the welfare loss because
of doing something considered annoying.
<P>
Given these possible obstacles that prevent the implementation
of efficiency improvement by itself, a number of government policies
is proposed in the literature to overcome these:
<P>
<ol><ul>
<li> direct regulations;
<P>
<li> subsidies on energy conservation measures;
<P>
<li> creation of energy services. The electricity and gas companies
can help agents with energy analysis (scanning the conservation
potential), advising, implementation (project management), taking
over the risks involved with implementation and lending money
(see, e.g., Moor <I>et al</I>., 1995).;
<P>
<li> tax shift from labour to energy. It is plausible that the obstacles
mentioned are only of relative importance. If energy conservation
becomes profitable enough, the obstacles mentioned are overcome.
</ul></ol>
<P>
Presently, it remains an open question to what extent the above
policy options (or others) are able to realise the measures to
improve energy efficiency mentioned in this study. More research
is needed and it seems self-evident that present government policy
is insufficient to overcome the (hidden) obstacles.
<P>
However, extra government policies will generally have extra side
effects on employment. Below we will discuss two possible forms
of these.
<P>
Extra government policies will in general cost extra money. One
can think of the extra costs involved with extra government workers
to implement the policy, extra advisers, extra people to facilitate
implementation, and so on. These extra `policy' costs would eventually
decrease the net profits for the private agents. Thus, less money
is saved in effect and the employment effect because of the net
savings would be smaller. However, this effect is compensated
by more jobs for people involved in the implementation policy.
So, it is plausible that the net employment effect would be the
same. Only the sort of jobs would be different: more jobs in `implementation
policy', less jobs spread out over the whole economy.
<P>
If the government chooses to achieve (part of) the CO<sub>2</sub> reduction
via a tax shift from labour towards energy/CO<sub>2</sub>, the shift in the
relative prices of energy and labour could have independent employment
effects. After analyzing the relevant theoretical and empirical
literature De Wit (1994) reaches the conclusion that, provided
that it is prevented that energy-intensive businesses move abroad,
such a tax shift has (modest) positive employment effects on the
short and medium term, while at the long term things are less
clear. These positive employment effects on the short and medium
term are due to a combined effect of (i) the investments in energy
conservation and (ii) the change in relative price of energy and
labour. However, as it is not possible to isolate the separate
effects of these two determinants, it is not possible to pin down
the separate employment effect of the change in relative prices.
As the combined effect of the two mentioned determinants is relatively
modest, one should not be too optimistic about the volume of this
effect.
<P>
A final caveat concerning the study seems in order. As explained
above there are all sorts of `hidden' financial and non-financial
costs involved in implementing measures to improve energy efficiency.
The existence of these costs do not in particular endanger the
volume of the employment effects. However, there is a possibility
that these costs appear so high that from an economic point of
view other ways to achieve the Toronto target are more preferable.
With the present state of knowledge this is an open question.
<P>
<br>
<align=right><a href="contents.htm">Back ||........></a><p>
