<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN">
<html>
<head>
<title>Protecting The Turtle Breeding Grounds</title>
</head>
<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ff">
<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=12 width=480>
<td align=left>

<h2>Protecting the turtle breeding grounds</h2>

<p>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>
<br>

<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=12 width=480>
<tr><td align=left>


WWF - Greece has invested more than US$2.5 million  into buying one of the Mediterranean loggerhead turtle's favoured breeding beaches. One in five of these turtles returns to the Ionian island of Zakynthos to lay her eggs, but the nesting grounds are threatened by illegal tourist development. "The turtles have been frightened off by noise, lights, and intense human activity," says Spyros Kouvelis, Head of Conservation, WWF - Greece, "and they won't go to other places to nest. Some of the females are releasing eggs into the water, frustrated after aborted attempts to dig a nest on a beach crowded with holiday makers."

</td>
<td align=left valign=top>

<img src="turtle.jpeg" alt="Picture of a turtle">

</td></tr>
<tr><td align=left colspan=2>


WWF has been campaigning for Zakynthos' Laganas Bay to be declared a marine park since 1992. Earlier this year, Greece was urged to demolish illegal buildings in the area and establish the marine park by the Standing Committee of the Berne Convention (of Wild Flora and Fauna and Natural Habitats in Europe) to which Greece is a signatory. Failure to comply means that the Council of Europe can take Greece to the European Court - harming the country's chances of future EU development funds.

<p>

Local authorities in Zakynthos have been dragging their feet and issuing contradictory statements about the status of an illegally built road. "As this is clearly an attempt to subvert our conservation efforts," says Kouvelis "we are taking legal action. The area we have bought is the only beach still unaffected by people. It should be the core of the marine park, and we will continue to campaign to make sure that Greece lives up to its international obligations."

<p>
<br>
<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<a href="page18-20.htm#one">Back to the previous page</a>


</td></tr>
</table>
</center>

</td>
</table>
</center>
