<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> WWF_Ecoregion200_page17.htm </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY background="../graphics2/bg7.gif" link="#4945eb" 
vlink="#e42f3c" alink="#e42f3c">


<table cellpadding=10  width=600  border=0>
<tr><td width=125  valign=top>
<img src="../graphics2/logo.gif" alt="WWF Logo">
<br><br><a href="/action/"><img src="/graphics2/actnow.gif" border=0 alt="Act Now"></a><br><p><center><a href="the200.htm"><img src="/graphics2/indexbut2.gif" border=0 alt="Index button"></center>

<p>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<p>
</td>

<td width=10><br></td>

<td width=465 valign=top>
<center>
<img src="../graphics2/global200ecoprofilehd.gif" alt="Ecoregional Profiles">
</center>

<p>
<h3>CORAL REEF AND ASSOCIATED MARINE ECOSYSTEMS</h3>
<p>
<font size=2>

<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Belize Barrier Reef - Belize, Honduras, Mexico
<br><b>Description:</b>			With a length of 720 km., the Belize Barrier Reef is the second largest barrier reef  in the world, after Australia's Great Barrier Reef. The reef system is also unique in featuring three atolls, one of which is considered to be the best example of an atoll in the Caribbean. Species diversity is high for the Caribbean and the reef is in generally good condition, although there are rapidly growing pressures from coastal development, tourism, sedimentation from changes in land use, and over fishing. Associated with the reef are extensive areas of relatively pristine coastal wetlands, lagoons, seagrass beds, and mangrove forest, which provide critical habitats for threatened species such as sea turtles and manatees. 

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Northern South America coastal marine ecosystems -- Colombia, Panama, Venezuela, Guyana, Surinam, French Guiana, Trindidad & Tobago, Netherlands Antilles
<br><b>Description:</b>			This region is noted for its diversity of habitat types including coral reefs, mangroves, seagrass beds, and upwelling areas.  It has also been recognized as a regional center of marine endemism, particularly for fish and invertebrates.  Threats include loss of mangroves and surrounding forests, pollution from oil development, overfishing, and nutrient runoff from land.

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Greater Antilles and Bahamian coral reef ecosystems - Jamaica, Cuba, Haiti, Dominican Republic, Cayman Islands, Bahamas
<br><b>Description:</b>			This ecoregion includes the Andros Barrier Reef, located 2-5 km. offshore of the island of Andros in the western Bahamas. The reef is considered one of the finest barrier reefs in the Caribbean and is the third largest reef system in the world. It is an extremely important resource for the fishing industry, and provides habitat for conchs (Strombus gigas), sea turtles, and such seabirds as white-tailed tropicbird (Phaethon lepturus), sooty tern (Sterna fuscata) and brown noddy tern (Anous stolidus). Other sites in the region include habitat for the endangered American crocodile (Crocodylus acutis). Tourism, over fishing, destructive fishing practices, and development threaten the reefs across this ecoregion.


<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		East African coast, particularly Mafia Island and Rufiji Delta 	(Tanzania), and Basaruto Archipelago (Mozambique)
<br><b>Description:</b>			The Rufiji Delta is one of the most important coastal wetlands in East Africa and has about 3,200 hectares of mangrove. Elsewhere along the coastline of Tanzania and Kenya, coral reefs form an almost continuous fringing reef. On Mafia and other islands, patch reefs predominate on the western sides and well-developed fringing reefs on the eastern sides, which may be among the finest remaining reefs in the region. The reefs around Mafia support 350 species of fish and 40 genera of corals. The Basaruto Archipelago supports a diverse range of marine habitats, including deep sea areas, coral reefs, rocky intertidal areas, sandy beaches, tidal sand flats, seagrass meadows, and mangrove communities. Four species of turtle nest in the archipelago, which is also the most important habitat in the region for dugong (Dugong dugon). Dynamite fishing, dredge fishing, loss of mangroves, and pollution threatens the survival of these marine ecosystems.

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Gran Recife de Toliara & marine ecosystems and mangroves of SW Madagascar
<br><b>Description:</b>			The barrier reefs of southwest Madagascar are the most extensive in the Indian Ocean and among the largest in the world, with about 200 km. of true barrier reef -- including the 18-24 km-long Gran Recife de Toliara -- and a number of offshore coral islands. Madagascar has high coral species diversity, with over 60 coral genera. The Toliara reefs have high fish diversity, with over 550 species, and supports an important artisanal fishery. Several endemic marine species occur here.  The region also contains mangrove and extensive seagrass beds.  Mangrove species include crab plover (Dromas ardeola), African spoonbill (Platalea alba), Madagascar malachite kingfisher (Alcedo vintsioides vintsioides), and Madagascar fish eagle (HaliaeÎtus vociferoides). pecies include crab plover (Dromas ardeola), African spoonbill (Platalea alba), Madagascar malachite kingfisher (Alcedo vintsioides vintsioides), and Madagascar fish eagle (HaliaeÎtus vociferoides).

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Red Sea coral reefs and marine ecosystems
<br><b>Description:</b>			The Red Sea is the warmest and most saline of the world's seas. No permanent coastal rivers or streams flow into the Red Sea, and it is partially isolated from the open ocean. All these features contribute to unique flora and fauna of the region. The diverse and spectacular coral reefs for which the Red Sea is renowned are found only in the central and northern portions, where the reefs are well-developed and drop steeply into deep water. Tourism and oil pollution pose threats to the Red Sea's coral reefs.

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Southern Persian Gulf -- Bahrain, Saudi Arabia, UAE, Qatar.
<br><b>Description:</b>			This ecoregion contains rare, high-latitude coral reefs and green turtle-nesting beaches. The shallow waters of Kuwait Bay are a critical nursery habitat for commercial species of shrimp and fish and contain a unique species of mudskipper. The Gulf is also the most important area for dugong (Dugong dugon) in the western part of its range, and second in global importance only to Australia. Dugongs are actively hunted and are also caught accidentally. Development and pollution pose the most severe threats to this ecoregion. 

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Chagos, Laccadive, & Maldive Islands 
<br><b>Description:</b>			The Maldives, the Chagos Archipelago, and Laccadives are composed entirely of atolls, with reefs and sandy islands, and form the Laccadive-Chagos chain that extends southward from India to the Central Indian Ocean. The Maldives contain extensive and largely intact reefs, and comprise perhaps one of the world's most complex reef systems. The Chagos Archipelago has the largest expanse of undisturbed reefs in the Indian Ocean, as well as some of the most diverse. In addition to five atolls,including Great Chagos Bank, the world's largest atoll in terms of area, there are two areas of raised reef and several large submerged reefs. The Chagos reefs are of particular interest for the presence of an endemic coral, Ctenella chagius. The Maldives and Chagos islands are important nesting sites for green turtles (Chelonia mydas), and many of the islands in the chain have seabird nesting colonies.

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Andaman and Nicobar Islands coral reefs and marine ecosystems - India
<br><b>Description:</b>			Unlike the Laccadive-Chagos chain, the Andaman and Nicobar Islands are high volcanic islands, arising from a submerged  mountain chain that follows a southward extension of the continental shelf. The Andaman and Nicobars have fringing reefs around many islands, and a 320 km.- long barrier reef on the west coast. While poorly known scientifically, these reefs may prove to be the most diverse and best preserved in India. Hawksbill (Eretmochelys imbricata), leatherback (Dermochelys coriacea), and olive Ridley (Lepidochelys olivacea) turtles nest in the region, as do saltwater crocodiles. 

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Isthmus of Kra marine ecosystems 
<br><b>Description:</b>			The isthmus of Kra extends south off mainland southeast Asia, forming a boundary between the Indian and Pacific Oceans and linking Thailand to Peninsular Malaysia. This ecoregion includes some of the best developed reefs in Thailand, on the west side of the isthmus, and globally important reefs belonging to Malaysia, on the eastern side. The area contains mangroves, and supports hawksbill (Eretmochelys imbricata), leatherback (Dermochelys coriacea), and Olive Ridley (Lepidochelys olivacea) turtles. 


<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Nansei Shoto marine ecosystems - Japan
<br><b>Description:</b>			The Ryuku Islands, a chain of islands off southwestern Japan, have been called the Gal·pagos of the western Pacific for their astounding biological richness and uniqueness. The marine ecosystems contain diverse coral reefs which support many endemic fish species and which support thriving populations of marine birds and mammals.  

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Central Islands marine ecosystems of Philippines
<br><b>Description:</b>			These reefs, once rich in species of fish and coral, have been severely degraded. Primary threats to marine environments in the Philippines include coastal erosion, sedimentation, and nutrient runoff from the land, coral mining and collection, and destructive fishing practices such as dynamite fishing and cyanide fishing for the pet trade. 

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Lesser Sundas coral reefs and marine ecosystems  -- Indonesia
<br><b>Description:</b>			The abundant coral reefs, mangroves, and seagrass beds of the Lesser Sundas support the richest array of coral reef animals and plants inthe world. Sedimentation and nutrient runoff caused by deforestation and agricultural activities, habitat destruction, and localized over exploitation of fish and sea turtles are major threats to the region, along with other unsustainable practices such as rock mining, blast fishing, and land reclamation.  

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		New Guinea & Moluccas coral reefs and marine ecosystems -- Papua New Guinea, Indonesia
<br><b>Description:</b>			The diverse and complex coral reefs and marine ecosystems of Papua New Guinea and the Moluccas support numerous endemic species of coral, fish and invertebrates, as well as populations of marine turtles, dugongs, and giant clams. The reefs and lagoon complexes also contain seabird rookery islands. Dynamite fishing, shark fin fisheries, uncontrolled tourism, and toxins and erosion from logging and mining pose threats to the region. 

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Palau and Micronesia coral reefs and marine ecosystems
<br><b>Description:</b>			Palau is considered to have some of the richest and most diverse coral reefs in the Pacific, with 300 species of coral. Micronesia's reefs also support diverse communities of coral, fish, and marine mammals. Species include all seven known species of giant clam (Tridacnidae spp.), hawksbill (Eretmochelys imbricata) and green turtle (Chelonia mydas). Over fishing and destructive fishing practices such as the use of cyanide threaten the reefs. 

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		South Pacific coral reefs and marine ecosystems -- Vanuatu, Fiji, New Caledonia, Samoa, Tonga
<br><b>Description:</b>			This ecoregion contains many internationally and regionally important sites for marine biodiversity, particularly coral reefs and mangroves. There are numerous lagoons, barrier and fringe reefs, and eelgrass beds. These and other habitats are key areas for hundreds of endemic fish species, marine turtles, and nesting seabirds. The islands also contain habitats for species such as the crested iguana (Brachylophus vitiensis). Over fishing, illegal fishing, pollution, siltation, and introduced species threaten various parts of this ecoregion.

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Great Barrier Reef -- Australia
<br><b>Description:</b>			The Great Barrier Reef is the largest single reef system in the world, extending 2,000 km. from the low-latitude tropics to temperate zones. It is also the most diverse in reef types, habitats, and environmental regimes.  The northern tropical waters are highly diverse, though there  are relatively few endemics species. The temperate portions of the reef, in contrast, have low overall species diversity  but a higher proportion of endemic species. 

<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Western Australia coral reefs and marine ecosystems -- Australia
<br><b>Description:</b>			Coral reefs extend for over 3,000 km along the western coast of Australia, with numerous reef systems. A wide variety of reefs are found, ranging from open ocean atolls to fringing and barrier reefs. The reefs contain a great diversity of fish, corals, and other  invertebrates.
 
<p>
<b>Ecoregion Name:</b>		Eastern  Polynesian coral reefs and marine ecosystems -- Hawaiíi, Marquesas, Easter Island, Societies and Tuamotu Islands
<br><b>Description:</b>			These isolated oceanic islands are at a greater distance from a continent than any other islands in the world. The Marquesas, along with Hawai'i and Easter Island, have the highest levels of marine endemism of any island or island group in the Pacific.



</font>
<p><br><center><a href="/graphics2/toolbar.map"><img src="/graphics2/toolbar.gif" border=0 ISMAP></a></center>
</tr></td>
</table>
