<head>
<title>Conservtion And Research In Malawi</title>
</head>
<body background="/graphics/back.gif" bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link+"#0000ff">
<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=10 width=510>
<td align=left>

<center>
<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=12 width=480>
<tr><td align=left>

<h2>Conservation and research in Malawi</h2>

<p>

<hr size=1 noshade>

<p>
<br>

For 2 million years, over 600 species of cichlid fish have evolved in Lake Malawi. The need to conserve the fish -- in great demand by collectors - led to the establishment of the world's first park dedicated to the protection of deep lake fish.

<p>

Lake Malawi National Park was declared a World Heritage Site in 1984. Today, with the support of WWF-South Africa, foreign and Malawian scientists - led by Dr Tony Ribbink, who was instrumental in setting up the park -- work with ranger-divers to study the fish and determine how best to manage the park without depriving the ever-growing lakeside population of their main staple.

<p>

The team is currently researching the impact of cichlid species introduced from the north of the lake to the 
south before it was known that different species were endemic to certain parts of the lake. "We are dealing with problems at the cutting edge of aquatic conservation," says Ribbink. "For the first time, we are considering underwater culling to ensure the park's long-term integrity."
<p>

A 100-metre zone from the lakeshore has been declared out of bounds for fishing. Outside this area, 
people living in the park's six villages have retained traditional fishing rights. One village alone has a population of 6,000, so an important part of the park officials' work is to persuade the communities that protecting the fish is in their own interest. 

<p>

"We see the local people as an integral part of the park," concludes Ribbink. "It is therefore essential that we involve them in all our plans."

<p>
<br>

<center>
<img src="fishy.jpeg" alt="Picture of a species of cichlid fish">
</center>

<br>
<dd><font size=2>One of the 600 species of cichlid fish found in Lake Malawi National Park</font>

<p>
<br>

<hr size=1 noshade>
<a href="page8-13.htm#strategy1">Back to the previous page</a>

</td>
</tr>
</table>
</center>

</td>
</table>
</center>
